title: Fairhaven Surf Life Saving Club
summary: Fairhaven is a well known surf beach. The beach is patrolled during December to the Easter. The Fairhaven SLSC was established in 1958.

title: Beach walk
summary: From Sprout Creek, Eastern View, Moggs Creek, Fairhaven to the bottom of the light house there is approx 6 km of beach, featuring rolling surf and spectacular views of the Otway Ranges and Lorne.

title: Rock pools
summary: See what sort of shells and stones you can collect. Can you find a bright red sea star? You can see all sorts of sea vegetation, small fish and crabs. Look at the bird life, gulls and cormorants.

title: Sand dunes
summary: The beautiful rolling sand dunes shape the beach. 2011 has seen significant erosion due to winter storms that have bought strong winds and big waves (up to 10 feet).

title: Painkalac Creek
summary: The creek separates Aireys Inlet from Fairhaven and forms an inlet behind the sand dunes before it cuts through to the ocean. A great place to shelter from the wind and for younger children to swim.

title: Rocks and caves under the light house
summary: There are more rockpools and rocky outcrops to explore under the light house. This area is part of the marine national park. This means that all wildlife is protected and cannot be removed.

title: Aireys Inlet playground and picnic ground
summary: There is small skateboard ramp for children to ride their scooters or skateboards. There are also swings and other play equipment for children and a picnic area.

title: Aireys Inlet lower shops
summary: Pick up a coffee, newspaper or Fish and Chips! To the left of the shops, on the other side of the river, kangaroos can be seen in the early morning or at dusk.

title: Loutit Bay lookout
summary: Return to Painkalac Creek inlet and walk to the grassed area on the left. At the light house bollard turn right and walk up the signed (steep) walking track. Enjoy panaromic views on your walk up.

title: Historical homestead and building
summary: At the lighthouse is the original homestead for the lighthouse keeper. The Aireys Inlet area was first settled in the 1840s. The first tourists arrived in 1919.

title: Split Point Lighthouse
summary: Follow the signs and continue up the walking track. Shipping along the Victorian coast was much safer once the combination of this and other lighthouses at Cape Otway and Point Lonsdale were built.

title: 1. Tramway signal box
summary: Built in 1928 soon after the electrification of the Swanston St and St Kilda Rd cable tramways. Originally included female public toilets, roofed passenger waiting area, small store and staff toilets.

title: 2. City Baths
summary: Built in 1903, the design reflected the social conventions of the time. Men and women were segregated for all facilities; second class baths were in the basement, first class on the main floor.

title: 3. Magistrates Court
summary: Built on the site of the earlier Supreme Court, the building retains fittings from the earlier court including the Gothic canopy that judge Sir Redmond Barry sat under during Ned Kelly trial in 1880.

title: 4. Old Melbourne Gaol
summary: Built between 1851 - 1864. As the oldest surviving penal establishment, it was the site where Ned Kelly was imprisoned, executed and buried, amongst many other criminals.

title: 5. Eight Hour Day Monument
summary: Built in 1923, the monument commemorates the Eight Hour Day movement started by stonemasons in 1856 to improve working conditions - eight hours labour, eight hours rest and eight hours recreation.

title: 6. Trades Hall
summary: Built in stages from 1873 - 1926, Trades Hall is of historical and social significance as a centre of radical and working class politics and activism in Victoria for over 100 years.

title: 7. Medley Hall
summary: Built in 1893 as a private residence, the building has since housed the Italian Club, Italian Consulate and for short time was used for a 'less reputable purpose'.

title: 8. Lygon shop corner
summary: Lygon Buildings is architecturally significant as the largest and most intact terrace of nineteenth century shops in Melbourne. There are no other comparable retail structures in Melbourne.

title: 9. Matthais House
summary: A two storeyed stucco faced bluestone house of 1865-6 with many charming and unusual features - a tower and weathervane, a cantilevered cast iron balcony and delicately glazed arched windows.

title: 10. Sacred Heart Catholic Church
summary: Built in 1855-56. In the 1930s and 1940s the Church of the Sacred Heart became a primary focus for Carlton's Italian community, and this continued into the 1960s.

title: 11. IMAX Theatre
summary: IMAX is the world's largest cinema format, with a screen up to eight storeys high. Films, from documentaries to latest release movies, can be experienced in 2D or 3D.

title: 12. Melbourne Museum
summary: The museum has eight galleries, including one just for children. Highlights include a complete skeleton of a blue whale, the Bunjilaka Aboriginal Cultural Centre, a living rainforest and Phar Lap.

title: 13. Royal Exhibition Building
summary: The Royal Exhibition Building is the only surviving Great Hall that once housed a 19th-century international exhibition and is still used for exhibitions.

title: 14. Carlton Gardens
summary: Developed in 19th-century Gardenesque style, the Gardens feature symmetrically-placed garden beds, significant avenues, the path system, specimen and clusters of trees, 2 small lakes and 3 fountains.

title: 15. Playground
summary: Wonderful playground with swings, slides and many opportunities to climb and clamber, plus small hills to roll down!

title: 16. Carlton Gardens Primary School
summary: The school is an Italian Gothic style building built in 1884 with a hipped roof central pavilion buttressed either end by slightly projecting gables.

title: 17. Terrace Houses (201 - 205 Drummond Street)
summary: Built in 1884, Holcombe Terrace is a fine example of boom style terrace architecture and notable among the works of Norman Hitchcock.

title: 18. Museo Italiano
summary: Museo Italiano displays and interprets the experience of Italian migration, and the culture created by Italians in Australia.

title: 19. La Mama Theatre
summary: Built in 1883, the building was used for various industrial purposes. In 1967, it was leased by Betty Burstall, teacher and theatre-lover, for use as a small theatre to nurture new Australian drama.

title: 19. Underground public toilets
summary: The underground public toilets, built in 1939, are one of eleven built in Melbourne in response to public demand for public toilet facilities in Melbourne that were both sanitary and discreet.

title: 21. 313-315 Drummond Street
summary: Built in 1889, the buliding is architecturally significant for its highly unusual grotesque Gothic facade. The kangaroo-gryphon grotesques on the parapet are highly unusual and distinctive.

title: 22. Carlton Court House
summary: The Carlton Court House is historically significant as part of the civic core of Drummond Street. It is directly opposite the 1878 Carlton Police Station.

title: The Mildura Wharf
summary: Mildura Wharf has been a vital part of the town and inland river transport system since the 1880s. It was established by the Mildura Progress Committee in 1888 to assist the burgeoning river trade.

title: Railway overpass
summary: A short walk across the railway overpass leads to Deakin Ave or head left down to the Hugh King Drive underpass to avoid the stairs.

title: Prince and Princess of Wales Fountain Plaza
summary: This fountain is very special as it was opened by the Prince and Princess of Wales on the 29th October 1985. Many Mildura residence crowded around to see the Princess Diana.

title: War Memorial
summary:
To the left is a War Memorial commemorating those who served in Vietnam, Korea
and South East Asia.

title: Sculpture commemorating Alfred Deakin, Primie Minister of Australia and the initiator of the Mildura
summary: Sculpted by Michael Meszaros and presented to the city to mark the centenary of the irrigation colony in 1987. The memorial represents  fruit blocks and irrigation channels as seen from the air.

title: The Grand Hotel (to the right)
summary: Enter the Grand Hotel’s main entrance and turn left. To your right, you will see a display of historical photos. Through the glass doors are one of Mildura’s original Chaffey fountains.

title: Commodore Motel former site of the Warren boarding house
summary: Back in 1888, this site was a early boarding house called the Warren. A plaque marking the site can be found at the entrance to the motel’s restaurant. The Warren was demolished in 1965.

title: WIN TV
summary: Originally STV8, opening in 1966 and next door is the Sunraysia Daily, the local newspaper.

title: The Cultivator
summary:
Mildura’s earliest newspaper was the Cultivator, begun in 1888. It was a
twice-weekly publication that moved to the current Sunraysia Daily site at
22 Deakin Avenue in 1912.

title: Sunraysia Daily
summary:
Local identity, C.J De Garis bought The Cultivator along with the Mildura
Telegraph and Merbein Irrigationist and merged them into one paper, the
Sunraysia Daily, in 1920.

title: George and William Chaffey Building
summary:
Across the road is a single story late Victorian, red brick building, with
a brick and iron palisade fence. The building was gifted to La Trobe Uni in 2009 by Don Carrazza.

title: Electric Supply Department Substation No.1
summary: In the centre plantation, stands the Electric Supply Department Substation No.1, dating back to 1936, when the production of electricity was considered a local responsibility, rather than a state one.

title: Queen Elizabeth II visit to Mildura, March 25th, 1954
summary: When Queen Elizabeth toured Mildura in 1954, a decorative dais was erected in this area of the plantation.  Pics of this day are displayed at the Carnegie Centre. Visit to Barclays Block in Red Cliffs

title: Bowring's Store, corner Deakin Avenue and 8th Street - Circa 1937
summary: The site of the ANZ Bank was previously known as Bowring Corner and was the site of Bowring’s Store, opened in 1888. It extended into Langtree Avenue in 1961 but ceased business two decades later.

title: Old Mildura Post Office (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: This corner building was for over a century, the Mildura Post Office. The earliest Post Office on this site was built in 1890, with much of the current building being erected in 1923.

title: George V Memorial Fountain (in centre plantation)
summary: Crossing into the centre plantation, you will find the George V Memorial Fountain, originally erected in the gardens of the Rio Vista, home of W.B Chaffey, it was moved to its current position in 1936

title: Mildura Law Courts (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Opened by Robert Hulls, Victoria’s Attorney General, on Nov 23 2004. This complex was built on the site that began as Washington Stores, before becoming Maples, before it all went up in flames in 1996

title: 70 Deakin Avenue (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Once the site of the Shire Offices, beginning as a modest, timber, two roomed building before the current building was erected in 1922. In 1971, the Shire Offices were relocated to Irymple.

title: Carnegie Centre - Home to the Historical and Genealogical Societies (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Constructed in 1908, as the Carnegie Library, courtesy of a 2000 pound grant made by Andrew Carnegie, in 1906, after a request from Lord Hopetoun. The tower was added in 1922 as a soldier memorial.

title: Civic Buildings  (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: The Civic Buildings, opened in 1958 and it’s also the site of the original Shire Hall, also known as the Mildura Town Hall.

title: Statue of W.B. Chaffey (in center  plantation)
summary: In the center  plantation is a statue of W.B. Chaffey, who died in 1926. The Paul Mountford sculpture was unveiled in 1929. A similar sculpture can be found in Renmark, SA.

title: Desailly Rotunda (in center  plantation)
summary: The centre  plantation is home to the Desailly Rotunda, named for Cr George Desailly, former Shire President, who died whilst in office in 1913.

title: 61 Deakin Ave - Mildura's earliest surviving building (RHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: On the RHS of Deakin Ave is the earliest surviving building in Mildura. It started out as Mildura’s first general store, owned by H.B Williams, in 1887. A bank altered the building appearance in 1937.

title: 69 Deakin Ave (RHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Built in 1914, this  Edwardian building has been a restaurant, a bank, a real estate agency and other businesses, which although altered over the years, still retains some of its original charm.

title: Mildura Club (RHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: The Mildura "Gentlemen's Club" began in 1890 with Lord Ranfurly as the first President. Meetings were originally held at the Coffee Palace, until this building was completed in 1920.

title: Deakin Cinema Complex  (RHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: The Deakin Cinema complex was  established in 1975. A point of interest is that the cinema includes the original site of the Masonic Temple, built in 1907, with the façade still remaining.

title: Mildura Workingmans Club (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: An iconic landmark, once famous for having the world’s longest bar (which was removed in recent renovations.). Begun in 1908, it was originally a 1 story structure with a 2nd level added in 1935.

title: Mildura Workingmans Club  War Memorial (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Has stood at the front of the club, since 1920, honoring Mildura’s war dead. The marble soldier is the work of A.D Thomson and the three-sided list of soldiers’ names underpins the heavy losses of WW1

title: Methodist Church (LHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Opened in 1912, this unique church had a number of architectural influences, including Byzantine, Queen Anne, Masonic and Art Nouveau . Image: Methodist Church under construction 1911.

title: The Church of Christ  (RHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: Built in 1908, the Church of Christ was first organised by Reuben Mansell in 1890 and members met in a variety of venues until this building was completed using all voluntary labour.

title: War Memorial (centre plantation)
summary: Commemorates those who died or were killed in World War One. Erected by the Mildura Branch R. S. & S. I. L. A.

title: Uniting Church / St Andrew’s  (RHS of Deakin Ave)
summary: The Uniting Church, known as St Andrew’s, started out as a Presbyterian church and was built in 1914, at a cost of 2097 pounds. It replaced a wooden structure that had been there since 1891.

title: St Margaret’s Anglican Church (LSH of Deakin Ave)
summary: This church opened in 1902, with the addition of the sanctuary in 1934 and the vestry and bell tower in 1957 that honours the lost soldiers of World War II.

title: Madden Avenue
summary: Madden Ave was originally planned to be the principal retail district of Mildura due to easy access to the wharf. However,  Langtree, with it’s proximity to the railway proved to be more significant

title: Mildura RSL Sub Branch
summary: The Returned and Services League with some 1500 Sub Branches Australia wide and with a membership of 240,000 is the largest service association in Australia.

title: Mildura Water Tower
summary: As you cross over 10th street, to your right you will see one of  Mildura's Water Towers. Built in 1957, the tower provides water pressure for thousands of homes across the urban area.

title: Mecure Hotel
summary: Commercial Hotel, commonly remembered as the Wintersun and now the Mecure Hotel was built in 1925

title: Disused water tower
summary: Behind the hotel is a disused water tower, which from 1912 until 1957 operated as Mildura’s sole source of water storage. Instigated by the former First Mildura Irrigation Trust. 180000 litre capacity

title: Under the Clocks
summary: Melbourne's well known and iconic meeting place is under the clocks at Flinders Street Station. Sit on the steps and see the world go by.

title: Mirka Mora mosaic
summary: Mirka Mora made this mosaic in about 1985, it is brilliant. Do not be one of the thousands who walk past it every day without stopping.

title: To Birrarung Marr
summary: The slope down to Birrarung Marr, always fills with expectation. The sculpture of hundreds of red poles is a cracker. Go up and push the poles firmly, what a noise!

title: Federation Square
summary: There always seems to be something happening at Fed Square whether it is concerts, buskers, festivals or people lolling about. The pavers are great to sit on on a sunny afternoon.

title: The Art Centre from Fed Square
summary: Looking over to the Art Centre spire from Fed Square.

title: Birrarung Marr playground
summary: The playground is always open. Watch kids play and enjoy the tube slides, sand pits, swinging hammocks, activity panels, rock and rope climbing features and balance beams.

title: Art Play
summary: Art Play is a great place for children it has lots of shows and creative activities for kids.

title: Mosaic outside art play
summary: I do not know what the story is behind this brightly coloured mosaic outside Art Play, but it is wonderful.

title: Textured path
summary: The winding, textured pathway of cast iron acknowledges the significance of the eel as a traditional food source for groups camped by the river.

title: Watching rowers from Birrarung Marr
summary: Sit on the seats under a shady tree watching rowers go by.

title: To Princes Bridge
summary: The gravel path on the river bank is a bit quieter. More seats and looking back to Princess Bridge.

title: West along the river
summary: From 'Angel' you can get a good look along the Yarra River

title: Angel
summary: Angel (ceramic, steel and concrete) by Deborah Halpern is an artwork commissioned by the National Gallery of Victoria. It is even more impressive than the photo suggests.

title: Grassy hill for rolling
summary: There should be more grassy hills like this one in the centre of cities. Watch the number of kids who are immediately drawn to it and roll down laughing.

title: Walking up the slope to the bridge
summary: The trees and shrubs set in the stone fence as you walk up the slope to the William Barak bridge.

title: William Barak bridge
summary: A purpose built walking (and cycling) space, William Barak bridge is one of true delights of Melbourne. Beautiful and functional.

title: Listening to Proximities
summary: Proximities is a public art installation commissioned for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.  The stories and songs from 53 Commonwealth nations come out of the many, many speakers across the bridge.

title: Sit and watch Melbourne
summary: Sit on the bridge and look south to the Yarra and Tennis Centre or north to the city and listen to the trains go by underneath.

title: Off the bridge to the 'G'
summary: Coming off the bridge and walk to the MCG under the shade of magnificent old Elm trees.

title: The MCG
summary: The MCG, what a collosseum. You don't realise how massive it is until you actually see it. Even if you don't like sport, the sound of the crowd cheering will grab your attention.

title: Dennis Lillee
summary: Bronze statues do around the MCG, none more impressive than the great Dennis Lillee.

title: Aussie Rules
summary: Statue commemorating the first game of Australian Rules Football said to be played nearby on 7 August 1858.

title: Jolimont Station
summary: Its a beautiful the old train bridge. Catch a train (or tram) back to Flinders St or keep going.

title: Watt's Cottage
summary: Home to early settlers in Sorrento, this house was built in 1869. The Pioneer Memorial Garden is well tended with blooms all year round. Tours available (at limited times).

title: Information boards and cafe
summary: Check out the information boards here for details about the history, local environment and features of the area. All Smiles Cafe located a short walk away from here.

title: Surf's up
summary: A good spot to watch the surf, have a picnic, go for a swim, read a book or do whatever you please.

title: Uphill climb towards the top
summary: Definitely a steep climb uphill but the scenery from the top is very worthwhile. Get your heart rate up!

title: Panoramic views
summary: A perfect spot to watch the sunset, or simply enjoy the sweeping panoramic views.

title: Heading down to the beach
summary: Follow the track, which will eventually take you towards the beach.

title: Fine sandy beach
summary: Enjoy the salty sea breezes as you feel the sand under your feet on this beautiful stretch of coastline.

title: Portsea Surf Lifesaving Club
summary: You can take a detour here if you need a toilet stop.

title: 'London Bridge'
summary: A great spot to explore the rockpools and wander under the 'London Bridge' (but not during high tide of course). You can continue along the beach all the way to Point Nepean if you like.

title: Public toilets and drinking fountain
summary: Phew! It's a pretty steep ramp that leads you up here. A convenient toilet stop and a chance to top up your water bottle before heading off again.

title: Start of Wilson's Folly Track
summary: There's a sign a near the car park marking the start of the track. Apparently Capt R Wilson simply lit a match wherever he thought the bush needed to be cleared for the army\'s weapons training areas.

title: Looking out to the sea
summary: Listen out for the twitter of small birds in this fabulous bit of coastal bushland overlooking the sea.

title: Unexploded bombs
summary: A former weapons training area. "All large unexploded ordinance has been removed but you may come across small arms such as rifle and pistol shells," which of course, you shouldn't touch.

title: Point Nepean Visitor Centre
summary: The visitor centre has plenty of local information and maps of the area. You can take a tour to the historical Fort Nepean (a buggy can transport you there). Public toilets and BBQ available here.

title: Mighty high fences
summary: You can take a short detour down to the beach via Cove Ave. Clearly residents here like their privacy but it's such a shame that the street is marred by these enormously high walls and fences.

title: Nature strip plantings
summary: Thankfully, there are patches of wonderful plants to enjoy as you walk down the street.

title: A little bit arty
summary: ... and even a bit of art to give some of these high walls a little bit of character.

title: On the other side
summary: Across the road are a row of charming cottages that reminds us of how the area used to look before the high walls and fences came along.

title: Bus stop
summary: You can catch bus number 788 back to Sorrento, or all the way back to Frankston along point Nepean Road.

title: Boardwalk near fishing platforms
summary: The boardwalks starts along the path just past the carpark on Lakeside Drive. A few fishing platforms go off the boardwalk.

title: Wetlands
summary: The inlet is on one side of the boardwalk and wetlands on the other, both have an abundance of birdlife and aquatic life.

title: The shared path
summary: The shared path is very popular with walkers and bike riders alike and is in pretty good condition.

title: Pelicans and piers
summary: There are many little jetties dotted along the path and it is hard not to spot a pelican or two perched on many of them.

title: Raised boardwalks
summary: The wonderful raised boardwalk provides a shady spot to look out to the inlet.

title: Mallacoota harbour
summary: Old and new, big and small boats (but nothing too flash!) in the Mallacoota harbour.

title: Coull's Inlet
summary: Coull's Inlet is beautiful on a still early morning.

title: Fishing spot
summary: One of the many fishing spots along the walk. Even if you are not into fishing, it's fun to watch early morning anglers.

title: Goat & other Islands
summary: Beautiful views abound on the walk. Goat Island, Rabbit Island and more...

title: Moored boats
summary: Over the summer, many camping ground visitors more theri boats along the shore. Boats for fishing, water skiing, bird watching or pleasure....

title: Mallacoota Foreshore Holiday Park
summary: The next part of the walk goes through the council caravan park, in summer there is always something to look at.

title: To Capt. Stevenson's Point
summary: If you want, you can take a short detour off the path and follow the water to Capt. Stevenson's Point (or stay on the path up above).

title: Capt. Stevenson's Point
summary: A great spot to look up the inlet or to the mouth (and watch boats go out to sea). You can even see Gabo Island from here.

title: Koalas
summary: If you look carefully you can often see Koalas in the trees, even the odd kangaroo.

title: Crossing the inlet
summary: To get across to the beach you have to wade across about 20 meteres of the inlet which is about 45 cm deep. In summer teh water is quite warm so it is very pleasant.

title: Dirftwood structure
summary: This structure that some have built in the sand dune out of driftwood has been there for a while, hope it lasts a while longer!

title: Mallacoota beach
summary: On a clear day the beach is beautiful other times it can be rugged and wild, but no less wonderful. This part is only for strong competent swimmers. But watch the surfers!

title: A walking beach
summary: The beach is certainly great for walking, but can get a bit blowy.

title: Patrolled beach
summary: This is the main swimming beach that is patrolled by life savers in the holiday season. Any one for cricket?

title: Bastion Point
summary: Rockpools to look at and a good spot for snorkling off teh rocks when the conditions are good.

title: Native flowers.
summary: You'll come to a fork in the path. Walk this route as a loop or simply walk along the river till the end and return. Either way there is much to see. We found these feather like flowers. How lovely!

title: Beautiful views of the river
summary: There are lots of birds enjoying the river. We saw several different types of birds swimming in the river.

title: Duck sanctuary
summary: We saw a mother duck and her young ducklings nestled in a log along the river. A clever nest away from predators and people. She's hard to spot in the photo because we didn't want to get too close!

title: Stray fruit bat
summary: We spotted a stray fruit bat in one of the trees. It had clearly fallen behind from the group and was trying to remain hidden from prying eyes. We photographed it from afar so we wouldn't disturb it.

title: Still reflections
summary: A lovely view from along the river.

title: Ducks and more birds
summary: Many birds of all sorts can be found near the boat house because they're used to people feeding them, even though feeding birds is harmful (see link).

title: Barbeque areas
summary: The bbq, tables and seats are under sheltered areas. There is plenty of idyllic picnic spots in shady areas close the river. Great spot for a picnic or gathering.

title: Signs
summary: So many options! Take your pick.

title: Popular route
summary: We passed several walkers, including children, a couple with a baby (must be a hardy 4 wheeler pram!) and others using the route for exercise.

title: Skate Park
summary: Large skate park ideal for families.

title: Jetty
summary: A jetty to admire the scenic surrounds or do a spot of fishing.

title: BBQ facilities
summary: Large undercover BBQ facilities.

title: Cafe by the lake
summary: A cafe overlooking the lake.

title: Bridge
summary: Walk across the bridge and take in the beautiful surroundings.

title: Canoe Club
summary: Canoe hire available from Visitor Information Centre.Canoes can accomodate 2 adults. Kayaks also available.

title: Aquamoves
summary: Aquamoves is an aquatic and leisure centre with facilities such as gym, creche sauna, indoor and outdoor pools.

title: All Abilities Playground
summary: A playground suitable for children and families of all abilities.

title: Aquamoves
summary: Aquamoves is an aquatic and leisure centre with gym and areboic facilities, creche, indoor and outdoor pools.

title: Playground
summary: There is a playground for the children to play on. So the whole family can come to the lake and enjoy the scenery.

title: Fitness Station
summary: Fitness equipment to help you in your work out.

title: dogs off leash area
summary: Area where you can let your dog off the lead. It also has a creek.

title: Bird Watching
summary: You can spy on many different varieties of birds in the wetlands.

title: Fishing
summary: One of the many good places to fish at the lake.

title: Boat Ramp
summary: A place to put your small boat.

title: The beach
summary: One of the beaches to relax on or walk along.

title: Cashins Mill
summary: Built in the early 1850s by Hugh Kneen of Fitzroy. After James Cashin Snr died in 1873, the mill was operated by sons James and William.

title: Farmers Market
summary: First Sunday of the month - 8am to 1pm. Bellbird Park (next to Lillydale Lake), Swansea Road, Lilydale.

title: Rivers
summary: Be alert for high river levels and fast flowing water which can make the Gorge hazardous.The best walking period lasts from early November until late March.

title: Variety of views
summary: The scenic walks take in a range of landscapes.

title: Falls
summary: There are three waterfalls along the track.

title: Australian Forest Walk
summary: Features all Australian plants, including sky-high trees and land-dwelling shrubs.

title: Eucalypts
summary: A collection of over 200 eucalypts; Australia's most iconic trees.

title: Lions Head and Separation Trees
summary: These trees are remnants of the River Red Gum and pre-date European settlement.

title: Lower Yarra River Habitat
summary: An ecological collection which contains Indigenous plants native to the Lower Yarra region.

title: Long Island
summary: A garden which is representative of vegetation pre-European settlement and contains many Indigenous plant species.

title: Sidney Myer Music Bowl
summary: Attend the free Wellbeing music concert at the Bowl at 12pm after the walk to celebrate the wellbeing of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.

title: Smoking Ceremony
summary: Experience a traditional Indigenous Smoking Ceremony in the midst of the ancestral lands of Kulin nation (allocated times).

title: Haven General Store
summary: Haven shop offers drinks, food, papers, a postal service, liquor and petrol. Workers from nearby businesses often drop in and the locals catch up for a chat.

title: Haven Tennis Courts
summary: Haven has teams in the local Tennis competition in both Juniors and Seniors.  Junior "Slam and Sweat" tennis sessions are also conducted here along with midweek competitions.

title: Haven Recreation Reserve
summary: Includes the Haven Hall which is used for a variety of groups such as Playgroup, Exercise classes and the Womens circus.  The Haven Market is held here the first Saturday of the month.

title: Black Saturday Monument
summary: A monument recognising the Remlaw fire that went through Haven and cuased much damage in February 2009

title: Haven Primary School
summary: Set partly back from the road, this school provides education for a little under 100 students.  The small numbers and intimate setting is appealing to many.

title: Tasma Terrace - 2-12 Parliament Place
summary: The terrace is the headquarters of the National Trust. It comprised important boarding houses from the 1870s. Managing a boarding house was one of the few employment options available to early women.

title: the Great Petition sculpture - Burston Reserve
summary: This artwork represents a giant petition with 30,000 signatures offered to the Victorian Parliament in 1891 as evidence of widespread support for equal voting rights for women.

title: Caroline Chisholm Cairn - Burston Reserve
summary: Commemorates the centenary of the death of philanthropist Caroline Chisholm, who served the community by welcoming immigrants and building shelters for travellers to the goldfields at Castlemaine.

title: Women\'s Underground Toilet - Gordon Reserve, near Spring St
summary: The toilet is one of 11 erected by the City of Melbourne between 1902 and 1939. The group is now unique in Australia.

title: Parliament House - Spring St
summary: Victoria was last to grant women suffrage in 1908.A plaque in the garden honours Vida Goldstein,pioneer suffragist and first woman in the British Empire to stand for election to a national parliament.

title: Windsor Hotel - 111 Spring St
summary: Sitting over the main entrance are 2 classically inspired figures draped in robes. The female statue on the right represents Peace, while the male figure on the left represents Plenty.

title: The Lyceum Club - 9 Ridgeway Place
summary: The Lyceum, the famous professional women's club was a purpose-built place, created by and for women, in Victoria.

title: Grosvenor Chambers - 9 Collins St
summary: This building was erected specifically as artists' studios. Amongst other women who had a studio here, Jane Sutherland was regarded as the leading woman artist of the Heidelberg School.

title: WCTU Rooms - 15 Collins St
summary: The Women's Christian Temperance Union was the largest and most influential of the various women's organisations in Victoria in the late 1890s.

title: The Melbourne Club - 36 Collins St
summary: Established in 1838, the Melbourne Club is Victoria's oldest institution. Women are excluded from membership of this bastion of conservatism and one of the most exclusive organisations in Victoria.

title: Harley House - corner of Collins & Exhibition St
summary: The National Council of Women, based here for 2 decades effectively lobbied for legislation and representation on all boards and committees relating women and children's welfare and legal rights.

title: Alexandra Club - next to Harley House
summary: Founded in 1903, this is one of Australia's longest established and exclusive clubs for women. Members include Dame Elisabeth Murdoch, community worker and women's rights activist Beryl Beaurepaire.

title: Le Louvre - 74 Collins St
summary: Formerly a boutique by Lillian Wrightman promoting high fashion European designers. The boutique played a role in establishing Melbourne as the fashion capital of Australia that it has become today.

title: Nauru House - 80 Collins St
summary: The Australian Conciliation and Arbitration Commission was located here from 1979 - 2006, and women campaigners for equal pay re-enacted the 1969 chain up demonstration at the site on 31 October 1985.

title: St Michael's Uniting Church - corner Collins & Russell St
summary: Women have been part of the congregation since its opening in 1867. The Uniting Church has allowed female ministers who serve in parishes, and some females have been Moderators.

title: Flinders Lane
summary: Thousands of women worked in the rag trade and endured poor working conditions such as long hours and low wages. Few buildings of the textile and clothing industries remain. Rosati's is one of them.

title: Former women's buildings - Russell St
summary: The city meeting place for many women's reformist groups. WCTU's first headquarters at 28 Russell St was where girls from nearby workrooms could get cheap good meals.

title: Scots Church - corner Russell and Collins St
summary: Dame Nellie Melba sang in the church choir as a child. When she died, the funeral service was held here. Women have been members of the congregation since 1874 but cannot serve as ministers.

title: Assembly Hall - next to Scots Church - 156 -160 Collins St
summary: Used for the Women\'s Parliament, which was conducted on parliamentary lines with a ministry and political parties and provided useful training in public speaking and parliamentary procedure.

title: Theosophical Society - 181 Collins St
summary: Once home to the Theosophical Society. Many women have been members of the society, and have been elected president over the years. The current Theosophical Society building is at 126-28 Russell St.

title: The Atheneaum - 188 Collins St
summary: The talented artist Clarice Beckett had large yearly exhibitions at the Athenaeum from 1924 until 1932. The building\'s facade contains a statue of Minerva, patron goddess of wisdom.

title: Former underground women's toilet - corner Rusell Bourke St
summary: Built in 1902, this was the first such toilet built as a result of the lobbying by many women, including members of the Womens Political and Social Crusade. It is now under the sculpture at the site.

title: Chinatown - Little Bourke St
summary: An early centre for prostitution and poverty, the Salvation Army established a hall in Little Bourke Street to do battle for the souls of prostitutes and larrikins in the 19th century.

title: Queen Victoria Hospital - 210 Lonsdale St
summary: One of only 3 hospitals in the world to be founded, managed and staffed by women. It was Australia\'s first female medical service, established by Australia\'s first female doctor in 1896.

title: State Library - 328 Swanston St
summary: Helen Garner wrote her well-known novel 'Monkey Grip' at the library. In the forecourt is the statue of Joan of Arc, the national 15th century heroine of France and saint of the Roman Catholic Church.

title: Storey Hall - 344-46 Swanston St
summary: Various women's organisations rented the premises, including the Women's Peace Army associated with Vida Goldstein. Purple and green are colours of the Irish and early feminists who once occupied it.

title: Women's Liberation Office - 16 Little La Trobe St
summary: Feminists from the Women's Liberation Movement Centre produced a newspaper Vashti's Voice, which promoted women's rights such as equal pay and abortion.

title: Welsh Church - 320 La Trobe St
summary: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

title: YWCA's Jasper Hotel - 489 Elizabeth St
summary: Established in 1882, the organisation provides housing services, job placement and mentoring for many women. Inside is a plaque acknowledging Alice Henry, pioneer journalist and unionist.

title: Emily McPherson College (now RMIT) - 379-405 Russell St
summary: Established to improve the domestic skills of women at a time when there was a push for 'scientific' mothering education, also when a young woman's access to secondary education was limited.

title: Old Melbourne Gaol - 377 Russell St
summary: Ned Kelly's mother, Ellen, was a prisoner in the women's cell block when Ned was hanged in 1880. She was in trouble for aiding and abetting Ned and charged with attempted murder.

title: City Watch House - next to the former Magistrates Court
summary: The first prisoner here was Beatrice Phillips, who was charged with indecent language. The National Council of Women and WCTU successfully lobbied to improve some conditions for female prisoners.

title: Magistrates Court - corner La Trobe and Russell St
summary: Jennie Baines was sentenced to 6 months' jail for repeated violations of the War Precautions Act in 1919 for flying red flags. She went on a hunger strike and was released after 4 days.

title: Green Latrine - corner Spring and LaTrobe St
summary: On 21 October 1969 Zelda D'Aprano, a feminist crusader chained herself to the Commonwealth Building (known as the 'Green Latrine', now demolished) until she was cut free by the Commonwealth police.

title: Princess Theatre - 163 Spring St
summary: Many famous actresses have performed at the theatre, including Nellie Stewart, Sibyl Thorndike, Marlene Dietrich and Marina Prior. Nellie Stewart, who starred in the first performance of 'The Mikado'.

title: Visitor centre and restaurant
summary: We start the walk from the visitors centre that overlooks Jells lake.  The restaurant is open every day except Christmas Day.

title: Wattles in bloom
summary: As soon as you start wandering down to the lake you will notice some wonderful native flora to your right.

title: Pacific Black Duck
summary: Around the lake there is abundant bird life including the versatile Pacific Black Duck. It frequents all types of water and is found in all but the most arid regions of Australia.

title: Eurasian Coot
summary: The Eurasian Coot is easy to find.  Its an omnivore, and will take a variety of small live prey including the eggs of other water birds, as well as algae, vegetation, seeds and fruit.

title: A stroll in the park
summary: The path meanders along the edge of open parkland before heading into the conservation area.

title: By the lakeside
summary: When you are near the lake listen out for some of the thousands of frogs that live here.  They do not drink water, and instead absorb it through their skin.

title: Chestnut Teal
summary: When you are crossing the creek you might spot a Chestnut Teal looking for lunch.   A male teal is pictured here agitating the shallow water ..

title: Chestnut Teal Upended
summary: .. before upending to bottom feed underwater.

title: Wetlands
summary: The wetlands act as filters, sponges and reserves of water.  Though only 2% of Victoria is wetland area, it supports 33% of our endangered plants and is home to mammals, frogs, fish and insects.

title: Nesting Boxes
summary: Hollows in old trees are home to many native birds.  As there are not enough hollows for all the native species that utilise the nesting boxes dotted around the park.

title: The conservation area
summary: The conservation area immerses you in native flora, while you are serenaded by the varied songs of the birdlife it supports.

title: Bird Hide
summary: The bird hide provides a great opportunity to watch the birdlife.  The hide has an information board with pictures and descriptions of some of the birdlife you may see.  Bring your binoculars!

title: Purple Swamphen
summary: The park is home to a sizeable population of the beautiful Purple Swamphen.  The male has an elaborate courtship display, holding water weeds in his bill and bowing to the female with loud chuckles!

title: Enjoy the scenery of the park
summary: Can you hear the peace and quiet? This stretch is great for spotting birds and listening to their songs.

title: Drouin Civic Park
summary: Drouin Civic Park is set in a small valley, with a pond, fountain, rotunda, playground and public toilets. The park also includes the 'Path of Achievement'.

title: Directional signage
summary: Directional signage is displayed along the trail to provide distances and orientation.

title: Pause places
summary: Pause places, like this one in the Drouin wetlands, includes recycled-plastic seating, rubbish bins and bike racks.

title: Drouin Wetlands
summary: Wetlands have been established through this part of the walk and the Drouin Landcare Group have planted hundreds of native trees to increase biodiversity and improve water quality and amenity.

title: Boardwalk
summary: After crossing Buln Buln road you will come to an elevated boardwalk over a creek and views across green paddocks.

title: View, Mt Baw Baw, Mt Worth, Strezlecki Ranges.
summary: There are lovely views from a number of vantage points along the trail including vistas to Mt Baw Baw, Mt Worth and the Strezlecki Ranges.

title: Mosaics
summary: Local artists created mosaics which have been set into each of the pause places along the trail.

title: Lardners Track Cenotaph
summary: Here a memorial is located in recognition to William Calder, the first Chairman of Country Roads Board, for his outstanding contribution to Victorias road network.

title: Pause places
summary: Another pause place to enjoy the views of the surrounding farms and mountain ranges.

title: Indigenous history
summary: A number of interpretive signs explain the local Indigenous history, creation stories and artwork of the Gunaikurnai, one of the Aboriginal nations of Australia.

title: Western Park BMX track
summary: The trail winds past the Western Park BMX track where you can try out the track or watch the locals on the berms.

title: Rotary Park
summary: Rotary Park is located on Latrobe Street in Warragul where you will finds a kids playground, outdoor gym equipment, public toilets, rotunda with picnic facilities, drinking fountain, and Hazel Creek.

title: Warragul Gateway Entrance
summary: The entrance of the trail will soon be marked by a large and significant piece of artwork which pays homage to local threatened species

title: Baw Baw Shire Council
summary: This walk is proudly brought to you by Baw Baw Shire Council.

title: Lysterfield Visitor Area
summary: A spot for all the family to gather and play!  Picnic, BBQ, go sailing and swimming, or head off for a leisurely walk around the whole lake.

title: Beach and swimming area
summary: This end of the lake is a designated swimming beach. The dam wall is in the background.

title: Boat Beach
summary: Sail boats launch from here, a lovely sight on your walk along this beach.

title: Dam Wall access
summary: At the end of the beach are steps to the top of the wall which begins your walk around the lake.

title: Trailmix Cafe and Visitor Centre
summary: Providing food, drinks and information as well as bike repairs, sales and hire.

title: Dam Wall
summary: From up here you can get a view over the 82ha lake which supplied fresh water to the Mornington Peninsula from 1936 till 1975.

title: West side of the Lake
summary: The tall tree canopy provides shade as you walk.

title: Acacia Nature Trail
summary: Step in here and step back in time to discover the native vegetation which once surrounded Melbourne.

title: Black Wattles
summary: Black Wattles grow in this area and are stripped bare when their bark is eaten by the Fire Blight Beetle in Winter and Spring.

title: Grassy area
summary: Stop here for a rest or a picnic and perhaps spot an Eastern Grey Kangaroos or Black Wallaby if you are here early or at dusk.

title: Conservation Area
summary: Numerous conservation projects are underway in this park.

title: East side of the Lake
summary: Look up and see how many birds you can spot flying amongst the tree tops.

title: Conservation Zone
summary: Only walkers can use this track amongst the lush green vegetation for the final stretch of this peaceful walk.

title: The end or just the beginning?
summary: The walk is a loop around the lake.  Look out for this sign from the north end of the carpark.

title: Mural on wall
summary: Beautiful wall art and part of a program to address problem graffiti.

title: mosaic artworks
summary: Mosaic artworks in the pocket parks

title: Frog art work
summary: More stunning art work and perhaps an artistic place to rest!

title: Old substation
summary: Historical substation

title: Early drive-through service station
summary: Back from early days of the car.

title: Party supplies shopfront
summary: Always great window displays

title: Old Italian Cake and Coffee Shop
summary: A high street "institution" run by a lovely elderly couple.

title: Architecture on Collins St corner
summary: Interwar architecture.

title: Lions Shop
summary: Shop/admire the Art Nouveau architecture

title: New cafe - active street frontage
summary: For those with an interest in urbanity, a good example of a shop activating the street.

title: Cafes with kerbside dining.
summary: More opportunities for refreshment!  Life on the street again!

title: South Kenginston station
summary: Bottle brushes line the station and are spectacular in flowering season. Listen for rosellas and parakeets.

title: JJ Holland Park Playground
summary: Set in bushy surroundings, this playground has a number of slides, climbing frames and hidey holes. There is a disabled toilet nearby.

title: Bill Vanina Pavillion
summary: Restored and extend in 2015, the Pavillion is used as a sport center eg.Football, soccer and cricket

title: Skate Park & Adventure Playground
summary: A popular place for older children with wheels! There is a public with disabled access at the Skate Park.

title: Kensington Community Recreation and Aquatic Centre
summary: This popular centre has a local gym, heated swimming pool and indoor basketball court.

title: Venny's
summary: The Venny is an adventure playground with a garden, social hub and activities. It's open for limited hours during the school term and school holidays. See link below.

title: Tankard's Reserve
summary: A fine collection of play equipment, plus a picnic shelter with table.

title: Newman's Reserve
summary: Bright and colourful, this playground is suitable for pre-school children. and has 2 slides. A great spot to sit and enjoy the scenery too.

title: View from Newman Reserve
summary: Look for double rainbow (two pots of gold?).

title: Open play area and basketball ring
summary: There is so much potential in an open play area. Cricket? Football? Egg and spoon race?

title: Open play area and  tennis courts
summary: These tennis courts  are available for hire. The key is available from the recreation centre  on Altona Street.

title: Newell's Paddock Lookout
summary: View over wetlands area. You'll often see a wide array of bird life, including swans, ducks and water fowl.

title: Former Stock Bridge
summary: This is a fine spot to admire the surrounding views.

title: Tidal river Bridge
summary: You needed to have crossed this wonderful bridge to have started the walk. On hot days you often see people jumping off the bridge or paddlers going under it.

title: The track
summary: The track is quite well maintained and mostly is quite a gentle climb.

title: Paddlers
summary: I love the view down to Tidal River, you can see them but them not you.

title: Norman Bay
summary: Norman Bay would have to be one of the best walking and playing beaches in Victoria, also great for swimming.

title: Grass Tree
summary: There are a lot of Grass Trees (Xanthorrhoea) around Wilsons Prom, bit only a few on this walk and this one is a beauty.

title: Tidal Overlook
summary: It is worth the short deviation off the track see the views from Tidal Overlook.

title: Rock with a view
summary: There is a rock just off the path with a great view of Squeeky and out to see.

title: View out to sea
summary: Could sit here all day looking out to sea.

title: The track
summary: The track appears like a shady tunnel.

title: Wildflowers
summary: Look out for wildflowers, like this little gem peaking up at you.

title: Life ring
summary: The life ring is there in case people fall off the rocks. Be careful, two young people drowned there in 1988. Best to keep to the path and you will be OK.

title: The Rocks
summary: These rocks are like a sculpture and the colour seems to change with the seasons.

title: To Squeaky
summary: The last part of the path to Squeaky, the anticipation...

title: Squeaky Beach
summary: Don't forget to squeak when you walk!

title: The sea
summary: Time for a dip? But be careful, it is not a patrolled beach.

title: Start
summary: You start the walk from the carpark.

title: No animals are allowed
summary: Because it's a national parks no animals are allowed.

title: Walking on the track
summary: This is how the walk feels, you will feel enclosed and enjoying nature as you walk through it.

title: Breath taking views
summary: There are numerous points to see the coastline.

title: Way down to the beach
summary: This is the point were you can walk down to the beach.

title: Stairs to the beach
summary: Be careful as you walk down to the beach as the stairs are uneven and unsafe.

title: Beach
summary: Enjoying a stroll around the beach with a picnic and a swim. You never know what you may find!

title: Animals
summary: Watch out for all type of creatures, they may just sneak up on you.

title: Melbourne Artists' Supplies
summary: This is my shop to get fancy paper, pens, paints and other bits and bobs. The staff are very helpful, and it's got a very groovy shopfront.

title: Mystery visitors
summary: Hard to tell what this wall's about, you can make up your own story to imagine which mysterious spirits might visit the people who live in this building!

title: Dragon
summary: This Chinese dragon looks like he's enjoying watching the traffic.

title: Detective stories
summary: There are a series of pictures here that tell a story about the man in the suit. What's this guy up to?

title: Robot man
summary: Looks like the robot man has made friends with the weird creatures to his left. Robots need friends too.

title: Nature's window
summary: Can't see the trees in the city? Check it out here.

title: Smell the art
summary: Live spray painting here if you're lucky! Otherwise come and see what you can find on these walls.

title: Al Pacino
summary: I know it's not Al, but it looks like Al.

title: Ballet school
summary: A lovely section on the joys of learning ballet.

title: Parquet man
summary: Parquet man is a connoisseur of fine coffee too. He recommends TOFWD (The Organic Food and Wine Health Store) - on the corner opposite the subway entrance. They serve Fair Trade coffee.

title: Pedestrian subway gallery
summary: Head down into the subway to check out the latest installations here. There's also a zine shop and other local fashion designers.

title: Hosier Lane
summary: Hosier Lane is the grand daddy of laneway art commissions in Melbourne. It's saturated with colourful creations. Well worth spending time looking around. Don't forget to look up every now and then!

title: Material
summary: Yes indeed, lots of material!

title: Camouflage
summary: Everything's been painted over with colourful tags and squiggles.  See if you can find the rubbish bins. They're very well camouflaged.

title: High in the sky
summary: The artists must have used a very tall ladder for this one.

title: Third eye
summary: Haven't found your third eye? No worries, there's one here.

title: Malcolm
summary: Homage the THE Malcolm. I like the way the reflection is painted on his glasses.

title: Pet viper
summary: Paynes Place and Croft Alley is full of bits and pieces of street art, including this guy's pet viper snake.

title: Dragon in car park
summary: Imagine the life of a dragon living in a car park. Not very glamorous! Maybe that's why he's hitting the can too.

title: Poetry
summary: All sorts of interesting words and ruminations.  See how many you can find (hint, don't forget to look up).

title: Look out for animals
summary: There are quite a few Echidnas and other animals about, such as the occasional Koala.

title: Boiling Point
summary: The view from boiling point is of more than 180 degrees of ocean view and is magnificent.

title: Good path
summary: The path is in very good condition and suitable for all abilities, although can get very busy at times.

title: Bush Turkeys
summary: Quite a lot of Bush Turkeys and other birdlife about.

title: Tea Tree Bay
summary: Tea Tree Bay is a beautiful little swimming and surfing spot that is quite sheltered, although the sign says swimming not advised.

title: Shady path
summary: The shady path gently meanders around the bush.

title: Dolphin Bay
summary: Looking towards Picnic Cove.

title: Path to Picnic
summary: The inclining path to Picnic Cove provides wonderful glimpses of the sea through the varied bushland.

title: Hells Gate
summary: Easy to guess why this got it's name. A beautiful spot to watch the power of the ocean.

title: View from Hells Gate
summary: Looking across to Alexandria Bay. It can get a bit wind swept here.

title: Little Creek
summary: Love these little creeks along the Bay.

title: Back towards Alexaandria Bay
summary: Sheltered little path that looks back the way you came. The path from here (after the beach) can be a bit rough.

title: Looking towards Hells Gate
summary: A great spot to sit, particularly early in the morning just after sunrise.

title: Rough Path
summary: As you can see the path is pretty rough here, so not great if you are not steady on your feet.

title: Towards Sunrise Beach
summary: On  clear day you can see for miles!

title: Steps
summary: Good concrete steps  down to Sunshine, although the last few metres of steps are bits of wood that are not very flat and even.

title: Sunshine Beach
summary: Most days there are lots of surfers to watch out on the water.

title: Patrolled Beach
summary: Looking up to the patrolled beach at the Surf Life Saving Club, its a good idea to swim between the flags.

title: Snails rule!
summary: Snails are unlikely pin-ups but here they seem to be appreciated a little more than usual.

title: Look out for cyclists
summary: This is a shared path so please keep left. Some cyclists are polite and ring their bell to let you know they\'re coming while others zoom past.

title: Knit it
summary: A few yarn bombers have been helping to decorate this area so lookout for their colourful creations.

title: North Carlton Railway Station Neighbourhood House
summary: A little sign to let you know that you can drop into the Neighbourhood House for a spot of yoga, singing, dancing and much more!

title: Playground
summary: A colourful playground to let your little ones run wild (if you've got kids to entertain).

title: Trees, shrubs and grasses
summary: Oh, there's lots of trees, shrubs and grasses. Thanks to council for making this area a gorgeous place to walk!

title: Basketball / lamp post
summary: Now that's a creative use of a lamp post!

title: An abundant nature strip
summary: Beans, herbs and flowers growing on the nature - looks good enough to eat! A lovely addition to the nature strip.

title: A funky shaped roof
summary: A curved roof, how clever!

title: Women's Dressing Pavillion
summary: Built in 1937, these unassuming brick buildings, track and jumping pit were constructed to provide specific facilities for women athletes (who were a novelty back then).

title: Recent revegetation work
summary: If you're interested in helping to help plant trees in this area, contact City of Melbourne for more information. They organise occasional tree planting days.

title: Beautiful gum trees
summary: A lovely place to sit and rest if you need a break (there are a few benches around here).

title: Royal Park train station
summary: This is the train station closest to the Zoo.

title: A map!
summary: At last, a map to show you what's around in the area. Always helpful to know what's to see and how to get there (or to find your bearings if like me, you've got a bad sense of direction).

title: Zoo entrance
summary: Fancy a tour of the zoo? Buy your tickets here.

title: State Netabll and Hockey Centre
summary: What noises can you hear from the perimeter of the Zoo? We heard low growling as we walked towards the State Netball & Hockey Centre. Lots of birds too!

title: Walking towards the grasslands
summary: Looks like the secret woods walking though this part.

title: Grasslands
summary: A great view of the city from the grasslands.

title: Birds
summary: The grasslands are a rich spot for wildlife. Here there plenty of insects and birds twittering away, looking for lunch, hanging out and doing a few fancy flights in they sky too.

title: Park pavillion
summary: It's terrific to have this park so close to the city. Even though you can hear the rumbling of the trams nearby, it's great to escape the hustle and bustle.

title: Lake
summary: This little lake attracts birds, frogs and other creatures. We saw a duck and stork on the day we visited.

title: The Walmsley House
summary: A prefabricated iron house imported from England in the 1850s to house Frank Meaker's family. Frank worked as a ranger then in various roles in the Zoo. A heritage listed house.

title: Sign to show the way to Jack's Track entrance
summary: The sign to look for

title: The entry to Jacks Track
summary: Jacks Track heads in to the bush, the old flour mill is on your right hand side.

summary: The Old Rupanyup Flour Mill

summary: Historic Sign to describe the mill

summary: Into the scrub

title: Bird Bowers
summary: There are the remnants of bird bowers as well as an abundance of wildlife in this area at times, including Kangaroos, Wallabies and many parrots etc.

title: A bench seat for a rest
summary: A bench seat for a rest

title: A good track condition
summary: A good track condition in a wonderful scrub area

summary: There is a long avenue below gum trees that shade in summer and lighten the rain in winter

title: Plenty of seating along the walk
summary: The seating is in good condition

summary: There is a left turn as there is a channel for water into some ponds that stops the walk here.

summary: The historical sign explaining the project here

summary: There is another seat to rest here

summary: The Rupanyup Golf Club is off to the right of this track and if you play, seek a few rounds here.

summary: The yard of tractors almost marks the end of your walk

title: Public Toilets
summary: There are clean and tidy brick toilets on the corner of Walter and Cromie (main) Streets.

title: Boydy's Take Away
summary: A take away for all those drinks etc..

summary: The main point of presence in Rupanyup

summary: Entrance to the Rupanyup Recreation Reserve, walk in past the hut and turn right

summary: The Rupanyup Community Centre, Netball Hall, Grandstand and Showgrounds buildings beside the oval, walk to the middle of the buildings where the driveway leads through

summary: Take the main driveway around the oval.

title: Spurling House, 38 Black St (1888)
summary: The Spurling House is the only known Melbourne design by Sydney based architect John Horbury Hunt, who was a figure of controversy in his time due to his innovative and daring new designs.

title: 7 Bleazby Ave (2005). John Tallis
summary: The philosophy behind the corrugated iron is that it wraps the inside spaces, as if protecting the family, with the timber-clad forms inside this metal skin.

title: Heazelwood, 66 Wilson Street (1891)
summary: Built as a residence for Brighton's Health Officer, Cornelius Casey M.D., Heazelwood was one of many Victorian era houses in the Brighton area to adopt elements of the Queen Anne style.

title: 26 Halifax St, Brighton (1878)
summary: Robert Wright, a successful miner from the Ballarat goldfields, built the first stage of this house, then became bankrupt the next year.

title: 166-168 Church St (1890)
summary: Rrumoured to be built for two sisters, there are only a few two-storey semi-detached residences in Brighton and these are  a sophisticated example of the Italianate style.

title: 161 Church St (1885)
summary:
Built by successful Melbourne stationer Alfred Harston as a family residence, the house features a tower with
a 'widow's walk' (the topmost lookout).

title: 167 Church St (1886)
summary: Calabria's asymmetrical facade is emphasised by a two- storey cast-iron verandah containing Gothic motifs in its lacework. From 1900-07, Emma A'Beckett (1838-1906) lived in this grand house.

title: 76-90 Church St (1888-89)
summary: Munro's Buildings consist of seven two-storey rendered brick shops, with a central laneway.  The original shop fronts have all been altered, but the facades of the upper level remain intact.

title: 71-73 Church St (1912)
summary: Brighton\'s former post office uses bold chromatic brickwork; the distinctive stucco and brick porch is unusual, with its strong position on the corner.

title: Former Congregational Church, 17 Black St (1875)
summary: The former Congregational Church is a superb example of an Early English-inspired Gothic church expressed in bichromatic brick. Designed by Charles Webb and built by James Bonham.

title: 58 Carpenter St (pre 1859)
summary: The first Brighton rate books are dated 1859, and no. 58 was already firmly established as a house and brewery. It is one of the few houses remaining that pre-date the rate books.

title: 37 Black St
summary: Wyuna, one of Brighton's stunning villas, features a wealth of decorative detail, a return verandah, and projecting bay windows on two sides.

title: Yolinko Reserve
summary: The Boardwalk meanders through some wonderful wetlands.  Along the way you will be seneraded by the frogs in chorus.

title: Wetlands
summary: The wetlands in the evening sunlight.  Magical.

title: Rowing on the river
summary: The river has a long history with rowing from the late 1800s to the present day.

title: Birdlife
summary: Keep an eye out for Purple Swamphens.  They are primarily waders and feed mostly on young shoots of reeds and other aquatic plants.

title: The Edge Cafe
summary: Entrance to the Edge Cafe.  A good spot to have some lunch on route.  It can also be used as the start/end point of the walk.

title: Walking along the river
summary: Walkers enjoying a well maintained paved pathway surrounded by flora on both sides of the path.

title: The Barwon River
summary: The Barwon River rises in the Otway Ranges of Victoria, Australia, runs through Winchelsea and the city of Geelong, where it is joined by the Moorabool River, and enters the sea at Barwon Heads

title: Canoe Crossing
summary: Watch out for the canoes at this junction.  But don't worry, they are usually accompanied by their owners.

title: Picnic Spot
summary: An excellent covered lunch spot by the riverside.

title: Ducks by the river
summary: Along this section you might spot Australian Wood Ducks searching for lunch on the banks of the river. It's short bill with serrated cutting edges is great for grazing.

title: Boardwalk
summary: The boardwalk near Queens Bridge.  Great views of the river, the bridge and the riverside vegetation.

title: Queens Bridge
summary: The bridge was first the site of a punt, with a wooden cattle crossing not being built until 1861.The bridge collapsed in the 1870 flood, with a new wooden bridge opened in 1872.

title: The present Queens Bridge
summary:
The present Queens Bridge
The current one lane steel bridge was built in 1930, a water main and footpath being added to the side in 1963

title: Shared cycle/pedestrian path
summary: The path is a shared cycle/pedestrian path.

title: Darter bird
summary: If the sun is out you might spot a Darter bird drying it's wings on the banks of the river.

title: Playground
summary: The playground is built on a large mound, giving it a "volcano" theme. It is modern and well designed, with swings, slides and shade sails, BBQ, toilets, and fitness equipment.

title: Snakes
summary: Being on the creek, there are reptiles! Snakes are shy creatures that will avoid you if they can. If you see one, don't disturb it and it will leave you alone. They are also protected under law.

title: Panoramic Views
summary: Enjoy sweeping views from the top of the mound across the Keilor Plains to Mt Macedon and Gisborne.

title: Birds
summary: There are always interesting birds to be seen here. Flame Robins, Whistling Kites, Pipits are among the frequent visitors. This is a Willy-Wagtail that stopped to see what we were doing.

title: Kororoit Creek
summary: Rises near Gisborne and enters Port Phillip Bay at Altona. It flows through the volcanic plains and has areas of great beauty.

title: The Special Tree
summary: This magnificent River Red Gum would be at least 500 years old. It sits on a bend of the creek, on a rocky escarpment, above a pool in remnant grassland and it is the most magical place here.

title: Cultural Heritage
summary: People have been visiting here for thousands of years. The nearby Maribyrnong has sites dated to possibly 45,000 years, and here probably as long!

title: Kororoit Creek 2
summary: Beautiful.

title: Crossing
summary: There are several places where you can cross and walk around in the grassland on the opposite bank. It is weedier but you can still find patches of remnant vegetation.

title: Waterbirds
summary: There are plenty of waterbirds, but please don't feed them bread. It doesn't agree with them.

title: Path
summary: North of the playground the path is "informal" and can be rocky and muddy.

title: The Upper Path
summary: The upper path takes you along the top of the escarpment and past peoples back (or some times , front)  fences.

title: The Grassland Reserve
summary: Grasslands are critically endangered. This area is being cared for by weed control, burning and revegetation. In Spring it is a mass of  wildflowers. Cup Day would be a good day to come for a look.

title: wide gravel track through the bush
summary: easy walking for little kids

title: walking track crosses road
summary: be aware that the track does cross over a road here. It is rare to come across traffic but  kids need to be warned before approaching this intersection

title: dogs are allowed
summary: you can take dogs to the You Yangs if they remain on the lead

title: woodfire bBQs
summary: a great place for a sausage sizzle or just to toast marshmallows for the kids!

title: Cubby Houses
summary: come and play in the cubbies that other people have made or come and make your own

title: nature's playground
summary: these boulders are great fun for kids to climb, explore and use their imaginations

title: nature's playground
summary: a great place to explore , climb and learn

title: Turtle
summary: If you look closely you will see a turtle sitting in the middle of the pond.

title: Lakeside Bistro
summary: The Lakeside Bistro offers a great view of the Japanese Garden.

title: Japanese Garden
summary: The Japanese Garden is a peaceful place to rest or have your lunch in the shelter overlooking the waterfall.

title: Tamarin
summary: Tamarins are very cute and fascinating to watch as they interact with each other. In the wild they are classified as ‘critically endangered’.

title: Meerkat lookout
summary: Stay a while at the meerkat enclosure. It is fascinating to watch the furry creatures stand up on their hind legs as lookouts then scramble underground to burrow. They never stop still!

title: Giant tortoise
summary: Aldabra Giant Tortoises are classed as ‘vulnerable’ on the endangered list and are currently protected but suffer from poaching and loss of traditional habitat in the wild.

title: Lemurs
summary: Lemur Island hosts the irresistible ring-tailed lemurs in a new exhibit.

title: Pygmy hippopotamus
summary: Hippopotamus means ‘river horse’ but their closest relatives are actually whales and dolphins!

title: Pelicans
summary: The pelican's long beak and large throat pouch is used for catching prey and draining water from the scooped up contents.

title: Butterfly House
summary: The Butterfly House is a fascinating place to study all shapes, sizes and colours of the flighty creatures. If you have the right colour on they may land on you.

title: Elephants
summary: The two baby elephants at the zoo are very playful.

title: Orang-utans
summary: It is hard to know who is observing whom at the orang-utan enclosure. They seem as interested in us as we are in their comical behaviour.

title: Giraffes
summary: The giraffe is the tallest living terrestrial animal and the largest ruminant.

title: Zebra
summary: Each zebra's stripes are as unique as fingerprints—no two are exactly alike.

title: Great Flight Aviary
summary: The stately Jabirus in the Great Flight Aviary make a handsome couple.

title: Wombat
summary: Wombats are solid and stocky, have short legs and large front feet and bear-like claws.

title: Emus
summary: Emus cannot fly but they can run up to 40-50km per hour.

title: Baboon
summary: The baboons' custom-built enclosure recreates the environment of the north-east African savannah.

title: Tapir
summary: Tapirs look something like pigs with trunks, but they are actually related to horses and rhinoceroses.

title: Peccary
summary: Peccaries are the only native wild species of pigs.

title: churchill national park
summary: Main picnic area: this popular picnic area was created in the late 1970s, with shelters, toilets, and powered barbecues. It is sometimes crowded on weekends, but much  quieter on week days

title: bellbird corner
summary: This aqueduct was created by horse power in the 1930s to feed nearby Lysterfield reservoir. This gully is one of the more moist spots upon this level, easy section of this walk

title: where aqueducts meet
summary: This siphon marks the point where a second aqueduct from a spring in the hills to the north fed into the main aqueduct. We can't follow the aqueduct here, but pick it up a little further on

title: The upper aqueduct
summary: The northern aqueduct is more overgrown, but the west embankment provides a reasonably clear course for the short distance of 250 metres. There are fine views to the north and west

title: Dandenong Shire  quarry
summary: This disused quarry only operated from 1913 to 1917, and provided Dandenong Shire Council with road metal via a narrow gauge 3 km horse-drawn tramway thru the Police Paddocks to Stud Road

title: crest of the range
summary: The actual summit is slightly north of the track on private property, but even from the fence line there are excellent views in the direction of the city, and also wildlife in the mornings and evening

title: stonemasons track
summary: The name of this track is literal. Beside the trail can be seen evidence of small scale quarrying, and the brick remains of buildings where the stonemasons lived and worked more than 100 years ago

title: flagpole
summary: This rusty flagpole is a link to Australia's darkest hour. In 1941, a military camp was hurriedly set up here to stop a Japanese invasion of Melbourne. Its commander, Col. George Knox, had it moved

title: Back on the aqueduct
summary: This is the east end of the main aqueduct we picked up 5 km earlier. The flat walking trail is an easy return route to the main picnic area, though there is much traffic noise from the nearby road

title: Centenary Park
summary: Access the start/ finish of the Cherry Walk from Centenary Park. Just a short walk from the town centre.

title: Swimming in the Ovens
summary: You can also take some time to enjoy the lovely river, or use the waterslide or diving board.

title: Big4Bright Holiday park
summary: The path continues along the back of the Big4 Holiday Park on Mountbatten Ave.

title: Bright Memorial Arboretum
summary: This is a wonderful park and garden area with a variety of plants and trees. Great spot to picnic. There are some lovely vistas over the river and across the valley.

title: Arboretum sign
summary: This sign tells more about the types of trees in the Arboretum. Have a quick read.

title: Arboretum entrance
summary: This is another good spot from which to access this walk. And note, there are free "poop bags"available to assist in cleaning up after your dog.

title: Bridge across the Ovens
summary: Find this bridge to cross the Ovens and return via the north side of the river. It is easy to find and well marked from the walking path.

title: Back Germantown Rd back to the walking path
summary: Continue along the road until you see the river path access again. Easy to find.

title: Bridge at Centenary Park
summary: At this point you can cross the bridge to return to the starting point or continue along the well marked Cherry Walk route.

title: Tirhatuan Park
summary: The park forms part of the Dandenong Creek vegetation corridor, providing important habitat for our native flora and fauna.

title: The path around the lake
summary: The two lakes in the park are home to many species of birds and natural vegetation.

title: Boardwalk
summary: Stop here for a spot of wildlife watching.

title: Water Kites
summary: This sculpture was selected by local residents to celebrate the parks many uses and to complement its natural beauty.

title: Another Playground
summary: This park boasts two playgrounds!

title: The jetty
summary: Its special to be so close to the water birds.

title: Purple swamp Hen
summary: The birds also enjoy a stroll in the sunshine.  Imagine walking with those big toes!

title: Wetland Birds
summary: The Pacific Black Duck and white domestic duck soaking it up.

title: Playground
summary: Designed and created with input from local residents and primary school students, it looks really fun!

title: Anderson to Kilcunda
summary: Start of the Walk

title: Bass Strait
summary: Cape Woolamai is in the distance.

title: Bass Coast Rail Trail
summary: Bass Coast Rail Trail

title: Mitchell Coal Mine Mullock Heap
summary: The remains of the Mitchell Coal Mine

title: Black Head
summary: Near Kilcunda

title: Interesting Rock Formation
summary: Near Kilcunda

title: Hooded Plovers
summary: A pair of Hooded Plovers

title: Bass Coast Rail Trail
summary: Wooden Trestle Bridge

title: Mob of Kangaroos
summary: Near Bass Coast Rail Trail

title: Kilcunda Coastal Reserve
summary: Kilcunda Coastal Reserve

title: Beautiful semi-rural surrounds
summary: The scenery quickly changes after stepping off the Princes Highway to become a beautiful and tranquil semi-rural setting.

title: Cross the road here
summary: At this point the ‘new’ path stops – to continue you need to cross the road and head north along the footpath on the other side of Toomuc Valley Road.

title: Tranquil Toomuc Creek
summary: The Toomuc Creek is a lovely little meandering creek which starts up near the Cardinia Reservoir.

title: There are lots of seats along the way
summary: There are many nice spots to rest those weary legs.

title: Underneath the canopy
summary: It is great to be hidden from the busy streetscape under the native tree canopy.

title: So many birds of all shapes and sizes
summary: If you stop and look up you will be amazed just how many birds there are to see!

title: First half of the walk is along a nice new concrete path
summary: First half of the walk is along a nice new concrete path.

title: Welcome to the Community Greenhouse Corridor
summary: The walk starts right next to the Princes Highway, or it can be an extension of the Toomuc Creek Trail existing south of the highway.

title: The path is a mix of grass, concrete and gravel
summary: The path is a mix of grass, concrete and gravel. The first half of the walk is a concrete path and well suited to prams and wheelchairs.

title: Careful crossing the side strees
summary: There are a number of side streets that need to be crossed, make sure you look both ways!

title: Tick Bush
summary: First stop. Look for the tick bush, an evergreen shrub. Its flowers usually  appear from September to December. Did they flower earlier? Check it out

title: Flannel Flower
summary: Out of the track, you will have the chance to observe the Actinotus Helianthi. Don't forget to upload the pictures you take on the ClimateWatch app.

title: Gymea Lily
summary: Continuing on the path, you are going to see  a giant tussock-like, rosette plant.  They can reach 5m high with the flower stalk.!

title: White Cedar
summary: The White Cedar is one of only a few native Australian plants that are seasonally deciduous, although many species drop their leaves during droughts.

title: Fuchsia Heath
summary: Fuchsia Heath's flowers are long and tubular, some of them have pink-red tubed and white lobes, others are white. Spot them!

title: Red Spider Flower
summary: You might ask what is this? It's not a spider. It is a bright red, occasionally pink flower. Its spider appearance  explains its name. Keep recording for ClimateWatch app!

title: Frogs
summary: Listen for frogs. The link below will help you to recognize them and to catalouge them. Have fun!

title: Silky Oak
summary: This giant tree is just past the cafe. Silky Oaks aren't related to other oak trees at all but are actually a species of Grevilla and are very popular with birds!

title: Firewheel Tree
summary: This beautiful native tree on your righ has striking red flowers. Are they out today?

title: Braybrook Community Hub
