summary: This state of the art Hub features a new library, community centre and spaces, community health services, maternal and child health services, early years centre, Men's Shed and  optometry services.

title: Braybrook Park
summary: Braybrook Park offers the community a peaceful place to walk and take in some fresh air.  Take friends and family, kick the footy or enjoy a picnic on the grass.

title: Paul Sadler Swimland Braybrook
summary: Paul Sadler Swimland has received many awards in Australia and USA, including the induction of Paul Sadler into the Australian Swim Coaches and Teachers' Association Hall of Fame. Call while it's hot!

title: Kinder Smith Playground
summary: Kinder Smith Reserve has been given a face lift, with a new concrete walking path around the oval, and fresh landscaping. The local young children will love this exciting new playground!

title: RecWest Braybrook
summary:
At RecWest Braybrook there is something for everyone in the community.
Owned by the Maribyrnong City Council and managed by YMCA Victoria, RecWest offers sport-based activities and programs for all.

title: GreenWORKS! Mural
summary: The GreenWORKS! project, a successful council and community collaboration, provides a strong connection between the built environment, the natural world and the place the Braybrook locals call home.

title: Kinder Smith Reserve
summary: Are you a team player? Kinder Smith Reserve is home to Sunshine Football Club, Sunshine YCW Cricket Club and RecWest Braybrook. Contact RecWest for enquiries about netball, basketball or futsal.

title: Blue Bamboo Vietnamese Restaurant and Cafe
summary: Try a selection of delicious dishes from the menu and discover the tropical paradise out the back. You will want to go back for more!

title: Regulations
summary: The Conglomerate Gully Flora Reserve has its own set of legislative regulations!  They ar eposted on a sign near the start of the walk.

title: Information board
summary: An information board near the start of the walk gives a summary of the history, ecology and geology of the reserve.

title: Hollow tree
summary: This hollow tree stands by the side of the path.  Great for hide and seek.

title: Fallen log
summary: In a number of places, particularly this part of the walk, large fallen logs or trees are a feature.  They make good seats for adults and excellent play equipment for children!

title: Hut
summary: This interesting hut provides shelter - and curiosity.

title: Lookout
summary: The track starts to climb alongside a small gorge, with a stream flowing through it after rain or at wetter times of the year.  A lookout provides this view down the gorge.

title: Climbing
summary: The climb starts to get steep in this area, but that only adds to the sense of accomplishment.  Keep an eye on any under 5s though.

title: A taste of NT
summary: At times the landscape in this area is reminiscent of the northern territory, with woodland on the rocky escarpment.

title: Cascades
summary: The stream falls down the gorge, with a series of small waterfalls after rain.  The wetter it has been, the better they are. Unfortunately, was dry at the time of our visit.

title: Pools
summary: Even at the driest times, small pools remain in the streambed.  They appear to harbour life, but I'm not an entymologist.

title: Clearing
summary: At the highest point in the walk, you reach a clearing next to the stream above one of the waterfalls.

title: Burnt tree
summary: Old burnt trees and stumps are a reminder that this area has high risk of bushfire.  In the summer, check the fire risk for the day before visiting.  Do not come on a day of total fire ban.

title: Rocks and lichen
summary: In this area particularly, rocks with coloured lichen will reward those who look carefully.

title: It's only grass
summary: Native grass dominates at ground level in Conglomerate Gully.

title: Waves of grass
summary: At times the native grass seems to be rolling down the hill in waves.

title: Native forest
summary: The interplay of native trees, grass and fallen logs is perhaps the defining feature of this walk.

title: Wildlife
summary: Wildlife on this walk is not used to humans and will typically move away from you - making it difficult to photograph!  Thanks to digital enhancement, you can make out this currawong.

title: Water Tower
summary: The Water Tower is one of a few peppered around the district. Built in 1957, the tower provides water pressure for thousands of homes across the urban area and has the capacity to store 2.7 megalitres

title: 158 Orange Avenue
summary: The building is now the Guide Hall, but originally was home to the Seventh Day Adventists, and  following that the Lutheran Church. The Church outgrew the site in 1966 when two congregations merged.

title: “Valetta” 223 Eleventh St
summary: Built 1891 and believed to be designed by D.T. Edmunds who supervised construction of Rio Vista.  Valetta is on the corner of Henderson Place and two pillars at its entrance mark the little street.

title: Mildura Primary Schoo
summary: Opened on September 13, 1890 with 300 eager students, despite the building not yet being complete. A year later, once all works were finished, Mildura Primary was official opened.

title: Proudfoot House
summary: Built 1891 for John Proudfoot who owned a produce store in Mildura. This fine example of a late Victorian brick house was later the Presbyterian Manse for many years, before moving into private hands.

title: Magnolia Avenue
summary: There are still a number of attractive homes in this street but sadly many have been lost.

title: Lemon Avenue
summary: Few streets in Mildura have retained their identity as well as Lemon Ave. This area was the tradesmen’s class and 3 of the houses along Lemon Avenue predate 1900 and another 14 are pre World War I

title: 50 Lemon Ave
summary: A good example of the simple Edwardian Style. Currently a backpackers’ hostel, but its original owner was A.C Pugsley, who commissioned the home in 1902.

title: Kathleen Kelly Kindergarten
summary:
Originally started down by the river, Kathleen Kelly Kindergarten was founded by 
Kathleen Kelly  (a member of the Bowring family) as a free kindergarten for children.

title: Mildura Settlers Club
summary: The ‘Setts’ as it’s commonly referred to, has been on this site since 1893. A prominent club until 1993, the 'Setts' is now  a modern office space,  popular bar, restaurant and function centre .

title: 77 Orange Avenue
summary: Original Methodist Parsonage and was designed by William Sheridan and built in 1892. It’s an unusual example of a Tudoresque Victorian brick villa.

title: Tea Tree tunnel
summary: A little after the start of the track is some beautifully gnarled Tea Trees that make the path look like a bit like a tunnel.

title: Tidal River footbridge
summary: From the path you can see the Tidal River footbridge. Cross the bridge to go to the tracks to Squeaky, Mt Bishop or other great walks.

title: First seat
summary: The is the first of a few seats that have been installed long the track. wonderful to sit and watch for a while.

title: Hello wombat
summary: If you take the walk at dusk you have a reasonable chance of coming across a wombat. Please don't feed the animals!

title: The Boadwalk
summary: From here on the track is a Boardwalk until the last little bit.

title: The first viewing platform
summary: There are three viewing platforms along the track that often used by people fishing.

title: The bend
summary: The boardwalk gets very close to the river at the first bend.

title: To Mt Obernon
summary: Fantastic view to My Oberon and the third viewing platform along the river.

title: View from the last platform
summary: Great view up the river from the final viewing platform.

title: Away from the river
summary: The quietest spot of the walk as you head away from the river.

title: Banksia stump
summary: Love this gnarly old stump, wonder what animals live inside?

title: Picnic tables
summary: Two picnic tables can be found next the boardwalk.

title: Oh dear!
summary: Unfortunately the Prom is being invaded by some pests, including feral deer that come to the river to drink.

title: Back into Tea Tree
summary: The final section of the boardwalk goes through a relatively youngish planting of Tea Trees.

title: Start at Coomoora Woodland on Serpentine Road
summary: There are many ways to access Coomoora Woodland. It's even on the walking/cycle trail along the Dandenong Bypass. This suburban street is a quieter access point.

title: Choose your own adventure!
summary: There are paths in Coomoora Woodland but none are signposted. It's not a huge reserve, so don't worry about getting lost. Instead, look up and take in the sounds of the birdlife above.

title: Home to endangered species
summary: Coomoora Woodland is home to a number of threatened and endangered species; the swift parrot, grey-headed flying fox and growling grass frog have all been spotted here.

title: Short cut
summary: There's a path along the back fences of houses that's good for bikes and short cuts. It takes you from the Serpentine Road entrance to the Coomoora Reserve sports ovals.

title: Sporting ovals
summary: If you fancy a run around, there's an oval here that's perfect for playing in. Cross the oval to reach Coomoora Road.

title: Dandenong Bypass walking/cycling pathway
summary: It's harder to hear the birds from the Woodlands here, with the whoosh of traffic flying by. Continue a little further to get back to the peace and quiet.

title: Coomoora Cricket Club
summary: At the time of writing this building was still under construction (November 2015). It may offer public toilets and drinking fountains in the future. Stay tuned!

title: Playground
summary: Small people might like to stop for a play before leaving Coomoora Reserve and heading out into the suburb. There are also bench seats and picnic tables nearby.

title: A detour through the suburbs
summary: Walk past the Keysborough Primary School and turn left onto Darren Road. You'll pass a milk bar along the way, if you need refreshments. Turn left at Harold Street.

title: Alex Nelson Reserve
summary: This sports ground and local reserve offers a playground and shade for sitting. There's a pavilion and ovals for sports fans to enjoy.

title: A lovely path through Alex Wilkie area
summary: Walk between the Alex Wilkie reserve lands. This public path will take you from Alex Nelson reserve to Mackay Street. Be sure to breathe in the scented bushland and look up for chattering birdlife.

title: Alex Wilkie Nature Reserve entrance
summary: Enter the Alex Wilkie Nature Reserve here on Mackay Street. This educational and cultural nature reserve is open on Fridays (9-3pm) and every third Sunday (10-5pm). Note, it is closed June to August.

title: Remnant bushland
summary: The Alex Wilkie Nature Reserve is a parcel of land that was bought by the Springvale South Community Association in 1950. Since then it has been protected. Join the ranger for a guided  bush walk.

title: Scented trail
summary: As you walk towards Mackay Street, take a breath in and smell the scented walk that's on your right. It's a separate trail in the Alex Wilkie nature reserve designed to engage all of the senses.

title: Play in the nearby park
summary: As you walk towards Springvale Road, there's another lovely park tucked behind the Mackay Street Centre. This park takes you south into suburban streets.

title: Where next?
summary: Walk or catch the 902 bus back to Coomoora Woodland, grab a bite to eat on Springvale Road or from the IGA, or cross Springvale Road and continue walking in Spring Valley Park on the other side.

title: Belgrave Station Sign
summary: Hop off at Belgrave station to begin your walk. Belgrave is a Zone 2 station easily accessible from the city.

title: Puffing Billy
summary: If you're in luck, you might catch the Puffing Billy leaving the station!

title: Puffing Billy tracks
summary: Cross the train tracks, carefully of course and preferably not in the path of an oncoming steam train.

title: National Parks sign
summary: A sure sign that you're on the right path!

title: Gate at start of Coles Ridge Track
summary: Your walk in the Dandenongs starts here! The gate at the start of Coles Ridge Track leads you in the right direction. Don't forget to breathe in the fresh air.

title: Coles Ridge Track
summary: The trees along this area are particularly scenic, particularly in the morning light.

title: Lots of signs
summary: No chance of getting lost in the woods with these many signs pointing you in the right direction.

title: Walking along the track
summary: More ferns and dappled sunlight on leaves.

title: Beautiful views
summary: Beautiful views all along the walk. A perfect spot to stop and see if you can hear the resident lyrebirds.

title: Even more beautiful views
summary: If only forests like these were all over Victoria!

title: Heading towards the end of the walk
summary: Make sure you fill your lungs with as much forest air as you can before leaving the park. Better still, come back for another visit soon!

title: Leave a message
summary: A lovely idea! Write or draw a message for the next person to see.

title: Snakes and ladders
summary: Come and play snakes and ladders! This is a colourful and fun way to play on the street.  Grown ups can play too :)

title: All creatures great and small
summary: Which animals can you find? Come along to see which creatures have been visiting the area.

title: Hopscotch
summary: Hop into it and show us your best moves.

title: Sports walk
summary: Can you name all the different sports show in this section? Can you name the sports people that play each of these games?

title: Track your numbers
summary: Maybe this is a numbers game?

title: Where the wild things grow
summary: Can you name all these animals? I think they\'re all native to Australia.  And what\'s that harvester doing amongst it all?

title: Track your numbers
summary: Is this a counting game? Make your own game up if you like.

title: Brimbank City Council
summary: This walk is proudly brought to you by Brimbank City Council.

title: Lucknow - Eastwood Supermarket Carpark
summary: Start the walk at the Lucknow - Eastwood Supermarket Carpark

title: Cross Howitt Avenue where safe to do so..
summary: Look out for cars near the supermarket carpark and cross where the school children cross for the Lucknow Primary School.

title: Enter the park where the busses turn to collect the Lucknow Primary School Students.
summary: The entry of the park starts at the bus turn area

title: Alfred Howitt Community Hall
summary: The Alfred Howitt Community Hall is where to cross the Balmoral Cres.

title: The new Alfred Howitt Memorial Hall
summary: A wonderful hall

title: The staircase
summary: This is the stairway to heaven

title: Baarton Place has a walk that cuts through the parks
summary: Take the footpath and walking path through the park and Barton Place

title: Wetlands
summary: There are some wonderful wetland full of birdlife here

title: Wetlands and footbridges
summary: Wonderful wetlands here and a few picnic spots

title: a few water crossings
summary: The Backwater from the Mitchel River is here

title: Picnic Point
summary: A lovely spot for a picnic

title: Fishing platform
summary: Fishing platform are down the side of the Mitchell River Backwater and Bream are found here..

title: Huge old gum trees here
summary: There are some wonderful old gum trees in this park on this walk

title: Finns Road footpath is 2.5 metres wide all the way
summary: Finns Road footpath is 2.5 metres wide all the way

title: Interesting tea tree growth and creek flow
summary: A pleasant boardwalk through tea trees and a creek

title: A great picnic spot here
summary: Fancy  a picnic?

title: More wetland areas with tons of cormorants and ibis and other water birds
summary: More wetland areas with tons of cormorants and ibis and other water birds

title: Lovely walks under cover
summary: There are a number of picnic tables under cover on this walk

title: Easy walking along the footpaths
summary: The footpaths are wide and very good (concrete)

title: The Nature Walk Car Park- a Heart Foundation Park Walk
summary: Surrounded by black box, redgum and river cooba trees, sets the scene for this nature walk.

title: First view of the Billabong
summary: The Billabong is a birdwatchers paradise. View the Australian Pelicans, herons, black swans and a variety of ducks.

title: Walking track across the dam wall.
summary: Kings Billabong took its name from the Indigenous word for still water-billabong. Local Indigenous people have enjoyed the Billabong's self supporting food supply for thousands of years.

title: Discover native wildlife up close.
summary: Walk or cycle in this dirt track through healthy woodland.

title: Native flowers in abundance along the Billabong bank
summary: Delightful flowers spread through out the bushland offering fantastic photo opportunities.

title: Old Pump House viewed across the water
summary: The Chaffey brothers selected Kings Billabong at the central water supply to establish the Mildura Irrigation Settlement.. Many trees were felled to feed the boilers of the steam powered pumps.

title: The Bird Hide
summary: Take a picnic and relax and enjoy the delightful views.

title: Bird Hide View
summary: A spectacular display of free flying birds perched peacefully on fallen trees.

title: Sit and ponder
summary: The track creates a loop and you commence your return.

title: One last  look before you cross the dam wall.
summary: This Park Walk is nearly at an end but your exploration of Kings Billabong Wildlife Reserve has only just began.

title: Starting off
summary: The walk is wonderful from the first steps!

title: Venus Baths
summary: Venus Baths is a picturesque area with a fresh water lake and many unusual rock formations. It is a wonderful spot to dip your feet in the water on a hot day.

title: Magnificent views
summary: Walking over the stoney outcrop gives some great views, and can be very windy on blowy days. Hold on to your hat!

title: Wildflowers
summary: In Spring there are a glorious array of wildflowers along the walk.

title: Orchid alert
summary: Look out for orchids!

title: Splitter Falls
summary: Take the small detour to see Splitter Falls, it's worth it!

title: The bridge
summary: Cross the bridge, but stop and look at the creek..

title: The steps
summary: The track is full of wonderful surprises, like these steps.

title: Wonderland carpark sign
summary: Stay left, don't go to Wonderland carpark, it's only a car park!

title: Grand Canyon
summary: The aptly named Grand Canyon is a very impressive rock formation.

title: Cool Chamber
summary: The Cool Chamber is as it sounds, a nice little spot to stop on a hot day.

title: Bridal Veil Falls
summary: Just the ticket of a warm day, stand under the little falls to cool off.

title: Silent Street
summary: Another pretty impressive park of the walk.

title: View to Lake Bellfield
summary: Looking down to the lake which is a local water supply and is about 5km from Halls Gap.

title: To Halls Gap
summary: Its a pretty spectacular view that is worth the walk!

title: The way down
summary: The start of the walk back down towards Halls Gap is a bit of a clamber over rocks, but once you are on the track it is well marked.

title: Over the rocks
summary: Keep going over the rocks. Once you get past the rocks its quicker to descend the mountain than it was to climb!

title: The steps
summary: There a few long sets of metal steps on the way down that makes it a bit easier to walk and to protect the bush.

title: Albert Park Primary School
summary: A great idea - a primary school playground that is open to all on weekends.

title: Jock's ice-cream shop
summary: Jock's is famous for its ice-cream - worth a visit either on your way to or from the beach.

title: Fairy Tree
summary: A delight at any time but lit with fairy lights (of course!) at night around Christmas!

title: Gasworks Park
summary: There are artists studios, a theatre and a cafe. Every 3rd Saturday there is a Farmers' Market.  In the park you'll also come across various wonderful sculptures and installations.

title: Station Pier
summary: Cross Beaconsfield Pde, head onto the beach, take your shoes and socks off and go for a paddle.

title: Plum Garland Playground
summary: Another favourite with our kids!

title: Reserve Entrance
summary: At the entrance to the reserve there is a small car park.

title: Start of the walk
summary: At the start of the walk, follow the sign to the picnic and BBQ area.

title: Reserve Map
summary: When you reach the aging reserve map, turn right and follow the Hakea Circle path to Acacia Walk.

title: Spreading Wattle
summary: This wattle has needle leaves. Its lemon-cream globular flower-heads brighten the forest during the Spring season.

title: Austral Bracken
summary: It is easy to find Austral Bracken which can out-compete other plants to form a dense understorey. It creates a humid microclimate under its leaves and is food for a variety of native insects.

title: Local housing development
summary: This bird box has a fairly small hole which would suit the White-throated Treecreeper, the Red-browed Treecreeper, the Feathertail Glider and the Sugar Glider amongst others.

title: Common Hovea
summary: Keep an eye out for interesting shrubs along the route.  The Common Hovea is a slender shrub, native to Australia. The upper leaves are narrow and long while the lower leaves are oval-shaped.

title: Look up
summary: It is worth stopping to appreciate the wonderful canopy overhead and the endless shades of green on show.  It is also a good opportunity to spot some of the 88 local species of birdlife darting about.

title: Abundant flora
summary: 336 species of indigenous plants have been recorded in the Reserve.  Every visit to the reserve is rewarded by new discoveries!

title: Bushy Needlewood
summary: The prickly foliage of these understorey plants provides safe nesting sites for small birds and also provides nectar for native bees.

title: Walking among the trees
summary: Trees along the walk include Stringybark and  the 60m high Mountain Grey gums

title: Sumner Park
summary: Home of the Brunswick Zebras and general community play area. Often see many dogs running around here too.

title: Bridge across to Merri Park
summary: You could take a quick detour over the bridge, there is a children's playground.

title: Kirkdale Street Park
summary: Features a recently upgraded children's playground (people have left toys to share in the sandpit!) and replanted, landscaped area.

title: Wales Quarry litter trap
summary: A unique purpose built litter trap (built by Nick from CERES) that looks like a sculpture when not in use. Link below is to videos of it in action that were taken on a school excursion.

title: Bench at path to Ceres.
summary: If you haven't been, a visit to CERES Community Environmental Park is definitely worth the detour (has food and drinks too).

title: The path
summary: The path drops down close the Creek.

title: Russian Orthodox Church
summary: A magnificent looking building, particularly when the sun shines on the spires.

title: Brunswick velodrome
summary: The velodrome has recently been improved and it is open to the public so you can see all sorts of people riding around. It is also the home of the Brunswick Cycling Club.

title: One of many seats
summary: A welcome seat on a warm day (there are other seats along the path)

title: Shady path
summary: A nice stretch of shady path.

title: Harding Street Bridge
summary: Great example of a suspension bridge. Cyclists are supposed to walk their bikes, like this respectful young chap, but be warned some don't and it's very narrow.

title: Farmgate: Merri Creek Market Garden
summary: Don't know anything about this urban farm but, it always good to look at what is being grown.

title: Retaining wall
summary: The  retaining wall is quite beautiful, it's bit like a sculpture.

title: New bridge
summary: This new bridge is a very welcome addition to the path, it is quite long and has a few dog legs which makes it interesting.

title: Big pool
summary: Most of the creek is quite narrow apart from this big pool. Don't know if anyone ever swims in it but it looks a little inviting.

title: Coburg Olympic Swimming Pool
summary: If it is a hot day, bring your togs and stop off at the pool for a swim!

title: Coburg Lake Reserve
summary: A popular park offering a great variety of activities including picnicking, playgrounds, barbecue facilities and nature play all set in a beautiful heritage setting.

title: Newport Park
summary: Walking path through park to skate ramp and children's playground.

title: Skate ramp
summary: Skate ramp in Newport Park

title: Children's playground
summary: Children's playground

title: Newport Park Athletics Facility
summary: Newport Park Athletics Facility with Newport Power station chimney in the background.

title: The Gatehouse
summary: The Gatehouse was once part of the original Newport Power Station

title: HMAS Yarra Memorial
summary: HMAS Yarra Memorial commemorates service in WW2.

title: The Warmies
summary: The Warmies is a popular fishing spot. Newport Power Station pumps out warm water that attracts fish.

title: Riverside Park
summary: Riverside Park is another popular fishing spot and a great place to view the ships in the Yarra River.

title: Scienceworks
summary: Scienceworks is a great day out. From the walking path the original pumping station is what you're looking at.

title: The Punt jetty
summary: The Punt takes bike riders and pedestrians across the Yarra River to Port Melbourne.

title: West Gate Memorial Park
summary: West Gate Memorial Park was made in memory of those who lost their lives during the collapse of the West Gate Bridge in 1970.

title: West Gate Memorial Park
summary: West Gate Memorial Park memorial

title: Stoney Creek Backwash
summary: The Stony Creek Walkway extends across the backwater and provides access to the Yarra River.

title: Stony Creek Backwash
summary: View of Stony Creek Walkway

title: Blue wren
summary: One of the many types of birds you might see along the trail

title: Toilets
summary: Good clean toilets at the start or end of your walk are always welcome!

title: The path
summary: Nice start to the walk past the blackwood and stringy bark trees. Wallabies are often here in the evening.

title: The Bluff lookout path
summary: This walk takes you to the Bluff Lookout not the base of the falls (make sure you are on the right path, this is the easier walk).

title: Wildflowers
summary: There are many beautiful wildflowers in Spring.

title: Seat
summary: A welcome seat to sit and smell and hear the sounds of the bush.

title: The Bridge
summary: The bridge over the little gully ensures a smooth path for prams and some wheelchairs.

title: Grass trees
summary: The sandy soils supports an Australian icon the Grass Tree, Xanthorrhoea australis. When in flower they are often called Kangaroo tails as they extend into the air, looking like a roo tail.

title: Beatiful bush
summary: The bush is really beautiful with grass trees, gums and lots of undergrowth.

title: McKenzie Falls
summary: The Falls look magnificent from up here, made us want to go down to the base too.

title: Burnt out stump
summary: Love this burnt out stump, although wouldn't want have been here when there was a fire.

title: Point Cook Homestead
summary: Open from 9am to 4pm daily, this wonderfully restored homestead was built in 1857 by the Scotsman Thomas Chirnside. He later went on to build Werribee Mansion with his brother Andrew.

title: Birdlife
summary: There are lots of bird species to spot on the walk including Pied Cormorants who live in colonies and dive underwater to catch fish.

title: Beach walkers
summary: If the tide is out, walking along the beach provides a lovely cool breeze in the summer.  As you walk there are shells to discover, birds to spot, and views of the CBD across the bay.

title: Red-necked Stints
summary: These small birds migrate from the northern hemisphere where they breed, to Victoria in summer.  They arrive in August and depart in February-March.

title: High-tide detour
summary: If the tide is in, you can walk along a wide path behind the beach, dotted with old pine trees.  It curves around Point Cook to the white beacon.

title: Wetlands entrance
summary: This is the point where you leave the beach behind and start walking along the track next to the beach.

title: A shorter option
summary: At the point you leave the beach you will see the track to a white beacon.  You can skip the Wetlands part of the walk by following this track back to the Wetlands car park.

title: The walking track
summary: The walking tracks are frequently exposed and quite sandy in places.  A good hat and sun cream are recommended.

title: The Tower
summary: There are great views from the tower platform.  Artist Bill Kelly designed it as A Monument to Migration and Aspirations - using the theme of bird migration as a symbol for human migration.

title: The Wetlands
summary: The wetlands are a migratory haven for birds, some from as far away as Siberia and Japan.  The area is home to more than 200 species of birds including rare and endangered species.

title: Saltmarsh flora
summary: If you look closely there are lots of hardy plants who find this challenging environment quite suitable for their needs including the Rounded Moon-flower and Beaded Glasswort.

title: The Falls
summary: View the falls from a viewing platform below the falls.

title: Car park
summary: park your car or bus at the car park before you head off for the walk.

title: New Facilities
summary: Since Black Saturday new facilities have been added for convenience of people walking to the falls.

title: The start of the walk
summary: Here is where you start the walk to the falls but there are also other paths for different walks.

title: New platform
summary: A new platform has been made down from the falls where you can stand over the flowing water.

title: Loose footpath
summary: be careful when walking along this path as it is made out of loose rocks and stones and there arent many rails along path.

title: A reminder of black saturday
summary: View the burnt trees and the new life that is coming out.

title: Old path to top viewing platform
summary: This was the path you use to take to the top platform above the falls. currently under construction.

title: Where old meets new
summary: Falling down trees over a running creek and surrounded by new life.

title: See the falls
summary: View Stevensons Falls from a distance.

title: Option for different route
summary: Another walk is connected to the walk to the falls, you can take this to the fern gully.

title: The sunrise
summary: No visit to Byron is complete without watching the sunrise!

title: Byron Bay Main Beach
summary: Byron Bay Main Beach is a walker's paradise. Flat, hard sand and plenty of things to look at.

title: The Pass beach
summary: Generally sheltered family beach and a great spot to watch surfers.

title: The Lookout.
summary: You have to clamber over rocks to get to the steps and if it is high tide wade through the water, but definitely worth the effort.

title: Looking to The Pass beach
summary: Looking back along the beach with Palm Valley behind.

title: Byron Bay
summary: It is easy to spend an hour up on the look out, a fantastic view on all sides.

title: Humpback Whales
summary: Not a great photo, but when I was here, I saw over 10 whales out to sea. Sometimes they come in quite close.

title: Palm Valley path
summary: A great walk through the bush, the path is well maintained and smooth. Suitable for prams and maybe wheelchairs, but quite steep in parts.

title: The Boardwalk
summary: The Boardwalk is fantastic and makes for easy walking. Good viewing out to sea as well.

title: The Kombi
summary: Love this artwork makes a drab electricity sub station look good. Very Byron!

title: Avenue of trees
summary: Nice avenue of trees and picnic area.

title: Middleton St artwork
summary: There is no information about this artwork, but it looks a bit like a wooden version of stonehenge.

title: Monumental Environmental Artwork
summary: Monumental Environmental Artwork is by John Dahlsen. The sign says it is temporarily installed, I hope not beacause it is a beauty. It is made out of a stump is Camphour Laurel.

title: Crossing Bay St
summary: Getting across Bay St can be diabolical. Many drivers do not pay attention & vegetation obstructs their view. There is no pedestrain crossing and some of the pram ramps don\\'t line up. Woeful!

title: Crossing Lawson St
summary: Very dangerous & inconvenient crossing. Pedestrains are forced away from crossing at the corner where they can see oncoming cars. The sign says it all, walkers are not important.

title: Footpath ends
summary: Another dangerous point for walkers, the footpath suddenly turns into a roadway.

title: The Shared Path
summary: Nice to have a shared path away from cars. Watch out for bikes, none seem to ring a bell when coming up from behind.

title: Byron Bay bats
summary: Look out for the colony of bats in the trees in Cumbebin Swamp Nature Reserve next to the path. If you cannot see them, you will smell them. Not the most pleasant of smells.

title: Ewingsdale Road
summary: Crossing Ewingsdale Road (Shirley St) is incredibly dangerous. There are heaps of fast cars and no pedestrian refuge, let alone crossing.

title: Kendall St no footpath
summary: Kendall St here has no footpath, so it is an extremely poor walking environment, and dangerous.

title: Camping and Picnic Spot under cover
summary: There are BBQs and seating at the main under cover area at Beulah Recreation Reserve

title: Boat Ramp
summary: There is a boat ramp for those that want to fish or cruise about the weir and creek.

title: Under the covers
summary: BBQ and seating in a wonderful area

title: This is wonderful BBQ areas
summary: Have a great stay and BBQ here

title: Plenty of picnic seating for a place to stay a while
summary: Picnic seating is new and clean

title: Under cover BBQs
summary: There is ample under cover BBQ places

title: The view of the weir area of the Creek here
summary: The Creek is dammed up into a weir at this point

title: Sports equipment installed on the walk
summary: Check out and use the sports equipment here

title: Wonderful bush walking tracks
summary: The tracks are well formed along the track

title: Views along the creek
summary: Yarriambiack Creek is quite photogenic

title: Down the Yarriambiack Creek
summary: Yarriambiack Creek View

title: More Gym Gear
summary: There are a number of Gym pieces along the walk

title: More Gym gear
summary: These Gym Pieces of equipment make the walk interesting and fun

title: Loads of track users
summary: There are a number of different users at the track including people walking their dogs.

title: The track heads to the road way
summary: The track heads from the Creek and bush to the roadway

title: Pickering Point
summary: Pickering Point Lookout

title: Merri River Bridge
summary: Bridge Entry onto Pickering Point Trail

title: Walking Track
summary: The walking track overlooks the Merri Marine Sanctuary

title: Thunder Point Lookout and Car Park
summary: Thunder Point Lookout

title: Shelly Beach
summary: Shelly Beach

title: To The Mahogany Walk
summary: Continue along the Pickering Point Trail to discover the Mahogany Walk. (Unsealed)

title: Joins to the Viaduct Road Foreshore Walk
summary: The Pickering Point Trail joins to the Viaduct Road section of the Foreshore trails

title: Loxton Lodge Community Garden
summary: It's always an inspiration to see what's growing in the garden.  Sometimes it's a busy hive of activity and other times quiet and peaceful.

title: Milk bar
summary: Sometimes I buy the paper in a milk bar, often wondering how these little shops survive financially.

title: Retro furniture galore
summary:
As I approach High St, I like to look in the windows of the 2 retro furniture shops full of stuff from the 60s 
that reminds me of my childhood.

title: Our very own Abbey Road
summary: Shopping mecca, with bonus zebra crossings that remind me of the Beatles Abbey Road album.

title: Prahran library
summary: Entering the library in the old Town Hall, the air conditioning and high ceilings give relief from the heat of the day at the height of summer.  Nice and warm in winter of course!

title: Groceries, coffee and pizza
summary: Sometimes I buy fruit on the way home, or stop off for hot chocolate and cake at an old fashioned cafe or pizza in the lovely upstairs courtyard of a pub.

title: Cake shop
summary: The most creative and fabulous cakes can be found here.

title: Fruit trees
summary: The other day I spotted a vine laden with bunches of grapes. I've got my eye on the lemon tree in Union St which last summer dropped so much fruit on the pavement I had free lemons all summer!

title: 1. Site of Ballarat's old haymarket (Doveton/Market/Armstrong/Mair block)
summary: This has long been a public and central meeting place - situated at the junction of roads, and a few minutes from rail transport and Ballarat's key cultural and civic institutions.

title: 2. The Civic Hall, 300 Mair St,  built 1953-1956
summary: Multi-purpose venue, with monumental presence.   Steel frame, local Selkirks bricks.  Main Hall holds c. 1600,  Performers included INXS.  Closed 2002, reopened 2014 for community design process.

title: 3. Statue of playwright William Shakespeare by Andor Meszaros, by 300 Mair St
summary: Statue added to front of hall 1960 depicts Shakespeare receiving applause after a performance.   Hungarian visitor Karoly Nagy was so impressed he organised a replica for Budapest unveiled 2003.

title: 4. Ginkgo trees planted by Sir Paul & Lady Hasluck 1972, western end  skate park
summary: Planted during Vice-regal visit, the trees are of the ancient Ginkgo biloba species (Maidenhair tree), native to China, called living fossils as similar to fossils dating back 270 million years.

title: 5. Statue of Scottish writer Sir Walter Scott by Stanley Hammond, by 300 Mair St
summary: The centenary of gold celebrations in the early 1950s gave a renewed push to plans for a new Civic Hall so it is fitting that both the Scott & Shakespeare statues record links to Goldrush times.

title: 6. Lower Hall entrance, Doveton St
summary: The architects of the hall made clever use of the fall of the ground on the site from West to East to build the foyer of the Lower Hall under the stage of the Main Hall.  Note messages on doors.

title: 7. View of fly tower, Doveton St
summary: The tall tower like structure at the northern end of the hall is the Fly Tower. This is the part of the building designed to store and launch the sets for large scale theatrical productions.

title: 8. Ballarat Library upper story offices, Market St
summary: The relationship with the Civic Hall was considered during the design of the Ballarat Library built 1993-1994,  The  upper story offices echoes the brickwork of the Civic Hall.

title: 9. Mural, Civic Hall/Library Car Park, off Market St
summary: A colourful public art mural has been created on the back wall of the carpark.   The mural was painted in 2013 by local youth working alongside professional artist Pauline O'Shannessy-Dowling.

title: 10. View to railway precinct, cnr Market & Armstrong St
summary: The proximity to the Provincial Hotel and Railway Station beyond it is evident from this corner of the site.

title: 11. Skate park, Armstrong St
summary: The skate park was the initiative of a young Ballarat skater and was added to the site in the 1990s.  A replacement skate park was built at the Len T Fraser reserve in 2004 but this remains popular.

title: 12. Regent Cinema, 49 Lydiard St Nth
summary: The cinema's interior was rebuilt in 1943 to the design of Cowper, Murphy & Appleford after a major fire attributed to visiting American service personnel.    Murphy was later co-architect Civic Hall.

title: 13. Mair to Sturt Block, Lydiard St Nth, east side
summary: This block is now one of the most treasured in Ballarat encompassing Victorian era architectural gems.  However records show that in the 1940s this was one site proposed for a new civic hall.

title: 14. Site of Alfred Hall, Cnr Curtis & Grenville Sts, demolished 1956
summary: Site of a predecessor of the Civic Hall, constructed n 1867 on the boundaries of East & West Ballarat for Ballarat's first royal visitor and formally closed on the day the Civic Hall opened.

title: 15. Former Walter Davis store, 86 Bridge Mall
summary: An example of the commercial work of Civic Hall architect Les Coburn who remodelled the store in 1935 with distinctive art deco features.  Coburn was known for both his commercial & residential work.

title: 16. Site of Coliseum, Little Bridge Street (vicinity Ballarat Senior Citizen's Centre)
summary: Another very large hall (capacity up to 10,000) owned by the South Street Society and used for society & civic events. It burnt down in 1936 creating impetus for the building of a new public hall.

title: 17. Her Majesty's Theatre ('Her Maj'),17 Lydiard St South
summary: Historic theatre first opened in 1875.   The history of the Civic Hall intersected with that of 'Her Maj' from 1990 - 2002 as the City of Ballarat combined management of the two facilities.

title: 18. Ballarat Town Hall, 225 Sturt St
summary: The eventual design of the Civic Hall was innovative in separating hall facilities and the Council admin offices.  Architect Les Coburn was greatly interested in civic matters as long-time Councillor.

title: 19. Block Arcade, 321 Sturt St
summary: The Sturt Street entrance of the Block Arcade was remodelled by Les Coburn in 1937. Look up to the first floor to get the best view of this work, the stylised parapet and lettering.

title: 20. State Government Offices, Cnr Mair & Doveton Streets
summary: To the west of the Civic Hall is another public building - the State Government Offices opened in 1981 and known as "The Glass House" because of its distinctive glass curtain wall design.

title: Start of walk
summary: Underwood Park sign with large map of main attractions - lots of free parking.

title: Seating under a shady tree
summary: Shady seats overlooking the wedding gazebo and bridge.

title: Wedding gazebo
summary: Wedding gazebo with landscaped surrounds.

title: Bridge
summary: Monet style bridge - no water lilies today.

title: Bush path
summary: A little less populated leading up to the duck ponds.

title: Path over duck pond
summary: This part of the path goes over the duck pond through the trees. There are lots of ducks, but you may have to look a little harder to find the large orange fish and the turtles.

title: Playground
summary: A shady playground for the kids - right next to tables, seats, toilets and some of the sporting fields (e.g. netball, softball). The caretaker's hut is also close by.

title: Dog park
summary: Two fenced dog parks with multiple access points. One is for smaller dogs and one is for larger dogs. Both parks have water, plastic doggy bags, bins and seats.

title: Daisy Painting
summary: All of the telephone poles have been painted with beautiful Australian scenes.

title: Building mural
summary: What a great mural! A few of the buildings in this area have been painted to blend into the scenery.

title: Picnic tables, BBQ and toilets
summary: This is a very popular picnic spot in summer. There are gas BBQs, several picnic tables and benches, and toilets. Photo by Parks Victoria.

title: Start of walking track
summary: We took Coranderrk Track, a vehicle track that follows Badger Creek. Alternate routes include Lyrebird Track and Slip Creek Track. They're roughly the same distance but have steps.

title: Fresh mountain air
summary: Fill your lungs with the fresh air from the surrounding forest. The sun dappled light made our walk truly magical!

title: Tree canopy
summary: Don't forget to look up every now and then as you might spot some local birds or simply to enjoy the view.

title: Popular walk, even in the middle of winter
summary: This walk is popular in summer as a lovely way to cool off, and in winter to enjoy the crisp and refreshing fresh air.

title: Colourful tree bark
summary: The colours of a forest are always a treat. The lush green ferns and the dew drops on them are gorgeous, while the colours of the barks of trees are varied and ever changing.

title: Get up close
summary: Forests are the perfect subject if you like photography. There's no shortage of beautiful landscapes and interesting close-ups to snap.

title: Badger Creek
summary: It's a treat to see the Creek after a rainy day as it's full and fast flowing.

title: Dam wall & spillway
summary: The dam wall was constructed in 1927, and raised in 1936. Stone came from the crest of the range via horse-drawn tramway. The east shore is a popular picnic nd recreation area

title: Lake track
summary: This section of track adjoins a flora & fauna conservation area, where local wildlife such as kangaroos may be sighted, especially in the mornings and evenings

title: Mahogany track
summary: The track is climbing, and there are farm ruins on the east side, not connected with those at the boy's farm. Thompson track is narrow and winding, with many tree roots

title: Boy's farm
summary: The former boy's farm is slightly off the main trail, with numerous ruins and the former orchard now growing untended. The boy's farm closed more than 60 years ago, yet much is still visible

title: Highest point
summary: This is the summit on this trip, the knoll to the right around 100m ASL. The descent on Lyster track is steep and rocky, but only for a short distance

title: Donelan's farm
summary: The Donelan family settled here in the 1930s, but only lived here a short time. Numerous exotic trees still grow here, and the farm dam is clear to see

title: Lysterfield tramway
summary: The walk joins the former Lysterfield tramway at this point for a long, gentle descent to the west side of the dam wall. This track is for walkers only

title: Lake view
summary: This point on the former tramway is one of the best view points of the lake on the west side. There is still something to see before rejoining the main path

title: Tramway display
summary: This static display shows the type of stone hopper used on the narrow gauge horse-drawn Lysterfield tramway. The hopper was manufactured in Leeds UK

title: Crayfish Bay signpost
summary: Crayfish Bay signpost, all you need do is decide which track to take first. I reckon, take the beach way and cliff top back there is best.

title: The grottos
summary: There a few grottos or small caves at the end of the first beach. Many a time on a rainy, cold winters day they have provided shelter.

title: Cape Otway Lighthouse
summary: The white spot in the cliff edge in the distance (middle of the photo) is the Cape Oyway Lighthouse.

title: Rockpools
summary: At low tide there are many, many rockpools to keep young and old fascinated.

title: Arriving at Cray Bay
summary: Arriving at Cray Bay at low tide, on a still warm April morning. Beautiful.

title: Crayfish Bay
summary: Crafish Bay at its best, on a very low tide, which is great for a snorkle (don't bother diving if it is not low tide).

title: Cray Bay and Otway Reef
summary: Climbing up the track and looking down on Cray Bay and out to the Otway Reef

title: The Southern Ocean
summary: A great spot to look out to the Southern Ocean and watch the rollers coming in.

title: The Cliff Top Track
summary: The Cliff Top Track is very narrow and sometimes a little overgrown, but a delight nonetheless.

title: The Boardwalk
summary: A shortish boardwalk.

title: Kensington Neighbourhood House
summary: Providing a variety of programs for locals. Kensington Neighbourhood House has been running for 40 years to help locals.

title: Women's Peace Garden
summary: The Garden was conceived in 1986 as a part of the International Year of Peace. Features plants symbolic of peace and colours of women's movement. It's a very relaxing place.

title: 'The Back Gate' Mosaic Murals
summary: Under the Epsom Road Bridge. Installed in 1998. Commemorates historic Newmarket Saleyards. Animals passed the 'Back Gate' to leave the Saleyards towards the abattoir or meatworks.

title: Kensington Banks
summary: Kensington is a nice place for walking around and there are many children’s playgrounds. It's a lovely place to live because public transport is very convenient.

title: Community Garden
summary: If you're interested in renting a plot to grow your own vegetables, please contact Kensington Community Recreation Centre on 9376 1633 or kensington@ymca.org.au.

title: Wildlife
summary: Apart from birds, sometimes you can see local wildlife on apartment balconies too.

title: Maribyrnong River and Wetlands
summary: You can walk or cycle along the river to visit the wetlands, or travel to other places from here.

title: Starfish
summary: When the water is low you can see starfish on the river banks.

title: Bayswater Road Park
summary: This playground is great for children of all ages. The park also has BBQ, tables , seats and a water tap.

title: Victorian houses
summary: Built during the reign of Queen Victoria. Many houses have been lovingly restored.

title: The Kiln
summary: When petrol rationing was introduced in 1940, charcoal was seen as a practical alternative.  This kiln is a rare example of a relatively intact charcoal burning kiln.

title: Friends of Kurth Kiln
summary: The Friends are actively engaged in maintaining the notice board, the kiln site and the tracks on this walk.

title: Brown Stringy-bark trees
summary:
This versatile tree provided food, medicines, containers, string and
tools for Aboriginal people.

title: The creek
summary: There are several great views of the creek along the walk.  Close your eyes and listen to the water running down stream.   What other sounds can you hear?

title: Common Heath
summary: The heath flowers, which mainly occur between late autumn and early spring are white, pink or red in colour.  See if you can find a pink one, it is Victorias floral emblem.

title: Foam build-up
summary: You can be forgiven for thinking it is a sign of pollution.  The foam is produced by the decomposition of a wide variety of plant material including aquatic plants and the leaves of trees.

title: End of Tomahawk Creek track
summary: The track returns to Beenak Road on the opposite side of the bridge to where we started.

title: Picnic Area
summary: After walking along the Tomahawk track, this is a great spot to relax and listen to the birds singing.   You may hear lyrebirds, honeyeaters, parrots and kookaburras.

title: Closer to nature
summary: The path narrows at times immersing you in the sights and smells of ferns, bushes and trees along the way.

title: Tree down
summary: A fallen tree has provided the opportunity for smaller plants to flourish.  Beneath the tree canopy you can find Silver Wattle, Spike Wattle, Christmas Bush, Silver Banksia and tree ferns.

title: Hakea
summary: Look out for Hakea along the route.  The nectar is used by insects and birds when it is in flower. Hakea requires fire to reproduce as the hard nut needs to be broken for the seed to be released.

title: Toilet on route
summary: This toilet might provide welcome relief along the way.  It is only a slight detour from the walking route.

title: The road home
summary: The last section of the walk is a wide gravel road leading back to the kiln.

title: The Heritage Peppercorn Tree
summary: South American Peppercorn trees were often planted near homesteads in the colonial period. The White and Clements families ran the dairy farm Flora Vale in this area from the 1840s to the early 1970s.

title: The Relocated Scarred Tree
summary: Scars on living trees are from Aboriginal people deliberately removing bark or wood.

title: The Possum Tree
summary: Years ago, major limb loss, fire and decay in this ancient river redgum (Eucalyptus camaldulensis) created a large opening with nooks and crannies for possums and birds to shelter.

title: possum
summary: Look out for some local wildlife using the habitat these tress and understory provide.

title: Lakeview
summary: Wetlands are home to aquatic and semi-aquatic indigenous plant species, water birds, frogs, fish and invertebrates. Wetlands were a major source of food, fibre and medicines for Aboriginal people.

title: The Fused-limb Tree
summary: This can happen naturally but Aboriginal people also made it happen by deliberately manipulating a growing tree. Either way, the trees are thought to have special significance.

title: Funky RMIT architecture
summary: Enjoy the views of the funky built form.  Kids love this walk too!

title: Burls
summary: A number of bulbous woody growths occur at the base of the trunk, called lignotubers or 'burls'.The Wurundjeri people sometimes removed the burls and crafted them into water containers called tarnuks.

title: Triple Scar and Redgum Grassy Woodlands
summary: Some of these redgums are well over 400 years old. Help the Friends of the Bundoora Redgums restore the grassy understory to boost biodiversity.

title: The 'Canoe' Tree
summary: The scar on this tree is probably from bark being deliberately removed to make roofing material or a small food-collection canoe.

title: The Staircase
summary: This non indigenous lemon scented gum  still provides nectar for the local possums as seen by the claw marks in its trunk.

title: The Resource Tree
summary: Trees were major food sources for the Wurundjeri people. Birds, eggs, honey and possums could all be harvested from trees. This one has an access hole.

title: The Rectangular Cultural Scar
summary: This is a highly significant tree. The scars size suggests the bark was used to build a shelter.

title: Frogpond
summary: 6 species of frogs have been recorded in Bundoora, most of which need the wetlands to survive. Frogs have been around for 190 million years and are an accurate indicator of environmental wellbeing.

title: Woodland View and Re-vegetation site
summary: The Friends of the Bundoora Redgums Inc, a volunteer organisation, has begun the long process of restoring the Redgum Grassy Woodland to its former glory. Join in!

title: Pedestrian path
summary: Coming out of the train station towards the Harbour Bridge  you will soon come to these steps - walk up them.

title: Business in the bridge
summary: The pedestrian path emerges on the other side of the railway line and you can walk alongside the start of the Harbour Bridge, which has some interesting businesses built into it, including this cafe.

title: Bradfield Park
summary: Bradfield Park runs alongside the Bridge - make sure you check out the signs explaining the interesting history of the Bridge.

title: Steps onto the Bridge
summary: Walk through Milsons Point train station under the Bridge, and at this point you've got the option of walking up onto it to take in the views.

title: Milsons Point shops
summary: Quite a few shops here if you need them, including more built into the Bridge itself.

title: Historic houses
summary: There are some beautiful historic houses on these very picturesque streets, including this real oldie.

title: Milson Park
summary: A nice walk down to this park, which has a small playground, toilets and access to the water.

title: Kirribilli wharf
summary: As an optional detour follow the signs down to the rather cute Kirribilli wharf, with a small cafe and great views.  There's even the option of taking a ferry to the city if you feel inclined.

title: Kirribilli House - Prime Minister's Sydney residence
summary: Not exactly Versailles, quite modest really.  However not an unpleasant place for one to reside.   Unsurprisingly, the house is not open to casual visitors, but you get this view from the street.

title: Lady Gowrie Lookout
summary: Another detour option for access to the coast (but there's more of that to come).

title: Down the steps
summary: Turn left down Mirradong Place (steps/walkway) just past Admiralty House.

title: Coastal path
summary: A meandering coastal path offers great views of some of Australia's most famous landmarks, including the harbour, Sydney CBD and the Opera House.  And the Bridge of course.

title: Luna Park
summary: Did I mention Luna Park?  There's a pool here too.

title: Lavender Bay path
summary: A beautiful path runs alongside the bay here, with views back to the city.  Look out for the whimsical sculptures hiding in the garden on the landward side of the path.

title: Wendy's Secret Garden
summary: Look for the little tunnel under the railway line and head up the steps.  Look for this little garden with some striking sculpture on the way up.  Make sure you look back at the view now and then.

title: Lake Weeroona
summary: A great place to walk, run or relax. Also a great playground for the kids.

title: Lake Weeroona
summary: A great place to walk, run or relax. Also a great playground for the kids.

title: Sacred-Heart Cathedral
summary: The third largest cathedral in Australia, it certainly is a gorgeous site to visit.

title: Myer
summary: The very first Myer was in Bendigo.

title: Hargraeves Mall
summary: Bendigo's main shopping precinct.

title: Rupanyup Post Office
summary: The Rupanyup Post Office is a great place to meet to start the walk. There is plenty of parking nearby.

title: Watch for traffic when crossing the Highway
summary: We have lots of Semi Trailer Grain Trucks coming through the district so beware.

title: Headers and Tractors in the yard of Emmetts Motors
summary: Emmetts are the local machinery and harvester company in town

title: The walking track around the billabong
summary: The walking track around the billabong is gravel but is in very good order, even in wet times.

title: The streets are quite free of cars mostly all day.
summary: The streets are often quiet at Rupanyup and can offer a well formed walking path if you prefer to walk or run on bitumen

title: A view across the billabong
summary: The Rupanyup Memorial Park is a great place to stay with a caravan

title: Walk among the native shrubs
summary: The flowering native shrubs are great habitat during the spring and summer months and native birds can be found here in abundance during nesting season.

title: Seating on the walk
summary: There is seating around the walk so keep an eye out

title: The Billabong has been stocked at various times with trout and other fish.
summary: A place to fish if you want to take a chance

title: A bridge over the culvert
summary: a quaint footbridge over the culvert

title: Picnic Benches
summary: There is ample covered picnic benches near a free BBQ

title: BBQ in the Sound Shell
summary: The Rupanyup Memorial Park sound shell

title: Playground
summary: There is a wonderful playground for kiddies.

title: Toilets and showers
summary: There are toilets and showers available here

title: walking bridge
summary: another walking bridge

title: More walks under shrubs
summary: This scrub is generally full of wild birds

title: A view up the billabong
summary: A view up the billabong

title: Old Rupanyup Water Tower
summary: This water tower used to be the source for all the towns water

title: Maryborough Railway Station, Station Street
summary: Maryborough’s iconic railway station was completed in 1890. Take some time to admire the intricate tessellated tiles, elaborate entrance hall and also the longest station platform in country Victoria.

title: Simson Memorial Cairn , Kennedy Street
summary: 1939 monument commemorating the Simson brothers: first white settlers of the Maryborough area back in 1840. Some of the stones are from the original homestead. Climb the steps for a sweeping view.

title: Box-Ironbark Avenue
summary: Walk the Box-Ironbark avenue between the tennis courts and Jubilee Oval and see if there are any blossoms attracting nectar-feeding native birds.

title: Lake Victoria
summary: Walk the willow path round Lake Victoria and pass by a playground, covered bbq facilities, Caravan Park and camping area, sporting fields, fishing boardwalk and many species of water-loving birdlife.

title: Outdoor Olympic Swimming Pool
summary: A heritage-listed 1940 Art Deco building houses the public outdoor pool area. With dense lawns, specimen trees and 3 separate pools, it’s one of Maryborough’s favourite places in the Summer months.

title: Princes Park historic rotunda & grandstand
summary: The historic rotunda was built in 1904/1905 to commemorate Maryborough’s Golden Jubilee. Look out across to the ornate grandstand and lush grass of the Princes Park sporting oval.

title: Memorial Gates to Princes Park
summary: The impressive 1885 cast-iron gates and pillars of Harcourt granite (c.1926) with the names of fallen WWI soldiers are a solemn reminder of loss in a community. Lest we forget.

title: Princes Park ticket box
summary: This quaint ticket box was built in 1908 and is the only known remaining one still in operation today.

title: The Bull and Mouth Hotel
summary: Admire one of High Street’s most ornate buildings, The Bull & Mouth Hotel. Built in 1904 with grand features, a multi-million dollar project has recently been undertaken to restore its former glory.

title: Site 1 - Engaging the senses
summary: The Market was part of the estate of the Aboriginal Wurndjeri-willam clan of the woi wurrung language group. The Market was in use 13 years before it officially opened in 1878.

title: Site 2 - A place to meat
summary: The Meat Hall or Meat, Fish and Rabbit Section as it is officially known is the oldest building on the Market site and was originally used as a wholesale meat market.

title: Site 4 - Deli delights
summary: The Dairy Hall is a wonderful intact example of an art deco building. Before modern refrigeration, marbel counter tops and special underground ventilation systems were used to keep products cool.

title: Site 5 - Produce and pioneers
summary: The real history of the Market starts with H & I Sheds and A & B Sheds - used as an outlet for Melbourne's Market gardens, which were run by the Chinese, then later by Greek and Italian communitites.

title: Site 6 - Melbourne's Marvellous Meat Hall
summary: In 1884 a new front to the Meat Market was added. The Meat Hall is both of architectural and social significance for its rarity as one of a few purpose built market buildings in existence in Australia

title: Site 7 - Market football
summary: By the 1920s, a strong sporting and social culture had developed among the stallholders and merchants at the Market. Football, cricket, bowls and golf clubs were formed with matches held in 1920 - 30s

title: Point 8 - Instant and delicious
summary: By the 1950s, food vans became a popular fixture. To satisfy the tastes of American servicemen stationed in Melbourne during World War II, cafe menus were expanded to include cola and hamburgers.

title: Site 9 - The Old Cemetary
summary: Much of the Upper Market is situated on cemetery land. Although closed in 1854, some families with vaults and reserved allotments were allowed burials up to 1917.

title: Site 3 - More than a facade
summary:
The facades are of architectural significance as are the iron gates
under the Produce Arch and between the shops and the Meat Hall.

title: Queen Victoria Market
summary: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in Australia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.

title: WCTU drinking fountain
summary: The fountain was erected in 1901 by the Womans Christian Temperance Union, who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its temperance concerns.

title: The Argus - corner Elizabeth and LaTrobe Street
summary: The building housed the Argus newspaper for 30 years. The Argus was one of Melbourne's three leading newspapers, all established the founding years of the city, until its closure in 1956.

title: The Welsh Church - 320 LaTrobe Street
summary: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

title: Republic Tower - corner Queen and LaTrobe Street
summary: Public art where you would normally expect a billboard. Designed by Melbourne architect Nonda Katsilidis, various international artworks have featured here. Cross the street for a close-up.

title: Laneway street art
summary: Step into this laneway to see a fantastic public gallery of street art. A hidden treasure trove of quirky, odd and creative pieces guaranteed to raise your eyebrows in surprise and wonder.

title: Queen Victoria Market
summary: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in Australia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.

title: WCTU drinking fountain
summary: The fountain was erected in 1901 by the Womans Christian Temperance Union who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its temperance concerns.

title: The Beeches Rainforest Walk
summary: Taggarty Cascades is part of a longer network of walks called The Beeches Rainforest Walk. Our 20 minute walk is to the timber footbridge and back, to see the waterfall tumbling down the rocks.

title: A picnic spot
summary: There's a table near the carpark that's perfect for having a picnic if the sun is out. Watch for lyrebirds that are known to frequent the area.

title: Fabulous fungi
summary: Keep an eye out for the different varieties of fungi as you descend into the rainforest understorey.

title: Viewing platform
summary: There's a viewing point half way down the path that gives you a taste of the rambunctious river that's flowing at your side. Your ears will already know about this. It's very loud.

title: A lush staircase
summary: As you descend into the rainforest, take care on the steps in case they are wet or slippery. Admire the lush tree ferns and Myrtle Beech that thrive in this cool dark world.

title: Viewing bridge
summary: This timber bridge takes you across the Taggarty River, giving you the perfect viewing platform to watch the waves of fresh water gush beneath your feet.

title: Stunning waterfall
summary: The Taggarty Cascades is an impressive site! Such a steady flow of clear gushing water tumbling over the granite boulders and down into the rainforest below.

title: Hooded Orchid
summary: Orchid

title: Orchid
summary: Orchid

title: Orchid
summary: Orchid

title: Boar Gully Camp Ground
summary: Boar Gully

title: Grevillea
summary: Grevillea

title: Brisbane Ranges National Park
summary: Brisbane Ranges National Park

title: Brisbane Ranges National Park
summary: Brisbane Ranges National Park

title: Common Rice-flower
summary: Common Rice-flower

title: Brisbane Ranges National Park
summary: Brisbane Ranges National Park

title: Echidna
summary: Echidna

title: Grass Tree
summary: Grass Tree

title: Sundews
summary: Sundews

title: Langtree Mall
summary: The recently refurbished Mall has lots of shade, seating and shops.

title: Langtree Restaurants "Feast Street"
summary: Large and diverse selection of restaurants including the Mildura Brewery and Stefano\\'s Pizza Caf. Lots of pedestrian priority here.

title: 8th St footpaths
summary: Like many of the streets around the CBD, 8th St has wide footpaths and seating available.

title: Fountain at Deakin Ave and 7th
summary: As you cross over 7th Ave at Deakin to access the footbridge to the river, you pass this lovely fountain.

title: Riverfront at rowing club
summary: Terrific spot to relax, picnic or walk the dog. Lots of lovely sights along the river. heading right you would hit the marina.

title: Locks
summary: From the riverbank you can see the locks. If you continue along the river, beyond this route, you would come to the Mildura Weir.

title: Rio Vista Park
summary: Mildura West Primary School spent five years rejuvenating this area of the park. There is lots of native bush and many signs indicating types of plants, trees, etc. Take your time to wander.

title: The Hut Sculpture
summary: Sculpture from 1988 Mildura Sculpture Triennial

title: More public art
summary: Art on both sides of the road here.

title: Mildura Arts Centre and public art
summary: Several pieces of public art on the grounds of the Arts Centre. Visit the Rio Vista House, built in 1889 by W.B. Chaffey, in Queen Anne style, the house features original furniture and fittings.

title: Mildura Bowls Club
summary: Lovely setting for a game! If entering the park from here, be aware this street does not have footpaths all the way, but you can walk along the grass.

title: Jaycee Park
summary: Lots to see and do in this Park. Playgrounds, picnic areas, open fields, enough for everyone!

title: Outdoor cafe
summary: Before heading back to the CBD you can relax at this outdoor caf with your favourite pooch.

title: North shore
summary: There are remains of structures, small 'make-ups' across water channels and other items. The barren hills to the north overlook 100 km of uninhabited country

title: slipways
summary: The cordwood slipways were built out from the lake shore to make salt extraction easier. Several are still in relatively good order considering their age

title: interpretive trail
summary: This signposted interpretive trail is the most accessible part of the former tramway. Relics include a former skip frame from the Sailor Salt Co.

title: Lake Becking
summary: The lake's east shore is a vast lunette dune. From this point, the tramway formation veers away from the lake shore and out into the wilderness

title: Remote area
summary: This section is several kms from the nearest track and feels very remote. Decaying sleepers and dogspikes are everywhere. If unsure of navigation or conditions, do not attempt this section

title: Grub Track
summary: Return is possible via Grub track and Ring road, but return via the tramway is more direct. The tramway formation continues south, but is soon out of the park and on private property

title: Playground for the kids
summary: A great activity for the kids in the flora and fauna park

title: Public Toilets in the Lions Park
summary: There are clean public toilets in the park

title: Covered BBQ and picnic areas
summary: There are a few covered BBQ and picnic areas in the Lions Park

title: Loads of bird avairies here
summary: There are loads of animals in pens, including goats and guinea pigs and many birds such as parrots and even peacocks and peahens.

title: Feed the guinea piga
summary: There are loads of guinea pigs in a pen and they are so friendly for kids and adults alike

title: The real start of the walk
summary: This is where the real track starts for the walk

title: Loads of seats along the walk
summary: If you have a need for seating along the way, you will find plenty of places to spend some time at a picnic or rest beside the creek..

title: Wonderful Views along the way
summary: There are loads of scenic views and wonderful bird life in the trees.

title: The Boardwalk
summary: There is a very well made boardwalk that keeps the walk beside the creek and away from the road and cars.

title: A creek view
summary: There are many great photo opportunities at the creek

title: A pretty place for a walk
summary: I find the whole creek area very appealing for walks

title: The bridge at Woolcock Street
summary: The Woolcock Street walking bridge

title: Plenty of seating
summary: Plenty of seating around the walks

title: Along the walk
summary: Under the trees along the walk

title: More views along the creek
summary: More views along the creek

title: A bridge across the creek
summary: The main walk bridge across the end of the creek

title: Picnic area and BBQ under cover
summary: Bicentennial Park has a picnic area and covered BBQ area

title: Children's playground and train
summary: Children are able to enjoy the stationary train at Marie Wallace Bayswater Park.It's an ex-Victorian Railways D3 4-6-0, built in the early 1900s.   A children's playground is located next to the train

title: BBQ facilities
summary: Enjoy a BBQ at the public BBQ facilities at Marie Wallace Park

title: Marie Wallace Bayswater Oval
summary: Marie Wallace Bayswater Oval is used by Bayswater Cricket Club Inc  and Bayswater Foorball club.  Public toilets are located next to the oval.

title: Dandenong Creek Shared Trail
summary: Follow the path from Marie Wallace Park toward Wantirna Road.

title: Playground
summary: Enjoy time with family at one of over 200 playgrounds in the City of Knox.

title: J.W. Manson  Reserve
summary: To find out more about the Dandenong Creek friends groups please see the below link.

title: Dandenong Creek bridge
summary: Cross the bridge to head back along the dirt path toward Marie Wallace Park. Alternatively keep following the trail past Wantirna Road for a longer walk .

title: Dandenong Creek Shared Trail
summary: Follow the trail along toward Wantirna Road.

title: Dandenong Creek trail
summary: To return back walkers are able to cross the bridge and head toward Marie Wallace Reserve.

title: Marie Wallace playground.
summary: The playground features an old locomotive as well as a wodden train  at Marie Wallace Park.

title: Marie Wallace playground
summary: The entrance to the playground is located next to the two trains.

title: Marie Wallace playground
summary: A large playground is available for children at Marie Wallace Park in Bayswater.

title: Knox Community Arts Centre
summary: Knox Community Arts centre is located across the road from Marie Wallace Park.  Bayswater train station is located a short walk from the Arts Centre on Railway Parade.

title: Enter the Gardens
summary: The path in is wide with an even surface for walking, so it's hard not to enjoy the walk after only a few steps.

title: The steps
summary: Take an optional small detour and walk up and down the steps to King St. It will get the blood pumping!

title: The Flag Staff
summary: A flag staff was erected here in 1830 to signal ships and the Victorian Government was proclaimed on the site in 1850.

title: The Bowls Club
summary: The historic City of Melbourne Bowls Club was founded 1866. It has a function room for 150 people and is a great venue for physically active social functions.

title: The playground
summary: A great playground to bring children to on the weekend, the Victoria Market is nearby for some healthy food options too.

title: Tennis, netball and volleyball courts
summary: The Flagstaff Gardens tennis courts have two hard courts with lights. Netball and volleyball can also be played on these courts. How about organising some lunchtime matches with colleagues?

title: The Court Favorite
summary: The statue was presented to the City by R. Baron Marks JP in 1930.

title: Magnificent Morton Bay Fig
summary: There are several very large Morton Bay Figs in the Gardens that are a sight to behold. You can do some step ups on the surrounding wall.

title: The lawns
summary: In the warmer weather the lawns are wonderful for picnics and getting a bit of green time.

title: Start of Spring Creek Walk
summary: The walk begins here at this lovely open area next to Spring Creek.

title: Spring Creek Track
summary: The compacted gravel track begins with a mild incline.

title: Track Intersection
summary: Tea Tree Walk heads up to the falls and Kanooka Track ends here at Spring Creek Track.

title: Vegetation
summary: In 1931 a mixture of exotic and native trees were planted in the Reserve and are now thriving.

title: Falls viewing platform
summary: A scenic place to rest and admire the falls (when there is water). Be sure to look out for water dragons!

title: Kanooka Track
summary: This track has some uneven and rocky sections and steps.

title: Lyrebird
summary: A rare sighting of a shy native Lyrebird. This female does not have the same unique tailfeathers as the male.

title: Swamp Wallaby
summary: The Reserve is a wildlife refuge so animal life is abundant. This wallaby was on the path!

title: Rowville Community Centre
summary: The centre runs a variety of programs and is dedicated to the provision of high quality, financially accessible services and educational programs in a welcoming and respectful environment.

title: Rowville Uniting Church
summary: Rowville Uniting Church is located on Bridgewater Way & Fulham Rd, Rowville

title: Rowville Lake
summary: Welcome to Rowville Lakes. There are over 300 minor parks, reserves and playing fields spread throughout the City of Knox that cater for all forms of leisure and recreational activities.

title: Rowville Lake walking track
summary: Follow the path running between Suttons Lake and Hill Lake

title: Suttons Lake
summary: Enjoy the view of Suttons Lake

title: Playground
summary: Enjoy some time out with family at the playground overlooking Suttons Lake. Knox has over 200 play spaces in parks and reserves.

title: Suttons Lake
summary: Enjoy the view and follow the path around to Superior Ave.

title: Map of Rowville from 1981
summary: The Knox Historical Society has included a photograph of the Rowville area from back in 1981. As you can see the Rowville lakes are featured.

title: Tarra Bulga Visitor Information Centre
summary: A great starting point for exploring this National Park

title: Bulga Picnic Area
summary: Tables, toilets and picnic shelter provided.

title: Corrigan Suspension Bridge
summary: Corrigan Suspension Bridge stretches through the rainforest canopy, affording spectacular views of the lush fern gully on the forest floor below.

title: Lyrebirds
summary: The fern gullies are the home of the Superb Lyrebird.

title: Ringwood Railway Station
summary: Start at Ringwood Railway Station fronting Maroondah Highway. The station was built in 1889 after the railway line was extended from Hawthorn to Ringwood. The line was electrified in 1923.

title: The Clock Tower's original site
summary: Proceed easterly to the intersection of Warrandyte Road and Maroondah Highway to the original site of the Ringwood Memorial Clocktower. Erected in 1928.

title: Blood Bros Stores
summary: Deviate under the railway viaduct to view the Blood Brothers store, built in 1914 and continuously operating for over 95 years.

title: Maroondah Federation Estate and Maroondah Art Gallery
summary: Walk along Greenwood Avenue to number 32, the site of the former Ringwood Primary School. It is now a Council owned & managed community, cultural and arts facility. Return the same way back to Highway

title: Ringwood Lake
summary: Continue easterly along Maroondah Highway, pause at Ringwood Lake, created in 1926 by the damming of Sandy Creek which used to follow the line of the gully and flow into Mullum Mullum Creek.

title: Ringwood Fire Station
summary: Cross the highway and head west. The former Ringwood Fire Station was built in 1930 at a cost of seven thousand pounds and provided an important service for over 65 years. It is currently a restaurant

title: Bamford's Timber Yards
summary: Bamford's Timber Yards were a landmark at the northwestern corner of Warrandyte Road and were close to the majestic Block Buildings (1912) on the northeastern corner of Adelaide Street.

title: Block Buildings & Coffee Palace
