summary: Block Buildings and the Ringwood Coffee Palace were amongst the earliest commercial premises in Ringwood, on the northwestern corner of Adelaide Street (now covered by Eastland Shopping Centre).

title: The Mail Office
summary: Head north into the Eastland precinct, which in earlier years was home to The Pines Private Hospital, Ringwood Football Ground, and the offices of the Ringwood Mail.

title: Ringwood Town Hall
summary: Return to the highway, at the northwestern corner of Melbourne Street, to the site of the Town Hall of the Borough of Ringwood, built in 1927 and demolished in 1970.

title: The State Savings Bank
summary:
A sign of prosperity in Ringwood was
the construction of the State Savings Bank in 1923 at a cost of three thousand pounds. The building still exists behind an unsympathetic facade.

title: Ringwood Timber & Trading Company Limited
summary: On the north eastern corner of New Street, the Ringwood Timber & Trading Company constructed a fine building to cope with demand for building materials at a time of rapid development. Demolished 1981.

title: Ringwood Co-operative Cool Stores
summary:
Crossing back to the south side of Maroondah Highway, wander back to the
Clock Tower, located on the site of Ringwood Coolstores (1911-65), evidence of the importance of Ringwood's orchard enterprises

title: Signage to show your walking choices
summary: At the Ollerton Ave entrance, you are given an overview of the walking track options available to you so you can choose each time you visit a different approach.

title: A place to play
summary: There’s plenty of room for the kids to run around in the Bushland Reserve as well as a couple of playground at the perimeters of the Reserve.

title: Walking the dog
summary: This is a popular place for taking your pooch on an enjoyable walk through native bushland, although remember to keep your furry friend on the leash.

title: Native bushland in the middle of Moe
summary: A visit to this Reserve showcases the indigenous landscape that used to cover this area.

title: Follow the track
summary: Whether you follow the concrete track or cut into the Reserve on one of the many natural paths, you’ll discover a healthy mix of native bushland.

title: The Fringing Lily
summary: Just one of the many native orchids you’re likely to see if you keep an eye out.

title: Cinnamon Bells
summary: This is a wonderful Reserve for fans of orchids and keen photographers, with magnificent specimens such as these.

title: The Bearded Orchid
summary: Yet another example of why this bushland reserve is so famous for its orchids.

title: Listen for lyrebirds
summary: The trail begins in the shade, walking through towering manna gums. Listen for lyrebirds and their complex bird calls ringing continuously through the forest.

title: Fantastic fungi
summary: Watch your step because there are several types of fungi growing along this trail. Learn more about mushrooms in Australia by the link below.

title: Leary Creek
summary: This trail crosses Leary Creek in two spots. Badly affected by the Black Saturday bushfires, the creek contains one of the few remaining populations of a nationally endangered fish, Barred Galaxias.

title: Rest spot
summary: There are a couple of benches along the trail and several interpretative signs if you'd like to know more about the flora and fauna native to this area. Look for signs of wombats digging as you rest.

title: Felled gums
summary: Even when felled, the beauty of these gums remain. Some of the fellings will be accidental and caused by the weather, others will be deliberate clearing efforts.

title: Tiny moments
summary: If you look carefully, you'll see tiny moments of interaction between the natural world, like a drop of sap that's fallen over 100 metres to land on this fern.

title: Bushland renewal
summary: After the Black Saturday bushfires, signs of renewal and regrowth came from the resilient tree ferns, their bright green fronds striking against a backdrop of burnt out Manna gums.

title: Fungi fiefdom
summary: As trail starts to descend into the tree fern groves, the fungi find themselves in a darkened paradise. At your feet, you might also notice birds foraging about, looking to feast on small insects.

title: Boardwalks
summary: This trail includes a fantastic boardwalk pathway through fern tree groves. In 1939, a bushfire rushed through The Beauty Spot and destroyed these very same groves, along with a popular tourist spot.

title: Hideaway
summary: This is a cooler spot to rest, hidden in the lush ferns and overhanging foilage. The trail is in a similar state of transition today, after being reconstructed following the Black Saturday bushfires.

title: Pobblebonk frog
summary: As you walk through the wetlands, listen for the call of the Pobblebonk or banjo frog, named because of the 'bonk' sound it makes, like a banjo string being plucked.

title: Follow the light
summary: The boardwalk resumes again, this time leading walkers in the direction of the light. Look up to spot bright-coloured parrots or wattle birds, raucously guarding their precious nectar supplies.

title: Valley beyond
summary: As you walk towards the carpark look out towards the other side of Marysville and the valley for a reminder of how much was lost in the bushfires and all that is now slowly regenerating each day.

title: Vervet Monkeys
summary: Observing the complex interactions between these highly social animals is one of the highlights of a visit to Werribee Open Range Zoo.

title: Lions
summary: The zoo provides a rare opportunity to see these majestic animals up close.

title: Hippos
summary: The zoo provides a rare opportunity to get up close to these intriguing animals. You can sit and watch the hippos along the Pula Walking trail as well as seeing them while out on Safari

title: Serval
summary: These slender and extremely agile cats are one of Africa's most successful hunters

title: Safari Station Tours
summary: Imagine being surrounded by magnificent wildlife, including rhinos, giraffes, zebras and antelopes, or taking the perfect safari photo just 30 minutes from Melbourne's city centre.

title: Przewalski's horse
summary: Przewalski's horse. The baby was born in 2014. It's name is Hatan. The breed is the last truly wild horse, is skittish, stubborn, naturally shy and sometimes very aggressive.

title: Ibis
summary: Ibis are a group of long-legged wading birds that inhabit wetlands, forests and plains. They all have long, down-curved bills, and usually feed as a group, probing mud for food.

title: Rhino
summary: Rhinoceros are a threatened species that have only one predator, humans, who prize them for their hooves, blood, urine and above all for their horns for use in traditional medicines.

title: Ostrich
summary: The ostrich is the fastest flightless bird and can reach sprinting speeds of up to 70 kilometres per hour. The ostrich also uses its wings for displays of courtship and dominance.

title: Impala
summary: Impala are medium sized African antelopes that inhabit savanna grasslands and woodlands in close proximity to water sources.

title: Lions Park
summary: A small park beside the Campaspe River with a playground, barbeque, picnic table and toilet facilities

title: Open Park
summary: Lots of open park land along the way, dotted with trees.  A great natural playground.

title: Flying Foxes
summary: Flying foxes travel up to 50km a night to feed on pollen, nectar and fruit.  They fulfil a very important ecological role by dispersing the pollen and seeds of a wide range of Australian plants.

title: Trees
summary: The park trees come in all shapes and sizes.  It provides a great opportunity to test your tree naming skills.

title: The path along the bay
summary: As you turn the corner here, the beautiful bay opens up on your right.

title: Corio Bay
summary: Looking out across the bay you can marvel at how much has changed as the city developed.

title: Geelong Play Space
summary: A play space for all, allowing physical and explorative play and a sense of wonder within a culturally sensitive environment.  There are 20 significant landscape areas or features to find and explore.

title: Botanic Gardens
summary: The gardens were renovated in 2002, with a new section for arid-climate and local native plants opened. It features a dramatic entrance combining architectural plants with modern garden sculptures.

title: Friends of the Garden
summary: Free guided walk in the gardens are offered by the Friends of Geelong Botanic Gardens on Wednesdays and most Sundays at 2pm, weather permitting.   For more information visit http://friendsgbg.org.au/.

title: The Gardens
summary: In 1851 the Government had the foresight to set land aside at the edge of the Geelong settlement for the development of a Botanic Garden.  The grounds can now be enjoyed throughout the year.

title: Flora of the gardens
summary: The gardens are full of fascinating plants with unusual shapes, textures and colours.

title: The Tea Room
summary: There is a lovely tea house in the Botanic Gardens which is open from 11am to 4pm.

title: Tim Neville Arboretum playground
summary: The upgraded Children’s Garden includes new walking paths, adventure garden rooms including a butterfly garden and all abilities playground.

title: Knox Memorial and Honour Roll
summary: The names of 120 members of the Australian military services from Knox who lost their lives while serving their country are honoured at the Knox Memorial and Honour Roll in the Tim Neville Arboretum.

title: Tim Neville Arboretum
summary: Walk along the duck pond toward the children’s playground

summary: Enjoy time with family at one of over 200 playgrounds in Knox

summary: Continue on the Blind Creek Trail.

title: Friends of Knox – Blind Creek Billabong Group
summary: This group assists with the implementation of the Blind Creek Billabong Management Plan. The Blind Creek Billabong Group meet regularly & conduct weeding, rubbish removal and indigenous planting.

title: Botanic Gardens
summary: This beautiful reserve off Narracan Drive provides shade, the rotunda, picnic facilities along with a skate park, and is a well-loved site for locals and visitors alike.

summary: This is a lovely spot to stop at and look across the Latrobe Valley to the Great Dividing Range as well as down upon the rail trail and wave to others making the trip.

title: Take a trip along the boardwalk
summary: There’s nothing quite like quietly walking along a boardwalk over a busy waterway, and depending on the time of day, you can be treated to a full orchestra of bird and frog song.

title: Lake Narraccan Jetty
summary: The detour at Sullivans Road to Lake Narraccan is well worthwhile, especially for a picnic or BBQ lunch, a throw of the fishing line, some sightseeing and even a swim.

title: Glimpses of Hall's Bay
summary: Looking north through the trees near the eastern end of the trail, this beautiful stretch of water is a popular venue for water sports and the site of more than one national water-skiing championship.

title: The Yallourn Cooling Towers
summary: A breathtaking view of the working example of a coal station, where these huge towers both cool and recycle the water in the process of generating electricity.

title: The Welcome Mural
summary: Gunaikurnai artist Ron Edwards provides an excellent overview of the cultural trail and murals.

title: Introduction to the cultural trail
summary: This mural is well worth reading as it provides the context for the cultural trail.

title: The bush tucker garden
summary: Over 27 species of native plants are included in this garden, all with important roles to play in the wellbeing of the Gunaikurnai people.

title: The Creation story
summary: This mural tells the Dreamtime story of Borun the pelican man and Tuk, his musk duck wife.

title: Basket weaving
summary: Local plants within the Waterhole Creek catchment can be used to weave useful (& exquisite) baskets that the Gunaikurnai nation is famous for.

title: Meeting places
summary: The gathering of the five clans and meetings with other nations is clearly depicted in this beautiful mural.

title: The five clans and their shields
summary: Each of the five clans of the Gunaikurina nation has its own particular shield identifying the clan to which tribal members belong.

title: Snake mural
summary: Framed by well-established trees, this mural is a wonderful depiction of an important story that details this dreamtime story.

title: A snake in the rain story
summary: As with all the other murals, you will learn about the story that informs Edward’s painting of the snake.

title: Findon Road Crossing
summary:
Findon Road is a main thoughfare for cars, trucks, and buses that can be quite busy at all times of the day. 
It is the only road crossing during the walk, so please take care when crossing here.

title: Foothills Park
summary: This photo shows the type of landscape you will be treated to on this beautiful walk

title: Foothills Park's Gates
summary: There are two of these gates on the walk that could prove tricky if you have a stroller, wheelchair, or walking aid. They can be a little tight to get through.

title: Foothills Playground
summary: This is a great spot of a picnic or a rest spot. A playground for the kids, electric barbeques for a hot lunch, and tables with shade.

title: Foothills Playground
summary: A different view of the playground area

title: Foothills Park Hill
summary: This is the steepest part of the walk, which is also a access road for park management.

title: City Views
summary: This is just one aspect of the 360 degree views you will get from this point on the walk.  Spend some time here to pick the the surrounding features.

title: Word of Caution
summary: Throughout the walk there mounded speed humps that could catch you unaware. Also the gravel path can be loose, so take care with foot placement.

title: Halfway Point
summary: This point is where the Foothills Circuit joins the other two walks in the Quarry Hills reserve.  Take a right hairpin turn to continue along the Foothills Circuit.

title: The back section
summary: You get to enjoy the flatest part of the walk here. This section also adjoins and has good access to the residential areas.

title: Henderson Creek Wetlands
summary: On your return to the Council offices and your starting point, you get the opportunity to sample some of the Henderson Creek Wetlands which continues under and on the other side of The Lakes Boulevard

title: 'Scar Tree' 2003
summary: Artist Tim Jones was commissioned to create this Scar Tree sculpture that commemorates a scarred box tree that once stood near this site. The tree was found to be 'damaged' between 1644 and 1784

title: 'The Urban Forest - Fire Memorial' 2010
summary: Created by Donal Molloy-Drum this memorial responds to the 2009 Remlaw Fire. The image of the birs is the actual shape formed by the Remlaw Fire (2218 hectares of land was burnt)

title: Old Weir and Swimming Area early 1900s
summary: "The Horsham Times in January 1882 commented on the need for a public bathing place, especially since many lacked a bath in their houses. By 1908 a swimming pool had been constructed in river upstream

title: 'Wimmera - Woven Vessels' 2012
summary: Created specifically for its site along the banks of the Wimmera River, the boat forms uses reclaimed fencing wire from farms including those affected by the 2011 floods. Photo by Michael Shiell.

title: War Memorial
summary: This was dedicated on 18 April 2004.  It was built to replace a Cenotaph and numerous memorials that were scattered around Horsham City

title: Wimmera River Environment Display - Mural 1999
summary: This piece of work by local secondary school students explores the theme of Wimmera wetlands above and below the water.  The colors and imagery are a direct response to the Wimmera's environment

title: Untitled Sculpture 2006
summary: Winner of the 2006 Horsham Spring Garden Festival Acquisitive Sculpture Prize.  Sculpturally the work is an allegory of the intimate relationship between water, trees and sustainable land use

title: 'Bunyip' 2010
summary: Artist Kevin Gilders was commissioned to carve two sculptures out of an old sugar gum which had to be removed from the gardens for safety reasons.

title: 'Thomas Brown' 2010
summary: The sculpture depicts founding Botanical Gardens Curator, Mr Thiomas Brown, planting the exact sugar gum on the birth of his son (circa 1895)

title: Horsham Botanic Gardens
summary: The original design of Horsham Botanic Gardens was undertaken by the curator of the Royal Botanic Gardens in Melbourne, Mr William Guilfoyle, between 1873 and 1880.

title: Playground
summary:
The park includes a significant interactive play space, toilet facilities and electric BBQ's.

The historic Maffra Sugar Beet Museum is located nearby.

title: Macalister RIver
summary: The walk will take you along the Macalister River.

title: Excellent pathways
summary: The walk is suitable for pushers and wheelchairs.

title: Saltwater Lake
summary: Start walk from the main car park, passing under an old prototype bridge span which acts as a noticeboard, walk to the right of the BBQ and shelter, up the gravel path towards Todd Road.

title: BBQ shelter
summary:
Freshwater lake from the BBQ shelter.
The toilets are to your left.
Head up the gravel path towards Todd Road passing thru the Red gum woodlands

title: Red gum woodlands
summary: Follow the path parallel to Todd Road to the end

title: Steps to Heat
summary: At the corner there are steps to down to the sandy Heath land plantings.

title: Heath walk
summary: Mixed plantings with an abundance of colour

title: Friends of Westgate Park compound
summary:
The nursery of "Friends of Westgate Park"
Continue following road to the end of the chain link fence.

title: Sandy Heathland
summary:
Turn left onto the walking track with the small pond on your left.
Sit and enjoy the birdlife.

title: Freshwater Lake
summary: At the end of the small walking track veer left on the gravel road towards the fresh water lake. Before the lake there is a set of stairs leading to a walking track. Take the stairs.

title: Back to Road
summary: At the end of the walking track after views of the freshwater lake you will join back with the road, continue walking right around the lake to again be at the BBQ shelter.

title: Freshwater Lake
summary: From industrial wast storage to a major water catchment.

title: Friends
summary: Don't forget to look up and down.

title: YWCA's Jasper Hotel - 489 Elizabeth Street
summary: The YWCA provided services to women such as housing, job placement and mentoring. Inside is a plaque acknowledging Alice Henry, pioneer journalist and unionist. Now a hotel and conference venue.

title: Queen Victoria Market
summary: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in Australia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.

title: WCTU fountain
summary: The fountain was erected in 1901 by the Women's Christian Temperance Union who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its temperance concerns.

title: The Argus - corner LaTrobe and Elizabeth Street
summary: The building housed the Argus newspaper for 30 years. The Argus was one of Melbourne's three leading newspapers, all established the founding years of the city, until its closure in 1956.

title: The Welsh Church - 320 LaTrobe Street
summary: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

title: Republic Tower - corner LaTrobe and Queen Street
summary: Public art where you would normally expect giant billboards. Designed by Melbourne architect Nonda Katsilidis, many international artists have had their art featured here.

title: Gallery of street art
summary: Take a wander down this public gallery of street art. All sorts of curious and interesting pieces guaranteed to raise your eyebrows in surprise and wonder.

summary: Catch Bus 235 or 606 to get to the Entrance.

summary: Cross Rail were left

title: Pond

title: Highest point
summary: At the windmill make a righthand turn up the hill to the highest point of the park to enjoy city  lake and bridge views. There is a seat provided. Retrace your steps to the windmill.

title: Freshwater lake

title: To the pink lake
summary: Continue along the road across the intersection to the track on your right to the pink lake edge

title: The pink lake

title: Revegetation
summary: Enjoy the revegetation of Westgate Park. The Friends Group plant approximately 20 000 plants and 300 species in the park annually.  Continue around the salt lake edge to the grass area.

title: Todd Road car park entrance
summary: Great views across the grassed area to the Saltwater lake and Westgate Bridge.

title: Why?
summary: Why is the lake pink?

Time to relax. Shelter, toilets and seats.

title: Swan Viewing
summary: There is a good viewing platform from which to watch the birds.

title: Friends

title: Lizards

title: Start of walk

title: So much to see

title: Beach view

title: Board walk
summary: Takes you across the creek.

title: Check out the crabs
summary: If the tide is out, it's possible to spot see and hear the tiny mud crabs as they climb in and out of their holes. Looks like synchronised mud dancing - quite mesmerising after watching for a while.

summary: Some welcome shade from the sun!

title: Pink crabs

summary: A great view across the sand. What a lovely beach!

title: Kyneton Botanical Gardens
summary: The Gardens date back to 1858. Wide lawns slope down to the Campaspe River. There are 17 trees listed as significant by the National Trust.

title: Historic weir
summary: The remains of the swimming pool formed between 2 weirs. 1935 has been cut into the base of what was the diving tower.

title: Our Lady of the Rosary
summary: A beautiful church, with fantastic wrought iron gates (one of the many historic buildings in the area).

title: Monsieur Pierre's
summary: A great coffee stop!

title: Kyneton Town Hall
summary: There are lots of activities happening at the Town Hall - festivals, workshops, performances.

title: After Black Saturday Memorial
summary: A beautiful mosaic to commemorate the fire in Redesdale and surrounding areas in 2009.  (see side of Town Hall building).

title: Post office
summary: This post office was built in the 1870s and continues to function as one today.  The clock tower helps the locals keep to the same time!

title: Puffing Billy Lakeside station
summary: Alight from Puffing Billy Lakeside station after your journey from Belgrave. Emerald Lake Park is a great spot for a stroll and a picnic lunch.

title: Trestle Bridge over Lake Treganowan
summary: Trestle Bridge over Lake Treganowan

title: Lake Treganowan
summary: Lake Treganowan

title: Emerald Lake Park Murals
summary: Murals depicting Carl A. Nobelius, the Puffing Billy Railway and portraits of four writers associated with the area.

title: Gus Ryberg Amphitheatre
summary: The largest and main amphitheatre, the Gus Ryberg, located north of Lake Treganowan, is named after one of the original park rangers.

title: Path beside Lake Treganowan
summary: Path beside Lake Treganowan.

title: Tarneit Library and Community Centre
summary: This great community hub features an impressive range of activities including women's only fitness classes, craft, music, cooking, playgroup, computer and English classes, and much more.

title: Alfred Park
summary: Lovely park with BBQ, playground, water fountain, shade and seating.

title: Skeleton Creek wetland area
summary: Lovely views of the wetland, complete with croaking frogs and chirping birds.

title: Gum trees galore
summary: The variety of Indigenous flora is spectacular, especially in spring when flowers are in bloom.

title: Dairy Fields Park
summary: Formerly a blue stone dairy owned by the Leake family. The area was severely affected by bush fires in 1969. The remaining blue stones commemorate the heritage of the area.

title: Rose Grange Boulevard Park
summary: Pack yourself a picnic and have a seat in this lovely pergola. The park also has a playground.

title: Tarneit Creek Wetland
summary: A shady spot to take in the scenery.

title: Sculpture
summary: This pelican welcomes you to the start of the wetland walk.

title: 2 ducks scultpure
summary: See if you can spot the 2 ducks hiding behind this wetland.

title: Seasons Park
summary: A fabulous park with playground, tennis courts, amphitheater, water fountain, BBQ and seating.

title: Eagle
summary: Watch out for the eagle soaring above you!

title: Pelicans
summary: These two fantastic birds farewell you as you complete the wetland walk.

title: Retirement Village
summary: Sneak a peek through the fence to marvel at the pretty gardens and immaculate lawns in Lifestyle Seasons Retirement Village.

title: Long view of start of walk
summary: first view of waterways and wildlife

title: Approaching first bridge
summary: First of many bridges

title: Over the Bridge view
summary: Rest spot and lovely view of waterway

title: Looking out over the bridge
summary: Bridge looking over of the thriving water rushes

title: Another beautiful view to look at more wildlife
summary: Waterway home to numerous bird life

title: Play time
summary: Perfectly situated playground

title: BBQ and drink stop
summary: Right next to the playground is the family BBQ and drinking tap.

title: Looking back at the last bridge
summary: Just taking time to look back at the waterway and bridge

title: View of the end  before turning aorund
summary: Picture actually taken from the other side of waterway. Shows the view and distance to the end of the walk before you turn around and enjoy these views all over again.

title: What are you looking at?
summary: A delightful aspect to this ride is the experience of being in the middle of a busy farming community, including the cattle industry with its curious cows.

title: The Great Dividing Range
summary: Along the way, you have exceptional views of what is Australia’s most substantial mountain range and the third longest land-based range in the world.

title: Take a seat
summary: Sometimes it’s worth stopping for a rest, and there are numerous seats on the Trail to do just that.

title: Tinamba Hotel
summary: The Tinamba Hotel is a famous example of colonial architecture. Coupled with great food, this is a place not to be missed (at 4 - 6 Tinamba-Seaton Road).

title: You might meet some horse riders
summary: The Rail Trail introduces you to so many fascinating elements, including stopping along the way to chat to some happy horse riders.

title: Port of Maffra
summary: A part of the fascinating fabric of the town today, this historic port was a key piece of economic infrastructure in the early days of European settlement.

title: Boulevard of trees
summary: Travelling through the parklands of Maffra is truly delightful, with well-established tree arches that take your breath away.

title: Explore the history
summary: The historic courthouse in Maffra is a good place to visit not only for its architectural significance but because it doubles as an information centre.

title: The Old Courthouse Inform
summary: Old Court House Visitor Centre on the corner of the Esplanade and Main St. It is open a minimum 11am to 3pm most days. The building is still in perfect condition with the original cell block.

title: Mornington Park
summary: Mornington Park where there is a children’s playground and barbecues all surrounded by a fort-like wall.

title: Mornington Football Disaster of 1892 monument
summary: On the corner of the Esplanade and Schnapper Point Drive is a monument to the Mornington Football Disaster of 1892 where 15 members of the football club drowned after the 'Process' sank.

summary: Grand entrance to Mornington Park

summary: Mills Beach Scenic Lookout on the Esplanade.

summary: Esplanade and Herbert St intersection

summary: Nachos at Taco Bill Mexican restaurant

summary: Restaurant Soy upstairs on the first floor overlooking Main St

summary: Afghan Marcopolo restaurant - good for dinner

summary: The Boyz 4 Breakie is good for breakfast. Very popular with bike riders.

title: Aboriginal Community
summary: The establishment of an Aboriginal community in this area by the Yorta Yorta families was a direct result of the Cummerangunja Walk Off on 6 Feburary 1939.

title: Traditional association
summary: This particular site was chosen, as the Yorta yorta had an extended traditional association with the environments in close proximity to rivers such as the Kaiela (Goulbourn River).

title: Population and housing
summary: A 1946 Police Report listed 130 people aged from 8 days to 80 yrs living on the Flats with a third of them less than 15 yrs old. Lodgings consisted of 29 dwellings, 22 being assortments of t

title: The river
summary: Provided food including crayfish, red fin, yellow belly, cod as well as possum, turtle eggs. Swan, duck, crane and other birds and their eggs. The women predominately fished whilst the men

title: KidsTown
summary: Every year the river would flood, causing the residents to move to higher ground on Daishs paddock, now home to KidsTown Adventure Playground.

title: Railway station
summary: This former railway station now houses the Railway Society Museum run by the Wonthaggi Historical Society. It is open every Saturday.

title: Wonthaggi Visitor Information Centre
summary: This sculpture represents the volume of coal each miner was expected to bring above ground each day!

title: Shaded rest area
summary: A quiet spot to sit under the trees and imagine the noisy steam locomotives chugging right past you, laden with coal from the State Coal Mine.

title: The walking track
summary: The walking tracks are well maintained and provide a nature trail alternative to walking or cycling along the road. Your dog will love it too.

title: State Coal Mine entrance
summary: Free entry to the site allows you to explore all the above ground facilities.  The site has historical buildings, a museum, a pit pony and steam locomotive.

title: Sheltered picnic area
summary: A relaxing place to eat, rest and digest all the information you have just learnt about Wonthaggis coal mining history.

title: Apex Park
summary: Is the final resting place for this historical poppet head and the State Coal Mine whistle. The whistle used to be heard 10 times a day and regulated the lives of many locals.

title: Wonthaggi State Coal Mine
summary: Go through the modern visitor centre and step into the past!  Pretend youre a miner arriving at work or a blacksmith going home to your cottage.

title: Fairfield Amphitheatre
summary: A scenic outdoor venue for performances and ceremonies which over-looks the Yarra River.

title: Fairfield boathouse
summary: The Fairfield boathouse was established in 1908 and restored and        re-opened in 1985.

title: Pipe bridge
summary: This pedestrian bridge is part of the Yarra River Trail.

title: Turn around point
summary: When you reach the road, its time to turn around and head back.

title: Divided path
summary: At this fork in the path, follow the path to the left.

title: Natural arch
summary: Nature has provided an archway over the path and a beautiful photo scene.

title: Native blossom
summary: As the seasons change, so do the plants in bloom.

title: Rainbow Lorikeet
summary: High up in the tree tops are the homes of many bird species.

title: A slow incline to start
summary: You’ll wake up your walking muscles as you head into the forest, but it’s a moderate climb so is suitable for all ages.

title: Crossing the creek
summary: A stairway and bridge takes you across the Stringybark Creek and onto the main track.

title: Follow the signs
summary: Along the track, you’ll find signage (starting at the beginning of the walk) and seats every now and again for you to take in the scenery.

title: Beautiful birdlife
summary: Whether you’re a keen birdwatcher or just enjoy the surprise of a fresh sighting of our feathered friends, you’ll love the number of birds you can see on this walk.

title: Healthy Forest
summary: As you walk along the trail, you will see wonderful old trees with detailed bark that tells its own story.

title: Spot the goanna
summary: A rustle in the forest floor can easily turn into the appearance of one of the many reptiles who make this their home.

title: Homes in the hollows
summary: There are numerous hollows beside the walking trails, and although it’s hard to guess who is at home in them, you can bet someone is.

title: Hello echidna!
summary: A rustle in the leaf litter might just mean there’s an echidna fossicking for food. If you see one, stand still because they’re very shy creatures and will try to hide from you.

title: Native orchids make for a special treat
summary: Throughout the year, over 43 orchid species including sun orchids (Thelymitra sp.) produce the most exquisite flowers at specific times of year.

title: Picnic time
summary: Whether you choose to start or finish with a bite to eat, a meal beneath the forest canopy makes for a fabulous picnic venue.

title: Werribee River Park
summary: Explore the beauty of the Werribee River and its natural surrounds.

title: Enjoy the views
summary: The river is lined by colourful Common Reed and looks as smooth and calm as the golf course behind it.

title: The track
summary: The gravel track runs off the escarpment and down to river level here.

title: K Road cliffs
summary: The striking red cliffs colour the horizon.  Its a great spot to watch birds too.

title: A feast for your eyes
summary: Layers of colour and varying landscapes make up this impressive view.

title: Footbridge over Werribee River
summary: The bridge joins this park to Werribee Park and Werribee Mansion.

title: Red Gum picnic area
summary: A natural setting under these magnificent trees which line the Werribee River.

title: Ramp
summary: A gently sloping ramp to take you from river level to the top of the escarpment.

title: Whistling Kites
summary: Whistling Kites soar above the ground, trees and water to search for prey such as carrion (dead animals) and small live animals such as mammals, birds, fish and insects.

title: Sitting ducks
summary: Sitting as still as their reflection.

title: Colourful common reeds
summary: With red cliffs in the background

title: Entrance Sign
summary: There are a number of informative signs at the entrance to the reserve, nearby the playground. These signs provide information about the walking tracks, and some of the reserve's flora and fauna.

title: Park Bench
summary: There are a number of park benches, like this one, throughout the reserve. These provide a great opportunity to rest and watch for birds, kangaroos and other animals.

title: Creek
summary: The reserve has two creeks running through it, connected to a billabong, that provide opportunities for looking for frogs and reptiles nearby. However, be wary of snakes in these areas.

title: Grassland Track Sign
summary: The tracks are well signposted, like this. Keep an eye out for kangaroos along the Grasslands Track as they tend to graze in this area.

title: River Red Gums
summary: The reserve has a number of large river red gum trees. Keep an eye out for these majestic trees as you complete the walk. Their hollows are excellent places to spot birds and mammals.

title: Wild Melbourne
summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialised in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

title: HV McKay Rural Discovery Centre - Campaspe Run
summary: Elmore’s tribute to the Sunshine Harvester, early pioneers and the sheep and grain industries. Campaspe Run is home to Elmore’s Community Quilt and has a fabulous gift shop. Open 7 days a week.

title: Overhead Railway Bridge
summary: The Overhead Bridge was opened on June 16 1928 (costing £454 to build) and removed Nov 24 1980. It was sold to the Elmore Progress Association and today links Campaspe Run and the EPA Museum.

title: Elmore Railway Station Water Tower
summary: Built in 1870 to supply water to steam trains, the 18'x15' tower was made from locally made bricks, with 27" thick walls. Water was pumped from the Campaspe River. Donated to the EPA in 1972.

title: Elmore Railway Station
summary: Opened 1870, originally named Runnymede Railway Station, the station was renamed Elmore Railway Station in 1876. The Queen travelled by train through Elmore on her 1954 tour.

title: Elmore Progress Association Museum
summary: Situated in the Railway Station Buildings, this volunteer run Museum is free and well worth a visit.

title: Victoria Hotel-Motel
summary: Built in the late 60’s to replace the gracious double-story Victoria Hotel.

title: Cardwell Street
summary: Gazetted as the main street & named after Rt. Hon. Edward Cardwell, Secretary of State for the Colonies, 1864. Traffic flow altered when a new bridge was built & Margaret St constructed in the 60’s.

title: Elmore Plaque Project
summary: Funded by property owners, the recently (2015) installed series of plaques relate the history of many buildings in Cardwell Street.

title: Former Parson’s Store
summary: This store was established in 1893 and traded as a general store until 1982. Today, Parson’s Store is used as a display area, storage and workroom for the Elmore Miniature Railway.

title: Michie Street
summary: Named after Hon. Sir Archibald Michie, MLC, MLA, Attorney-General.

title: Athenaeum Hall
summary: Built in 1885 for £800, & opened in 1886, the Athenaeum Hall was designed by W.C. Vahland & built by Mr G. Galbraith.

title: Elmore Scout Hall
summary: This former Methodist Church built in 1874 was purchased as the Scout Hall in 1983.

title: Michie Street Play Space
summary: Michie Street Play Space has a drinking fountain, shade sails, a range of play equipment, seating and a large grassed space at the rear.

title: Clarke Street
summary: Named after John Clarke, owner of Boramboot or Stewart’s Plains station from 1850-1852.

title: Uniting Church
summary: Originally St Andrew’s Presbyterian Church opened June 18 1899 (Vahland designed), the Uniting Church was formed by an amalgamation of Methodist & Presbyterian Churches in 1969.

title: Elmore and District Preschool
summary: The Preschool was built as an Infant Welfare Centre (circa 1960s) and extended as a Preschool in 1972.

title: Elmore Memorial Hall
summary: In 1920 it was proposed to build a Memorial to the local service men of World War 1 & provide work for some returned service men. Refer to the information board for more details.

title: Elmore CFA Fire Station
summary: The Fire Station was opened on September 26 1972, replacing the one in Railway Place (1910-1972). The former site is now known as Progress Park near the Raywood Road Rail Crossing.

title: Police Station
summary: The current station was built recently to replace the former station which was opened in 1968. The previous station was situated diagonally across the intersection (now a private residence).

title: Law Courts
summary: The building next to the Police Station was built as the Law Courts but is now privately owned and used as a Solicitors and Accountants office.

title: The Old Water Tower
summary: Used to store the town’s water supply (pumped from the Campaspe) the pumping station was on rails to move up the bank in times of flood. The station also produced the town’s electricity until 1948.

title: Coffee Palace/James’ Bakery
summary: Originally a Coffee Palace & later James’s Bakery which was well known as the place for lovely bread fresh from the oven, this building (south side of Cardwell St) is now a private residence.

title: Jeffrey Street
summary: Named after the Jeffrey brothers who owned Burnewang Station from 1852 to 1867.

title: The Old Mill
summary: Originally the site of the Runnymede (later Elmore) flour mill which traded for 85 years with just two owners. Demolished in 1958, The Old Mill Roadhouse is now a private residence.

title: Campaspe River Walking Track
summary: The Campaspe River Walking Track meanders alongside the captivating Campaspe River. Dotted along the track are information boards which highlight the unique attributes of this stretch of the river.

title: Campaspe River
summary: The Campaspe River rises in the Kyneton area & enters The River Murray at Echuca. Lake Eppalock (constructed by State Rivers & Water Supply Commission of Victoria 1961-64) is situated on the Campaspe.

title: Campaspe River Natural Play Space
summary: The Elmore Progress Association in conjunction with the City of Greater Bendigo are currently creating a natural play space on the former playground site. Parking, drink fountain & seating available.

title: Campaspe River Pepper Tree Avenue
summary: The Avenue of pepper trees between the Campaspe River Bridge and Childers Street along Campaspe Street was planted on August 10 1898. The trees were donated by the Elmore Water Trust.

title: Senior Citizens Flats (now Public Housing)
summary: The Catholic Church donated the triangle land (junction of Campaspe & Jeffrey Streets) to the former Shire of Huntly to build flats for Senior Citizens. Today they are Public Housing.

title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Catholic Church
summary: The Vahland designed Church was built in 1904. The Presbytery is next door.

title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Convent
summary: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Convent is situated on the corner of Jeffrey and Childers Streets.

title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Primary School
summary: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Primary School is commonly known as OLSH.

title: Elmore Bush Nursing Hospital
summary: The Bush Nursing Hospital, established in 1937, became the Elmore District Hospital until 1992 when smaller hospitals were amalgamated. The hospital buildings are now Elmore Primary Health Services.

title: Elmore Showgrounds
summary: The land immediately across the intersection was the site of the Elmore Showgrounds. A housing development is underway on this land.

title: Elmore Senior Citizens
summary: The Elmore Senior Citizens Clubrooms were built in 1973.

title: Brummy’s Seat
summary: An Elm tree with a circular seat placed around it, was known as Brummy’s Seat after Mr Bremner, blacksmith & Fire Brigade Capt, who loved to smoke his pipe & hide his tobacco in a hollow in the tree.

title: Water tower
summary: This water tower supplies the town and is a UV water purification plant.

title: Elmore Swimming Pool
summary: Opened on December 2 1959.

title: Elmore Cemetery
summary: Gazetted in 1872. The earliest internment is unknown but the earliest headstone reads, ‘Henry S. Alt, Age 2, 1867.’ Murder victim, John Duggan, (Corky Jack) was buried here in 1888.

title: Elmore Recreation Reserve
summary: Sporting facilities include football and cricket ground, netball courts, bowling greens, golf course, tennis courts, skate park, swimming pool and light harness racing track.

title: Silos
summary: Grain silos.

title: Elmore Miniature Railway/Apex Park
summary: Built on the site of the Cohuna Goods yard, the Elmore Miniature Railway (EMR) line extends for 1.5kms, with the EMR station situated at Apex Park.

title: Elmore Primary School
summary: Elmore Primary School 1515 opened March 23 1875.

title: Masonic Lodge
summary: The former Masonic Lodge was built in 1922. It is now privately owned.

title: St Peter’s Anglican Church
summary: The Vahland designed church was built in 1877, and the Parish Centre built in 1984.

title: Former Bank of NSW/Westpac
summary: This double story building on the South side of the street is now privately owned and operates as Elmore Old Wares.

title: Shopping Strip
summary: The current main shopping strip (extending left, right and over the pedestrian crossing), connects here with the original shopping strip - Cardwell Stree.

title: Campaspe Run Play Space
summary: Situated in the town centre between the Railway Station & Campaspe Run, the Campaspe Run Play Space has lush lawns, parking, public toilets, picnic tables & a BBQ. A great space to enjoy a picnic.

title: Post Office Bell
summary: Renowned Australian bell sculptor Dr Anton Hassall was involved in the casting of the bell.  "Littel Sister Bell" is suspended in the centre and chimes on the hour. Atop sits a corella figurine.

title: Painted Tiles 1997
summary: Images on the tiles reference changes in Horsham city life through the seasons.  The pictures are children of the five Horsham Primary Schools individual reflections on their culture and environment

title: White Hart Hotel
summary: Mark Twain stayed here during a visit to Horsham in the 1880's

title: 'Platanus acerifolia: Woven Nest' 2009
summary: This environmental work by Michael Shiell was installed as part of the 2009 'Art is...Elemental' Festival.  Michael's art practice is deeply seated in an ephemeral environmental response to the site.

title: Exchange Hotel
summary: One of the local Hotels in Horsham

title: Royal Hotel
summary: One of the oldest hotels in town

title: Original Horsham Letterbox
summary: This Original Horsham Letterbox inspired the design of the Post Office Bell sculpture in Firebrace St.

title: Horsham Aquatic Centre
summary: The outdoor 50m  pool was built in 1957 after the Melbourne Olympics, the smaller pool  in 1968 and the indoor heated polls in 2006. Also includes gym, Recreation Hall, Creche and cafe

title: Botanic Gardens, Established 1870's
summary: Sir William Guilfoyle planned these gardens between 1873 and 1880.  At teh time he was curator of the Royal Melbourne Botanic Gardens and planned many rural botanical gardens

title: City Oval
summary: This was the original site of the showgrounds from 1879-1897 when a storm wrecked the grandstand and buildings.  The site then became a recreational reserve and later city oval.

title: Wimmera Live Steam and Model Engineering Society
summary: This is a miniature railway which runs on special occasions

title: Sunrise along the Kangaroo Track
summary: With views to the horizon, one can't avoid the delights of the 'magic hour'.

title: Views across Wodonga and the Murray Valley
summary: The track is solid and provides great views to the north.

title: The Baranduda Range
summary: Another site to walk in the distance!

title: Before sunrise on Kangaroo Track
summary: Macfarlanes Hill is visible in the distance.

title: Tree silhouette
summary: It's great how these little 'windows on nature' pop up when least expected.

title: The start
summary: Start at Treasury Gardens at the statue of William John Clarke near Spring St.

title: The path to Fitzroy Gardens
summary: Already city noises start to fade into the distance. There are lots of seats along here and the whole walk. Listen for birds.

title: The gentle incline to the Fountain
summary: Once you cross Lansdowne St, get the blood pumping and pick up the pace along this gentle incline to the River God Fountain.

title: River God Fountain
summary: There is something wonderful about the sound of the water at this fountain. Take a moment to pause and look back down the Gardens.

title: Grey St Fountain
summary: This brilliant fountain and flower garden is about halfway.

title: The Rotunda
summary: The Rotunda was built in 1873 and is one of a few along the walk that can provide shelter during inclement weather.

title: The Fairy Tree and Tudor Village
summary: These two icons of the Gardens bring a smile to many. If you have children, why not bring them here on a weekend?

title: Captain Cook's Cottage
summary: Cooks' Cottage is on the left. Built in England in 1755 and said to be the oldest building in Australia, it was brought to Melbourne in 1934.

title: Finish on Spring St
summary: How's that for a walk? Hope you are feeling refreshed and alive and ready to face the working afternoon.

title: Williamstown timeball tower
summary: The Williamstown tower was built in 1849 of local bluestone. It was originally a lighthouse, and later served as a timeball tower from 1861 to 1926.

title: Williamstown railway station and historic footbridge
summary: Ann Street footbridge

title: View to Hobsons Bay
summary: Point Gellibrand Coastal and Heritage Park

title: Sculpture in Cyril Curtain Reserve
summary: Sculpture looking out to Hobsons Bay

title: The Rocks Williamstown
summary: Williamstown Football Clubrooms on Cyril Curtain Reserve

title: Foreshore from Hatt Reserve walking path
summary: Foreshore from Hatt Reserve walking path

title: Pelicans at Williamstown Beach
summary: Pelicans waiting for fish scraps from the fishermen at Williamstown Angling Club.

title: Williamstown Beach
summary: Williamstown Beach at Shelleys Beach Pavilion (formerly Sirens)

title: Gloucester Reserve
summary: The water here is known to locals as 'the crystal' because it is usually crystal clear and good for snorkelling.

title: Fishing village
summary: The fishing village made famous by artist, John Perceval, in his painting ‘Gannets diving’ 1956.

title: Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve
summary: Beach at Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve

title: Boardwalk at Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve
summary: Boardwalk at Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve  allows walkers to look around without endangering the flora and fauna.

title: Bird life
summary: Take your time and enjoy the swans, pelicans, gannets, ibis and many other birds that make the most of the lakes.

title: Cute bird
summary: Cute bird

title: Overview of Jawbone Flora and Fauna Park
summary: Looking back towards the city

title: Paisley-Challis Wetlands
summary: The path continues along Kororoit Creek to Altona Coastal Park and further on to Altona Beach

title: Victoria State Rose Garden - november
summary: 5500 roses in 6 acres . Managed by Parks Victoria, looked after by volunteers of the rose garden throughout the year. Beautiful and relaxing a great place to walk and smell the roses.  Romantic  too.

title: Festoons of roses surrounding the garden.
summary: In November , December the outer festoons of roses are a site to behold.

title: One of the standard avenue of roses Sevilliana
summary: Standand Avenue leading to the gazebo.

title: The corten steel arch leading into the rose garden
summary: start your walk here. The arch leads you into the rose garden.

title: Gazebo in the centre of the garden
summary: A focal point in the centre of the Tudor Rose garden. It is surrounded by rosees Victoria Gold and Pink Iceberg roses.

title: roses in bloom
summary: Rose Perfume Pefection as a standard Avenue is spectacular at the rose garded.

title: Westfield Knox City
summary: Our starting point and/or meeting point for this walk.  Knox City has  plenty of parking and cafes for that after-walk coffee.

title: Distance Signage
summary: The signage allows to gauge you are on the right track and gives you an idea of distance and time into your walk.

title: Wildwood Close Playground
summary: This simple playground can be a good break if you are walking with small children or you feel like a bit of swing yourself.

title: Lakewood Nature Reserve
summary: Lakewood Nature Reserve was part of the Scoresby Horticultural Research Station until the mid-1980s. The Reserve was formed in 1990, this allowed the protection of the native vegetation and wildlife.

title: Shared Path
summary: Please be aware that there is a shared path around the lake from this point on.

title: Lake Creek
summary: Take a peek at the lake for the first time here. There is potential for spotting frogs, nesting waterbirds or small fish, plus the beautiful view.

title: Conservation Area
summary: As meandering through the bushland track, don't forget to look into the canopy of the trees. You never know what you might see.

title: Lakewood Lake
summary: Constructed in 1985, the lake covers 3.3 hectares and has a maximum depth of two metres, perfect for the abandant waterbirds. The lake has a small jetty and an island to the east end.

title: A foggy, winter view to the Kiewa Valley.
summary: This vantage point is below the level of the picnic area and car park.

title: Huon Hill summit
summary: This is where the ascent levels out as it approaches the vehicle access picnic area.

title: Wodonga below the fog
summary: Looking out west across town

title: Northward - Albury under cover
summary: Views to Albury obscured by fog

title: Lake Hume: where?
summary: Under the sea of fog lies Lake Hume in the distance.

title: Liberty Swing
summary: The Liberty Swing is an accessible swing for children and adults who use a wheelchair, and gives them the ability to experience the joy and recreation of using a swing.

title: Dog Park
summary: A secure space to bring your dog to play or train.  It has two agility runs and biodegradable dog waste bags are provided at each entrance to the park. You will need to bring water for your dog.

title: Rest area with a view
summary: One of many rest areas around the park. Its a brilliant spot to sit and relax and simply take in the view.  You will often find many birds including ducks on this walk.

title: Children's play area
summary: A safe and fun play space for kids. Surrounded by beautiful trees that provide shade. Plenty of seating areas for mum and dad. Brilliant place for a picnic and some quality family time

title: Wildlife
summary: There are many beautiful birds that you are likely to come across on this walk. Of course they include ducks!

title: Bryces Flat
summary: A picnic area with plenty of shaded parking , this is a great place to leave your car while you walk.

title: The Blowhole
summary: The Blowhole is a remnant of the gold rush, created to expose gold in the water, and after heavy rainfall it appears to shoot water. Unfortunately, it is currently closed due to a recent rock fall.

title: Waterholes
summary: Even in the dry months of summer there are pools of clear water to dip your feet in on a hot day.

title: Ruins
summary: Keep an eye out and on the other side of the gully you'll spot an old stone wall, half-hidden in the bush.

title: Wildlife
summary: Small lizards are a common sight underfoot, and in the greener areas of the gully the odd wallaby can be spotted. Towards the end of the track you'll find this homely-looking cave on your right.

title: Breakneck Gorge
summary: A deep, tree-filled gorge that appears suddenly around a bend, Breakneck Gorge is a great place to watch birds in the treetops below.

title: Wild Melbourne
summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

title: Space man
summary: A vision of the future?  Who, what, where and how - well that's best left to the imagination.

title: Worm wall
summary: Wall full of lyrical whimsys.  Get up close and you'll find out who's lamenting what and other funny sayings.

title: Taxi rider
summary: Is the cat innocent or conspirator in this midnight adventure?

title: Lemming wall
summary:
Who's naming the lemmings?
Lemmings or meerkats?  Where are they going? Lemme know!

title: Amnesty International wall
summary: Fantastic series of wall panels describing the work of Amnesty International (it's where their office is).

title: Mermaid under attack
summary:
So much to marvel here.  Make sure you look up and around.  Also check out the laneway nearby too, it has lots of hidden secrets!

Thank goodness for colourful and creative types.

title: Whitlam Place
summary: Check out the back wall of this park. Are the pictures of local residents?

title: Playground
summary: Let your child run free in this well designed playground. There is a range of different equipment for climbing, swinging and exploring. Includes a swing with harness and double-width slide.

title: Bird hide and billabong
summary: This bird hide is the perfect spot to have a look at who might be nestling or feeding in the water. You might like to have a look at the tree farm near the billabong to see what's growing there too.

title: BBQ, seats and shade
summary: This is the perfect spot for a picnic, BBQ and to refill your water bottle.

title: Beautiful gum trees
summary: There are many beautiful gum trees lining the side of the ovals and creek. A shady spot and a great reminder of how the looked before it was colonised.

title: Don't feed the birds
summary: Contrary to popular opinion, it's not healthy for ducks and birds to eat bread. This can lead to poor health, loss of hunting and foraging skills, and dependence on humans. See link below.

title: Archery Club
summary: Stay away from the archery paddock is archers are in action! Obviously, don't cough or sneeze too close to them either, in case ....

title: Dog training
summary: Furry friends of all colours and sizes are often seen in the park. It's a popular spot for dog walkers.

title: Under the bridge art
summary: Clearly, the artist feels an affinity with the furry creatures that frequent the area.

title: Glass Creek revegetation works
summary: A beautiful array of indigenous plant seedlings were recently been planted. These include River Red gums, native grasses and bottlebrushes. This area should look spectacular in a few years.

title: End of path
summary: The path ends rather abruptly at the road. Council have painted a section here but there is no footpath. You can continue on here carefully, or take the long and scenic route back the way you came.

title: Aquamoves Lakeside Shepparton
summary: First of all the path takes you past the Aquamoves swimming complex, which has a variety of different pools and playgrounds. Entry is via Tom Collins Drive.

title: Greater Shepparton's All Abilities Playground
summary: This playground is a good stop for the kids. It has tables and chairs, toilets, water fountains, slides and all kinds of play equipment. Children are required to have adult supervision in the park.

title: The Jetty
summary: A boardwalk allows you to walk out over the water. The wood can become slippery when it is wet and ther aren't guardrails all the way along it.

title: Shepparton Canoe Club
summary: At the waters edge near the canoe club there is a sandy beach and a small boat ramp. There is also toilets near the canoe club.

title: Cafe and Greater Sheparton Visitor Information Center
summary:
At the cafe there are indoor and outdoor tables as well as toilets. The cafe provides the opportunity to purchase a drink and take a break along the way.
The visitor centre is next door.

title: Picnic areas
summary: Along the track there a number of BBQ areas with tables and facilites.

title: Skate Park
summary: The skate park is a popular park for the young children and the big kids too. There are occasionally competitions held and there is always someone to watch.

title: Slavonija deli
summary: This deli has an unassuming exterior, but inside, it's full of delightful treats.  I particularly recommend their boreks and poppyseed rolls.  Closes around 2pm so make sure you get there early.

title: Mumbai Mirch
summary: Spices, sauces, pickles, herbs, snacks, pots, pans - everything you need to make a delicious Indian meal.  Next door's restaurant is simple and tasty, though service can be a bit leisurely.

title: Hanna's coffee
summary: Hanna opened this coffee shop maybe 4 years ago.  It's a busy place stocked with nuts, interesting biscuits, sweets and magazines.  Regular patrons are the older fellas from the former Yugoslavia.

title: Cake shop
summary: This shop has a fine display in the window.  Filled with cakes, rolls and a few Vietnamese buns, it's always a good place to stop to check out what's on offer.

title: Vietnamese deli
summary: There are all sorts of mysterious and delicious food items here.  Some are sweet, some savoury, some both sweet AND savoury!  I don't quite remember what they're called so I just point at what I want.

title: Ha Noi Pho
summary: Tucked in a laneway is my favourite Vietnamese restaurant.  The owner Dao is lovely and hospitable.  The pho is terrific. My favourite dish is lemongrass beef wrapped in vine leaves.

title: Chinese chess
summary: If you loiter long enough, you might learn how to play Chinese chess from one of the locals.  A popular pastime for the blokes visiting Alfrieda Street.

title: Chilli bakery
summary: I usually have an egg and salad roll from here, though there are many variations to choose from.  There is a short wait as this is probably the most popular place for Vietnamese rolls in the area.

title: Fish galore
summary: There are a couple of fishmongers on this side.  I try to pick sustainable fish from Australia (snapper is always yummy).

title: Vietnamese grocery stores
summary: This is one of many Vietnamese grocery stores in the area.  I like checking out the aisles of cans and bottles from different places.  There's plenty of fresh veg that I've never seen elsewhere too.

title: Shady seats
summary: Take a seat here and stop to watch the crowds go by.

title: St Albans market
summary: St Albans market has cheap and fresh fruit and veg.  Unfortunately there was a fire recently.  I hope it's open again soon!

title: Wildlife - kookaburra & snake
summary: A kookaburra chick being fed a tiger snake by its parent.

title: Trail waypoint
summary: Waypoint marker displaying orientation and distance of key landmark features.

title: Wildlife - orb weaver spider
summary: An orb weaver spider preparing its web for the evening.

title: Unpaved, natural path
summary: An option for the curious seeking a more natural setting when walking.

title: River view
summary: A view of the river as seen from the football oval.

title: Parks & picnics
summary: Open parklands along the river provide the perfect spots for large or small picnics

title: Tree-scape view
summary: A view of  the river and surrounding tree-scape extending into the distant suburbs.

title: River crossings
summary: One of the many bridges spanning the river.

title: Running track
summary: Running is frequently enjoyed along the picturesque trail.

title: Wild Melbourne
summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

title: Read the sign
summary: You’ll need to familiarise yourself with the rules: only walk through the green gates (& close them) then follow the orange arrows.

title: Follow the orange markers
summary: You could get lost at some points during this walk if you stray off the track in the grass sections (and end up in the middle of a paddock). Arrows are helpfully spotted along the fence lines.

title: Olive groves
summary: Just one of many agricultural pursuits that populate the agricultural profile of this region, olives are on the menu.

title: Valley views
summary: There are numerous views of the Latrobe Valley on this walk, from all sorts of perspectives.

title: Diverse landscapes
summary: As you wander through the paddocks, you come across forests of pines, grasslands, the coal country and the mountains beyond.

title: Down the track
summary: There’s something special about this track, as you find yourself coming close to farmhouses while at the same time finding yourself in the middle of a vast view.

title: Follow the fence line
summary: There are tracts of this walk that take you through mowed paddocks, mostly along the fence line but then cutting through paddocks, forests and nearby farms. It feels good to take this stroll.

title: Who was CJ Tyers?
summary: Once you’ve done this walk, you may wonder how Tyers got its name. Interpretative signage will give you the answers you’re looking for.

title: Ring Road versus tranquility!
summary: It is an interesting juxtaposition – the big busy noisy freeway versus the small peaceful walking track. I know which one I would rather be on!

title: Ducks and ducklings
summary: The river and wetlands is swarming with birdlife, we were lucky to be there to see this family of duck and ducklings.

title: Lots of waterways in the wetlands
summary: Depending on rainfall the rivers and ponds can be plentiful with lots of lush foliage surrounding them.

title: Johnstone Street Reserve
summary: This Reserve has it all! Big new BBQ area, skate park, playground, heaps of grassed area and even 2 flying foxes!

title: Back to the real world - careful crossing the road
summary: Back to the real world - careful crossing the road

title: Great view looking back over the jaunt
summary: Make sure you turn around and have a look back into the valley, you can see how far you have come.

title: Careful crossing the busy road
summary: There is an overpass over the Western Ring Road, however walkers need to be careful crossing the off-shoot road – there are pedestrian traffic lights.

title: Turn right and cross the bridge
summary: When you get to the bridge, turn right to head towards Johnstone Street Reserve. If you want to head straight check out the walk “Moonee Ponds Creek Trail – Westmeadows” as this is its starting point.

title: You take the high road, I'll take the low road
summary: Again, you have options where to walk! Take the low road (right hand) and follow the valley to continue with this particular route.

title: Access to Jacana Station
summary: When exiting/entering Jacana Station it is best to use the pedestrian tunnel under the busy Pascoe Vale Road.

title: While the cars slog away above its peaceful down here!
summary: At this point of the walk you are basically directly under the Western Ring Road. If you wish you can turn left here, go under the Road and head south, however to continue with this route head straigh

title: So many options where to walk
summary: There are lots of signs along the way showing walkers where they are where they can go – almost too many options!

title: Robert Booth Reserve
summary: Start at Robert Booth Reserve. Bus stop on Clow Street. The reserve offers an off-leash dog park, playgrounds, sporting fields and an athletics track.

title: A lush start
summary: This part of the walk is particularly leafy and green. Enjoy the shade!

title: Watch out for trail regulars
summary: This walking and cycling track covers miles north and south, so you're bound to spot cyclists and joggers in training along the creek path.

title: Art sculpture
summary: As you walk towards Heatherton Road, you're bound to spot the Freedom Cycle sculpture. A bright cut-out style design of a cyclist taking off out of a yellow square!

title: Underpass at Heatherton Road
summary: Walk up onto Heatherton Road and down to the underpass on the other side of the creek. Avoid the underpass if flooded.

title: A swimming spot?
summary: We're not sure if this is a good idea but we have seen it with our own eyes! Someone went for a quick dip in the wetlands and we think, lived to tell the tale.

title: Handy signposts
summary: If you're keen to get your bearings, there are signposts dotted along the creek trail, with distances from major roads and venues. Handy if you're keen to walk further!

title: In search of shade
summary: Wetlands are typically shrub-filled spots, so it's always a relief to find a huge tree offering shade for many. Stop here a while if the sun is high in the sky.

title: Playground
summary: This is a wonderful playground for all ages, with toilet facilities nearby.

title: Covered BBQ area
summary: After a long walk, catch your breath over a BBQ lunch or have a rest in the shade. We spotted two studious locals studying outdoors the day we visited. Great idea!

title: Dandenong Stadium
summary: One of the largest stadiums of its kind in the southern hemisphere, you might like to explore this venue, visit the cafe or use the facilities. It's said to attract 15,000 visitors each week!

title: Myuna Farm (across the creek)
summary: Across the creek is Myuna Farm. A popular spot for saying hello to farm animals, learning from the farmers, having a bite to eat and even taking a train ride around the property. Admission fees apply.

title: The Age building
summary: Check the screen at ‘The Age’ building for the news, weather and time.

title: The Grand Hotel
summary: The Grand Hotel is the former Victorian Railways Head Office. It has a strange train-like sculpture in the front.

title: Batman Park
summary: Rebecca Walk is a group of eclectic shops in Batman Park. There is an enormous pigeon coop near King St.

title: SeaLife Melbourne Aquarium
summary: Cross King St to SeaLife Melbourne Aquarium perched at the corner of Kings Bridge.

title: Enterprize Park
summary: Enterprize Park where the first settlers on the ship Enterprize went ashore on 30 August 1835.

title: Scar Project
summary: Indigenous artists created the ‘Scar Project’ (decorated sculptures) from original wharf poles from Queens Bridge.

title: Banana Alley
summary: These railway vaults were built to support the rail viaduct that connected the stations at Flinders Street and Spencer Street.

title: Sandridge Bridge
summary: Sandridge Bridge used to be the gateway for Port Melbourne trains crossing the Yarra River. Now it houses ‘The Travellers’, giant steel sculptures representing immigrants to our shores.

title: Pony fish Island and Pedestrian Bridge
summary: Pony fish Island is perched under the Pedestrian Bridge that is weighted down by locks hooked on by lovers. The Eureka Tower dominates the background.

title: Arbory Cafe
summary: ‘Arbory’ café sits in between Flinders Walk and Flinders Street Railway Station.

title: Princes Bridge
summary: Princes Bridge with the Arts Centre spire in the background from Flinders Walk.

title: Federation Square
summary: At Federation Square there are cafes, ACMI, special events and the Melbourne Visitor Centre for all things touristy.

title: Flinders Street Railway Station
summary: Flinders Street Railway Station

title: St Paul's Cathedral
summary: St Paul's Cathedral

title: City Square
summary: Melbourne's City Square hosts many events during the year.

title: Melbourne Town Hall
summary: The Melbourne Town Hall is a focal point of the city and hosts many events.

title: Chinatown
summary: At Lt Bourke St is Chinatown with many options to eat Asian.

title: QV shopping centre
summary: QV shopping centre was built on the site of the The Queen Victoria Memorial Hospital. One of the original buildings still stands in Lonsdale St. It now houses the Queen Victoria Women’s Centre.

title: State Library Victoria
summary: The State Library is a popular spot for lounging on the lawns at lunchtime. The free wifi is an added attraction. It also holds many talks, discussions and exhibitions, which are usually free.

summary: 1. Federation Square

summary: 29. Princes Bridge

title: Union St pavers
summary: See up to 40 mosaic pavers made by local residents, many of them are set in wonderful nature strips of indigenous plants (some have a few pests like agapanthus).

title: The seahorse
summary: The seahorse paver is a beauty!

title: Bird of Paradise mosiac
summary: Bird of Paradise, there is one in a front yard too.

title: Crossing Westgarth St, Watch out for fast cars!
summary: Cars coming racing around the bind corner from Merri Pde, so watch out! VicRoads puts the speed limit at 60 km/h which is absolutely ridiculous. When will they learn?

title: Dog off leash area
summary: This big off leash area is a great walk even if you don't have a dog. You can even walk down to the creek or up along the train line but watch out for trains if you have kids.

title: The mural
summary:
Love this mural but don't know much about it though. 

Unfortunately, the mural has now been painted over :((

title: Rushall community garden
summary: Sometimes I sit on the hill among the indigenous grasses and trees and watch the gardeners.

title: Community garden mural
summary: My kids love this wild looking vegetable!

title: Rushall station, no cycling!
summary: Despite the no cycling signs, many cyclists illegally ride in the underpass. Some don't even bother to ring their bell (very inconsiderate!). Makes it hard for kids and elderly.

title: The shared path
summary: They recently widened the path which is great. So many wonderful plants and animals, walkers and riders. It is always interesting, the light changes with the seasons and time of day.

title: The Merri Creek
summary: The joy of the sound of running water. Sometimes I walk along here at night in winter, shut my eyes and think of the bush. A saw a snake here once.

title: Inner - Gary Deirmendjian, 2005
summary: Made of sandstone, the installation aims to evoke and question the tensions between one's objective and subjective realities - the former striving for perspective and the latter for engagement.

title: Meant To Be - Colin Langridge, 2005
summary: Mean To Be is the result of developing the cooperating process of wooden construction, where bent wooden laths are shaped to form hollow containers.

title: Zephyr - Tim Edwards, 2005
summary: Zephyr is a sculptural self portrait by Edwards. The interface of the human and the machine is a source of contemplation acting as a metaphor for production, aspiration and restriction.

title: The Comrade's Reward - William Eicholtz, 2004
summary: This popular 19th century genre is reintrepreted in an eclectic and contemporary way, deliberately references antiquity and unfashionable ideas of heroism and folly within a camp and knowing artifice.

title: Ether - Ari Purhonen, 2002
summary: Ether embodies an optical effect produced by the natural phenomenon of light. Rotating vertically around the axis, the illusion is created by an optical interference patter within the sculpture.

title: Death of white good - Alexander Knox, 2005
summary: Far from the chaos of an airline crash, Death of a White Good is a picturesque ruin. It is unclear if seconds or millennia have transpired since the crash.

title: As weeks go by - Laurens Tan, 2004
summary: As Weeks Go By represents 4 weeks of time as they disappear before our eyes, including the opportunities built into each day as represented by randomly perforated cans.

title: Meniscii - Julia Davis, 2007
summary: Meniscii explores the perceptions of, and relationships between objects, spaces and places. In particular the relationship between the earth and the sky.

title: Migration - Ian Burns & John Clark, 2005
summary: Migration is concerned with movement and the relationship between the individual components and the mas they represent in formation.

title: Meanwhile... Down South in Tasmania - Bob Jenyns, 2005
summary: This sculpture explores the way in which aspects of history repeats itself, often in unexpected and ironical ways.

title: Hut - Karen Ward 2000
summary: Hut symbolises the house, the home, the shack, the cubby-house and he hermit's retreat. It also alludes to the potential to dream that is inherent within all of these structures.

title: Fractal construction - David Jensz, 2005
summary: The curved form of Fractal Construction approximates the end of a massive pipe projecting from the ground.

title: Prosthetic apartment B - Richard Goodwin, 2004
summary: Prosthetic Apartment B is an installation which creates a building within Werribee Park. As a site-specific work it brings the idea of habitation to a public park.

title: Portal to another time and place - Deborah Halpern, 2004
summary: As related by Halpern, her work is 'An arch in the shape of a face, leaning on its nose. To see something whimsical, surprising and delightful in the landscape is always inspiring'.

title: Swarm - Nigel Helyer
summary: Swarm consists of a series of laser cut acrylic objects closely resembling microscopic marine forms, each supporting a solar powered digital circuit, amplifier and speaker.

title: Exoskeleton pod - Richard Goodwin 2000
summary: Exoskeleton Pod speculate about minimum architectures and the point at which the body stops and architecture begins.

title: Remannt - Mike Taylor, 2004
summary: A burnt gum tree gives Remnant its primary form but the work has much to do with historical allusions as natural forces.

title: Upperground - Ewen Coates, 2006
summary: Upperground resembles a cathedral structure; raising questions about the relevance  of the church and evolution of traditional teachings, in an era when religion causes schisms in our world.

title: Passage - Fiona Orr, 2002
summary: The concept of the frame has strong associations with history, painting and museums. Orr's been developing sculptural frames over recent years and is interested in taking the frame out of the gallery.

title: Rothko's chapel - Konstantin Dimopoulos, 2007
summary: Rothko's Chapel is a dynamic sculpture exploring and expressing through colour, line and movement, the simple and reverential colour variations of renowned 20th century painter Mark Rothko.

title: Werribee River
summary: Take a rest along the river and enjoy the scenery.

title: Wall - Mark Stoner, 2002-03
summary: Wall is suggestive of great density and permanence; it is tough and uncompromising in its form - asserting itself within the landscape but remaining separate from it.

title: Werribee Park Historic Orchard
summary: Planted in the late 1800s, the orchard produced apples, quinces, pear and stone fruits.

title: Werribee Park
summary: Werribee Park has superbly landscaped gardens that seem to stretch on forever. In it are many heritage trees and curious plants from exotic countries.

title: Werribee Mansion
summary: Built in the late 1880s by the Chirnside brothers, successful pastoralists from Scotland. The Chirnside family lived here till the 1920s. The site was later used as a seminary by the Catholic Church.

title: Alexandra Fountain and historic tram
summary: Alexandra Fountain and historic tram

summary: Rosalind Park entrance on View St

summary: Bridge over the Bendigo Creek in Rosalind Park

title: Golden Dragon Museum
summary: Golden Dragon Museum entrance to garden

title: Colourful parrots having a bath
summary: Colourful parrots having a bath

title: Path crosses the Spring Spring Creek
summary: Path crosses the Spring Spring Creek on the Back Creek Trail near the Bendigo Tennis Academy

summary: Lake Weeroona

title: Lake Weeroona
summary: Lake Weeroona from the middle

summary: Interesting bridge over the Bendigo Creek

summary: Start of the O'Keefe Rail Trail which is gravel

summary: The path terminates here so cross this bridge to the other side.

summary: White Hills Public Cemetery gates

title: White Hills Public Cemetery Chinese graves
summary: About 1000 Chinese are buried in White Hills Public Cemetery from Gold Rush times.

title: Bendigo Botanic Gardens
summary: Cross the bridge to the opposite bank for a side trip to the Bendigo Botanic Gardens. Definitely worth a look.

title: Pavilion made in Gold Rush times in Bendigo Botanic Gardens
summary: Pavilion made in Gold Rush times in Bendigo Botanic Gardens
