summary: Bendigo Botanic Gardens

title: Bird feeding upside down on nectar
summary: Bird feeding upside down on nectar

title: Friendly horse near Epsom
summary: Friendly horse near Epsom

title: Bendigo Creek Trail map
summary: Bendigo Creek Trail map. The trail ends here in Epsom. Turn right into Howard St for a shopping centre with cafe for a break before returning into Bendigo.

title: BBQ and Picnic Area
summary: Start and end point of the walk.

title: Look Out
summary: View Beaufort from above

title: Oyster Track Junction
summary: Take Oyster Track

title: Fork in the road
summary: Take the left track

title: Fork in the road
summary: Take the left track

title: Connect with Camp Hill Road
summary: Turn right onto Camp Hill Road and continue to the BBQ and Picnic Area

title: Furry Friends
summary: If your quite might come across some of the local wild life

title: Grahams Wetland Reserve
summary: Wander through a vast area of wetlands, with the You Yangs in the distance and boats bobbing in the bay to your left. It's largely unsigned and without paths, but impressive all the same.

title: Werribee South Boat Ramp
summary: Beside the wetlands, where the Werribee River meets the bay, there's a marina of jetties and boats waiting to set sail. Excellent pathways and facilities here, if needed.

title: Look out for birdlife
summary: Look out across to the pointy sandbank on the other side of the river mouth. Here you might spot birdlife relaxing on the shore. This area is home to flora and fauna unseen in other parts of the bay.

title: JD Bellin Reserve
summary: This area is adjacent to the Werribee South Boat Ramp and offers an excellent spot to have a picnic or BBQ, with new facilities, toilets and a playground for the kids.

title: Boy sculpture
summary: As you walk along the shared foreshore pathway, you can't miss 'Boy' a sculpture of a young child's silhouette gazing at the grasslands. This piece is part of Wyndham Council's public art collection.

title: Price Reserve
summary: If you're in need of more space, Price Reserve (on Beach Rd) offers ovals and playing fields, a playground, toilets and a take away store, tucked away at the rear of the reserve on O'Connor Street.

title: Werribee South foreshore beach
summary: While you're here, why not wade in the shallows and walk along the shoreline? You can reconnect with the shared foreshore pathway when you've had enough of the sand in your toes or when the path ends.

title: Werribee South market gardens
summary: There aren't too many places in the world where vegetables grow across the road from a beach! With 41% of Victoria's food grown in this region, it's a good time to stop and savour what's around us.

title: Pathways under construction
summary: This new stretch of path leads to Wyndham Harbour, following new residential developments, past the marina that is currently under construction. It promises to be a thriving hub in years to come.

title: Wyndham Harbour foreshore
summary: If you're feeling peckish, you can finish the walk at Joe's Cafe and explore the new Wyndham Harbour foreshore area. While still under construction in October 2015, it's due to be completed very soon!

title: Choose your own adventure
summary: Choose the track that best suits your needs and timing.

title: Billabong
summary: A good place to listen to the frog symphony.

title: Beach turn off - short cut
summary: If you prefer a shorter route to the beach, turn left here, or keep going for a longer walk.

title: Variety of trees
summary: That's my educated guess!

title: Track becomes a bit sandier
summary: Walking on sandier tracks is a good workout for the legs.

title: Beach views
summary: Best to take your hat off here or have it blown away by the strong winds.

title: Beach walk
summary: Take a walk along the beach for as much as you like. Then you can follow the same route back, or take the short cut back to the car park (it's more scenic).

title: Tunnel
summary: We loved walking through this tunnel of tea trees.

title: More trees
summary: Yup.

title: Zombie mingling point
summary: Zombies have an hour before the walk sets off to admire each other's gruesome costumes and disgusting makeup.

title: La Trobe Street
summary: The shuffle gains momentum...

title: Bourke Street Mall
summary: The crowd really gathers here, it's prime zombie shuffling territory. Make sure you put forward your most hideous face for the cameras!

title: Flinders Street Station
summary: A great place for iconic zombie photos.... Can be rather dangerous crossing the road - be sure to follow directions of police.

title: Footscray Community Arts Centre
summary: A little way along to the left is Footscray Community Arts Centre  known for exhibitions, classes, venue hire and the magnificent bluestone building it is housed in.

title: Bunbury St railway bridge
summary: Bunbury St railway bridge- note the face underneath

title: Heavenly Queen Temple
summary: Further along the Maribyrnong River is the Heavenly Queen Temple , a Buddhist temple complex and statue of the Heavenly Queen next to the railway bridge.

summary: Heavenly Queen near the railway bridge

summary: Newells Paddock comes into view just as you see the former cattle bridge across the river.

title: Footscray Park
summary: Footscray Park is a little oasis of greenery.

title: Edgewater Lake
summary: The path passes Edgewater Lake on the left and crosses Burndap Park Island in between the Maribyrnong River and Edgewater Housing Estate.

title: Pipemakers Park
summary: Pipemakers Park is next with its unusual dolphin statue and the Living Museum of the West.

title: Anglers Tavern
summary: Anglers Tavern, an icon on the river for decades. It constantly gets flooded when the Maribyrnong River breaks its banks.

title: Band Rotunda
summary: On the opposite bank is the Band Rotunda erected by the Essendon River League in 1922 and The Boathouse Restaurant

title: Viewing stone steps for regattas
summary: This is a prominent spot for regattas among the many rowing clubs in this area. The stone steps are a popular viewing platform.

title: Afton St bridge
summary: Cross the river at the Afton St bridge

title: Pirate ship playground
summary: There are playgrounds dotted along the river. This one has a magnificent pirate ship as its focus.

summary: The footbridge at Pipemakers Park is an alternative crossing point on the river.

title: Thomastown Library
summary: It is a large and bright space with a spacious childrens area and collections in Arabic, Italian, Macedonian and Turkish.

title: Oval Scoreboard
summary: If you pass the scoreboard you know you are on the right track.

title: Path and Playground
summary: The first playground on the walk with lots of activities for the kids.

title: Optional Detour
summary: Optional scenic detour along a dirt track which brings you closer to the flora along the creek.

title: Detour pathway
summary: A view along the detour pathway

title: Creek View
summary: A view along the creek bank with signs of recent native flora revegetation work.

title: Second Playground
summary: Another great opportunity for the kids to sea-saw, climb and swing.

title: Wooden seat
summary: A beautiful carved wooden seat offers the opportunity for a rest.

title: Entrance to the church grounds
summary: After crossing the bridge you will see the entrance to the church grounds.

title: Church Gate
summary: The old church gate with the wonderful 1850s Lutheran church in the background.

title: A Tree Outside Historic Ziebells Farmhouse
summary: Our first view of the old 1850s farmhouse.

title: Ziebells Farmhouse Gardens
summary: A view of the wonderfully maintained gardens in Ziebells Farmhouse.  The buildings here represent the heart of Ziebells original 102 acre farm, built between 1851 and 1856.

title: Gazebo and Barbecue
summary: A optional start and end point of the walk offers the chance to enjoy a barbecue at the end of your walk.

title: Library Mural
summary: Part of a large mural running along the rear of the library building.

title: Old Mornington Post office
summary: The old Mornington Post Office is now a museum of all things postal. The inside is original and takes you back to the days of massive wall-mounted wooden telephones.

title: Mornington Park to Fishermans Beach, Mornington
summary: Mornington Park has a children's playground, barbecues and picnic facilities.

title: Entrance to foreshore track
summary: Entrance to foreshore track that winds its way behind the Mornington Bowling Club.  Single file only on a dirt track.

title: Access point to water views
summary: One of the many access points with seating to water views

title: Mornington Bowling Club from The Esplanade
summary: A friend we met on the way back along The Esplanade on the fence of Mornington Bowling Club.

title: A view of the coast
summary: A view of the coast

title: Marker 7 Europeans meet the Aboriginal people
summary: This is Marker Seven - one of several we saw on the day along the path.

title: A glimpse of the City of Melbourne
summary: A glimpse of the City of Melbourne

title: A flock of seagulls
summary: A flock of seagulls on the beach near Fishermans Beach boat ramp

title: Another view of the coast
summary: Another view of the coast

title: Diver sculpture
summary: At the entrance stands the sculpture ‘Diver’. It is carved out of bluestone and appears to be a duck diving into the bluestone paving

title: Pavey’s Picnic Area
summary: To the left of the entrance is Pavey’s Picnic Area where there are barbecues and a sheltered seating area.

title: Map of Lakes Nature Trail
summary: Information on Newport Lakes Reserve

title: The Main Lookout
summary: Number one is the main lookout when you first walk in.

title: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing are number four.
summary: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing are number four. Note the purple swamphen on the path - one of the many birds attracted to the area

title: Two is the amphitheatre
summary: Two is the amphitheatre, an open area where concerts sometimes are held.

title: Three is the Waterfall
summary: Three is the Waterfall where stormwater gathers in the park and is recycled through a series of pipes and ponds.

title: At six there is a bird viewing area
summary: At six there is a bird viewing area built by the Friends of Newport Lakes in 1999.

title: Frog mosaic
summary: There are many mosaics dotted around the park depicting the wildlife.

title: The path
summary: The path is gravel and steep in some areas.

title: Open area
summary: Open area accessible to the lake where birds feed.

title: Picnic area
summary: Tables are available for picnics. No shops so bring your own food. Water is available at the entrance barbecue area.

title: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing
summary: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing are number four.

title: Lake and gravel path
summary: Lake and gravel path

title: Newport Lakes Indigenous Nursery
summary: After wandering around Newport Lakes Reserve you may be inspired to take home some vegetation. Newport Lakes Indigenous Nursery is adjacent to the carpark.

title: View of both lakes
summary: View of both lakes

title: Monkey
summary: This laneway usually has a couple of illustrative pieces, mostly sprays but sometimes stencils. My favourite is this funny little monkey man. Will he still be there when you walk by?

title: Darren's Owls
summary: Darren Henderson is a local artist who has a thing for owls... And I love these!  See if you can spot another of his owls when you get to Wall Two 80 further in the walk

title: Big Men Laughing
summary: These guys are HUGE! And this vacant site where they are is the biggest graffiti canvas in Balaclava. Walk this way often for an ever changing exhibition.

title: Railway Walk Brick
summary: Good big brick walls here are always covered and often turned over with new pieces. Look at the detaills to see messages between artists and how they respond to eachother's work.

title: Railway Walk Tin
summary: If tags are your thing then this section of the railway walk is for you.

title: Wall Two 80
summary: Wall Two 80 is a favourite local cafe, and its big outside wall is always covered with art.

title: The End of the Wall
summary: It's worth walking to the end of the wall as curious little bits of street art pop up here. Paste ups, stencils, the odd diorama...

title: Dragon Lane
summary: This is a long way from the rest of the walk but it is worth it. On one side is a huge and amazing Chinese themed piece that is the biggest single piece I've seen. On the other is an awesome mix up!

title: Tile Faces
summary: I forgot to put this in the walk and can't change the map, but it's good to go for a wander through the playground at the Williams St reserve just nearby, there are sneaky tiled faces stuck on walls!

title: Murchison Heritage Centre
summary: Located out the side of the museum is a large pump that was used to pump water from the river for the townspeople.

title: River bank gardens, boardwalk and three information lecterns
summary: Discover Murchisons bygone era with images of the old streetscape, pub and paddle steamers. The boardwalk provides an impressive view of the Goulburn River.

title: Aboriginal Protectorate Station
summary: Signage marks the location of the protective that operated from 1840-1853. This is one of only four stations established in the then colony of Port Phillip.

title: Roderick Square
summary: Roderick Square was the original proposed river crossing point however, the river crossing was constructed in Robinson Street in 1871

title: Murchison cemetery and the Italian Ossario (Mausoleum)
summary: Grave of King Charles Tattambo, 1866, a local Aboriginal who was buried here as his dying wish was to buried in a box like a white man. The Ossario hold the remains of a number of Italians from WWII

title: Longleat Wines
summary: Home to a selection of delectable indulgences.

title: Maffra Visitor Information Centre
summary: The  Centre is located in the historic Maffra Courthouse building in Johnson Street, and is full of the most intriguing gems, crystals, fabulous fossils and fluorescent minerals.

title: Macalister River  Country
summary: The views in this area are particularly beautiful.

title: Suitable for riding or walking
summary: The trail is predominantly flat and easy going on packed gravel.

title: Tinamba Hotel
summary: First Established In 1874, the hotel is still catering for travellers - bookings essential for meals,

title: Carpark
summary: Carpark with Info Sign

title: Great Western Primary School
summary: Great Western Primary School

title: Great Western Shop
summary: Fantastic Shop including Post Office

title: Great Western Hotel
summary: Great Western Hotel

title: Salinger's Cafe
summary: Salinger's Café is the perfect spot to stop for lunch

title: Petrol Station
summary: Just incase you need a refill

title: War Memorial Gates
summary: Great Western War Memorial Park commemorates those who served in World War Two.

title: Old Police Camp Gaol
summary: Old Police Camp Gaol

title: Toilets and Park
summary: Toilet and Park

title: Seppelt Winery View
summary: Seppelt Winery View

title: Seppelt Winery View
summary: Seppelt Winery View

title: Seppelt Winery
summary: Walk through the Carpark and go on in for a visit. Founded in 1851 Seppelt Winery has so much history winemakers at Seppelts have been crafting wines of quality and diversity for many years.

title: Seppelt Winery
summary: Walk through the Carpark and go on in for a visit. Founded in 1851 Seppelt Winery has so much history winemakers at Seppelts have been crafting wines of quality and diversity for many years.

title: Watch Out as you go a bit bushland, the road turns to Gravel
summary: How Fun!

title: Best's Winery
summary: Founded in 1866,  one of Australia's oldest family owned wineries with some of the oldest vines in the country.

title: Quarry St Reserve
summary: A peaceful park surrounding a pond that many waterbirds have made their home. A good spot for a picnic.

title: Stoney Creek Reserve
summary: A patch of bushland along a creek which is well managed by the local community.

title: Birdlife
summary: Birdlife is abundant around town. Here, a flock of corellas sweeps up into the trees above a paddock beside Stoney Creek Reserve.

title: Trentham Cemetery
summary: Though you won’t walk through the cemetery itself, the trail passes through land owned by the cemetery, alongside its boundary fence.

title: Chimney Stack
summary: Just beyond the cemetery, an old chimney stack stands alone in a patch of grassland.

title: Trentham Racecourse
summary: All that remains of the Trentham Racecourse is this walking trail, which follows the original curve of the racetrack.

title: Signage
summary: Consistent signage keeps you on the right path throughout.

title: Wild Melbourne
summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

title: Boardwalk at Macalister Wetland Reserve
summary: This is a delightful way to discover the wild and wonderful world of a wetland.

title: Cow sculptures
summary: In recognition of the influence of the dairy industry and as a celebration to cows, check out this zany iron sculpture installation.

title: Maffra’s Motor Vehicle Collection and Museum
summary: A must for any motoring enthusiast (& even those that aren’t!), this vintage car museum showcases an extraordinary array of the beloved car.

title: Remnants of the past
summary: It’s hard to imagine just how much work this old truck did over the years, but it’s one more example along the trail of the previous lives of other Gippslanders.

title: Walking the dog
summary: You don’t have to follow the rail trail on wheels. Lots of locals use the trail as a great place to walk the pooch.

title: Stratford sculptures
summary: A side trip in Stratford is recommended, making sure you take the short trip beside the Avon River to enjoy the fantastic sculptures dotted along the way.

title: Stratford Railway Station
summary: Whether you start from the Trail’s most eastern end or return by train, this is a lovely old station to visit.

title: Look for the sign
summary: Find your way to Tyers Primary School on Mt Hope Rd and you can’t miss the Reserve (just up from the school on the opposite side).

title: A welcoming walkway
summary: Enter the Reserve via the footbridge and iron gate.

title: The Reserve
summary: Whilst this is not a large area, it’s a tribute to one of our national botanical treasures and worth the visit.

title: Sunlight streaming
summary: If you time it right, you can catch the rays of the rising or setting sun at various sites in the Reserve.

title: Nodding Greenhood Orchid
summary: These beautiful orchids are found in the eastern states of Australia, and flower in winter and spring.

title: Take a seat
summary: This is a lovely spot to rest and imagine life in Jean Gailbraith’s day.

title: A stand of Cherry Ballarts
summary: These beautiful trees, which belong to the sandalwood family, are also known as the edible indigenous species Native Cherry (Exocarpos cupressiformis).

title: The historic homestead, Dunedin
summary: This is the home Jean was raised in and lived at until well past her 80th year. You can see the rooftop clearly as you look across the road from the Reserve’s gate.

title: Watt's Cottage
summary: Home to early settlers in Sorrento, this house was built in 1869. The Pioneer Memorial Garden is well tended with blooms all year round. Tours available (at limited times).

title: Walk towards Cape Schank
summary: Did you enjoy looking at the lovely cottages along the way? At the end of the road, you'll notice signs indicating a variety of walks. Keep going until you see one directing you to Cape Schank.

title: Beautiful views
summary: You might need to pause a few times as there are many places to appreciate the very fine views along the way.

title: St Paul's beach
summary: Follow the sign, it leads you down some steps to a lovely beach but check the tide. If it's high tide you might get flooded or washed away (the currents are strong here)!

title: At St Paul's Beach
summary: A fabulous rock formation that you can walk through. What's on the other side? Only one way to find out!

title: Follow the sign to Jubilee Point
summary: This is the perfect picnic spot (although it can be a bit windy). This short detour gives you great views as well as nice spots to sit and relax.

title: Sorrento - Portsea Artists' Trail
summary: This painting by Emanuel Phillips Fox from 1915 depicts Jubilee Point. It is Point 13 of the Sorrento-Portsea Artists' Trail.

title: Walk towards Jubilee Point
summary: Feels like you're heading out into the horizon!

title: Jubilation at Jubilee Point
summary: You'll not be disappointed by the  spectacular views!.

title: Sunset views
summary: We enjoyed the light and shadows cast by the late afternoon sun.

title: Pram, stroller and wheelchair friendly
summary: The whole loop’s surface is either concrete or high-quality boardwalk and therefore usable by all most everyone.

title: BBQ and Playground
summary: At the western end of the lake is this great BBQ and playground, perfect spot to bring the family.

title: Friendly locals
summary: It is amazing juts how many birds there are in the lake!

title: Read about the native flora and fauna
summary: There are plenty of signs and information sheets around the loop providing plenty of information for walkers.

title: Duck feeding central!
summary: The pier at the eastern end of the lake, just in front of the Cardinia Cultural Centre, is a perfect spot to feed the duck, swans and other types of birds.

title: Cardinia Road Train Station is less than 1km away
summary: As Cardinia Road Train Station is just under a km away, the lake is very easily accessible by public transport. The pedestrian facilities between the station and the lake and great.

title: A beautiful view all the way around
summary: You will be pleasantly surprised just how pleasant the views and amenity of the lake are.

title: What are these two up to?
summary: What are these two up to?

title: Some inspiration from the Council!
summary: The Council estimates the loop is 2,000 steps, which they consider is one fifth of the number of steps you should aim for per day.

title: Try not to fall in!
summary: Most of the walk has no guard rail, however the water depth is very shallow so do not be alarmed!

title: Toilet, Carpark and Recreational Facilities
summary: A good place to start and end your walking adventure. These facilities are all available to the public.

title: Endeavour Fern Gully entrance and carpark
summary: This is the main  entrance to Endeavour Fern Gully and more car-parking spaces are available here if necessary.

title: Interpretive signage
summary: Interpretive signage and markers are located along the Endeavour Fern Gully trail. There is also a picnic area, shelter and map as you enter the walking loop.

title: Burnt-out hollow in a messmate stringybark
summary: Have a look around and spot the burnt-out hollow in a large messmate stringybark. This is believed to have been a place where Indigenous people smoked animals for food, such as eels.

title: Manna gums
summary: This area in the gully boasts some impressive native trees as well as more low-lying flora.  Have a look up and see birds fly busily to and from their nests.

title: Creek
summary: The creek is a great place to see a variety of fungi and ferns, amongst the sounds of the water trickling and the birds humming and whistling.

title: Wild Melbourne
summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more

title: Rupanyup Post Office
summary: An old Post Office building where you can park and assemble and is a good place to start your walk

title: Boydys Take Away
summary:
Excellent place for a meal or some well earned cold drinks before or after your walk.
Plenty of parking in front of the shop or in the space under cover of trees in the  middle of the main street

title: Rupanyup Public Toilet block
summary: Brick constructed toilet facilities that are well serviced by council and clean..

title: Rupanyup Supermarket
summary: If you camp or stay at the local Lions run community park at the billabong you may need supplies, the Rupanyup Supermarket has some of the essentials you may need.

title: Rupanyup Memoral Hall (former picture theatre)
summary: The Rupanyup Memorial Hall was built in 1920 and is used for all sorts of social functions including a local emergency centre during the floods of 2010/11 and was originally a country cinema.

title: Rupanyup Commercial Hotel
summary:
A welcome place for some on a walk in summer is the Rupanyup Commercial Hotel and their drinks are ice cold.
Sadly, the Rupanyup Café next door has been closed for some time.

title: Picnic spot (under cover)
summary: There is a picnic pot under cover with good seating in the middle parking section of the street. This seating is easily found almost opposite the front of the Hotel

title: New Rupanyup Police Station
summary: We have a new Police Station in the town however, it is a country one man station that is often unmanned.

title: Custs Store
summary:
Custs Store is a replica of a traditional general store & is located in the middle area between the Rupanyup Supermarket & The Rupanyup Hardware.
It was named after one of the first shops erected.

title: The old Dunmunkle Shire Council Building and now Yarriambiack Shire Office
summary: This is the original building of the Shire Offices when Rupanyup was the Dunmunkle Shire, the local communities merged to being the southern end of the Yarriambiack Shire Council in the 1990s,

title: Stone Memorial in Shire offices Driveway
summary: There is a stone memorial with a few plaques explaining the councils history, it is to the left of the front of the building in the driveway.

title: The Rupanyup RSL Hall
summary: A very tidy Country RSL Hall that also has a Restored 25 Pounder Military Gun in the front yard, this is worth a look and has a memorial plaque to explain the history of the gun.

title: Memorial 25 Pounder Gun at the RSL Hall
summary: There is a 25 Pounder Gun in the front yard of the RSL that has this plaque to describe the restoration.

title: Watch out for semi trailer grain trucks when crossing this highway
summary: This walk crosses a busy highway that has two separate lanes divided by a centre median area and can make visibility an issue.

title: Plenty of Parking Spots
summary: There is plenty of parking around the town and ample spaces in front of the Post Office

title: Watch out for semi trailer grain trucks when crossing this highway
summary: This walk crosses a busy highway that has two separate lanes divided by a centre median area and can make visibility an issue.  There has been fatalities in the main street before so please take care.

title: St. Philips Anglican Church
summary:
Address:  74 Cromie Street, Rupanyup,  Vic.  3388.
Built 1912.

title: Watch out for semi trailer grain trucks when crossing this highway
summary: This walk crosses a busy highway that has two separate lanes divided by a centre median area and can make visibility an issue.

title: Rupanyup Nursing Home and Doctors Surgery
summary: The Rupanyup Nursing Home and Doctors Surgery provides a range of health services for the township and wider Yarriambiack Shire communities.

title: Map and information board
summary: At the start of the walking trails, signage provides a list of bird species, flora, ferns and orchids that you may spot along the way as well as a map indicating your walking options.

title: Look and learn
summary: Sharing knowledge between the ages can only be enhanced by a fantastic location, with a boardwalk over the wetland that provides a rich tapestry of aquatic plants and birdlife.

title: Coral Fern Walk
summary: One of three bridge crossings, take a wander through a swathe of spectacular Coral Fern (Gleichenia dicarpa) and flowering Snow Daisy Bush (Olearia lirata) woven within the tree ferns and forest.

title: Lovely misty morning
summary: Springtime is renowned for the floral explosion in the Reserve, including the beautiful wattle blossom (some of which is non-native but which the Committee of Management is steadily removing).

title: Superb Fairy Wren
summary: Fairy-Wrens are just one species of the numerous birdlife that can be spotted in this area and makes a walk just that bit more enjoyable, especially when they stop by to spot you.

title: Wonderful boardwalks
summary: This is a well-kept reserve, with wide boardwalks that protect the vegetation as well as ensuring you don’t get your feet wet!

title: Perfect sunset
summary: You may choose to wind down at the end of the day to watch the sun sink below the horizon, reflected on the water’s surface.

title: Wonderful wetlands
summary: Looking through the Tall Spike Rush (Eleocharis sphacelata) is a fertile wetland. At the end of a hot day, you can find almost all the birdlife taking a dip, which is a spectacular site.

title: Pink Hyacinth (Dipodium roseum)
summary: This beautiful flower is one over 50 species of orchids in this Reserve, meaning there’s something in flower throughout the year.

title: Planning a picnic?
summary: Whether you eat first and then walk, or reflect on what you’ve seen over a tasty meal after you’ve discovered this beautiful reserve, the facilities are kept clean and comfortable.

title: The Welcome Entrance
summary: A beautifully constructed archway welcomes walkers to this brilliant overview of Gippsland’s history.

title: An easy stroll
summary: The path around Kernot Lake is user-friendly to all ages and abilities, and is populated by numerous information boards.

title: Five clans: one nation
summary: Gippsland’s original inhabitants, living in this region for thousands of years, are the Gunaikurnai nation with its five clans sharing the land.

title: The creation story
summary: This plinth tells the creation story of Boorun, the male pelican, and his wife Tuk, the female musk duck.

title: A rich fabric of history
summary: Settlement stories are told through both photos and text, starting with the prospective squatters who came south over the Victorian Alps to settle in the central Gippsland Plains and beyond.

title: The migrant statue
summary: Created by sculptor William Eicholtz, this central figure stands in the centre of the Gippsland Immigration Wall of Recognition.

title: Town life
summary: Learn about how the various townships were established across the region over the years.

title: A captured history
summary: Whatever time of day you take this walk, you will be treated to an extraordinary diversity of historical facts about Gippsland.

title: Rest and read
summary: Take some time to absorb the information and contemplate the photographs which, as the saying goes, prove that a picture can paint a thousand words.

title: Time for a BBQ
summary: An excellent venue for family and community gatherings, there are two covered areas with electric barbeques as well as a children’s playground.

title: Gum trees
summary: These gum trees greet you at the start of the walk.

title: Pigs face flowers
summary: These beautiful flowers instantly brighten up the walking path!

title: Shady trees
summary: There are many sheltered spots along the way. A good place for a picnic if you're bringing food and a few friends.

title: Walk across the laneway
summary: Cut through to the opposite side when you see a grassy laneway. This is Kennedy Court and it will take you through to Kingston Boulevard.

title: Manor houses
summary: Time to admire the grand houses and immaculate gardens!

title: Cockatoo Community Garden
summary: The Community Garden features allocated as well as communal plots and is run by the local community

title: Sensory garden
summary: Sensory garden is located in the Cockatoo Community Garden

title: Alma Treloar Reserve, Cockatoo
summary: View along the path

title: Tarra-Bulga visitor centre
summary: A beautiful and peaceful area to enjoy a picnic.  Opening times for the centre are 10am-4pm during school holidays, weekends and public holidays.

title: Lyrebird Track options
summary: Turn left to continue this walk or turn right to take a short diversion to a gully lookout.

title: Gully lookout
summary: Lyrebird Ridge Track is accessible for people with disabilities and will lead you to this lookout over a fern-filled gully.

title: Ash Track
summary: A level and very well maintained compacted gravel pathway.

title: Giant Mountain Ash
summary: This immense tree is over 60 metres high and can you imagine how old?!

title: Corrigan's Bridge Lookout
summary: Another lookout which places you above the height of the fern trees below but look up and take in the magnificent height of the taller trees.

title: Fern Gully Nature walk
summary: This section of the walk takes you down to the bottom of the gully, past the Lyrebird pool where you might spot one having a drink and splash in summer!

title: Myrtle Beech tree root
summary: A rare and special look at the root system of this ancient tree.  It provides the perfect home for mosses and fungi to grow.

title: Yabby
summary: This fresh water crustacean was spotted swimming in the Lyrebird pool. He is well camouflaged!

title: Bulga picnic shelter
summary: A big wooden shelter with forest views, a place to stop and rest or enjoy a picnic.

title: Track to visitors centre
summary: This track is off to your left after you leave the Bulga picnic area.

title: The Path
summary: No a lot of shade for the fist little bit, but great to get going.

title: Little bridge
summary: Great bridge to cross after rain.

title: View to Tidal River
summary: Love it when you can see the sea from the track!

title: Rocky path
summary: The path gets a little rocky in parts, but it's not a problem for people steady on their feet.

title: Near the top
summary: Path gets a bit smoother again as you near the top.

title: Looking to Mount Oberon
summary: Wonderful spot to stop for lunch as it's usually sheltered from the wind the summit isn't).

title: Tidal River
summary: View to Tidal River and Norman Bay.

title: Squeaky Beach
summary: View from the summit to Squeaky Beach is definitely worth the walk!

title: Tarra Valley picnic area
summary: Tables, toilets and picnic shelters are provided.

title: Ferns
summary: Thirty nine species of ferns have been recorded and there are more than 200 kinds of fungi.

title: Cyathea Falls
summary: Meander through a rainforest gully and across trickling mountain streams to Cyathea Falls.

title: Turnstile entry
summary: Thanks to Parklands Albury Wodonga management, a trusty turnstile points the way

title: Ascent tracks - either west or east
summary: Both lead to the same junction, on either side of the fence line

title: Lake Hume
summary: The first glimpse of Lake Hume comes into view.

title: Lake Hume
summary: The expanse of Lake Hume can be appreciated once you gain some altitude

title: Mahers Hill ridgeline
summary: The destination is a reasonably gentle ascent

title: The splendour of the Murray Valley
summary: With views past Tallangatta and Corryong to the snowfields of Kosciuszko and Perisher Valley. This view alone made the walk worthwhile!

title: The descent on return
summary: Returning via the west track

title: Tyers River
summary: It’s a shame how many of us haven’t visited this beautiful river, because the idyllic walk along its riverbanks is well worth your while.

title: Great fishing spots
summary: Whether you’re going to sling your hook or just sit and look, there are tracks leading down to the riverbank where you can spend quite a bit of time.

title: Historic pipeline
summary: There’s some memorabilia of times gone by in this area, including the old pipeline that transported water from the river to the township of Traralgon.

title: Follow the orange markers
summary: Small orange arrows are situated on trees as you make your way along the track, but make sure you don’t go further than the sign to Wirilda Track if you aren’t planning a very long walk.

title: Track on the hillside
summary: It’s a wonderful feeling to know you are safely balanced between the base of a large hill and the fall to the riverbank.

title: A steep track
summary: One of the joys of this walk is the contrasting heights and varying vegetation types that come with the changes.

title: A home in the hollow
summary: This burrow sits at the edge of the track, so presumably its resident waits until nightfall when the walkers have left the park before it takes its own stroll.

title: Fern forest
summary: The lush forest sensation hits you when look up, but also when you look down to discover a flush of ferns (also known as Fish Bone Ferns) by your feet.

title: Healthy understory
summary: Great swathes of Dogwood (Cassinia aculeata) can be seen as you wander along the track, as well as numerous other understorey plants.

title: Rupertswood Mansion
summary: Built in 1874-76 for Sir William Clarke, in 1882 a cricket match between England and a local side resulted in the presentation of a pottery urn containing 'The Ashes' of a burnt bail - 'The Ashes'.

title: Rupertswood Lake
summary: This lake was constructed by Sir Willam Clarke and included an island shaped like Australia. Today it is a nice place to feed ducks, swans and other birdlife.

title: Melbourne-Bendigo Railway Bridge
summary: In July 1861 the Sunbury to Woodend government railway opened. This included construction of many impressive arched railway bridges. The Blind Creek bridge is listed on the Victorian Heritage Register

title: Riddell Road Childrens Playground
summary: This new playground was constructed in 2011 and includes many challenging activities for children.

title: Clarke Oval
summary: Large oval used by Sunbury Lions Football Club.

title: Sunbury BMX and Skate Park
summary: Just a little detour from the path is the Sunbury BMX and Skate Park with great facilities.

title: Stewarts Lane Nature Reserve
summary: Nature Reserve, look for native animals and enjoy the natural setting.

title: Bridge over Livingstone Creek
summary: Cross the bridge to get to the other side where the walk starts!

title: Track sign
summary: This walk describes the Ah Fong Loop Track but you can walk from here to the Omeo reservoir in the town center also.

title: Steps Up
summary: The landscape and track are very up and down as a result of the gold mining methods used.

title: Claims information sign
summary: Ah Fong must have been quite a character and you can learn why if you read the signs along the walk.

title: The track and the cliffs
summary: The cliffs have been exposed to get to the gold they were hiding.

title: Starlight Claim
summary: These caves were dug out by hand to get to the gold when water was unavailable.

title: Gully bridge
summary: Water was a vital tool for extracting the gold here so the miners dug more than 50km of ditches and channels to bring water upstream.

title: Track sign
summary: From here you can cross the bridge and go to Omeo or continue to your right and loop back to the start.

title: Rocks
summary: Possibly part of a race used to divert water to high points above the mining sites.

title: Steps to Livingstone Creek
summary: Go down here to get to a waterhole and sandy area.

title: Livingstone Creek
summary: This creek was severely impacted from muddy water being washed into it but today it looks clean and healthy.

title: Sandy creek bank
summary: A sandy spot  by the creek  to rest or picnic.

title: Water hole
summary: Perhaps have a swim?!

title: The end
summary: Follow the creek back to the bridge back to the beginning.

title: Ocean Grove Surf Beach
summary: This is a beautiful beach for walking and playing. The sand is so soft and the views of the Barwon Bluff are exquisite.

title: Sand Play
summary: If your kids want to play in the sand then stop for a rest. It is so therapeutic for kids to play in the sand. Try and keep your kids off the dunes  though. There is a good spot later on this walk!

title: Barwon Heads Bridge
summary: This bridge is great fun to photograph and the kids really love walking under it.

title: Between the bridges
summary: This section of beach is really fun because there is a large deposit of sand here and it is ok for kids to play here without damaging  the dune system.

title: Ocean Grove Surf Beach
summary: It is so nice to run in some open space!

title: More sand play
summary: Kids can never get enough sand play!

title: Along the Barwon River
summary: The tide will dictate how much sand you have to walk on but walking on the rocks is always an option!

title: Take your shoes off
summary: The sand is very "squelchy" and feels wonderful between your toes!

title: Cut through the Caravan Park
summary: You can walk through the Caravan Park to get to the road. Find a safe place to cross over to the carpark.

title: BMX track
summary: Hidden away, it might not look like much but when people are using the track it taks on  whole new life. Definitely worth checking out!

title: Felltimber lagoon
summary: Located next tot he Felltimber Community Centre, this is a peaceful spot to sit by the water. There are many ducks that will approach you - especially if you have something for them to eat.

title: Wodonga Sports and Leisure Centre
summary: This centre offers a wide range of activities and includes and indoor pool. Major tournaments are held here and it's home to the Wodonga Wolves CBL basketball team.

title: Willow Park
summary: Besides being scenic to walk through, there's  a great play ground, hidden bird houses, 2 ovals, outdoor gym gear, a BBQ area and its attached to a skate park

title: Balyang Sanctuary
summary: Plenty of parking available at Balyang Sanctuary. Start walk from here.

title: Pedestrian and cycle bridge
summary: pedestrians and cyclists can use this overpass to cross the river

title: Breakwater Rd
summary: Half way point of walk

title: Rowing
summary: Walk past the rowing sheds. Lots of action of people on land getting ready to get into the water and lots of people already on the water!

title: Kilcunda General Store & Meikle's Pub
summary: The store has gourmet breakfast and lunch, fine produce, handmade craft and a few everyday supplies. It doubles as a post office. The pub next door opens for dinner, offering fine tucker and wine.

title: Crossing the road
summary: Be extra careful crossing the road to the shops as huge trucks, trailers and cars tend to tear down the highway in excess of the speed limit.

title: Information board
summary: Start along the dirt track (also a rail trail). You'll spot a sign to the left soon afterwards. Contains useful historical info as well as details about the flora and fauna here.

title: Wildflower 1
summary: As you begin the walk, you'll notice the variety of plants growing on each side.

title: Wildflower 2
summary: If only I knew the names of all these little flowers!

title: Wildflower 3
summary: These are near an impressive cliff face. Don't step too far out or it's a long way (and bumpy way) down to the rocks.

title: Steam driven winch
summary: Somewhere around this area is a historical remnant from the area's coal mining past. Peek behind the sign to see what it looks like.

title: Wildflower 4
summary: These are Dianellas. I have them in my front yard. The purple flowers are great. Plus, they're a very hardy plant that will grow in the toughest environment (eg. my front yard).

title: Sandy's blowhole
summary: Walk down to Sandy's blowhole for a shower! The rocks here are rather strange and interesting. The waves can be quite sudden and powerful so be careful, especially if the tide is high.

title: Wildflower 5
summary: I've never seen this before! It's furry and feathery. How peculiar.

title: Wildflower 6
summary: Are these daisies? They look like daisies. There are yellow and white ones along the path too.

title: Wild grasses
summary: The sound of rustling grass can be quite soothing. When the wind blew (which was often where we were here), it made the field of tall grasses look like a sea of green waves.

title: Wildflower 7
summary: These are tiny flowers we found along the path. They are very dainty and easily missed, or trampled on! They were the size of a fingernail.

title: Wildflower 8
summary: Trusty tea trees. The smell of tea tree is refreshing.

title: Wildflower 9
summary: We found these on our way to the beach.

title: Beach
summary: We ended our walk here but you can keep going till you get to Punchbowl Road. Dip your toes in the water but don't freeze them off. We had a snack here then headed back the same way we came.

title: Gateway Lakes precinct
summary: Gateway Lakes hosts a large number of events and activities each year and is home to Wodonga’s water ski, canoe, dragon boating and rowing clubs. Take a slight detour and check it out!

title: Indigenous art and history
summary: Look out for the Indigenous cultural displays along the trail as you enter into Harris Road. You will learn about our local history.

title: Picnic by the Murray River
summary: Enjoy one of the many lovely picnic spots along the Murray River for a family picnic. Quiet, calm and very picturesque. Enjoy!

title: Wildlife spotting
summary: Along the nature trail, keep your eyes peeled for some local wild life – can you see a kangaroo in the long grass, some new ducklings even?

title: Historic Murray River railway bridge
summary: Walk under the historic Murray River railway bridge that crosses from Victoria into New South Wales. If you are lucky to have a train crossing above, you are in for a thrill as you walk below.

title: Gateway Village gardens
summary: Stop for some shade, possibly even spot a wedding taking place and enjoy the beautiful surrounds of Gateway Village’s gardens and pond area.

title: Gateway Village precinct
summary: Gateway Village has a lot on offer from yummy food, hot or refreshing beverages, art displays, theatre performances to the Hume Murray Farmer’s Market from 8am every second Saturday. Visit www.hmfb.or

title: Mills Park Circuit
summary: A glimpse of the green open space and lovely native trees. You are on your way.

title: Time for some stretching
summary: Some stretching posts have been perfectly placed to stretch your muscles ready for your walk or run.

title: Beautiful path,   paved with native trees. Nearly half way.
summary: Mid way and it is glorious and so relaxing. Over the rise and in the centre is a BBQ.

title: Exercise point, chin ups. if you dare
summary: If you want to test your strength, this is the exercise point to do so.

title: BBQ spot surrounded by open green spaces
summary: Perfectly situated, BBQ for the family to have lunch after the circuit walk, plenty of room to run and play and Go Fly a Kite.

title: Beacon Cove Seating
summary: There is plenty of seating along Beacon Cove. Sit to rest, people watch or enjoy the local fish and chips.

title: Port Melbourne railway line
summary: Enjoy the walking/ bicycling trail along the light rail route.

title: Edwards Reserve
summary: This is a lovely park that runs along the light rail, a popular spot for dogs.

title: Leading Lights
summary: Constructed by the Melbourne Harbor Trust in 1924 to a Trinity House design, the beacons define the centre line of the Port Melbourne Channel.

title: Princes Pier
summary: Built between 1912 and 1915, Princes Pier was the third major pier constructed at Port Melbourne and served as a major passenger terminal.

title: Beacon Cove
summary: Cafes, restaurants, grocery store, Spirit of Tasmania ferry terminal, tram stop.

title: The Patrobus monument
summary: Patrobas is the only Gippsland racehorse to have won a Melbourne Cup, and the only racehorse to have won the cup, Caulfield Guineas and Derby in the same year, 1915.

title: Willow Park
summary: This Park is also a free overnight camping spot (maximum stay of 36 hours).

title: Coffee shop, bakery etc
summary: Stop for coffee or lunch at one of the eateries along the main street.

title: Bendigo Health - John Bomford Center
summary: Specialized in Mental Health services

title: Strath Village Shopping Center
summary: It is really exciting shopping center and ranks the third busiest one in Greater Bendigo

title: Walking around Kennington Reservoir
summary: Fresh air and the lake is so wonderful to walk around. Perfect for a picnic with comfortable seating and shades

title: Kennington Primary School
summary: Located in a Hill looking down Kennington Reservoir Lake, green and fresh environment for students

title: Kennington Pre - School
summary: Small but lovely and green playground for children, located beside the lake

title: "I only count the sunny hours" Clock
summary: The old clock was constructed by the Shire of Strathfieldsaye with the assistance of The Bendigo - Strathdale Rotary Club. Opposite the Clock is Reservoir Hotel.

title: Historic houses
summary: I like to admire these lovely houses.  They make the town a pleasure to walk around.

title: Stones
summary: I like the way these stones decorate the street.

title: River view
summary: Our stretch of the Campaspe River is beautiful, though it did flood recently after heavy rains.

title: Old historic hospital
summary: My brothers and I were born here.  At present, it's future is uncertain.  Will it be sold to the developers?  Will it become a community facility?  Would be good to see it preserved.

title: Wedge Street
summary: Tree line boulevard.  Pretty in spring, cool in summer, stunning in autumn.  If only all our streets could look like this!

title: Trough
summary: For a time when horses and carriages were our main form of transport (apart from walking of course!).

title: Brocklebank Drive
summary: Always an amazing spot for a wander.  The fresh air from the trees is amazing, especially after walking up a steep hill!

title: Grand old gum trees
summary: Beautiful gum trees greet you as you begin your walk. If you look closely enough, you might spot the Yingabeal Aboriginal scar tree.

title: Doll's House
summary: An old milking shed that was later used to store artwork by Sidney Nolan, including his famous Ned Kelly series!

title: Heide kitchen garden
summary: A garden brimming with fresh herbs and produce used by the onsite cafe.

title: Wild garden
summary: This rambling cottage garden is delightful at any time, especially in the morning with the sun's rays streaming through.

title: The oak tree
summary: This grand old oak tree was planted in 1935. It's beautifully shady and its autumnal hues are still apparent in the middle of winter!

title: Heide I
summary: This is the house that the Reed family lived for 35 years. Here, many artists, including Sidney Nolan, Albert Tucker and Joy Hester came to visit, stay and create.

title: Rings of Saturn, Inge King
summary: Inge fled to England from Germany as a refugee, then later settled in Australia. Her other famous works include the black waves on the lawns of the NGV, and red ringed structures on EastLink.

title: Heide II kitchen garden
summary: A most productive kitchen garden. Stroll through here and be inspired about what to grow for your own garden :)

title: Rose Walk Pavillion
summary: This is the perfect place to have a seat to enjoy your surroundings, have a picnic or simply catch the rays of sunshine as they filter through the wooden grooves of this beautiful structure.

title: Flowing Yarra
summary: You can catch glimpses of the Yarra as you walk past in the wooded river bank. You can extend your walk by joining the path to the neighbouring Banksia Park.

title: Trees for climbing
summary: We discovered some grand old trees that were perfect for climbing, admiring or simply for enjoying its shade.

title: Cows, Jeff Thomon
summary: Perhaps the most photographed sculpture at Heide. Presumably this art work pays tribute to the history of the property as a dairy farm.

title: Bee hives
summary: We spotted a whole lot of bee hives! There must be an abundance of honey. We enjoyed listening to the buzz of activity near the hives (obviously you shouldn't get too close, or else...).

title: Hallett Cove Beach
summary: Looking from the cafe, along the beach. Those boulders  were dropped there by the melting of a continental ice-sheet at the end of the Permian era some 270 million years ago!

title: Singing Honeyeaters
summary: Singing Honeyeaters are plentiful in the coastal heath.

title: The Amphitheatre
summary: A short climb takes you to the Amphitheatre, the Sugarloaf and right into the layers of sediments.

title: Red sand with Kestrel
summary: The colours are amazing!

title: The Bluff
summary: The path moves from beach level to the cliff tops.

title: Permian Pavement
summary: This sheet of rock is covered with deep scratches. "So what?", you say. Well, they were only made by a continental ice-sheet that covered Australia and Antarctica 270 million years ago.

title: Permian Pavement Close-Up
summary: There are only a few places in Australia you can see evidence of the permian Glaciation. Here is one, Werribee Gorge near Bacchus Marsh in Victoria is another.

title: Rugged Cliffs
summary: The path continues along the craggy Pre-Cambrian cliff tops.

title: Boardwalks
summary: Most of this walk is done on boardwalks. They are well made and designed, and take you everywhere you want to go.

title: Another Layer Cake
summary: Pretty sure these sediments are from the Pliocene.

title: Waterfall
summary: During the last Ice Age 10,000 years ago, St Vincent Gulf was a large grassy plain. This little waterfall flows over Pre-Cambrian rock, so it has been running for much longer than a mere 10,000 years.

title: A hasty retreat
summary: The weather was closing in - time to go!

title: A last look
summary: The threatening weather only made the view across the Amphitheatre even more dramatic.

title: Captain Charles Sturt marker
summary: About 50 metres along the Rower’s Lawn is a marker that commemorates the passing of Captain Charles Sturt through this area in 1830.

title: Cureton Avenue
summary: The road leading up the hill is Cureton Avenue, and is named after Stephen Cureton, the man George Chaffey first sent to the district to explore the potential of developing an irrigation colony.

title: Water Play
summary: Formally the Ornamental Lakes (pic attached), this area mark the site of the old Risby Sawmill, circa 1888. The area was transformed into a recreation water play are in 2015.

title: Nowingi Place - host to outdoor concerts and entertainment
summary: The sound shell was given the name Nowingi, to acknowledge the tremendous community effort that went into successfully fighting against a proposed toxic waste dump in the Mallee locality of Nowingi.

title: Lock Island
summary: Cross over the lock and explore Lock Island. During Mildura’s temperance era (1887-early 1900’s), this island was known as Pinkie Bend, due to the amount of illegal liquor drunk on the island.

title: Various Sculptures
summary: Along Cueton and in the Art Centre lawns you will see significant sculptures from the Mildura Sculpture Triennials which took place between 1961 and 1988.

title: Mildura Arts Centre and Cafe
summary: In 1966, an art gallery and theatre were added to Rio Vista house and the whole complex became known as the Mildura Arts Centre and was officially opened by Sir Henry Bolte in November 1966.

title: The Grand Hotel
summary: Enter the Grand Hotel’s main entrance and turn left.  To your right, you will see a display of historical photos. Through the glass doors are one of Mildura’s original Chaffey fountains.

title: Prince and Princess of Wales Fountain Plaza
summary: This fountain is very special as it was opened by the Prince and Princess of Wales on the 29th October 1985. Many Mildura residence crowded around to see the Princess Diana.

title: Railway overpass
summary:
A short walk across the railway overpass leads back to the riverfront, to
your car and to the end of this walk or head down to the Hugh King Drive underpass to avoid the stairs.

title: The Bungalow
summary: A Queen Anne style home, it is in keeping with its revered neighbor. The original owner of the Bungalow was Lancelot Conway-Gordon and later was home to J.H Shilliday. It remains a private residence.

title: The Mildura Wharf
summary: Mildura Wharf has been a vital part of the town and inland river transport system since the 1880s. It was established by the Mildura Progress Committee in 1888 to assist the burgeoning river trade.

title: MIldura Rowing Club
summary:
Rowing is a popular sport in Mildura and the club hosts an annual Easter Regatta that sees crews visit from across three states.

Attached is a photo of the Rowing Club in the 1931 floods.

title: The Powerhouse
summary: The Powerhouse, which operated from the 1920’s through to the 1950’s, until the S.E.C took over Mildura’s electricity supply. It is now used by several community groups inc the Mildura Theatre Company

title: Jaycee Park
summary: Jaycee Park is adjacent to the Powerhouse and is a perfect spot for family fun with and fabulous play equipment, BBQ areas and shady spots. A large locomotive dominates the grassed area to the front.

title: MIldura Lawn Tennis Club
summary: One of Australia's leading tennis venues, featuring 32 world class grass courts. In 1997 some Davis Cup matches were played on these courts, and it attracts a number of tournaments each year.

title: Mildura Weir
summary: Construction of the Mildura Weir began in Aug 1923 with the aims of raising both the water level & the pressure from the Mildura & Red Cliffs irrigation pumps. Picture,:View of Weir from Lock 11.

title: Lock 11
summary: Completed in 1928. Paddle steamers still pass through the lock daily. The Mildura system is the only site on the River Murray where a lock and weir are separated by an island. Image: Construction 1927

title: Rio Vista House
summary: Rio Vista, which is Spanish for River View, was completed in 1892 . Rio Vista was the home W.B Chaffey, built in a tangible show of his faith in the future of the district he founded.

title: Old Railway Carriage Sheds
summary: The old sheds, 36 metres long, extending from Olive to Pine Avenue, had 24 bays for carriages which were an essential form of protection from Mildura’s extreme heat.

title: MIldura Railway Station
summary: Mildura’s railway commenced operation in 1903 and the current station was completed in 1978.

title: The Legacy StreetArt Mural Project
summary: The Legacy StreetArt Mural Project is an art installation created by members of the Legacy family to celebrate the Centenary of ANZAC.

title: Graffiti dragon
summary: Graffiti dragon in Drewery Lane

title: Baroq House
summary: In Drewery Lane is Baroq House, which has an enormous white sculpture of two entwined figures attached to the building.

title: St Francis Church
summary: St Francis Church, Melbourne’s first Catholic cathedral.

title: Phillips Shirts
summary: Phillips Shirts,  a family business that has been making shirts for over 60 years.

title: Thousand Pound Bend
summary: Thousand Pound Bend café, formerly a garage.  It looks a bit grungy on the outside but good food and coffee can be found within

title: Victorian Titles Office
summary: Victorian Titles Office, 283 Queen St. Now a campus of Victoria University

title: Former Records Office
summary: Former Records Office, 295 Queen St.  Now a campus for Victoria University now.

title: 364 Lt Lonsdale St
summary: The former buildings for the Women’s Venereal Disease and adjacent TB Clinic sit at 364-378 Lt Lonsdale St.

title: 364-378 Lt Lonsdale St
summary: The former buildings for the Women’s Venereal Disease and adjacent TB Clinic sit at 364-378 Lt Lonsdale St.

title: Children's Court of Victoria
summary: The Children’s Court of Victoria is another notable building at 477 Lt Lonsdale St

title: Former Royal Mint
summary: The grand old Royal Mint building  is now the Hellenic Museum.

title: Flagstaff Gardens
summary: Flagstaff Gardens near the entrance to Flagstaff underground loop station.

title: Flagstaff Gardens caretaker cottage
summary: Flagstaff Gardens caretaker cottage

title: City of Melbourne Bowls Club
summary: City of Melbourne Bowls Club

title: The County Court
summary: The County Court houses ‘The Lady of Justice’ sculpture by William Eicholtz , which sits above the entrance to the building.

title: Supreme Court
summary: The historic Supreme Court at 459-505 Lonsdale St was built between 1874 and 1882 and still in use.

title: Waverley Court
summary: Next to the County Court is a 3-storey building formerly known as Waverley Court at 470 Lonsdale St. It was formerly advertised as a place of lodgings in the ‘The Argus’ newspaper on 19 January 1937.

title: State Public Offices
summary: At 436 Lonsdale is the State Public Offices.

title: Emporium
summary: Emporium shopping complex

title: Tatura court House
summary: dates back to 1891. Has been used in a number of movies such as "Till Human Voices Wake Us" with Helena Bonham Carter.

title: Private Robert Mactier VC Memorial Gardens
summary: Named after Robert Mactier, a winner of the Victoria Cross who lost his life in circumstances of extraordinary bravery during WWI

title: Tutura Hot Bread
summary: Dates back to 1878 and houses a historic oven.

title: Victory Hall
summary: Opened in 1925 by the then Governer General.

title: Sacred Heart Parish Curch
summary: Oped 7 august 1889. Rebuilt at a cost of 9000 pounds in a Romanesque style and blessed in 1912 as it had outgrown the previous building.

title: Sisters of Mercy Convent
summary: Blessed in June 1941.

title: St Mary's Church Building
summary: build 1901 with its beuatiful balcony and cast iron work.

title: Tatuta Wartime Camps Museum
summary: Home to a plethora of artefacts depicting the history of the camps in the Tatura/ Murchison area from WWII.

title: Bridge
summary: Across the Bridge (near the Chinese Garden)

title: River View
summary: River awaiting more rain

title: Park
summary: Park with toilet block.

title: Skate Park
summary: Track and Skate Park

title: Track under the Bridge
summary: Walk under bridge to playground

title: Chinese Garden
summary: Take a stroll in the Garden

title: Wild Life
summary: You might spot some wild life in and around the river

title: River views
summary: River views along the walk

title: Black Rock Clock Tower
summary: This 4 faced clock and brick tower was built in 1959 and still keeps the time today.

title: Playground and picnic area
summary: The playground has a nautical theme of course! There are picnic tables, BBQ's and toilets here also.

title: Path to walled walk and beach
summary: Take this path down to the beach.  There are several other options also.

title: The bluestone sea wall
summary: The sea wall was developed to protect Beach Road.  Sections have been built using original bluestone from the Old  Melbourne Gaol. The inscriptions on stones are still visible.

title: Ricketts Point Marine Sanctuary
summary: A special place to snorkel and see schools of fish and other marine creatures.  Be amazed at what lives just below the surface!

title: Swans and pelicans
summary: There are often swans and pelicans at this spot.  If they are not there, they are probably further along at Rickets Point.

title: Quiet corner beach and picnic area.
summary: The wall ends here at this peaceful beach.  Further along the beach is Rickett's Point.

title: Coastal walking path
summary: The narrow unsealed coast walking path runs parallel with Beach Road winding its way through coastal heathland with elevated views out over the Bay and beaches to the city.

title: Rugged beauty of the beach landscape
summary: With the water on one side and the natural vegetation hiding the road on the other, the is nothing to disturb the peace!

title: Stairway between road and beach
summary: Another access point to the beach.

title: Wonderful rock pools
summary: The rocks are covered with green and red algae which shelters a range of invertebrates including brittle stars, bristle worms and crustaceans.

title: Jetty
summary: Begin with a walk out on this jetty near the Warneet boat ramp.

title: Pelicans!
summary: Western Port is recognised as a 'wetland of international importance' under an international treaty called the Ramsar Convention so local and international birds can be seen here.

title: Warneet coastline from the jetty
summary: Looking back at the Warneet Motor Yacht Club and boat ramp.

title: Fisherman and fishing boats
summary: Try your luck at fishing while you are here, you are likely to have some company!

title: Beach
summary: If the tide is out you can walk along the beach for sections of the walk.

title: Seat and view
summary: Take a seat, there are plenty along the way.

title: Mangroves and rowboat
summary: A local coming ashore from his boat.

title: Track
summary: The track is flat and well defined.  Pack your hat on the sunny days as it is mostly exposed.

title: Jetty near Warneet North Boat Club
summary: Enjoy the view from this shady picnic area.

title: Picnic area
summary: There are many facilities here to make for a pleasant stop.  Picnic tables and BBQ's and a toilet and shelter shed.

title: Cute bridge
summary: Another opportunity to walk along the beach.

title: Enjoying the walk
summary: This walk can be enjoyed by you and your dog!

title: Picnic area and oval
summary: Another spot for a picnic is by the Warneet reserve.  There are drinking water taps here.

title: Lookout
summary: Have an elevated view over the coastal vegetation and the Rutherford inlet.

title: Haven
summary: You can see why Warneet is a perfect spot for fishing and boating and for our feathered friends to roost, breed and feed!

title: The end
summary: This is the end of this walk but you can keep going along this marked walk through the Warneet Nature Reserve.

title: Braybrook & Maidstone Neighbourhood House
summary: This organisation is made up of residents of Braybrook and Maidstone  and surrounding areas who are committed to listening to and representing local people to build a proud community.

title: Ash Reserve, also known as Braybrook Reserve
summary: Ash Reserve is a peaceful park tucked away inland from the bustling Ballarat Road. The inviting playground and barbecue makes it a great family spot for weekends or those warm Summer evenings.

title: 1950s house
summary: Don't you love these reminders of 1950s Melbourne in Braybrook? The housing shortage of the 40s and 50s was addressed by the Housing Commission which operated from a large new factory in Holmesglen.

title: Kinder Smith Reserve
summary: This lovely green space sports a  new playground with state of the art equipment for young children. The area also offers a new GreenWORKS! Mural, RecWest YMCA activities and Sunshine Football Club.

title: Caroline Chisholm Catholic College
summary: This popular co-educational Catholic secondary school offers many examples of contemporary architectural and educational art and design for the school community to enjoy.

title: Skewes Street Laneway Mural
summary: As you walk along Skewes Street and through the laneway to the shops you'll be pleasantly surprised by this fresh mural which showcases the creative expertise of some Melbourne artists.

title: Goodstart Early Learning Centre
summary: At Goodstart Braybrook, the staff strive to maintain a clean, safe and engaging environment for the children. Goodstart is  a multicultural centre with bilingual staff.

title: Cao Ðài Vietnamese Temple
summary: Cao Dai  is a new religious movement founded in Vietnam. It mixes ideas from other religions and was  officially established in the city of Tây Ninh, southern Vietnam in 1926.

title: Murtoa Pool
summary: In summer months, the Murtoa pool is a fine place for the kids to play whilst adults may take in a walk

title: Lake Pier.

title: First seat
summary: There are a few seats, but this one faces the wrong way away from the view! But you can say hello to other walkers on the path which is nice.

title: The bridge
summary: The bridge makes for an easy walk.

title: Cairns
summary: There are many cairns or rock sculptures along this stretch of the walk.

title: Rocky outcrop
summary: A beautiful spot to look around for lizards.

title: More cairns
summary: There are heaps of cairns around here, maybe stop and build one. If you are with children, they love it here.

title: Beautiful mosses
summary: If you are lucky you might find some beautiful mosses among the rocks.

title: Wildflowers
summary: More wildflowers, when we were here in early November there were heaps!

title: Bush seats
summary: There are three seats that someone has cut out of old tree stumps, very creative.

title: The track
summary: The track gets a little more shelter from some taller trees here. Nice dappled light and look for the odd wallaby.

title: The lookout
summary: Anticipation as you near the lookout.

title: The Balconies
summary: The view is amazing, you could spend the day here!

title: Merri Street Estuary
summary: Stop at the estuary platform to view the flora and fauna that surrounds the Merri River

summary: Enter the Rail Trail via Lake Pertobe Trail

title: Rail Trail

title: Looking across to the Indigo Valley
summary: At this elevation one has a number of vistas to take in, including this view toward Barnawartha and beyond.

title: Birdlife
summary: Birdlife can be viewed all along the walk

title: Loch Sport Marina
summary: Enjoy the Marina and perhaps even the Marina Hotel!

title: Lake Victoria
summary: The walk will take you along the shores of Lake Victoria.

title: Caravan Park Entry
summary: Walk through Caravan Park. Please be aware this is share zone with Caravan Park, walking track and cars

summary: Some of the local wildlife

summary: Seating along the lake and nice view

title: Track across the Lake
summary: Across the Lake, nice when there has be rain
