summary: Boat Ramp

title: Wall Acrossing
summary: Across the wall to other side

title: Bridge home
summary: Bridge to second boat ramp and BBQ area. Start of the walk

title: BBQ Area
summary: BBQ Area

title: White Necked Heron
summary: With lots of wetland along the walk you have a good chance of seeing a Heron or two.  They spend lots of time standing very still, keeping a sharp eye out for frogs, insects and fish.

title: Echidna
summary: If you're lucky you might spot an Echidna out looking for ants, termites and other small invertebrates which it captures with its long sticky tongue.

title: Walk markers
summary: There are a number of markers along the way.  This walk follows sections of two walks - the Morang Wetlands Walk and the Ridge Track.

title: Sheoak tree
summary: The mat of fallen branchlets under sheoaks prevents the development of undergrowth.  For aboriginal people it was considered a safe place to leave children as snakes are said to avoid these areas.

title: Kangaroo Apple
summary: There are lots of Kangaroo Apple trees along the way, a hint of things to come further along the walk.

title: Beauty on a small scale
summary: The wetlands support beautiful succulents thriving in the shallow waters along the walk.

title: Park view
summary: The walk meanders through a diverse range of bushland and wetlands.  Along the way you get a real sense of being out in the bush.

title: Eastern Grey Kangaroos
summary: Eastern grey kangaroos are gregarious and form open-membership groups. The groups are made up of 2-3 females and their offspring with the same number of males of which one is dominant.

title: Grasses and Sedges
summary: The wetland areas support a wide variety of native grasses and sedges.  See how many different varieties you can spot along the way.

title: Wetland view
summary: One of several small lakes along the walk.  Each one supports a wide variety of birdlife including Black Swans, ducks, Purple Swamphens, Egrets, Grebes and Eurasian Coots.

title: Black Swan and cygnets
summary: Like other swans, the Black Swan is largely monogamous, pairing for life - there is apparently only a 6% divorce rate!  They also share parenting responsibilities of the cygnets.

title: Dragonfly
summary: Dragonflies usually patrol a particular area looking for insects to eat. Mosquitoes, flies and midges are a large part of their diet. This fact alone should endear these delightful creatures to us!

title: Walking in open bushland
summary: The pathway is a mix of gravel path and some more overgrown pathways like the one in this picture.  Overall the route is quite level.

title: Eastern Great Egret
summary: The Great Egret breeds in colonies, and often in association with cormorants, ibises and other egrets.  Their nest is a large platform of sticks, placed in a tree over the water.

title: Foot bridge
summary: Though the pathway is mostly quite wide at one point along the route there is a very small footbridge.  If you would rather avoid it, there is an alternative route back to the carpark.

title: Hallam North Road car park
summary: This car park was first provided in the 1980s, but was much enlarged for the Commonwealth Games in 2006. Sometimes crowded on weekends, it has the only toilets and water on this trip

title: Down in the valley
summary: This section of Valley View track is the lowest point on this trip. Watch for mountain bike riders, but also for wildlife in the mornings and evenings

title: Head of the incline
summary: This landing was once the top of a 1 in 10 tramway incline. A 'powerful engine' once sat here to winch the empty skips back up. What kind of engine? We don't know!

title: The hidden quarry
summary: A narrow defile on the right leads into the hidden quarry. This is not visible from the track, though walkers on the Rock Gardens track can look down from above

title: Tramway cutting
summary: Tramline track does not follow the course of the old tramway at this point. The cutting on the right shows where it went. Cuttings were rare on tramways as being expensive to escavate by hand

title: Crest reservoir
summary: This reservoir at the crest of the range is long out of use. What was it for? Walk from the north corner slightly west of north across Ridge track...

title: Horse drinking trough
summary: This cement lined drinking trough provided water for thirsty horses at the top of the long climb from the quarry. Still intact despite being out of use for over eighty years

title: Lysterfield hills summit
summary: The trig point marks the highest point of this range, with fine views through 360 deg, including Dandenong to the south, and the city of the north-west. The view is worth the 700 m walk

title: Les Stone Park Wetlands
summary: A great spot to try your hand at fishing. Even better if you have young children as it offers a safe space to teach them the skills.

title: Pirate Ship
summary: This play area is great. A safe space that lets the imagination run wild. Grab your eye patch and perch a bird on your shoulder and see what adventure you end up on

title: Under road crossing
summary: Avoid crossing this busy road by taking the optional path underneath the thoroughfare. Great low risk option for people walking with groups of children or animals.

title: Football oval
summary: If you are walking along this path, why not stop for a kick of football on the way. The oval is well manicured and is home to permanent AFL posts. A little friendly competition never hurt anyone...

title: Nature at its finest
summary: The path is edged by beautiful trees almost the whole way along. Providing much needed shade in the warmer months and an excellent display of colour in Autumn, they are also home to many types of Bird

title: Bird houses
summary: Someone has built and installed some unique bird houses in the trees here. They're dated and initialled. I'd love to know who did this!

title: Skate Park
summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!

title: Netball courts
summary: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at Martin Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park

title: The Aboriginal Cultural Heritage Trail
summary: For those wishing to discover more about Gippsland’s rich indigenous heritage, this cultural trail is an excellent place to visit.

title: Bush tucker
summary: Over 27 species of native plants are included in this garden, all with important roles to play for the Gunaikurnai nation.

title: A must for the keen BMX bike-rider
summary: A busy place for the BMX enthusiasts and fun for others who just like to enjoy watching the skill involved.

title: Picnic and play
summary: A fitness station for adults and children alike, and a sheltered BBQ area for those days when a picnic enhances a lovely walk.

title: Under the willow
summary: One of many picnic table areas along the way is this beautifully shaded area under the Willows.

title: Bev's Wonder World of Dolls
summary: Open Tue-Fri from 10am to 3pm or by appointment at 31-33 The Boulevard, this is an extraordinary collection of dolls from around the world.

title: Walk among the gum trees
summary: Remnant vegetation is home to numerous animals, and the birdsong emanating from the canopy is a delight to hear.

title: Bridge crossings
summary: Along the trail, you will find bridges that can take you along the other side of the Waterhole Creek and back to the start of the walk (linked to the Gippsland Heritage Trail).

title: Fertile reed bed
summary: The healthy mix of reeds provides habitat for a multitude of aquatic species as well as being useful in the making of baskets.

title: Box Hill shopping centre
summary: This shopping centre constructed in the early 1980s has obliterated all traces of the former Box Hill station. The tramway crossed Carrington St through the centre of this roundabout

title: Tramway
summary: This footpath follows the alignment of the former tramway. All earthworks have long since vanished due to extensive re-modelling. A 1905 map shows an embankment along what is now Surrey Drive

title: Surrey Dive
summary: In its days as a swimming hole, the Surrey Dive had a fearsome reputation, and was the scene of several drownings. Today the scene is more placid, with model boats gliding across the water

title: Box Hill brick works
summary: Proposals to demolish the derelict brick works have been rejected as this is one of the few Hoffman-type rotating brick kilns surviving in Australia. However, neglect and vandalism have taken a toll

title: Morning greeting
summary: I'm not sure who this saint is but he looks like he's happy to be up early!

title: Calder Reserve
summary: There's a small playground here.  I wish it had a bbq and seats too.

title: School veggie garden
summary: If you peek in the cracks between the fence, you'll see the school veggie garden! I think it would be good if the school had a wire fence so you can see what's growing in the garden.

title: Trugo Club
summary: Whats Trugo?  It sounds Italian.  Must be a good game to play if theres a whole club set up for it!

title: Lawn Bowls Club
summary: They play mostly on Saturday mornings I think.  I've seen lots of people here, in their best whites (probably why I'd never be able to play - all my whites are attracted to food stains).

title: Coburg Leisure Centre
summary: Coburg pool, spa and gym. Friendly staff, fun pool for kids and a much improved cafe.

title: Bridges Reserve
summary: A lovely park to sit in, with benches, a weird sculpture and a bright red mural on the walking path.  There's also a monument to Harry (who's Harry?),  lovely flowers and a funny shaped tree.

title: Coburg Mall
summary: A nice place to sit and listen in on the local gossip if you speak Italian, or Greek or Lebanese?  Good spot for coffee and a great kebab/falafel.  Post office is here too.

title: House on the corner
summary: Who knows what this is! There's no explanation.  I asked a bloke passing by - his theory was that it was a house for the pigeons.  Unlikely.  The mystery continues...

title: Coburg Library
summary: Coburg library is fabulous!  You can borrow up to 30 items at a time - I usually stick to 5.

title: Coburg train station
summary: You can book Vline tickets here.  Recent improvements with lots of new plants, separate lane for cyclists and better lighting and disability access.  Good work!

title: Boronia/Dorset Rd intersection
summary: An apparent slip by 1888 surveyors resulted in Melbourne's worst intersection before the rail line went underground. Major collisions on the crossing took place in 1926 and 1952, each claiming 9 lives

title: Turner Road
summary: Torrens Ave was previously Turner Rd north and south of Boronia Rd. The 1920s post office was on the south side, the 1970s post office on the north corner

title: Boronia station square
summary: The retail complex on the east side was built in the  early 1970s, Boronia Mall in the early 1980s. The car park was re-modeled in the early 2000s. Some retailers have done better than others

title: Dorset Road
summary: In earlier days Ringwood Rd, Dorset Rd has been busy for many years, though the shops have changed much. The site of Maguire's garage, long a local landmark, is now the Commonwealth Bank

title: Boronia rail station
summary: Boronia station was opened in 1920. The first station was burned down in 1971, and was replaced in 1982, burned again, a third station in 1988, and today's sub-surface station is actually Mk IV

title: Erica Ave
summary: Erica Ave became a retail area in the 1960s. It was home for many years to Boronia fire station. The fire brigade practiced in Maguire Park, where pranksters put detergent in the fountain

title: Boronia Progess Hall
summary: The progress hall opened in 1926, hosting local dances for many years, and rallies in World War II. Damaged by fire in the 1990s, the hall was repaired, and still hosts community events today

title: "Post Office Bell" 2008
summary: Dr Anton Hasell created the bell.  Hassells "'Little Sister Bell" is suspended in the centre and chimes on the hour.  Atop sits the historic 1880's Horsham Post office bell and a corella figurine.

title: Jubilee Hall / Horsham Regional Art Gallery
summary: Jubilee Hall was opened in June 1924, the jubilee year of the Methodist Church next door.

title: Wesley Performing Arts Centre
summary: Formerly the original Horsham Methodist Church (opened in 1912).  Inside still today is the original pipe organ; the diapered designs on the display pipes are outstanding.

title: St Michaels and St Johns Church
summary: Built in 1987; the award winning design is the work of distinguished and internationally renowned Australian architect Greg Burgess

title: St Andrews Uniting Church 1962
summary: Designed by architect Keith Reed.  Much of the original stone from the old church was used in constructing the new building.  The stone was quarried from McKenzie Creek

title: Horsham Theatre
summary: An outstanding example of the work of Bohringer, Taylor and Johnson, one of the most important and prolific cinema architectural firms in Australia

title: 'Platanus acerifolia: Woven Nest' 2009
summary: This environmental work by Michael Shiell was installed as part of 2009 "Art is...Elemental" Festival.

title: Original Horsham Letterbox
summary: This original Horsham Letterbox inspired the design of the Post Office Bell sculpture in Firebrace Street.

title: Horsham Town Hall / Horsham Regional Art Gallery
summary: Built in 1938/39 as a municipal complex and was designed by Melbourne architect Charles Neville Hollinshed, who also designed Her Majesty's Theatre in Melbourne

title: Roof Top Ribbon 1998
summary: During the 'Art is....Energy' Festival in 1998, New Zealand sculptor Jeff Thomson, "the undisputed Iron Man of Australasia", was commissioned to create a sculpture.

title: Boer War - Avenue of Honour & 'Roberts' Tree 1901
summary: The only avenue to commemorate the Anglo-Boer war was planted in Horsham in 1901.  The remaining elm  of the original Avenue was planted to commemorate Field Marshall Lord Roberts.

title: Totem Pole 2000
summary: Angie Polglaze was commissioned by the 'Art Is... A River of Time' Festival in 2000, to create this piece of Chainsaw Art.  It was carved publically and noisily during the festival.

title: "Wimmera River Burnt Creek Meeting Place" 2007
summary: The sculpture takes the form of a seating arrangement.  The work uses stone mosaic to depict the intersection of the Wimmera River and Burnt Creek as a meeting place of the 5 traditional owner groups.

title: Painted Tiles 1997
summary: Images on the tiles reference chnages in Horsham city life through the seasons.  The pictures are the children's individual reflections on their culture and environment.

title: Bradbury Lane Mural 2008
summary: Local visual artist Nichola Clarke worked with youth groups from the area to create the Bradbury Lane Mural.  The inspiration for participants was to paint their idea of a future Horsham.

title: "Aerial" 2009
summary: The metal sculptural mural "Aerial" depicts aspects of the Wimmera's unique landscape; a ravens eye view of the area made in conjunction with students of McKenzie  Creek campus of Horsham College.

title: St John's Anglican Church 1957
summary: Features an expansive wooden ceiling, various stained glass windows and two significant sculptures.  'Wayside Calvary' and 'Compassionate Christ'

title: That view!
summary: When you reach the top of the hill, make sure you spin around and take in the view. Look over the new estate and see the beautiful hills in the background.

title: Fishing Lagoon
summary: This beautiful lagoon, surrounded by reeds is the perfect place to stop and try your hand at fishing. Shaded by beautiful trees, the picnic area is also a good place to stop for lunch.

title: Felltimber Community Centre
summary: The under road crossing to the community centre makes it easy to get to so you can check out what's on and what's coming up. Learn a new skill or just spend some time with likeminded people.

title: Clyde Cameron Reserve
summary: A beautiful piece of serenity, well off the road, this reserve makes it feel like you are miles away. It is a well shaded and easy path.

title: Skate Park
summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on the way!

title: The start
summary: Start near the 'Princes Walk' sign in between Federation Square and Princess Bridge and walk down the path to the river.

title: Path to Birrarung Marr
summary: Walk down to Birrarung Marr and you soon leave the traffic sounds behind.

title: View of the Yarra
summary: Looking across the Yarra river to the Boathouses. If you walk in the morning or evening you will usually see rowers on the water.

title: Angel
summary: An iconic Melbourne Sculpture by Deborah Halpern.

title: The shady path to the bridge
summary: The wide shady  path is gravel for the first few hundred metres before it becomes paved near Batman Avenue. There are some toilets on the left hand side.

title: Looking up the river
summary: This magnificent view may help you ignore the traffic on the bridge.

title: High and low path
summary: Once off the bridge, you can choose the higher more shady or lower path near the waters edge.

title: The steps
summary: There are two sets of steps nearby. Why not go up an down them a few times to get the blood pumping!

title: The high path
summary: More shade on the high path and a better view across the river.

title: Left before the Bridge
summary: Turn left before the bridge back up to St Kilda Rd (or continue on to Southbank and cross the river at the footbridge back to Flinders St Station).

title: Princess Bridge
summary: Cross Princess Bridge and you are back at the start, and should feel fresh and reinvigorated!

title: Foster Information Centre
summary: Marvel at our local talent in Stockyard Gallery or catch up with your facebook friends with free wi-fi in the Library. Community and tourist information available 7 days a week.

title: Pearl Park
summary: Enjoy Harry the Miner's view of the vegetable and flower gardens or put a snag on the free bbq.

title: Stockyard Creek
summary: The first alluvial gold was found in the Creek in 1870.  Can you spot a platypus - about as elusive as the gold!

title: Foster Skate Park
summary: Between the South Gippsland Water Board and the Scout Hall, we dare you to dangle your skateboard over the precipice.

title: Foster Primary School
summary: Site of one of the first Stephanie Alexander school gardens and still going strong.

title: Humungus eucalyptus tree
summary: Wrap your arms around this ol' timer.

title: Foster Adventure Playground
summary: Swing like a possum or climb like a koala over this large adventure playground for all ages.  Situated in the Foster Showgrounds. Public toilets available.

title: Ambulance Station playground
summary: Through the Tassie Tiger gate, a fire truck and ambulance are just waiting to be revved by young drivers.

title: Op shops
summary: There are a few op shops along this road, all with bargains to be discovered.

title: Secret creek
summary: This creek is quite hidden!  Don't quite know where it goes but is probably connected with the lake.

title: Blackburn Lake Sanctuary
summary: A beautiful lake, often with different types of birds and surrounded by a small pocket of forest.  Particularly atmospheric on foggy mornings as the mist rises from the lake.

title: Whitehorse Heritage Trail
summary: There are a few signs marking the trail, but I'm not sure where the Trail starts or ends!

title: Playground
summary: Playground recently given a bright red coat of paint.  Now it really stands out and gets the kids going.

title: The Pines Senior Citizens Centre
summary: I've walked past and seen dancing classes and morning tea on offer. What else do they get up to here?

title: War memorial and tennis courts
summary: War memorial and local tennis courts in the background.  A pretty garden and lots of places to sit and watch what's going on.

title: Blackburn library
summary: Lovely library with benches and mural.

title: French cake shop
summary: This French cake shop has some amazing cakes!  I once saw a queue all the way outside around Easter time.

title: Op Shop
summary: Bargains galore!  Great shops around this area too, including bakery, cafe, art shop, hairdressers and more.

title: Rotary Saturday market
summary: There's a little market outside Blackburn station every second Saturday of the month.  Fresh fruit and veg, craft, plants and other bits and pieces.

title: Playground
summary: Playground outside Blackburn station, a good spot for kids if you're waiting for the bus or next train.

title: View of Thompson River
summary:
There is a great view of the Thompson 
River and the new Pearson Crossing Bridge to your right.

title: Revegetation of the Sanctuary
summary: Indigenous tree planting has been completed by local primary school children and Wellington Shire Council staff.

title: Superb Fairywren
summary: The Superb Fairywren feasts on insects. The males are bright blue while female are brown.

title: Eastern Yellow robin
summary: The Eastern Yellow Robin is a common resident of Herb Guyatt Sanctuary which hunts insects.

title: Azure Kingfisher
summary: The Azure Kingfisher eats small fish and yabbies. You may see it as it darts between trees.

title: Lush Forest
summary: As you leave Mirboo North, you pass over some massive embankments and travel through a mix of remnant temperate rainforest and dry schlerophyll forest.

title: The Darlimurla Station & Picnic Rotunda
summary: A great place to stop to learn more about the rail trail through interpretative signage as well as finding remnants of the brick kiln used to create numerous culverts along the line.

title: Cartwrights Bridge
summary: A spectacular crossing over the wetlands of the Little Morwell River might entice you to take a break at the picnic table to watch out for an abundance of birdlife.

title: Post-fire forest regeneration
summary: This part of the trail has rebounded magnificently from the damage caused by the 2009 bushfires.

title: Cows in the reeds
summary: Signs of farming appear along the trail, especially when you come across a herd of cows munching on the tasty greens of the wetland reeds.

title: The Rolling Hills
summary: The Strezlecki Mountains became known by European settlers as “The Heartbreak Hills" due to the difficulty of eking a living from the steep, thickly forested, often sodden and remote country.

title: Daisies in the meadow
summary: Close to Boolarra is a lovely stretch of meadow, filled with wild flowers and swathes of daisies.

title: Welcome to Boolarra
summary: The old pylons of the railway are used as an archway as you enter Railway Park. As you approach, look for the interesting and historically significant brick drainage culverts under the trail.

title: Playground
summary: Start from the play ground south of Heidelberg round and east of Westfied reserve. Walk West along the asphalt path  avoiding left turns down the hill.

title: Turn right here
summary: Turn right just after the oval onto a concrete path (POI 2) between the oval and building. Cross Yarra Bend Road (a very small road) and follow the path south along Merri Creek.

title: Viewing platform
summary: A nice spot to stop for a picnic or to enjoy the view.

title: Path towards the city
summary: This (POI 3) is my preferred path into the city.  You can then take Roseneath Street West which is quite pleasant.

title: Bridge over the highway
summary: The second option (POI 4) appears preferable - you don't have to cross Alexander Pde, and you spend more time on park, but can be jarring once you reach Hoddle Street.

title: The Rushes
summary: Simply gorgeous parkland full of native plants and grasses. It also has an outdoor gym. Stop here to listen to the sound of twittering birds. Very relaxing!

title: Bottle brushes
summary: Bianca Boulevard's median strip is planted with flowering bottle brushes, which when in bloom, look spectacular.

title: The Ruins - Davis Park Heritage Area
summary: Here lie the remains of a blue stone cottage built by the Davis family in the 1850s. There used to be a cellar, dairy, irrigation channels, wells and more.  See boards for more information.

title: Orchard
summary: Look closely and you'll find various fruiting trees, including lemon, apple and olives. The park also has a cricket pitch outdoor gym, BBQ, seats and shelter.

title: Moorookyle Avenue Park
summary: This park has lots of seats and a fabulous playground. It's right next to the Moorookyle Country Club though entry is limited to Moorooklye Estate residents only.

title: Davis Family Park
summary: This park has a variety of features for outdoor recreation - ovals, basketball, playground, outdoor gym and climbing frame.

title: Birds of paradise
summary: Davis Family Park has fabulous plants that are colourful and unusual.

title: Map of Rowville in 1981
summary: The Knox Historical Society have included a map of the Rowville area from 1981. For more information on the History of Knox see the link below.

title: Emerson Place Reserve
summary: The walk begins at Emerson Place Reserve across the road from the Wellington Village Shopping Centre.

title: Emerson Place Reserve Playground
summary: Enjoy time with family at the Emerson Place Reserve Playground. Knox Council has  over 200 play spaces in parks and reserves.

title: Outdoor Gym
summary: The first outdoor gym in the City of Knox is now ready for everyone to use, for free! The outdoor gym consists of four separate stations in an easily accessible circuit. See website below for details.

title: Liberty Avenue Reserve shared path
summary: Follow the shared path toward Liberty Avenue Reserve. Knox has more than 100kms of shared paths that connect with major parks, reserves, schools and shopping precincts.

title: Outdoor Gym
summary: The next outdoor gym station at Jackie Close Reserve features a body dip station and two sit up benches.

title: Outdoor Gym
summary: The next outdoor gym station at Liberty Avenue near Magdalena Place consists of step ups, pull ups, leg raises and a stretch station.

title: Outdoor Gym
summary: The Liberty Avenue outdoor gym consists of a body twist, multi bars, eliptical trainer and leg press. It also features a set of instuctions on how to use the equipment.

title: Liberty Avenue Reserve Playground
summary: Enjoy time with family at the Liberty Avenue Reserve Playground.

title: Liberty Avenue tennis and basketball courts
summary: Enjoy a game of tennis or basketball at the public courts located at Liberty Avenue Reserve. Knox City Council provides a wide range of leisure and recreation facilities and programs.

title: Track sign and No. 5 Brace
summary: The building in the distance was a sorting plant for the coal, operating from 1909 to 1968. For hundreds of 14 year old boys this was their first place of work as they picked stones out of the coal.

title: Pioneer Mines Area
summary: This is where it all began. Mining commenced in 1909, producing 780,000 tons before closing in 1914. Underground workings were very shallow, evident by the depressions in this area.

title: Overgrown path
summary: Keep a lookout for this sign post. The red arrow points right, so take this short but narrow and overgrown path.

title: Fallen tree branch
summary: You may encounter a natural obstacle on this track as it takes you into the heart of the heathland.

title: Western Area Haulage Line
summary: A 3km rail track where skips were hauled overland by cable. Have a look for the cable on the ground. Pine trees line both sides of the track.

title: Baxters Beach track
summary: After you cross the road there is an option to walk to Baxters Beach. The red track to Baxters Wetland is clearly signed and heads to the right.

title: Nos. 9 and 10 shafts
summary: Together these mines covered an area of almost 200 hectares. Thats 160 underground cricket grounds! The coal has gone but this concrete shaft remains.

title: Baxters Wetland and bird hide
summary: Nesting boxes and permanent water make this a perfect home for many birds and water fowl. Watch out for Pacific Black Ducks, Purple Swamphens and White-faced Herons.

title: Campbell Street track entrance
summary: Leave the street and follow this gravel track back into the heathland. On the right is the Cinder Loop track which formed part of a horse drawn tramway used for transporting bricks.

title: Tent Town
summary: The site where 12 miners first lived when the State Coal Mine opened in 1909. By mid 1910 the township of Wonthaggi was established with the construction of 100 miners' cottages.

title: Amazing large mural by Smug, 2016
summary: This is a massive and striking piece of art by artist Smug, of his own grandparents.

title: Uniacke Court - Art by Deb
summary: Some great pieces of art by Deb, a Melbourne artist now working in te US. Some of these are from at least 2010, but still look fresh.

title: Dosa Corner - Indian restaurant
summary: As the name suggests, this place specialise in Dosa - thin, crispy pancakes served with a filling and a selection of tasty sauces to be mopped up. I can't go past a Masala Dosa - spicy potato filled.

title: Flagstaff Gardens
summary: Melbourne's oldest park and a beautiful open space. So named as it was the site of a flagstaff erected in 1840 to allow the city to communicate with the port.

title: Nomads back bar
summary: This alley was one of the locations of this years Meeting of Styles festival, an international street art event. This alley hosts artwork by Dvate, Adnate and French artist Choq.

title: Muleta's cafe alleyway
summary: Another MOS site, this back alley is overflowing with brightly coloured and fun pieces of art, including some great paste up work.

title: Blender Lane artists studio
summary: A studio, hosting some of Melbourne's most up and coming and established artists , this lane is forever being added to and evolving. An excellent spot for stencil art.

title: Queen Victoria Market
summary: Melbourne's most buzzing market - not open on Monday or Wednesday's though. Also open evenings with live music on some nights - check their website.

title: Redleap Reserve Northern Playground
summary: An adventure climbing playground close to the lake and picnic facilities

title: Public Art Pieces
summary: You admire the public art, like 'Brolgas and Eggs' by artist Kevin Free

title: Redleap Reserve Nothern Picnic Structure
summary: Facilities include seating, electric barbeques and cover structure

title: Peter Hopper Lake
summary: Peter Hopper Lake supports plenty of bird and animal life

title: Hungry Ducks and Water Birds
summary: Bring along some food for the birds if you enjoy getting surrounded by hundreds of hungry mouths

title: The Stables Shopping Centre
summary: This shopping centre has just about everything.

title: St Francis of Assisi Primary School
summary: There are plenty of quality primary schools in the local area

title: Findon Primary School
summary: There are plenty of quality primary schools in the local area

title: Roycroft Kindergarten
summary: Support your local childcare services by strengthening the concept of community

title: Roycroft Reserve
summary: Behind the the playground, you will find two football fields and connections to a greater network of walking paths

title: Mimosa Park
summary: A fantastic setup for a park. Barbeques, full-size basketball court, plenty of open space, playground and plenty of paths for the kids on scooter to roar around on

title: Mimosa Park
summary: Have a shoot around or challenge others to a game

title: Mill Park Primary School
summary: Mill Park Primary School supports walking and safe routes around schools

title: Safe Routes to School
summary: These recommended crossing points not only educate kids about road safety but show drivers that there could be children crossing also

title: Mill Park Community Centre
summary: This centre is used by senior groups, special interest groups and activity groups. Facilities include 5 rooms, kitchen and outdoor area.

title: Mill Park Preschool
summary: Another service in such close proximity to other community services

title: Aquastyle Swim School
summary: Learning to swim is a life-saving skill

title: Norparrin Centre, Dr Harry Jenkins Reserve and the Mill Park Tennis Club
summary:
The recreational opportunities are quite endless in the Mill Park area.
Norparrin is an Early Childhood Intervention Centre, providing services to children with developmental delay or disabilities.

title: Native grasses and billabong
summary: View across the billabong to Papillon Parade.

title: Playground and outdoor gym
summary: There are also seats and a BBQ.

title: Farfalla  Way Park
summary: A you-beaut playground, with BBQ, water fountain, basketball half-court, seats and shelter. A perfect place for a rest, picnic or family get together.

title: Overlook of Playground Reserve
summary: This is a very nice overview look of the playground reserve in the park which includes plenty of playground equipment, free public sheltered barbeque, bins, nicely cut grass and water fountains.

title: Oval
summary: One of the best ovals around. This one looks very nice and green with very finely cut grass. Looking good for ball games and running.

title: Bundoora Homestead Art Centre
summary: This art centre is a historic house gallery with a cafe and free admission. The front garden looks amazing.

title: Beautiful looking house
summary: This house or mansion was the finest looking in my opinion out of the already nice looking houses in the street and area. I thought it was a hotel.

title: Electric towers
summary: Two electric towers located close-by the hill just on the edge.

title: Mount Cooper scenery view
summary: A very nice distant outlook from the top of the hill. A lot can be seen from here. It's 137 meters above sea level- the highest point in Melbourne's metro area.

title: Lake
summary: This lake (or pond) had many ducks swimming in it. The bench there was great for sitting down, relaxing, and seeing the ducks.

title: Electric towers
summary: Two big electric towers close-by the hill just on the edge.

title: Information Hut
summary: At the day car park there is an information hut with toilets and a big map to help you find your way.

title: Map of Dinner Plain Village and walking tracks
summary: This walk goes through the Alpine bog reserve, onto the red lined 4WD track then to Charmichael Falls.

title: Playgound and picnic area
summary: Right next to the information hut and sign posts is a playground, giant chess board and picnic tables.

title: Vehical access  track
summary: This track loops the village and takes you to the start of the Charmichael Falls track.

title: Fallen Tree
summary: Much of this area was cleared to make a fire break to protect the village from the 2012 summer bushfires.

title: Start of the Charmichael Falls track
summary: Look out for this sign on your right and follow this path.

title: Track markers
summary: Look out for these orange markers hanging on the tree trunks to guide your way.

title: Natures colours
summary: The colors of nature change with the seasons.

title: Secret falls
summary: Look out for the unmarked fork in the path leading down to another mini falls.

title: Mini falls
summary: The fresh snowy water making it's way down the mountain.

title: Hazard
summary: There can be water on the track in places.

title: Alpine beauty
summary: The highland scenery.

title: Alpine Bog track
summary: Turn around here so you can take note of the entrance to the Alpine Bog track on your return.

title: Zig- Zac down the mountain
summary: The track cuts back and forth down this steep section to the viewing platform.

title: Viewing platform
summary: Just a little way further down the track is this viewing platform.

title: Charmichael Falls
summary: As seen from the viewing platform.

title: Tree tops view
summary: From the viewing platform you can see for miles over the undulating mountains and tree tops.

title: Alpine Bog Reserve
summary: Turn off to your left and follow the track through this permanently wet area which supports rare flora and fauna.

title: Hidden Grove wetlands
summary: There are several ways to access these wetlands, best to jump in and start exploring.

title: Keep your eyes open
summary: Even a bird this small can catch your attention! This fella was chatty and chirpy, posing for a photograph.

title: Pencil Park playground
summary: Look out for the towering pencils in different colours. The playground nearby is great fun too.

title: Covered BBQ facilities
summary: With the playground nearby and so many walking paths on the horizon, this is a handy spot to have a picnic or bbq and let the little ones play.

title: Keysborough Golf Club
summary: Walk along the south perimeter of the parklands, you'll spot the lush greens that belong to Keysborough Golf Club. Follow this path along until you reach the start of the next wetland area.

title: Tatterson Park wetlands
summary: As you wander through the Tatterson Park wetlands, envious of the homes on either side, look for other homes of the watery variety. A family of black swans have taken up residence here.

title: Chirpy residents
summary: As you walk, see if you can spot some of the native birds in the area. Black swans are easier to see than some of the smaller varieties. While others are louder than most!

title: Blue sky view
summary: A footbridge in the centre of the park offers a sweeping view of the wetlands.

title: Springers Leisure Centre
summary: This is the perfect spot for an air-conditioned rest, a cuppa and snack. You might even shoot some hoops while you're here!

title: Beautiful walking trails
summary: Be sure to wear a hat on sunny days. While there are trees closer to the woodland area, it's pretty steamy in full sun along the wetlands walking track.

title: Tatterson Park Community Sporting Complex
summary: You can't see it right now, but if you look south to the two ovals in the distance, that's where a brand new sporting complex is set to be built in 2016. Stay tuned!

title: World of Insects
summary: Quite possibly the cutest playground in the world, this one features ladybugs, ants, beehives and a giant magnifying glass! The design was chosen by the community and has an environmental theme.

title: Arachnophobes beware...
summary: Just joking. These spiders are for climbing on! Bugs too. Another aspect of the World of Insects playground in Tattersons Park. Not everything's cute it seems.

title: 20-hectare woodlands
summary: Maurie Jarvis Woodland is named after a councilor and three-time local mayor who had a passion for native trees and their preservation. More than 20,000 indigenous trees were planted here in 2005.

title: Transition into wetlands
summary: It's here on the edge of the woodlands that the wetlands begin. A stunning transition.

title: One of many playgrounds
summary: This playground is closest to Lake View Boulevard. There's a big tree nearby and a duck colony too.

title: Distinctly different wetland
summary: Cafardi Boulevard offers a different style of wetlands, at first, as it moves away from the rich woodland of Tatterson Park. Follow the street to reach Hidden Grove.

title: Dunolly Town Hall
summary: It was the original County Court from 1884 swapped functions and became the Dunolly Town Hall in 1890.

title: Dunolly Museum
summary: Dunolly Museum is home to the anvil that the world's largest nugget (69kg), 'The Welcome Stranger', was cut up on in 1896.

title: Original streetscape showing Coach Office and Billiards buildings
summary: Original streetscape showing Coach Office and Billiards buildings and part of TP Daly General Merchant.

title: Dunolly Post Office 1892
summary: The Dunolly Post Office was built in 1891 with the clock installed in 1949 as a Second World War memorial as well as the soldiers plaque in the front wall.

title: London Chartered Bank
summary: ‘The Welcome Stranger’ nugget was brought to Dunolly to be sold at the London Chartered Bank in Broadway. The building is now a private residence.

title: McBrides Ironmonger
summary: The two-storey ironmongery shop and dwelling was built in 1863 by Peter and Catherine McBride, who came to Dunolly from Scotland in 1857.

title: Footers Mansion 1865
summary: Once a privately-owned grand house, it is now a B&B.

title: Dunolly Uniting Church
summary: One of the few buildings in Dunolly that hasn't changed its use!

title: Wesleyan Jubilee Sabbath School 1886
summary: A very grand building that is now used as an op shop.

title: Belleville 1869
summary: Owned by politician James Bell and designed by a local store keeper, Thomas Tyrer.

title: Original Dunolly Town Hall 1862
summary: The town hall was complete with a public library and reading room, as well as council chamber and offices.

title: Lock Up 1863
summary: The Lock Up was built as one of the police and court buildings on the government and legal precinct on Market Street. It was used until the Dunolly Court closed in 1981.

title: Police Station 1958
summary: This is an example of a typical 1950s standard rural area police station.

title: Land Titles Office
summary: It was also a Postal and Telegraph Office 1872-91

title: Post Office
summary: Lands and Survey Office 1861

title: First Court House, County Court 1858
summary: The former County Court House was constructed of coursed bluestone by James Nichols. It is now a Masonic Temple.

title: Chauncy Cottage 1859
summary: Chauncy was District Surveyor from 1861

title: Noisy Miner
summary: Not to be confused with the Common Myna, the native Noisy Miners assist each other to raise their young.  They form large groups and actively defend their territory.

title: Heathlands
summary: The last section of the walk winds along the edge of beautiful native heathland that supports a wide variety of fauna. A large section of heathland is fenced off for conservation.

title: Wooden Sculptures
summary: Just as you set out on the walk you will pass by two beautiful new sculptures of native fauna.

title: The track
summary: The track is very level and well maintained throughout.  Just make sure you have brought a hat for sunny days.

title: The Bird Hide
summary: The bird hide gives you the opportunity to watch birdlife undisturbed in their natural habitat. An information board contains pictures and names of all the bird species you might see.

title: Great Egret
summary: There is a lot of birdlife living among the wetlands including the Great Egret (pictured), Australian Wood Ducks, Black Swans, Pelicans and many more.

title: Shared path
summary: You might meet the occasional cyclist traversing through the park at a very relaxed pace.

title: Salinity and Trees
summary: When salty groundwater comes to the surface it can be too much for some trees as this group demonstrates.  Rangers and volunteers are planting thousands of trees to keep the groundwater low.

title: Kangaroo Apple
summary: The Kangaroo Apple adds a wonderful splash of colour to the park when in bloom.  The fruits were eaten by Aboriginal people, but only when very ripe, as they are poisonous at other times.

title: Echidna
summary: If you hear a rustle in the grass it might be an Echidna out looking for lunch.  But if he hears you he will quickly try to hide.  If you see one, please keep your distance, they are very shy.

title: Port of Echuca entrance
summary: Port of Echuca entrance at the corner of Murray Esplanade and Leslie St

title: Port of Echuca Information Centre
summary: Port of Echuca Information Centre and the Bridge Hotel looking back.

title: Emmylou paddlesteamer
summary: Emmylou paddlesteamer

title: Houseboats on the Murray River
summary: Houseboats on the Murray River

title: Boat ramp on the Murray River
summary: Boat ramp on the Murray River

title: Picnic table at the bend
summary: Picnic table at the bend

title: The Canberra on an outing
summary: The Canberra on an outing

title: Corella in a gumtree
summary: Plenty of birdlife along the way including corellas.

title: A spot of fishing?
summary: A spot of fishing to while the time away.

title: View through the bush to the river
summary: View through the bush to the river

title: Bush track
summary: Bush track

title: Speed boat at the junction of Murray and Campaspe Rivers
summary: Speed boat at the junction of Murray and Campaspe Rivers

title: Overlooking the Murray and Campaspe Rivers junction
summary: Overlooking the Murray and Campaspe Rivers junction

title: Bush track
summary: Bush track

title: Campaspe River
summary: Campaspe River

title: Exit the reserve on Crofton St
summary: Exit the reserve on Crofton St

title: Victoria Park Oval
summary: Victoria Park Oval, home of the Murray Bombers

title: Fountain, statues and the James Mackintosh Red Gum Trophy
summary: Fountain, statues and the James Mackintosh Red Gum Trophy

title: Riverboat Dock
summary: Riverboat Dock

title: Busy Balmoral and Buckingham streets
summary: Although you have turned off the main road the action only seems to intensify as you are immediately surrounded by bustling people and shops.

title: Springvale Market
summary: This huge market has a vast array of food options, it takes up most of the block between Buckingham, Windsor, St. Johns and Balmoral avenues. It is open from 10am to 6pm 7 days a week.

title: Milan Teahouse
summary: Milan Tea House is tucked in a laneway between Springvale Rd and Buckingham Ave. It has a huge selection of Chinese teas. Purple clay, tea sets, hand craft and Chinese paintings.

title: Bun Bun Bakery
summary: Bun Bun Bakery , a very popular bakery specialising in meat and salad rolls, is one of many Vietnamese bakeries along this walk.

title: Peaceful suburban route
summary: After the hustle and bustle of Springvale Rd and Buckingham Ave it is nice to veer off onto this nice quite suburban street on the way to the park.

title: Norman Luth Reserve
summary: Norman Luth Reserve is a big park with 2 soccer grounds, 2 BBQ areas, big playground and a walk/running gravel track around the perimeter.

title: Library and Playground
summary: You can stop in at the library, to borrow a book, use the internet or simply read the paper – there are also public toilets inside. There is a playground and picnic area out the back.

title: Resting point in the flowers
summary: The flower garden in the entry way to the Springvale Town Hall and Council Chambers is a very pretty spot to sit down and watch the world go by.

title: Book Sculpture
summary: This book inspired sculpture is the footpath in front of Springvale Rise Primary School, I am sure it is encouraging the kids to read more!

title: Springvale Train Station
summary: The easiest way to get to Springvale is by public transport, the station is right in the middle and has lots of services to Melbourne CBD and suburban Melbourne.

title: Poinciana
summary: The Poinciana is originally form Madagascar but you have the chance to see it here in Brisbane! Don't forget to upload you recordings on the ClimateWatch app.

title: Silky Oak and Firewheel Tree
summary: Both evergreen tree, the Silky Oak's leaves are silvery green and fern-like while the Firewheel's leaves are dark glossy green.

title: African Tulip Tree
summary: Flowers usually appear in September. Are they out today?

title: Gymea Lily
summary: Continuing on the path, you are going to see a giant tussock-like, rosette plant. They can reach 5 m high with the flower stalk!

title: Illawarra Flame Tree
summary: An iconic Australian tree which flowers in spring. Scientists think that these trees and others might flower earlier due to climate change, so please record what you see.

title: Jacaranda
summary: Stop in at the mighty Jacaranda tree on the right. What stage of its annual life cycle is it up to?

title: Cannon Hill
summary: War memorial

title: View of Warrnambool's Foreshore
summary: Beginning of the walk

title: Mini Golf
summary: Enjoy a game of Mini Golf

title: Skate Park
summary: Skate Park

title: Viaduct Road
summary: Entry onto Pickering Point Trail

title: Entry onto the Foreshore
summary: You can enter onto the foreshore or beach via the Lake Pertobe Road section of the walk.

title: Breakwater
summary: Breakwater

title: Breakwater
summary: Wander around the cities beautiful breakwater

title: Point Richie Lookout
summary: Here you will find Public Toilets and Parking

title: Loagans Beach Walk
summary: Here Logan's Beach walk joins Warrnambool's Foreshore walk

title: The Flume (Surf Beach)
summary: Car Parking

title: Surf Life Saving Club
summary:
Surf Life Saving Club.
BBQ and Public Toilets.

title: Car Parking
summary: Direct access to the beach.

title: Car Parking
summary: Car and boat trailer parking

title: Car Park
summary: Car Park with direct access to Sting Ray Bay

title: Public Toilets and BBQ
summary: Public Toilets and BBQ

title: Point Park
summary: This environmentally sustainable parkland, features rain gardens and water storage cells cleverly concealed within the design.  Free BBQs and picnic tables are available.

title: Marina YE
summary: This Yarra's Edge Marina offers 175 private and public berths and boasts a range of facilities and services just minutes from the CBD.

title: Webb Bridge (2003)
summary: The sculptural Webb Bridge (Robert Owen & Denton Corker Marshall) was the result of an art competition transforming a disused cargo link into an artwork that functions as a walking and cycling link.

title: Blowhole (2004)
summary:
Docklands' prevailing winds
have been harnessed as a
medium in this 15-metre
sculpture by Duncan Stemler, creating a
spectacular animated beacon
within Docklands Park.

title: Docklands Park
summary: This community park is always humming with activity from family play time to lunchtime gatherings. Free BBQs and picnic tables are available.The children's area is located at the end of the park.

title: Cow up a Tree (1999)
summary: Created by John Kelly this artwork attracts an amazing amount of attention. The artwork was inspired by a flood that swept cattle into trees in Victoria's Gippsland region.

title: NewQuay
summary:
NewQuay's superb array of waterfront dining and drinking options range from Cambodian to Italian, Cantonese to Indian.
Day and night, people gather to enjoy the unique waterside atmosphere on NewQuay.

title: Silence (2003)
summary:
Sculptor Adrian Mauriks has
described this work as a series
of forms arousing to the mind,
appealing to memory, reminding
you of natural things  clouds,
a tree, a forest  questioning
and gesturing'

title: NewQuay
summary: NewQuay is home to the Melbourne City Marina and NewQuay Marina, with berthing for public and commercial vessels. Enjoy the view of luxury cruisers and boats for hire.

title: Sport equipment for use on the walk
summary: The Council has provided a few sport aparatus for walkers to use.

title: Hindmarsh Shire should be congratulated
summary: The plaque

title: Picnic tables are dotted around the park and the walk
summary: Picnic tables are dotted around the park and the walk and the Wimmera River is in the background

title: The scene at the Wimmera River
summary: Looking South along the Wimmera River

title: Wimmera River View
summary: The Wimmera River is magnificent

title: View along the roadway
summary: Wheelchair bound people can take the roadway if the do not wish to brave the gravel walking paths

title: The roadway
summary: The roadways is in excellent condition

title: BBQ areas
summary: The BBQ areas are well supported with water and bins etc

title: Playground and sport amenities, netball court
summary: There are loads of things for the kids to do whilst you are on a walk

title: Boat Ramp
summary: The turn around point is the Dimboola Boatramp

title: Car parking area
summary: The boat ramp car parking area

title: Boating details
summary: Details for boating and fishing

title: Picnic or seating area
summary: There is seating along the walk

title: Along the walk by the river
summary: The river walk is quite pretty and under trees. The trees are filled with all manner of birdlife such as parrots, cockys, galahs, corellas, lorrikeets, magpies, crows and other birds

title: Wonderful walk
summary: There are plenty of scenic spots along the walk

title: River walk
summary: make sure you take in the river walk

title: Check out where the birds are nesting
summary: The birds have loads of nesting areas in the trees and many are able to seen at breeding season

title: Walk towards the pavillions
summary: Take the walking track behind the pavillions closest to the river

title: Another piece of gym equipment
summary: Gym equipment to keep fit by

title: looking back toward the river
summary: At the main pavillions here is located the main public toilets

title: The wide view to the sports oval and buildings
summary: The wide view to the sports oval and buildings

title: Take the left fork in the road
summary: Take the left fork in the road

title: There are a few tracks
summary: There are a few tracks here that can also lead you to other ways around the park, but stick to the main track if you are in a wheelchair please.

title: Looking up Park Street
summary: The road up Park Street

title: River Gums
summary: The river gums are magnificent

title: BBQ and Picnic Area
summary: There is a few BBQs and picnic table under shady tree lined areas where you park the cars. There are bins and water is available here.

title: Under Cover Picnice Area
summary: A large picnic area is under cover and can be used in poor or wet weather

title: Knobby Club Rush
summary: Very hardy and successful near coasts.  It helps to bind sandy soil, is also good for getting rid of polluted water.  Aboriginal people used this in combination with sedges for weaving.

title: Seat on the coast
summary: As soon as you reach the beach there is a seat where you can rest for a moment.  You might spot a dolphin or banjo shark if the water is calm.

title: Beach walk
summary: If the tide is out you can return to Beach road via the beach.

title: Dog Whelk and Cockle Shells
summary: Shells can tell some interesting stories. Dog whelk (right) drill holes into cockles through their shell and then into their flesh. The flesh weakens from pressure, the shell opens. Dinner time.

title: Start of the walk
summary: At the start of the walk there is a very good information board giving details about the walk.

title: Picnic Bench
summary: Just inside the gate there is a picnic bench in a lovely setting.  A good spot for lunch when you return.

title: Coastal Woodland
summary: This is the last remaining section of coastal woodland on the Bellarine Peninsula.  There is a vast array of indigenous plants along the way.

title: Gnarled Tree
summary: This particular tree cannot be missed on the walk.  It tells the story of a hard and windswept life.

title: Beetle crossing
summary: Watch your step as you walk along the path.  You might encounter very interesting insects braving the open plains of the pathway to find food on the other side.

title: Bench
summary: A bench immersed in local flora, where you can sit and take time to spot some of the abundant wildlife that this coastal woodland supports.

title: Small Leaf Clemitis
summary: From July to November you will see cream, star-shaped flowers in abundance.  Male and female flowers are borne on separate plants.  The Aborigines cooked and kneaded the tap root to make dough.

title: Marshes
summary: Great views of water filled marches great the walker when you leave the coastal woodland.

title: Pelicans
summary: Look up!  Pelicans normally fish together.  They herd fish into a central position, and then plunge their bills into the water to capture a fish.

title: The boardwalk
summary: This fabulous boardwalk allows the walker to explore life in and around the lagoons.

title: Beaded Glasswort
summary: Beaded glasswort is abundant around the boardwalk. Their seeds are a major winter food source for the very rare Orange-bellied Parrots who migrate to Swan Bay from Tasmania each winter.

title: Grasses and sedges
summary: Grass skinks and tiny birds shelter and forage among grasses and sedges.  Butterflies lay eggs on sedges, a food source for their caterpillars.

title: The Grand Hotel
summary: Originally the Grand Hotel was known as the Coffee Palace.  The change of name to the Grand Hotel occurred in 1920. Head inside to see historic pictures. See walk description for more.

title: Feast Street
summary: Mildura’s iconic restaurants, The new Spanish Bar and Grill, Seasons and Stefano Cellar's.  This end of Langtree Avenue is fondly known as Feast Street.

title: The Mildura Brewery
summary: Mildura Brewery is the original site of the ‘hard top’ Wonderland, a wintertime cinema. Its name was changed to the Astor in the 1920’s and recent renovations have preserved parts of the old cinema

title: T&G building
summary: The T&G building on the corner of Eighth and Langtree has a distinctive clock tower. In the 1920’s it was the site of the Zimmers Building.

title: Hudaks Bakery
summary: Mildura’s bakery institution, Hudaks. It started life as Bowrings Buildings. The lane behind the building is still named Bowrings Lane.

title: Shillidays Corner
summary: Site of Mildura’s old department store Shillidays.  Shillidays ceased operation in the 1980’s. A short walk down from Shillidays Corner is the store Doug Haynes. It was the site of Mildura’s Bakehouse

title: The Ozone
summary: Where Rockmans is now located, was the site of yet another cinema, the Ozone. It closed in 1971, choosing the film ‘Ryan’s Daughter’ to say goodbye with.

title: Banjo’s Bakery
summary: Banjo’s Bakery was once the surgery of Mildura’s first resident dentist, Claude Sutton. Mr. Sutton practiced here for 50 years.

title: Dr. Abramowski’s Chemist
summary: Where the Bendigo Bank stands was once the site of Dr. Abramowski’s Chemist, similarly to Mr. Sutton, he was the first physician in the town and he gained an impressive reputation.

title: Mildura Fire Station
summary: On the left, 89 Langtree Avenue marks where the Mildura Fire Station stood from early in the 20th century until 1980, currently Tristar Medical Centre

title: St. Andrews Church
summary: Across 11th and left towards Deakin Ave is the Uniting Church, known as St Andrew’s. It started out as a Presbyterian church and was built in 1914, at a cost of 2097 pounds.

title: Mildura Public Offices
summary: Across 11th Street are the Mildura Public Offices.

title: Sacred Heart Peace Memorial Roman Catholic Church.
summary: Across 11th St is the  Catholic Church.  In 1896, a wooden structure was built in Pine Ave & in 1924 that building was relocated to this site. In 1921 the original brick church was built.

title: Catholic Church and Presbytery
summary: The neighbouring presbytery was erected in 1935. A walk inside the church is welcomed and the 14 Stations of the Cross, fine timberwork and stained glass are worth closer inspection.

title: Lime Ave
summary: Lime Ave was once a primarily residential street but is now an extension of the commercial centre. Places such as the Ballerina Ballroom, a popular dance spot in the 60’s are long gone.

title: Nash Building
summary: The Nash Building, named for G.A Nash, the original occupier of the building. Th building was completed in 1917, however the Nash Backery and Grocery business dates back to 1888.

title: Telephone Exchange
summary: Opposite the Mildura Brewery is the Telephone Exchange. In 1910 it was the site of Wonderland, an open air cinema.  Entry was 1 shilling for adults, 1/2 for children and 2 shillings to reserve a chair

title: The Rotary Children's Park
summary: A nice open play area, with a miniature train track (runs seasonally check beforehand if it's running).

title: Notice board
summary: Some good information about the Port Phillip Heads Marine National Park - it's history, local inhabitants and aquaculture.

title: Memorial Cairn
summary: In 1989 a 16 year old boy was drowned trying to save his brother.

title: Official start of Rambler's Walk
summary: Watch out for fellow bike riders. If you're bringing your pooch, please keep your dog on a lead.

title: Native trees and bushes
summary: The scenery is very pleasant along Rambler's Walk. There are various indigenous plants to admire along the way.

title: Fisherman's cottages to modern mansions
summary: Portarlington used to be a small seaside town. There are now many enormous houses as a result of more recent developments.

title: More trees and bushes
summary: Some well established tall trees have been planted by residents.

title: Rest stop
summary: There are several benches on this walking track. Take your pick from one of these two charming blue seats and gaze out to the You Yangs and beyond.

title: Coastal vegetation
summary: Salt bush and noonflower.

title: A small lagoon
summary: These areas provide protection from strong coastal winds for birds. You might see seagulls, pelicans, cormorants or ducks. These areas are at risk of inundation with storm surges and rising sea levels

title: Olive grove on the hill behind the town
summary: Look to the south, between the houses and over to the hill for our local olive grove!

title: Federation Square
summary: Home to major cultural attractions, world-class events and an exceptional array of restaurants, bars and specialty stores, this modern piazza, opened in 2002, has become the citys meeting place.

title: Bourke and Wills Statue
summary: Designed by Charles Summers, costing ₤14,000, the statue was unveiled on 21 April 1865, four years after the fateful expedition. It has had many city locations and was installed here in 1994.

title: Melbourne's Laneways
summary: Al fresco eateries, one-off shops and cosy litte bars, nestle side-by-side in laneways threading through the city. Each arcade has its own individual character and charm - choose your own adventure.

title: Southbank Promenade
summary: With splendid city views this path stretches along the south side of the Yarra River from the Southgate shopping and dining complex to the glittering Crown Casino.

title: South Wharf Promenade
summary: Situated in and around lovingly restored heritage cargo sheds on the edge of the Yarra River, this location brings together some of Melbourne's best food and beverage operators.

title: Webb Bridge (2003)
summary:
This sculptural bridge was the result of an art competition to transform a disused cargo link into an integrated artwork that could function as a pedestrian
and cyclist bridge.A great photo spot too.

title: Victoria Harbour
summary: Home to the Cow Up A Tree sculpture this location gives visitors an insight into the water activity of Docklands. From morning, rowing crews to charter vessels there is always something happening.

title: NewQuay
summary: Home to restaurants and cafes with cuisine from all over the world. Choose from a relaxed snack or a la carte dining. Enjoy the view across Victoria Harbour as you stroll the promenade.

title: Life can be a picnic
summary: Surrounded by Mountain Grey Gums, enjoy the well-kept picnic facilities in this delightful Park.

title: Home in the hollow
summary: Birds such as Rosellas and mammals (including the Brush-tailed Possum) make their nests in the hollows.

title: Bountiful birdlife
summary: This Fantail is just one of many bird species you’ll spot, such as Honey-eaters, Eastern Spinebills and White-throated Tree-creepers.

title: Take a seat
summary: Spend a little time on one of the many seats you’ll find along the track and you should see and hear some of the Park’s rich wildlife.

title: A wealth of orchids
summary: Home to over 43 species of native orchids, such as sun orchids, the flowers are simply superb.

title: Land of the Lyrebird
summary: You have now entered the habitat of the superb Lyrebird. The male is renowned for its varied and powerful song – including the mimicry of other bird songs.

title: The walking track
summary: A rich canopy of tall trees provides shade, and the track is well-maintained so you don’t need to worry about having to clamber over logs on your walk.

title: A diverse forest
summary: There aren’t many stands of remnant forest remaining in the region, but here you will come across a diverse mix that includes beautiful old eucalypts.

title: Spot the koala
summary: The well-loved Koala is common in this section of the track, and can be seen taking a nap in the tree branches during the day.

title: PepperTree Place
summary: This is a beautiful community garden full of edible delights. The Monthly Edibles Swap, Cafe Cooperative and nursery are open on the first Sat each month 10 -12pm; the nursery on Weds from 10 -3pm.

title: Pentridge Prison
summary: The imposing bluestone walls are a reminder of the prison, now converted into a residential development. Take a walk through the area to get a glimpse of its past. Click link for detailed description.

title: Pentridge Village - old and new
summary: An interesting contrast of colours. The brightly painted new houses and units are the complete opposite to the heavy and sombre blue stones of the former prison.

title: Rocketship
summary: There are 3 playgrounds at Coburg Lake Reserve. This one features a rocketship with a fancy slide that kids would love. Endless hours of fun!

title: Lookout platform
summary: A lovely area to sit and look out to the lake. The wooden benches display some interesting etchings / graffiti messages from locals who have made their mark here.

title: The Other Tea Party
summary: This set of tables and chairs are perfect for an afternoon tea party. Nearby is a fantastic playground, complete with flying fox and super cool swings.

title: Outdoor Gym
summary: This outdoor gym is very popular. Try out these various contraptions and give yourself a little workout.

title: Coburg Olympic Swimming Pool
summary: A perfect place to chill out during hot days. Entry to the pool is from Murray Road. The pool is open from 1 Dec to 31 March. Photo courtesy of Moreland City Council.

title: Yam Daisies (also known as Murnong and Native Dandelion)
summary: Yam Daisies are an an edible Indigenous plant. They have been planted here by the Merri & Edgars Creek Confluence Area Restoration Group. Look for the cluster of plantings south of Murray Road.

title: Hidden Creek Neighbourhood House - 20 Murray Road
summary: A lovely mosaic welcomes you to the House. Tucked behind the shops, the House offers courses and activities such as craft making, computer classes, women's groups and much more.

title: Merri Creek Market Garden
summary: Come and see what's growing this season! This organic garden is managed by CERES and has a strong volunteer program and is used for horticultural training.

title: Lake view
summary: There is plenty of bird life on the lake. Swans, ducks, magpies are common. You might spot cormorants and swallows too. See link below for the type of birds that visit the lake.

title: Trugo Court
summary: Trugo is a game created by railway workers in the 1920s. In its heyday, Trugo clubs were found in many suburbs to the north and west of Melbourne. This one will be converted to a community garden.

title: Fig Tree
summary: Figs are plentiful during summer. It's great that these residents have left a bit of their tree overhanging to share with passers by, but please be respectful and don't take more than your fair share.

title: Indigenous nature strip
summary: Here's a great way to jazz up your nature strip and bring some birds and beauty to your street!

title: Rubbish in the Merri Creek
summary: Plastic bags, drink bottle and various bit of rubbish continue to pollute the Creek. A good reminder to always dispose of our litter thoughtfully as they end up in waterways and affect local wildlife.

title: Picnic spot
summary: From the carpark there is a small footbridge across the stream and then you find this great spot for a picnic.

title: Climbing frame
summary: Next to the picnic spot is a very large fallen tree, great for climbing by young (and not so young) kids.

title: Picnic table and bridge
summary: Where the road bridge crosses the creek, there's a picnic table and a pipe intake (maybe).  Pleasant enough, but the other picnic spot is better.  You can access the walk here on foot from Jones St.

title: The little things
summary: This photo is of a piece of bark on the trail. Always good to keep an eye out for the little things while walking.

title: Little log
summary: Some smaller fallen logs provide occasional distractions for the kids.

title: The joy of ambling
summary: The path is wide, the forest high.  All is well with the world.

title: Big tree
summary: Gratuitous tree shot.

title: The forest
summary: Look up and this is the sort of thing you will see.

title: Ampheatre
summary:
Carl Stomp ampitheatre Seat 120 people
One of five used for performances and functions.

title: Nobelius Track
summary: Marker for start of Nobelius Track

title: Flora
summary: Native and exotic trees.

title: Great train race track
summary: Part of the Great train race fun run track.

title: Nobelius Station
summary: Unused station halfway between Belgrave and Gembrook.

title: Playground
summary: Children's playground also suitable for teenagers.

title: Fitness centre
summary: Outdoor gym consists of eight different work stations.

title: Puffing Billy railway line
summary: Railway line for Puffing Billy along side walking track.

title: Great train race track
summary: Another part of the Great train race track fun run track.

title: Puffing Billy railway
summary: Puffing Billy railway along side walking track.

title: Flora Emerald park
summary: Ferns and plants of Emerald Lake.

title: Packing Shed
summary: Historical site where Nobelius nursery dispatched plants by train.

title: Nobelius Siding
summary: Located at the end of the walking track at the Packing shed.

title: Former Tea Rooms
summary: Opened in 1919, the tea rooms were voluntarily staffed over the summer months to provide refreshments and entertainment to picnickers. The Tea Rooms are now used for exhibitions and events.

title: The Summerhouse
summary: Originally built in 1872, the reconstructed version was erected in 2000, after a successful fundraising effort by the Friends of Castlemaine Botanic Gardens.

title: Playspace
summary: Built in 2011, this unique play area features abundant locally sourced natural materials, and reflects the history of the area (eg. gold miner's hut). There's plenty to climb on and explore!

title: Assortment of trees
summary: There's a wide variety of native and exotic trees to marvel at.

title: Bridge
summary: You can cross this bridge to take a longer track around the western end of the gardens. It's also a good spot to listen to the local frogs.

title: Lake Johanna
summary: The perfect spot for bird watching (please don't feed them).

title: Wisteria heaven
summary: Come in spring time for an especially heavenly experience. The sight, smell and colour of wisteria is simply stunning.

title: Fountain
summary: What botanical gardens would be complete without a fountain? This was restored in 2011, and as you can imagine, is especially popular in the warmer months.

title: Riverside Park
summary: BBQs, multiple playgrounds, expansive lawns, basketball half court.

title: Milloo St Parkland
summary: Boat ramp, BBQs, River Red Gums.

title: Skate Park
summary: The usual

title: Medibank Icehouse
summary: A world-class ice sports and entertainment venue, containing two Olympic sized ice rinks, stadium seating for 1000, specialist winter sports gym, cafe and bar. Open daily from 9am.

title: Harbour Town Shopping Centre
summary: Harbour Town Melbourne, includes over 120 outlets and 70 specialty stores. Open daily from 10am. Visit the onsite tourism lounge for special shopping offers and visitor information.

title: Silence (2003)
summary:
Sculptor Adrian Mauriks has
described this work on NewQuay as a series of forms arousing to the mind,
appealing to memory, reminding
you of natural things: clouds, a tree, a forest.

title: NewQuay
summary: Family friendly waterfront cafes and restaurants can be found along the promenade from simple and delicious take aways to dine-in options. Enjoy the views of Victoria Harbour while you dine.

title: Etihad Stadium
summary: A multi-purpose venue which hosts as many as 85 sports and entertainment events every year - AFL, rugby, soccer and cricket, plus major performing artists such as U2, Bon Jovi and ACDC.

title: Victoria Harbour
summary: Take the time to relax and enjoy the view of the entire Harbour from the public space along the waterfront. See the in-water artwork of Ari Purhonen: 'White Caps' (2012).

title: Docklands Park Playground
summary: A combination of art and playground, it features a big circular ring with five swings, a tunnel and two metal slides, sandpit and two stand-on spinners. Free BBQs and picnic tables are on site.

title: Webb Bridge (2003)
summary:
This sculptural bridge was the result of an art competition to transform a disused cargo link into an integrated artwork that could function as a pedestrian
and cyclist bridge. A great photo spot too!

title: Point Park
summary: Situated on Yarra's Edge, Point Park is a great place for the children to run free on the green grassy knolls.Equipped with picnic tables and free BBQs, this is a great location for a gathering.

title: Nowingi Place
summary: Sing a song on the outdoor stage, have a swing in the playground or grab a drink from the water fountain.

title: Mildura Bridge
summary: Get a great view of the George Chaffey Bridge.

title: Mildura Wharf
summary: The old wooden wharf is used on a daily basis by the local paddlesteamers.

title: Mildura Skatepark
summary: Watch the youth perform their tricks and spins.

title: The Moreton Bay Fig Tree, Carlton Gardens
summary:
Wurundjeri Elder Colin Hunter Jr welcomes you to country in the video below.
From the 1920s-1940s, many legendary Aboriginal speakers such as Pastor Sir Doug Nicholls addressed gatherings here.

title: The Koori Club, 43 Gertrude St
summary: Established by Aboriginal artist, Lin Onus, this was a social and political meeting place during the 1960s for young people influenced by the Black Power Movement.

title: Aboriginal Housing Board of Victoria, 79 Gertrude St
summary: This was established in 1981 to advocate for Aboriginal families, whose needs were not being met by State housing services, resulting in high rates of eviction and homelessness.

title: Victorian Aboriginal Legal Service, 11 Brunswick St
summary: Established by volunteers in 1973, this service sought to combat disproportionate and unjust impacts of the legal system on Aboriginal people in Victoria.

title: Victorian Aboriginal Child Care Agency, 5 Brunswick St
summary: Established in 1976, this agency took steps towards healing effects of racist Government practice and policy that saw separation of Aboriginal children from their families (see: Stolen Generations).

title: Atherton Gardens Housing Estate
summary: During the 1980s, this was a popular and safe meeting place for homeless Aboriginal people as well as other Aboriginal people looking to find family and community. See 'Stories Around the Fire' video

title: Koori Information Centre, 120 Gertrude St
summary: Established in the early 1980s, this was an effective coordination centre for Aboriginal political activity that eventually attracted unwarranted covert surveillance by federal police.

title: Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, 136 Gertrude St
summary: This was the second site of the Health Service, considered one of the largest and most important Aboriginal organisations to have emerged from Fitzroy.

title: Fitzroy Stars Aboriginal Community Youth Club Gymnasium
summary: The Youth Club gym (184-186 Gertrude St) was established in 1977 as a preventative health program to combat the increasing drug and alcohol problems within the metropolitan Aboriginal community.

title: George Wright Hostel, 66 George St
summary: This hostel was initially established as a half-way house (in 1974) to support the increasing numbers of homeless Aboriginal men in and around Fitzroy.

title: Nindeebiya, 99 George St
summary: Established in 1983, this was a local community meeting place where Aboriginal people could gather to practise arts & crafts, play sports and have a feed.

title: Builders Arms Hotel, 211 Gertrude St
summary: Known as the 'Black pub of Melbourne', this was an important social and political gathering place for Aboriginal people from the 1940s until the 1980s.

title: Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, 229 Gertrude St
summary: Established in 1973, this was the first Aboriginal community controlled health and dental service in Australia.

title: Koori Kollij, 42 Cambridge St
summary: Established in 1982, Koori Kollij was an Aboriginal health worker training program that forged new and enduring standards of Aboriginal healthcare in Australia.

title: Victorian Aboriginal Co-operative Limited, 108 Smith St
summary: Established in 1976, this co-op provided local housing and welfare services to the Aboriginal community of Melbourne.

title: Pastor Doug Nicholls Church of Christ, 258 Gore St
summary: In 1943, Pastor Doug Nicholls and his wife Gladys Nicholls, with support from the Church of Christ, established a church service that attracted a devoted Aboriginal congregation.

title: Yarra City Council
summary: This walk is proudly brought to you by Yarra City Council. This walking map provides a brief outline for each point of interest. Please click on the link below for fuller descriptions.

title: Helen Street views
summary: Before you turn the corner, check out the leafy street scape ahead along Helen St. For all you know, you could be in an old English village....bet you didn't expect that.

title: Fancy a BBQ?
summary: Underutilised BBQ facilities ready to cook up a BBQ lunch. Also public toilets if you forgot to go before you left work.

title: Stop to Smell the roses
summary: Take a moment to enjoy Morwell's pride and joy - the rose garden.

title: Botanic beauties
summary: Many varieties...

title: And a sunny moment...
summary: What is your favourite rose?

title: Council native garden lanscape
summary: You might drive past this every day and never notice how beautiful it is

title: Street scape
summary: Another pretty street view that you may have never noticed

title: Walk start: Primrose and Albion St
summary: Meet here at 8.20am to start the morning walk to school.

title: Crossing Fitzgerald St
summary: Always remember to stop, look, listen and think as this crossing does not have lights.

title: Crossing Pascoe Vale Rd and  then Fletcher St.
summary: There are two streets to cross here, they are quite busy roads but both have traffic lights.

title: Flowers and frontyards
summary: There are lots of interesting things to look at on the walk including flowers, trees and interesting ornamanents in front yards.

title: Crossing Buckley St
summary: Another busy road to cross but it has traffic lights. Always check for turning cars, they are suppose to give way but always check they have seen you as you cross.

title: Along Buckley St
summary: This street is a little quieter. Council has laid some new sections of footpath and ensured the old path is nice and smooth. Keep an eye out for cars coming our of driveways.
