title: Crossing Hutcheson St
summary: Stop, look and think before crossing as they are no traffic lights here. There is a refuge in the middle of the crossing to make it safer.

title: The laneway
summary: Check for cars before you cross the little laneway. Council has made the laneway speed limit 10km/h which is great.

title: Heritage St
summary: Check before crossing this little street which is  a no through road. You are nearly at school!

title: St Monica's Primary School
summary: Well done, you are here!

title: Dolphins at the beach
summary: The Southern beach is a bit more windy and has litle waves for the kids to play in. You might be able to see a dolphin in this photo (black dot in the middle).

title: Towards Vincentia
summary: The interesting rocks form wonderful rock pools near the water.

title: Round the corner
summary: The inviting soft white sands beckon!

title: Looking backwards
summary: This walk always makes we want to sopt look where I am going, where I have come from, out to the Bay... The area is made for strolling

title: Rocks to climb over
summary: Love these little rocky outcrops. Kids and adults alike, climg over them

title: Sand beach
summary: Lots of little sandy beaches, all invite a swim!

title: Towards Vincentia
summary: The way the tall gum trees come down to the beach means that you can often see and hear a fantastic array of birds while you walk.

title: Heidelberg Artists' Trail
summary: A brief description of Arthur Streeton and his work 'Autumn' (also known as 'Eaglemont'). For the full Artists' Trail - visit http://www.artiststrail.com.au/ Below fuller description of 'Autumn'.

title: Eaglemont shops
summary: A pleasant shopping strip constructed between 1920 - 1960s. On Silverdale Road, there are 2 heritage listed Eucaplytups trees that are approx 200 years old - see if you can spot them.

title: Impressions of Eaglemont Village circa 1930
summary: Unveiled in 2004, the mural depicts the streetscape of the area.

title: Tribute to the Heidelberg School of Artists
summary: Gives an impression of what the area looked like before urbanisation.

title: Roadside planting
summary: A walk along this secret trail is a delight, thanks to community members who have planted the native bushes and tended to the seedlings on warm days!

title: Bridge
summary: Beware of traffic at this junction as drivers tend to speed through or around the corner. Although many pedestrians and cyclists use this area, the intersection has been a hazard for many years.

title: Odenwald Road
summary: Literally 'old world', the road is shady with many impressive Eucalypts and other trees lining the street.

title: To Albert Jones Reserve
summary: Eaglemont is a hilly area so enjoy the down hill walk while you can!

title: Albert Jones Reserve
summary: Albert Jones was a local resident that set aside the land for the reserve when it was threatened by development many years ago. It has a lovely playground but no bins so please take your litter home.

title: Delbridge House, 55 Carlsberg Road
summary: One of the most extraordinary and intact ultra-modern homes of the 1950-60s, the floating structure and all-glass appearance, was achieved only by daring structural engineering.

title: Desbrowe Annear House - 38 The Eyrie
summary: Built in 1903, the house was designed by Harold Dsebrowe Annear, one of Australia's leading and most innovative Arts and Crafts architects of the early twentieth century.

title: Heidelberg School of Art
summary: 'The Heidelberg School' refers to artists in the 19th century who were inspired by the beautiful landscapes of the Yarra River and the unique light that typifies the Australian bush.

title: Chadwick House - 32-34 The Eyrie
summary: Designed by Desbrowe Annear, Chadwick House incorporated Modernist ideas and Medieval-inspired design principles and was influential in the developmentof the Art and Crafts movement in Australia.

title: Steps
summary: The road now turns into a pocket park full of bushes and trees. Follow the path down the steps for a walk amongst the trees. This will take you to the next house.

title: Officer House - 32-34 The Eyrie
summary: The third of Desbrowe Annear's designs, Officer House is of architectural significance as a particularly good example of a work displaying the early expressions of modern architecture in Australia.

title: Lookout
summary: A good spot to lookout towards the Yarra river and Bullen Park and imagine what the landscape used to look like.

title: HIlls
summary: The hills are an excellent workout. Imagine how fit you would be if you walked this area every day!

title: Burnley Griffin Place
summary: Named after Walter Burley Griffin and Marion Mahony Griffin, who advocated garden city planning and the idea of a neighbourhood as a physical and social planning unit.

title: The Righi Reserve
summary: A lovely playground with plenty of shade. Perfect for a picnic.

title: The Eagles - 32 Eaglemont Crescent
summary: An unusual and eclectic inter-War villa with many distinctive details including vermiculated rendered panels, elliptical arched entrance porch, wrought iron balustrading and leadlighted windows.

title: Dowling Avenue gardens
summary: Lovely cottage gardens, and a very spectacular gum tree that looks burnt (but probably isn't).

title: Cambridge Sports Reserve Trail
summary: A pleasant and popular trail with walkers and dog owners. The reserve has a cricket oval, seats and shelter, tennis courts and a playground.

title: Playground
summary: Cute little playground for younger children, and possibly grown ups who like using some of the equipment to help them with stretches.

title: Tennis Courts
summary: A family oriented club catering for players of all ages and levels. There are 6 courts. Lessons available and competitions are organised to help sharpen your skills.

title: Box Place Kookaburra
summary: This kookaburra has found a beautiful garden to rest in. A wonderful example of a low maintenance yet delightful garden.

title: Jillard Walk gardens
summary: A spectacular little pocket of gardens! Take a stroll to admire the fantastic range of bushes and flowers planted here.

title: Carruthers Way Gardens
summary: More lovely gardens to walk past.

title: Latrobe River
summary: Heading east, you cross over a number of waterways but the first one across the Latrobe Valley floodplains involve an impressively long bridge utilising the old railway trusses and pylons.

title: Wonderful wetlands
summary: No need to wade through water to enjoy the experience of being within the midst of numerous birds and aquatic wildlife!

title: The great Australian pie!
summary: Welcome to Glengarry, which has a bakery famous for its tasty pies that are well worth making a stop to experience (Bushies Bakery at 19 Main Street).

title: Sea of poppies
summary: The diversity of agriculture in the region is beautifully illustrated by this field of poppies that are grown for medicinal purposes as well as being a superb sight in bloom.

title: Wide open road
summary: At Toongabbie, the trail opens up to become a wide boulevard and the historic township is worth taking a side trip to explore.

title: Home is where the hearth is
summary: Against a backdrop of farming enterprise, you will come across numerous examples of historic ruins that speak of this region’s rich history.

title: Things you can do with a soup can
summary: Just one example of the many innovative sculptures you’ll discover along the way is this upcycled representation of a cow, paying homage to the days when Cowwarr was home to a busy butter factory.

title: Cowwarr Art Space
summary: Internationally renowned artist-in-resident Clive Murray-White opens his studio at the Cowwarr Art Space to show interested parties the magic of transforming stone into sculpture.

title: The Dawson Connection
summary: Take some time to wander around the adjacent Flora Reserve before heading onto the quiet back roads towards Heyfield and then returning to the gravel path.

title: Heyfield Wetlands
summary: This is an excellent spot to pull over to enjoy the sound of frog song at sunset and a rich habitat for birdlife at any time of day.

title: Birds Land
summary: This well equipped picnic area is the starting point for this heritage walk. Birds land has BBQs, toilets and shelter, and is only a short distance from the main road in Upwey

title: Lake circuit
summary: The flat and well maintained paths around the two lakes are the most popular local walk. There is much birdlife, and many wayside seats at which to stop, rest, and take in the view

title: Retaining wall
summary: This flood mitigation basin was constructed in the early 1980s. The nearby gate is a meeting point for several tracks: Nixon Road to the north is steep

title: Dargon's homestead
summary: Thomas Dargon 'selected' this land and built a homestead in 1845. He drowned attempting to cross Dandenong Creek in 1862. His widow re-married, to Robert Nixon, and is buried in FT Gully cemetery

title: Strettle's granite
summary: Abraham Strettle purchased a property in this area in 1866 and called it 'Strettle's granite'. The view from the tors to the north and west is worth the steep climb from Dargon's track

title: Abrahams track
summary: This section of track is sheltered on a warm day. The farm on the other side of the fence is modern, but evidence of earlier farms is just around the corner

title: Sunset track
summary: Sunset track descends steeply to rejoin the main trail to return to our starting point at Birds Land. The dams beside the trail are evidence of earlier farms, and now home to numerous frogs

title: Mt Gordon
summary: This trail begins by walking in the direction of Mt Gordon, with a street of houses on the right and Murchison Street above on the left.

title: Lyrebird prints
summary: Gilberts Gully is home to many lyrebirds. Look for footprint etchings in the red earth. If you listen you might just hear their distinctive call.

title: Wilks Creek
summary: The first of two crossing at Wilks Creek, which was named after the engineer Clement Wilks who designed bridges and culverts in the 1860s that opened up access to the Woods Point Goldfields.

title: Spongy fungi
summary: As you walk, be mindful of what's beneath your feet. A pile of dry leafs can often be a home to another organism, in this case, a bright yellow fungi.

title: Mixed-species forest
summary: The trail continues up a small sloping hill, with tall manna gums pointing skyward and a thickening blanket of tree ferns covering the ground below.

title: Crossing Wilks Creek again
summary: This end of Wilks Creek is more vibrant and fast-flowing. The water is deeper and it seems more likely that other species might call this spot home.

title: Native birds
summary: If you're lucky, you might spot some of Australia's native birds, like this beautiful Crimson Rosella, which paused just long enough for a photograph at the end of the trail.

title: Richmond station murals
summary: A huge whale, by Makatron, and a whole host of other fun pieces of art to brighten up the daily commute.

title: The Corner Hotel's car park
summary: One of Melbourne's best known venue's for up and coming bands, this place is home to some excellent nights. During the day, check out the car park which is full of art, including a large piece by Bode

title: Lou Reed tribute
summary: Take a walk on the wild side and enjoy this monochrome Lou Reed tribute piece.

title: Super wall
summary: Need I say more? You may be lucky enough to spot an older piece of work by Adate here too.

title: Racehorse mural
summary: A piece of public art that is regularly defaced and then repaired, because not everyone thinks horse racing is a good thing. Pretty cave painting kind of style to my mind.

title: The green wall!
summary: A wall that has been covered by a number of artists, almost exclusively in shades of green. The centrepiece is a tribute by artist Dvate to his father.

title: Heesco, Putos and Mysterious Al wall
summary: A collection of pieces that I always ejoy seeing from the train on my way into town!

title: Coe and Coe cafe
summary: This place does amazing sandwiches and great coffee. A regular spot for Melbourne shock artist Lush - love him or hate him, he does make me laugh!

title: Indigenous boy by Adnate
summary: The eyes - I can't help but wonder what this innocent young boy is thinking whenever I see him, wonderful wall.

title: Kwik Kopy
summary: What a striking feature this building has been transformed into thanks to Beastman.

title: Start walk in Batman Park opposite the General Store
summary: At Batman Point, enjoy the view of the paddlewheels of the P.S. Ozone paddle steamer off shore and the information board. Walk north along the trail to Batman Rd. Public toilets only on foreshore.

title: Batman Rd lookout over Half Moon Bay and P.S. Ozone Memorial
summary: This lookout over Half Moon Bay is the highest point in Indented Head. Relax and enjoy views of the Melbourne skyline and the anchor of the Wreck of the P.S. Ozone.

title: Batman Road
summary: Batman Road is a wide road. Enjoy walking on the nature strip or the road edge. Go west on Batman Rd 200m to Ibbotson St or 700m to the Grassy Woodland.

title: Ibbotson St. Alternate route 800 metres to McDonald St.
summary: Ibbotson Street bypasses the Grassy Woodland and connects with McDonald Street, a Moonah trees conservation area.

title: Batman Road to Grassy Woodland
summary: Proceed west on Batman Road to Seascape Drive and enter Seabreeze Estate with the indigenous Grassy Woodland.

title: Seabreeze Estate and Seascape Drive
summary: Proceed south along Seascape Drive and view the significant Grassy Woodland and the wetlands basin with its abundant birdlife.

title: Grassy Woodland
summary: The 13 hectares of Grassy Woodland contains River Red Gums and Coast Manna Gums plus Golden Wattle and Hedge Wattle. Sun Orchids in November.

title: Glenrana Drive - 600 metres
summary: Proceed south and continue to Glenrana Drive with its winding path to Ibbotson Street.

title: Ibbotson Street - 300 metres
summary: Once at Ibbotson Street turn south/right until the next intersection and proceed east at McDonald Street.

title: McDonald Street  1 Km
summary: McDonald Street is a beautiful conservation area, lined with arching Moonah trees. Due to the Moonah trees high environmental value, the street has no through traffic but welcomes pedestrians.

title: The Esplanade - Wrathall Reserve
summary: Once at The Esplanade cross over and view the historic Batman Memorial and relax under Cypress trees in Wrathall Reserve Re-connect with the coastal trail and proceed past the BBQ shelter.

title: Coastal Trail - 600 metres
summary: Proceed north along the trail and view the historic boatsheds and cypress trees and the main swimming beach.

title: Coastal Trail to rigging area & Hall
summary: Cyclists continue behind the Boat and Yacht Club buildings on the foreshore, walkers can proceed in front to Batman Park.

title: IH Boat & Yacht Clubs and Indented Head Community Hall
summary: The much loved Community Hall has panoramic views of the Bay. When nearing the boat ramp look out for boating activity.

title: Batman Park Camping Reserve
summary: Back on the coastal trail, Batman Park has campers from November to April. The Wreck of the Ozone will come into view signifying the end of the Beach 2 Bush Walk. Public toilets and BBQ here.

title: Red Gums
summary: Red Gums growing along the lake shore.

title: Red Gums
summary: Red gums growing along the shore

title: Toilet, Camping & Picnic Ground
summary: Toilet, Camping & Picnic Ground

title: Flooding Point
summary: Normally dry, but if flooding occurs this section will be difficult to pass

title: Old Orphanage and School
summary: This is just a view of the old school and Orphanage which is a pleasant view throughout the first part of the walk.

title: Strath Village Shopping Centre
summary: Just to the south of this point is the Strath Village Shopping Centre. This possesses severeal pram and wheelchair friendly Cafes.

title: Kennington Reservoir
summary: A Beautiful lake to walk around with good parks and paths

title: Strath Sporting Reserve
summary: A good size sporting reserve, Great for kicking the footy or just mucking about.

title: Strathdale Park
summary: A nice large park with BBQ's, Toilets, a playground and plenty of Space. Great for Mucking around with the kids, picnicking or just lazing about.

title: Bushland
summary: This reasonable sized patch pf busland contains many paths, bot sealed and gravel to explore

title: Picnic and Play
summary: At the Mackey Rd carpark, you will find the Apex Bicentennial Park that provides an excellent picnic area with BBQ facilities, toilets and a playground for the young and old.

title: Popular spot for model boat enthusiasts
summary: The Model Boat Club has a Driver’s Stand that is a fantastic platform from which to launch your remote control miniature craft, or just watch others with the expertise.

title: Over the boardwalk
summary: No need to get your feet wet as you cross the wetland area that is brimming with wildlife of all descriptions.

title: Walking the dog
summary: You’re bound to meet a pooch or two on your travels along this walking track, and they seem to enjoy the surrounds as much as their human friends.

title: Beautiful native plants populate the park
summary: A dedicated Friend’s Group ensures that the vegetation within the Park is both diverse and appropriate to the area, with so many magnificent flowers such as this beautiful banksia.

title: Beautiful array of birdlife
summary: Mathison Park is extremely popular with birdwatchers because it provides so many habitat areas. You’re bound to meet a Moor Hen or two as you walk around Lake Hyland.

title: O'Hallaron and Hare Farmhouse Site
summary: A fine example of farmhouses in Hazelwood during the early 19th century. See in particular the domed wall.

title: Bush tucker
summary: An excellent interpretive sign provides an overview of the plants that have a range of uses for the Gunaikurnai nation that has lived in this region for thousands of years.

title: Gone fishing
summary: Anglers can choose from one of five fishing platforms, with the Latrobe Valley Fly Fishing Club and Associated Angling Club regularly stocking the lake with rainbow trout and redfin.

title: Sensational sunset
summary: This really is one of those places you can go to that will engender calm. At sunset and sunrise, Lake Hyland rings with the song of birds, frogs, insects and many other native animals.

title: Outdoor gym
summary: Check out the basic exercise equipment on the path and at a few pull ups or crunches to your walk

title: Bird houses
summary: Someone has built and installed some unique bird houses in the trees here. They're dated and initialled. I'd love to know who did this!

title: Netball courts
summary: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at Martin Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park

title: Skate Park
summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!

title: Picnic and BBQ area
summary: The oval along with the children's playground and BBQ area make this a great start/end point for a walk and for a picnic with the family

title: Park Beach South
summary: Not for swimming (dangerous currents), but great for walking.

title: Surfers on Park Beach South
summary: Lots of surfers to watch, sit on the sand   on Park Beach South or the breakwater rocks.

title: Fishing boats Coffs Harbour
summary: Love looking at fishing boats.

title: Yachts in the harbour
summary: If you are lucky you might see a yacht coming in.

title: Mosaic in the sea wall
summary: Look out for the mosaic in the sea wall. I only saw one, what's the story? Who put it there?

title: Along the Breakwater
summary: The path is great (good for prams). Sometimes waves can splash over the breakwater, on a warm day it is a delight!.

title: Eddies in the water
summary: Sit on the breakwater and watch the waves curl around into this little bay. The waves form eddies and patterns in the water. Very mesmerising.

title: Mutton Bird Island info
summary: Nice little rest spot and information on Mutton Bird Island. It is the last of the flat, get ready to climb.

title: Steps to Mutton Bird Island
summary: The steps to Mutton Bird Island, this is where you start to work. But, keep going. It is worth it!

title: The steep path
summary: Yes, the path is steep!

title: South Solitary Island
summary: Looking across to South Solitary Island. It has an historic lighthouse that you can just see.

title: Corambirra Point
summary: Looking across to Corambirra Point and the amazing rock formation. Boambee Beach is behind.

title: Looking back to the harbour
summary: Looking back to the harbour, Coffs Harbour and the many National Parks behind.

title: Little Mutton Bird Island
summary: Looking back at Little Mutton Bird Island.

title: Onto the Eastern tip of Mutton Bird Island
summary: Onto the Eastern tip of Mutton Bird Island. Smell the sea air, look out to the ocean. Heaven!

title: Tip of Mutton Bird Island
summary: The tip of Mutton Bird Island, this is what it is all about. It can be quite secluded and worth the walk. Sit, rest, think and smile.

title: Jetty Beach
summary: Jetty Beach is as good as it looks. Swim, sit, paddle, body surf or lie in the sun.

title: Jetty Beach picnic area
summary: The Jetty Beach picnic area has seats, toilets, water, shade and an abundance of bird life.

title: Coffs Harbour Jetty
summary: The Coffs Harbour Jetty is a great walk, love the sound of the boards under foot.

title: Jetty Beach from the jetty
summary: Looking back onto Jetty Beach from the jetty.

title: Mutton Bird Island from the jetty.
summary: The end of the Jetty and Mutton Bird Island.

title: Museum of the Living West
summary: Melbourne's Living Museum of the West occupies these historic bluestone buildings for its office, resource centre and exhibition space.

title: Willy Wagtails
summary: You are sure to spot Willy Wagtails darting about.  When feeding they distract insects by wagging and fanning their tail.

title: The walking route
summary: The route is flat and accessible to all.  It is mostly paved and has very well maintained gravel tracks.  A short section at the end is not readily accessible by wheelchair, and can easily be avoided.

title: Cumbungi
summary: Around the first small pond there is lots of Cumbungi growing.  It provides protection against bank erosion and is an excellent nesting site for water birds.

title: Riverside pathway
summary: The path alongside the river is a wide shared path.  There are also sections of gravel path nearer the river bank as an alternative to the shared path.

title: Lounging by the lake
summary: This recently developed area provides some wonderful resting options, fit for giants.  There is also a cafe in the apartment block behind.

title: Little Pied Cormorant
summary: Cormorants and seagulls spend time resting and socialising around the moorings here.  The cormorants dive in shallow waters to find fish and crustaceans.

title: Wetlands
summary: Built as part of the nearby apartment development, the wetlands cleanse the stormwater entering the river and provide a habitat for wildlife.

title: Masked Lapwing (or Plover)
summary: Around the lake and billabong is a feast of birdlife, including the Masked Lapwing (pictured), Eurasian Coots, Purple Moorhens, Seagulls and Ducks.

title: BBQ Area
summary: Near the end of the walk, and close to the car park, is a BBQ area with park benches and a drinking water fountain.  A great place for a picnic after your walk.

title: History of the Land Garden
summary: The gorgeous garden is a patchwork of small ornamental gardens and mosaics.  Information boards describe the many uses of the area over the years.

title: Mosaic
summary: One of the many colourful mosaics in the garden, depicting Aboriginal life before European settlers arrived.

title: Bluestone fords
summary: The first of two bluestone fords  you can turn left here, cross the ford and turn left again when you meet the river to make a shorter version of the walk.

title: Braybrook & Maidstone Neighbourhood House
summary: This organisation is made up of residents who live in Braybrook and Maidstone and surrounding areas and are committed to listening to and representing local people to build a proud community.

title: Wheelbarrow Garden
summary: Check out some of the wonderful gardens, like the wheelbarrow garden, on the walk. Very inspiring!

title: Cao Dai Vietnamese Temple
summary: Cao Dai is a new religious movement founded in Vietnam. It was established in the city of Tây Ninh, southern  Vietnam in 1926. Admire the topiary dragons!

title: Blooming Roundabout
summary: Enjoy the view of the roundabout, planted by Maribyrnong City Council and maintained by local residents, before you turn right onto Churchill Avenue.

title: Maribyrnong City Council Public Art - People
summary: People created by TRUC artists, Jonathan Leahey and David Burrows and made with corten steel.

title: Braybrook Library
summary: Braybrook's first library has transformed the community. Young, old, and everyone in between make their way to the library to read, relax and connect with others.

title: Braybrook Commons Community Garden
summary: The garden was set up by Maribyrnong City Council to help improve food security in Braybrook and surrounds.  The garden members are now an incorporated group. Join up and grow your own food!

title: Braybrook Park/Skinner Reserve
summary: Enjoy a wander around the park, walking and talking with friends.  Breathe in the fresh air nine kilometres from the city centre. Join in a kick of the footy or soccer ball and get your heart rate up!

title: Viewing platform
summary: Before you walk down to Steavenson Falls, visit the look out for a stunning view of the valley below. The 84-metre-tall falls has a year-round flow due to its forested catchment.

title: Information
summary: The falls begins its descent 350 metres higher up, on the crest of the Great Dividing Range. It drops 84 metres into a catchment of 16 square kilometres and supplies the town of Marysville with water.

title: A gentle path
summary: Follow the gravel path down towards the falls for a spectacular view. The falls mark the most dramatic point in the journey of the Steavenson River as it flows north to the town of Buxton.

title: From a distance
summary: Observe the falls from a distance for a sense of just how tall they really are. Keep watch for wildlife and you may see a platypus in the river pools nearby.

title: Turbine generation
summary: Walk along the lower path to access the turbine generation. At the base of the falls is a small weir that collects water, sending it down a 300mm-diameter pipe to power this hydroelectric turbine.

title: Water power
summary: This cross flow turbine is believed to be the only one of its kind in Australia. It was upgraded after the Black Saturday bushfires so that excess power could be sent to the national power grid.

title: One of the ponds
summary: There a couple of ponds in the Gardens with water birds and fountains.

title: Restored garden
summary: Museum Victoria restored the former German Garden of the Western Forecourt in 2009, it was a carpark covered in asphalt.

title: Amazing Gum tree
summary: This fantastic gum tree gives a glimpse  of the types of trees that once dotted the landscape.

title: Playground
summary: A great playground to bring children to on the weekend?

title: Basketball court
summary: How about bringing a basketball and some work colleagues for a game?

title: Melbourne Museum
summary: You could always stop and do some step ups onto the stone benches, that will get your blood going!

title: The Royal Exhibition Buildings
summary: Completed in 1886 for the Melbourne International Exhibition it was the site of Australia's first Parliament in 1901

title: Westgarth Drinking Fountain
summary: Make sure you have a look at the fountain of two embracing kangaroos that was built in 1888.

title: The Exhibition Fountain
summary: This intricate, multi-level fountain is a sight to behold.

title: The Avenue of trees
summary: Wonderful

title: View from Port Melbourne Beach
summary: View from Port Melbourne Beach to the observation deck

title: View from the boardwalk
summary: View from the boardwalk

title: Gravel path to observation deck
summary: Gravel path to observation deck

title: View across Hobsons Bay to Princess Pier and the City of Melbourne
summary: View across Hobsons Bay to Princess Pier and the City of Melbourne

title: View from the observation deck to the West Gate Bridge
summary: View from the observation deck to the West Gate Bridge

title: Bird life in the newly-planted vegetation
summary: Bird life in the newly-planted vegetation

title: View to Williamstown
summary: View to Williamstown

title: Observation deck looking towards the city
summary: Observation deck looking towards the city

title: Sandridge Life Saving Club
summary: A beach shelter at Sandridge Life Saving Club

title: Port Melbourne Beach
summary: View along Port Melbourne Beach

title: Part of the original Princes Pier from 1912
summary: Part of the original Princes Pier from 1912

title: Princes Pier building
summary: The newly refurbished Princes Pier is well worth a wander down.

title: Original Princes Pier pylons
summary: The newly refurbished Princes Pier is well worth a wander down to view the bare pylons under what was the original pier.

title: Highrise apartments from Princes Pier
summary: Highrise apartments from Princes Pier

title: Lighthouse
summary: One of a pair of lighthouses in Port Melbourne

title: Water sports
summary: Water sports with Station Pier in background. Unusual to have no ships in.

title: Beacon Cove Light Rail
summary: Beacon Cove Light Rail

title: Station Pier
summary: Station Pier

title: Side pier
summary: Side pier that overlooks Station Pier

title: Pier near Port Melbourne Life Saving Club
summary: Pier near Port Melbourne Life Saving Club

title: Victoria Hotel
summary: Victoria Hotel at the corner of Kerford Rd

title: Heritage buildings
summary: Heritage buildings on Beaconsfield Pde

title: West Beach Bathers Pavilion
summary: West Beach Bathers Pavilion

title: Catani Gardens
summary: The Catani Gardens, an icon on the St Kilda map and an oasis of shade in summer.

title: Royal Melbourne Yacht Squadron
summary: The Royal Melbourne Yacht Squadron with a history of almost 140 years.

title: Monuments on the foreshore
summary: Monuments on the foreshore

title: View  from St Kilda Pier to Melbourne
summary: View  from St Kilda Pier to Melbourne

title: Scenic view
summary: Belview terrace is a steep climb, but there are excellent views to the south across Lysterfield to the Mornington Peninsula beyond

title: The Boulevard
summary: A very rusty steel and concrete fence on the right is not the garden of some long forgotten house. It's the boundary fence of the former Ferntree Gully Zoo, dating from the 1940s

title: Mount Miller
summary: The actual summit is about 50m east of the track. On a clear day, there good views through the trees, including the city to the west, and Mt Macedon to the north-west

title: Lantern track
summary: Lantern track is more gently graded and quieter than The Boulevard, with fern gullies and wildlife, only 1 km from Ferntree Gully station

title: Kerrs quarry
summary: The view from the top of the quarry is one of the finest in the area. WARNING: entry into the former quarry site is hazardous

title: Upper Ferntree Gully rail station
summary: This was the terminus when the line opened in 1889, and starting point for 'Puffing BIlly' for many years. Part of the walking track back to the start are on the old rail right of way

title: Upper Gully primary school
summary: This grassy slope was the site of Upper FT Gully primary school until the school moved to Talaskia Rd in 1963. Kids could watch 'Puffing Billy' laboring up the slope from their playground

title: Shared pathway
summary: Stick to the left on this shared pathway that will lead you all the way to the waterfront.

title: Seating area overlooking the bay
summary: A great spot to sit down and enjoy the views.

title: Spectacular views over the waterfront
summary: The view just before you begin your descent down to Eastern Beach.

title: Bollards on Eastern Beach
summary: Check out the bollards on Eastern Beach as you go - note that there is plenty of seating available in this section of the walk as well.

title: Austin Park
summary: Plenty of seating and picnic tables available at Austin Park for you to sit down and enjoy your lunch.

title: Cafe Go
summary: Stop and pick up some lunch or grab a caffeine hit on your way back to the hospital.

title: Hilltop start - What a view!
summary: Start the walk with a downhill stroll through leafy, suburban Balwyn. Magnificent view towards  Kinglake - Yarra  Ranges on a clear day!

title: Leigh Park
summary: A great playground that has just been upgraded. Plenty of seating and a picnic table!

title: Boroondara Shops
summary: A great little shopping strip tucked away on the "other" end of Balwyn Road. Maybe too early in your walk for a drink stop, but there is also a public toilet should you need one!

title: Connecting to the Koonung Trail
summary: The pavement ends at this point on the west side, but the path is in sight! Continue on the grass or cross to the east side and follow the pavement. Watch for cars travelling too fast around the bend!

title: Drink stop!
summary: Drink fountain designed for dogs and people! Located on the bitumen path -the gravel one is just off to the left.

title: Indigenous Flora Reserve
summary: If you choose to walk on the gravel path, watch out for signs providing information about plantings and other items of interest.

title: Bridge to Doncaster
summary: This bridge provides access across the freeway back to Doncaster.

title: Billabong
summary: Perfect place for a mid-walk stop! Watch the ducks (and dogs) or meander around the  wetland area. There are many informal paths to explore - seating provided at several locations.

title: Exercise Equipment
summary: AB crunches anyone? There are several points along the bitumen path where you will find  exercise equipment.  Kids and adults playing! What a great idea!

title: Playground and toilet
summary: Another chance for a toilet stop and a play for the kids!

title: Right fork please!
summary: Take the gravel path heading toward Doncaster Road.  The bitumen path continues for several kilometres along the Koonung Creek Trail -great for another day!

title: Old Orchard
summary: The remains of an old orchard can be seen on the left hand side. A reminder this area was once farmland. Some of the tress are dead or dying, but the formal rows can clearly be seen.

title: Doncaster Road Exit
summary: Join back up with the busy Doncaster Road! Amazing what walking treasures are hidden behind this hard to see car-park. Great place to start explorations of BOTH directions of the Koonung Creek Trail.

title: Bus it back!
summary: Bus connects to Westfield Doncaster or back to the starting point!

title: Sculptures and Greythorn Shops
summary: People of the Community Sculptures outside the fire station. A busy shopping strip that offers everything! Explore the Op Shop, grab a meal or just have a coffee. Public toilet available too!

title: End in sight!
summary: Gentle hill climb back to the Tram stop!

title: Visitors centre
summary: A small free museum tells the story of Hanging Rock

title: The forest
summary: On your way up the track you walk through tall forest and start to get glimpses of the Rock through the trees

title: Edge of the rock
summary: The track splits and you start to walk along the edge of the rock face

title: 'Hanging rock'
summary: Appropriately, the path goes under this 'hanging rock' suspended between boulders

title: Natural amphitheatre
summary: This natural amphitheatre provides the first opportunity to explore amongst the rocks

title: Check out the views
summary: As you climb through the rocks to the summit, take the time to look back at the picturesque views to the north

title: The top!
summary: Congratulations, you've made it!  Take the time to play in the maze of rocks around the summit. You might lose the track up here but don't worry, you'll find it again.

title: Views of Mount Macedon
summary: At various points you will get glimpses of Mount Macedon amongst the views in all directions.

title: Rock pillar
summary: Take the loop back to go past this tower of rock.

title: Wildlife
summary: Make sure you keep an eye out for wildlife like this superb fairy-wren, especially in the forest.  If you are lucky you might even spot a koala.

title: Newtown Bridge
summary: Newtown Bridge was built by Scottish stone masons.  The channel under the bridge was cut through solid granite in the late 1860s for gold prospecting.

title: Mining Race
summary: This tailrace was cut through solid granite in 1856 to drain the Spring Creek flats, to enable miners to scour the area for gold.

title: Rocky outcrop
summary: Rocky outcrop along Gorge Road

title: The Cascades
summary: A series of waterfalls from which Spring Creek drops down into the valley below. Spectacular after rain.

title: Scenery from the top
summary: Scenery from the top overlooking the valley

title: Gorge Scenic Drive 5km
summary: This sign is at the driving entrance of the Beechworth Historic Park. The road is one way only. This walking map starts at the exit.

title: Queen Victoria Park
summary: In 1891 a group of volunteers began to develop this area. European trees were planted and two cannons mounted on the rock face known locally as the Giant's Grave.

title: Beechworth Gaol
summary: Beechworth Gaol is now privately owned and open for tours.

title: Beechworth Visitor Information Centre
summary: The information centre is formerly the old Shire Offices. The present front dates from 1889.

title: Beechworth Historic and Cultural Precinct
summary: This is the Courthouse from 1858.

title: Post Office
summary: The Post Office was rebuilt in 1867 with the bell and clock tower.

title: Tanswell's Commercial Hotel
summary: Thomas Tanswell replaced the original wooden structure in 1871 with the present building.

title: View over the valley
summary: View over the valley

title: Beechworth Honey Discovery
summary: Formerly the Bank of NSW dating from the 1850s

title: Queen Victoria Park cannons
summary: One of the cannons in Queen Victoria Park on the Giant's Grave.

title: Elsternwick Garden Playground
summary: An old fashioned wooden playground that's very popular with the locals, especially on weekends.

title: Lake
summary: Dip your toes in the water, watch the birds or simply go for a stroll around the lake and enjoy its peaceful atmosphere.  BBQs and seats are available in this park.

title: Skate Park
summary: We saw several young children having a great time whizzing around on their scooters.

title: Elwood local shops
summary: This is a lovely spot for a walk - there is plenty of shade, seats and the traffic travels at a slow pace.  I love window shopping here. Good spot for food, fashion and other stylish things.

title: Random art
summary: Great to see that Elwood is not immune from street art!

title: Rubbish bin
summary: An odd location for a rubbish bin - in the middle of a footpath! No doubt it was moved from the edge because of the bus stop, Might be more suitably located somewhere else?

title: A little girl's fairy tree
summary: "This is a very special little girl's fairy tree". What a treasure! A tree lovingly decorated by hand made toys, paper butterfly and colourful sign.

title: Roundabout cafes
summary: Around this roundabout are a handful of cafes that are certainly very popular on the weekends! These magnificent trees and plantings make the street look fantastic.

title: Grand Hotel
summary: The Grand Hotel is the former offices of the Victorian Railways Administration

title: Tram sculpture outside Grand Hotel
summary: Tram sculpture outside Grand Hotel

title: South Wharf Promenade
summary: South Wharf Promenade looking towards the Melbourne Convention/Exhibition Centre and the Polly Woodside

title: The Yarra River looking towards MCEC and the Polly Woodside
summary: The Yarra River looking towards MCEC and the Polly Woodside

title: The Tea House
summary: The Tea House was built between 1887 and 1888 as a warehouse for Fergus and Mitchell, manufacturing stationers, and later used by Robur Tea.

title: Colonial Tramcar stop
summary: Have dinner or lunch on one of the Colonial Tramcars. The stop has been moved (as of Jan 2016) to allow an upgrade to the tram line.

title: South Melbourne Market
summary: South Melbourne Market

title: South Melbourne Market
summary: Browse the shops at the South Melbourne Market

title: Browse the shops in Clarendon St
summary: Browse the shops in Clarendon St

title: South Melbourne light rail stop
summary: Catch the light rail back into the city at the South Melbourne stop behind the South Melbourne Market

title: Wombat's chai
summary: The first stop on the walk is Wombats Chai caf. Organic wholesome food is what Wombat's Chai cafe is all about. Fabulous, fresh flavours and homemade cooking has made Wombat's Chai cafe

title: Helaseville Hotel
summary: There are many shops to see along the way, but the next stop on the walk is the Healesville Hotel. Stop in for a bite at the newly improved Quince restaurant.

title: Cafe argyles
summary: This quirky caf serves freshly made treats and bites to eat made from locally sourced produce, along with local wines and beers, Its a great place to stop in and have a chai and muffin.

title: White Rabbit Brewery
summary: Just over the Bridge and around the bend is the crme de la crme. This brewery has an amazing selection of white and dark ales to choose from and if beers aren't your favourite- try their ciders!

title: Ian Potter Museum of Art
summary: Designed in 1998, the gallery houses the University's extensive art collection, ranging from classical antiquity to contemporary art.

title: Elisabeth Murdoch Building
summary: Previously named Old Pathology, this building housed the Medical School from the 1880s.

title: Wilson Hall
summary: The original Hall burnt down in 1952. Its replacement features a mural, stained and etched glass screen, pipe organ and sculptures. See the Trial of Socrates above the main entrance.

title: Architecture Building
summary: Originally designed in the 1960s by then Professor of Architecture Brian Lewis, with a 1990s addition by Daryl Jackson. Within are several sculptures.

title: Eight hour day plaque
summary: Commemorates a stonemason\'s stop work in 1856 which launched the campaign for the 8 hour day, an event of international significance in the history of workers\' conditions and industrial relations.

title: Cussonia Court
summary: Named for the Cussonia Spicata tree gracing the middle of the courtyard. This tree was propagated from a cutting from the original tree planted in the 1880s by one of the University's first professors

title: Deakin Court
summary: The pillars in the middle of the courtyard and at the eastern end are relics saved from the original Gothic Revival style Wilson Hall.

title: Union House
summary: The original building housed the National Museum (now Museum Victoria) from 1863 to 1899. Only a few fragments of the original building are still visible. Gallery on level 2 features contemporary art.

title: Underground car park
summary: An engineering innovation using mushroom shaped columns to support the roof and accommodate drainage for the lawn and trees above. It's atmospheric interior featured in the Australian film Mad Max.

title: Gatekeeper's cottage
summary: Built in 1860, the cottage was a residence up until 12 years ago.

title: University Square
summary: The Alan Gilbert Building houses Australia's first large scale building-integrated photovoltaic solar power generator which won an award for sustainable architecture.

title: Frank Tate Building
summary: Built in 1939, it was originally part of the Melbourne Teachers' College, this Art Deco building is now home to a learning centre for students providing individual and collaborative learning spaces.

title: Sidney Myer Asia Centre
summary: Built in 1999, the Centre is home to the Asia Institute and Asialink. The Centre prmotes public awareness and understanding of Asia.

title: Start here
summary: If a Wednesday, Thursday or Friday, catch the Kyneton Town service and get off at the bowling club.

title: Play ground, Library
summary: Stop here for a play on the equipment next to the Kyneton Mechanics Institute with a mix of equipment for ages up to about 10. Or take a visit to the library or a play under the trees in the forecourt

title: Kyneton Town Hall
summary: The Kyneton Town Hall hosts a shows for a variety of ages across the year, and the rails are great fun to play on. Have a look down the side of the building at the Black Saturday Memorial

title: An interesting display!
summary: An interesting display on the corner of historic Piper St.

title: St Paul's Park
summary: A great open space to play with the colourful leaves of autumn. Plenty of cafes nearby to have a break at. Stairs may be difficult for people with a mobility difficulty.

title: Kyneton
summary: Kyneton

title: An interesting church garden
summary: An interesting church garden with an amazing mosaic paving area to explore for young kids.

title: Sheep Dog and Sheep
summary: It could be a little difficult to get a pram or wheelchair in this entrance. The Kyneton Botanic Gardens are a great place for children of all ages to play and explore.

title: Botanic Gardens
summary: The Kyneton Botanic Gardens are a great place for children of all ages to play and explore.

title: Back toward Mollison St
summary: This area is a wonderland of colour and texture for children to explore. Follow the bluestone steps back up to High St, slippery when wet! Not a very accessible area of the gardens

title: Waterfall
summary: A waterfall runs down the side of the bridge, if it's rainy it will flow very quickly!

title: Station
summary: Time to head home!

title: Stop by for a quick game of hopscotch!
summary: Why not stop by for a quick game of old school hopscotch! Fun for all ages!

title: Bluestone steps
summary: Bluestone steps

title: Check out the view!
summary: View out over the Campaspe River.

title: Town Hall
summary: The Town Hall ramp and steps are great fun for younger children to swing and play on.

title: Town Hall
summary: Town Hall

title: Kyneton Primary School
summary: The Kyneton Primary School playground offers open space for playing and a selection of equipment for climbing and other activities. Wall murals engage with local wildlife and sporting traditions.

title: The trailhead
summary: Here's the start of the 2km trail, it's hidden on the left with a small car park attached. There's a Keppel Falls Lookout 350 metres further along Lady Talbot Drive, not to be confused with this walk.

title: Roaring river
summary: As you walk, the river will be beside you. Chances are, you'll hear it the minute you start walking on the track. It's a great view from up high on the path.

title: Afternoon frost
summary: Even if it's sunny, there's a chance you could still see frost on logs and boulders that are closer to the river. This photograph was taken at 3pm on a sunny autumn day. Brrr!

title: Fallen Manna gums
summary: Many trees have been felled in the area, but there's a healthy undergrowth that keeps this walk lush and cool in temperature. Admire these once proud Manna gums, tall enough to cross the river twice!

title: Signs of regrowth
summary: After the Black Saturday bushfires of 2009, the national parks have needed to regenerate themselves. Everywhere you look there are signs of the past and future, in the towering trees and vivid ferns.

title: Keppel Falls
summary: The falls were discovered by the Keppel brothers in the early 1800s. After the rains and the snow melt, the falls drain the nearby mountains into the Taggerty River.

title: Leave before dusk
summary: This walk takes you down into a valley, so it quickly becomes dark the minute the sun sets behind the mountains. Be sure to head back to the car park before dusk.

title: The Anchorage Restaurant
summary: A view to the city beside the Anchorage Restaurant

title: Williamstown Cenotaph
summary: Williamstown Cenotaph

title: HMAS Castlemaine
summary: Gem Pier with HMAS Castlemaine moored

title: The rotunda at Commonwealth Reserve
summary: A lovely spot for a picnic in the gardens of Commonwealth Reserve

title: Wilkinson Memorial Drinking Fountain
summary: The Wilkinson Memorial Drinking Fountain sits on the corner of Syme Street and Nelson Place, just in front of the Tourist Information office

title: J E Morley Reserve
summary: The most photographed view in Melbourne - historic cannon across to the City of Melbourne

title: Ferguson St Pier
summary: The view across ships moored at Ferguson St Pier to the tall buildings of Melbourne

title: Commonwealth Reserve
summary: The seaplane landing looking across to HMAS Castlemaine and Melbourne beyond

title: Mildura Arts Centre
summary: Mildura Arts Centre includes a newly constructed Theatre, Art Galleries and the historic Rio Vista house (originally owned by W.B. Chaffey) or grab a bit to eat at the cafe.

title: Lock 11
summary: If your timing is right, you can watch the workings of Lock 11 and see paddlesteamers and boats pass through on their way up or down stream.

title: Mildura Weir
summary: See the Mildura Weir in operation as it holds back the water and cascades 3-4 metres to the lower water level downstream.

title: MIldura Rowing Club & lawns
summary: A great place to take a rest and view the might Murray River.

title: The Mildura Wharf
summary: The old wooden wharf is still used on a daily basis by the local paddlesteamers.

title: Mildura's Langtree Mall
summary: For all your shopping delights, a snack or a meal.

title: City view
summary: Part of the amazing Melbourne skyline over the tram rails & start of the walk

title: Graham St. Skate Park
summary: Great place to hang out for skaters and amazing graffiti

title: Morris Reserve
summary: Tennis court and funny little playground

title: Garden City Reserve
summary: Beautiful park for a pick-nick and some playtime

title: 1st Lighthouse
summary: The Port Melbourne Lighthouses were built in 1924, and in conjunction guided ships. They have been preserved as part of a new housing estate that has transformed the old industrial port area.

title: 2nd Lighthouse
summary: The tower used to show a fixed green light over a 26 degree sector, whilst a second green light every six seconds in the four degree sector marking the center of the Port Melbourne Channel.

title: Restaurants and cafe's
summary: With so many places to go, it's hard to choose. Enjoy your break!

title: Spirit of Tasmania
summary: A buzzing place when the ferry just arrives or almost leaves. Wave people goodbye who go back to Tasmania or just starting their holidays!

title: Typhoon Cafe
summary: **Optional Resteraunt

title: Bendigo Wholefoods & Bulkfoods
summary: Sells organic and other bits and pieces food items.

title: The Epicurean Delicatessen
summary: Cured meat and cheeses

title: Typhoon Cafe
summary: **Optional restaurant

title: Favourite Flavours
summary: Handmade icecream shop.

title: Bath Lane
summary: Various cafes and boutiques

title: The Good Loaf
summary: Cafe

title: Indulge Fine Belgian Chocolates
summary: Chocolate shop

title: Turkish Kitchen
summary: Turkish Restaurant.

Wines and a range of 'nibbles' 

**Not reccomened for children

summary: Assortment of cafes.

title: Riverside Bridge
summary: This was rebuilt in 1962.  When water is low stumps of the first bridge can be seen on the north side.  This bridge was subject to regular flooding.

title: Bidjin Sign
summary: The Bidjin (meaning freshwater mussel) sign is from the Wergaia indigenous language of the Wimmera.

title: Jetty and Picnic Bench
summary: Right near the Bidjin sign is a jetty and picnic bench where you can enjoy a peaceful rest.

title: Wirringgal Sign
summary: Wirringgal (meaning Golden Perch) is also from the Wergaia indigenous language.

title: Jetty and Picnic Bench
summary: Located just near the Wirringgal sign is another opportunity to enjoy a rest or walk along the jetty

title: Yalam Sign
summary: Yalam (meaning Waterhole) is the last of the three indigenous signs along this particular part of track.

title: Jetty and Picnic spot
summary: Located near the Yalam sign is another opportunity to enjoy a walk out close to the water and chance to rest yourlegs and enjoy a snack.

title: The Capital Performing Arts Centre and Bendigo Art Gallery
summary: The Capital Performing Arts Centre and Bendigo Art Gallery

title: Dudley House
summary: Dudley House

summary: Borchelli's Ristorante

summary: Buildings at the corner of View St and Pall Mall

summary: Walk along Pall Mall towards the Soldiers Memorial Museum
