title: Pause Spot One
summary:
Take 5 deep breaths. What can you
See
Hear
Smell
Touch
Taste
Deep belly breathing and focus on your five senses. This is a popular way to relax and bring you into the moment

title: Pause Spot Two
summary:
Looking for Colours.
This can be helpful when your mind is going in circles.
Can you find something that is:
Green
Blue
Red
White
Yellow
What other colours can you see.

title: Pause Spot Three
summary:
Listening for Sounds
To fully in the moment we need to stop and absorb what is around us.
Listen for these sounds:
Birds 
Water 
People 
Traffic

title: Pause Spot Four
summary:
Take a moment to be grateful and reflect on your strength.
Say to yourself, I am strong like this tree because ............
Take a moment to be grateful and say to yourself, I am grateful for ......

title: Pause spot Five
summary:
Count your steps to the next pause spot.
Shift your weight from one foot to the other and walk with awareness one step at a time and count your steps until you reach your next spot.

title: Pause Spot Six
summary:
Congratulate yourself you have reached half way.
You achieve so many things over your lifetime. Take time to acknowledge them. Now turn and walk slowly, mindfully and enjoy the walk back.

title: Big Hill Track West, Greater Bendigo National Park
summary: The walk begins at the carpark for Crusoe Reservoir & Number 7 Park.

title: Historic Water Race
summary: The track takes you over water races, some empty…

title: Water Race In Use
summary: some full!

title: Track Intersection
summary: Take the track to the left at this first intersection.

title: Water Tank
summary: After the yellow gas pipeline sign, turn right and head towards the water tank.

title: Dam Wall
summary: The track goes between a small empty reservoir on the left and this brick building on the right.

title: Old Fence
summary: At this landmark, continue straight ahead.

title: Fork In The Track
summary: Turn right here and continue back to the beginning. The Number 7 reservoir will be on your left.

title: View along the way
summary: Number 7 Reservoir

title: The Ol' Duke Hotel
summary: The hotel and related buildings are a part of Portarlington's history. Enjoy music by an open fire at the National Celtic Festival.

title: The Ol' Duke - Harding Street side
summary: Admire the excellent restoration and redevelopment of an historic building.

title: The Portarlington RSL Memorial Garden
summary: This building was formerly a National Bank and houses a collection of military memorabilia.

title: St Patrick's Hall
summary: This church hall dating from the 1940s has unusual, harlequin glass windows and is still an important community meeting place.

title: Traditional timber houses
summary: This is a small enclave of traditional timber houses, especially lovely in autumn when the leaves are on the ground.

title: Intersection of Harding and Smythe Streets
summary: Be careful crossing this road!

title: Crossing Smythe Street
summary: You are leaving behind timber 19th century domestic buildings for large modern mansions.

title: Arlington Rise Development, turn left at the flags
summary: Experience a good footpath on this side of the road.

title: Across the roundabout take the upwards curving footpath
summary: This path will take you to a delightful small rest place and garden, with a spectacular view over Corio Bay to the You Yangs.

title: The park at the top of the hill
summary: Catch your breath and take a well-earned rest here!

title: Breathtaking views
summary: A beautiful view at any time, but a great sunset experience! Return to Newcombe Street where there are a number of enticing places where you can enjoy your choice of food and drink.

title: Train Station Precinct
summary: The Visitor Centre located here and can provide loads of information about Ararat and the surrounding areas.

title: Masonic Hall
summary: Look for this building as you head east on the Western Highway. It’s stand out paint work makes it very easy to spot! Turn left into Queen Street.

title: Langi Morgala Museum
summary: This red brick and bluestone building was built in 1874 and boasts a very interesting history.  It opened as the Langi Morgala (Home of yesterday) Museum in 1970.

title: Astor Cinema
summary: Completed in 1938 in the art deco style, The Astor was one of the largest purpose-built cinemas in rural Victoria. It closed with the advent of television, but re-opened in 1959.

title: Shire Hall
summary: The Shire Hall was built in 1871 – arguably one of Ararat’s most distinguished buildings. The building houses a WW1 honour board and a beautiful stained glass window that honours the fallen.

title: Cenotaph
summary: The monument was dedicated in 1930 to those who served Australia in various conflicts and in memory of those who died.

title: Town Hall and War Memorial Fountain
summary: The Town Hall was built in 1869. The fountain, planned to mark Queen Victoria’s diamond jubilee, also commemorates volunteers who fought in the Boer War.

title: Barkly Street with Vine covered verandas
summary: Barkly Street showcases many historic buildings and the vine covered verandas of the modern businesses. The first vine was planted in 1874 by Mr Grano outside his mixed business store.

title: Public toilet and seat
summary: Here if you need it! A small detour will take you to the Bull and Mouth Stables.  Built in 1866 these bluestone stables were described at the time as “one of the finest in the country”.

title: Nurses memorial – View Point
summary: The memorial was erected to the English-born nurse Edith Cavell who was executed in 1915 for assisting prisoners to escape from the Germans. Each Anzac day a nurse lays a wreath in her memory.

title: Historic buildings - Vindel House
summary: On the northern side of Barkly Street, pass  Vindel House. Constructed in two parts, the Sub-Treasury and Assay office in 1858 – the post office was attached in 1862. The  clock was installed in 1890.

title: Water station
summary: A modern and thoughtful addition to the street provides the means for walkers to refresh and refill! Leave the main drag at this point and turn left into Ingor Street.

title: Gum San Chinese Heritage
summary: This dramatic two-story building with its authentic Chinese tiled roof houses a fascinating selection of audio-visual and static displays. Well worth a visit!

title: J Ward - Lunatic Asylum
summary: Completed in 1861, this building was originally a goldfields prison. From 1866 to 1991 was the only institution in Victoria entirely devoted to the care of the criminally insane.

title: Pyrenees House
summary: Completed in 1886 in the Queen Anne style it operated as a general hospital until 1937. Since 1988 it has been used as administration offices and a nurse education centre.

title: Alexandra Gardens
summary: The Alexandra Gardens is home to the Active Pathway Project consisting a multi use pathway around the perimeter of the lake, two exercise stations, a wetlands boardwalk and better wayfinding signage.

title: Celebratory Coffee
summary: Head back to your car after leaving the gardens, or if you are in the mood, try Fred and Bet's  for a great coffee and an indulgent treat.

title: Starlight reserve
summary: This reserve dates from the 1970s, but contains Aboriginal bush tucker sources, and also remains of the Rowville military camp, built in 1942 to protect Melbourne from Japanese invasion

title: Tirhatuan wetlands
summary: This wetland is named for the homestead occupied by Rev. James Clow, first European settler in the City of Knox, 1838. The wetland are  home to much bird life, and aquatic species such as frogs

title: incline tramway
summary: This is the only incline firewood tramway in the City of Knox. The home owner has a wood fire or stove, and has constructed a 15 metre winch hauled tramway out of angle iron

title: Police Road retarding basin
summary: This massive retaining wall was constructed in the 1970s for flood mitigation by the Dandenong Valley Authority. The DVA was absorbed as part of Melbourne Water in the 1990s

title: Magic 1278 transmission towers
summary: These radio broadcast towers were constructed in the 1970s for AM radio Magic 693. Today operated by Magic 1278, transmissions from here are so powerful they can be picked up (just) in Antarctica!

title: Kilcatten Park site
summary: Kilcatten Park homestead was built by James Quirk in 1856, and home for many years to the Golding family. The homestead has now vanished, but exotic fruit trees still mark the site

title: VFL Park
summary: This arena was to be the home of Australian Rules football, staging the Grand Final and provided with its own rail line. Today, a moldering section of grandstand is all that remains

title: Wonderful shady seat
summary: On a warm day, this is a great seat to sit and watch the world go by.

title: The playground
summary: There always seems to be children in this playground.

title: Looking back to Apollo Bay township
summary: The path looking back to Apollo Bay township, the grassy knolls make wonderful slopes for rolling down.

title: Heading towards Barham River
summary: I love this part of the walk where you start to get inviting glimpses of the sea and start wondering what lies beyound the trees.

title: The Barham river
summary: Through the shady path and the Barham river appears, Marengo lies in the distance.

title: Dogs swimming
summary: Not sure if it is an official dog off leash area, but there always seems to be dogs here.

title: Expansive views and little rock pools.
summary: The ocean and sea breezes (sometimes gales!). The rock formations and great for hopping along and see things in the rock pools.

title: Collecting cuttlefish and shells
summary: Lots of things to keep children interested, shells, birds, cuttlefish shells and general stuff to pick up and look at.

title: The breakwater
summary: The stonework on the breakwater is truly a work of art!

title: The end of the breakwater
summary: Who can resist wallking to the end of the breakwater? Great fishing spot too (caught a flathead there).

title: Shelterd harbour beach
summary: Beautiful sheltered beach with crystal clear water. When we were there, two nesting Cape Barron Geese cmae hissing towards us.

title: Craypots, fishing boats and anglers.
summary: The piles of neatly stacked craypots and fishing boats in the water are really beautiful.

title: Apollo Bay beach
summary: The beach is most sheltered nearer the harbour and the swell gets bigger as you walk along the bay. It is a great beach for swimming, body surfing, surfing and flying kites (it can get very windy).

title: The skate park
summary: I love stopping and watching skaters, scooters and bike riders mucking around on the skate park.

title: The seals sculpture
summary: Next to the Tourist Info this is the first of many fantastic sculptures along the foreshore.

title: Seat and sculptures
summary: The grassy area across from the shops is a fantastic place to wander, stop, picnic and sit. If is also quite sheltered from southerly sea winds.

title: North Boundary Track
summary: Lookout which offers 360 views of the Churchill National Park, & you  can see all the way out to Stud Road

title: Car Park Entry
summary: There is parking out the front of the park on Churchill Park Drive which offers easy access to the hiking trails

title: Army Track
summary: You'll find many of the trails around the park quite wide with a loose gravel surface

title: Wildlife
summary: The park has an abundance of wildlife & quite a serene & tranquil place to visit

title: Fauna
summary: The park is full of hidden wonders

title: Escarpment
summary: Taylor's Creek cuts through the so-called "new volcanic" layer of basalt that makes up most of the terrain of the Western Suburbs. You can see plenty of volcanic features like this outcrop.

title: The Weir
summary: This Weir has been here for a fair while, and nearby is a strange bluestone box contraption that was probably a sheep dip. Crossing over takes you to a silcrete quarry. Beautiful red gums abound.

title: Native Vegetation
summary: As well as magnificent gum trees, there are native grasses, wildflowers and shrubs. Brimbank Council, Melbourne Water, and the Friends of Taylor's Creek actively care for the grasslands.

title: Housing
summary: People who live along the creek have been making their backyards their front yards so that they can better engage with their local environment.

title: Tool Scatters
summary: This whole area is very important for the Marin Bulluk clan of the Wurundjeri people, and has been inhabited for ten of thousands of years. Taylor's Creek silcrete  is found for kilometres around.

title: Have a seat
summary: Sit on the bench and enjoy the view

title: Wildlife
summary: There is always plenty of birds and animals around. In this case a Meadow Argus butterfly.

title: More trees
summary: This stretch of the creek is particularly blessed with big trees.

title: Ochre
summary: As we get further downstream, we get deeper under the basalt, revealing layers of gravel, Silurian bedrock, and this amazing ochre wall.

title: Birds
summary: Red-rumped parrot

title: Up the hill
summary: It's pretty steep up that hill. Have a breather on a slightly different seat.

title: Nature's Art
summary: Sculptural forms

title: View across to the Wheel
summary: A great place to start, if you are going to do a brisk walk, you might want to time yourself to see how fast you go for the next time you do the walk.

title: Grassy lunch spot and flower bed
summary: Why not stop and smell the roses? Great water side view on this lawn area makes a pleasant lunch spot.

title: The wide boardwalk
summary: There are quite a few seats or benches along this stretch if you need to take some notes on your walking meeting.

title: Harbour Esplanade
summary: A favourite leg of the walk with many other people out on a lunchtime walk. Time to talk, think or simply turn off and get some exercise.

title: Table Tennis
summary: Anyone for Table Tennis? Bring a work colleague, some table tennis bats and balls  and have some fun!

title: Cow up a tree
summary: Cow up a tree by John Kelly is a wonderful public sculpture. Look up every time you walk past and see if it makes you smile.

title: Monument Park
summary: Another interesting spot to stop for lunch. Sit on the lawn or bench look at the artworks and enjoy the view.

title: Silence
summary: 'Silence' by Adrian Mauriks is a fibreglass sculpture along New Quay Promenade. It's nearly time to turn around. Why not pick up the pace a little and get the blood pumping?

title: Looking South
summary: Always nice to look back at where you started, or where you are going!

title: The Rush Gateway - Bendigo Library Gardens
summary: Start your walk under The Rush Gateway. What do the strange shapes on the top mean? Don't even think of climbing this as it is huge.

title: Chancery Lane artwork
summary: Drop by Chancery Lane and see if you can spot these colourful creations! There's local artwork, coffee shops and clothing boutiques to enjoy.

title: Meet a Chancery Lane resident
summary: Not quite a doggy in the window but you can make friends with this one - he won't bite!

title: Who do you know?
summary: Take a closer look to see who you might recognise on these walls.

title: Shamrock Hotel - corner Pall Mall & Williamson St
summary: Built in 1854. The gold miners who came to see a show allegedly threw gold nuggets at the feet of a performer one night. Hotel staff later picked them up as tips! What a great job!

title: Bendigo Visitor's Information Centre - 67 Pall Mall
summary: You can find lots of information about things to do here. There are brochures, displays and more. Toilets are available at the rear of the building.

title: Bendigo Magistrates' Court , 71 Pall Mall
summary: There are fantastic lions and gargoyles at the front of the Magistrates' Court. How many lions and gargoyles can you see? What are they doing outside the Magistrates' Court?

title: Conservatory Gardens
summary: Established in 1901 and home to Australia's oldest glass hothouse, and the sculpture of a man fighting a leopard being bitten by a dog! Water tap is at the rear of the gardens towards Rosalind Park.

title: Rosalind Park
summary: The creek was an important source of food and water for the Dja Dja Wrung people who lived in this area. This grassy woodland with River Red Gums became a goldfield, then converted into a public park.

title: Chinatown precinct
summary: Once home to the Chinese miners in Bendigo, this place gives you a taste of Chinese culture and history. It's also a great space to run around and explore! See how many lions and dragons you can find.

title: Golden Dragon Museum
summary: Dragons are a popular and auspicious mythical creature in Chinese culture. See these fearsome and colourful creatures up close!  Check out the fun activities if you\'re here during school holidays.

title: Lotus flower
summary: The Lotus flower is often used as a symbol for purity and truth. Can you find the other giant flowers in the area?

title: Rosalind Park Fernery
summary: Enjoy the cool air as you walk through the fernery. The River Red Gums here are from the original landscape hundreds of years ago. Look up and see if you can spot a bat or two!

title: Rosalind Park - resting stop
summary: There are many shady areas where you can stop and have a rest, or simply run around to explore the area.

title: Playground - open after school hours
summary: Playground heaven! Slides, climbing decks, fireman's pole, bridges, a sandpit, and a large climbing net! Wheelchair accessible in most areas. There's also a drinking fountain here.

title: Cascades fountain and waterfall
summary: A cool spot for birds and people to enjoy the park. Built in the 1880s, the original structures fell apart until it was partially rebuilt in 1997.

title: Peter the Rabbit
summary: This Rabbit is called Peter. What's Peter looking at? What\'s he thinking? Who put him here? Why? So many interesting questions for a giant rabbit. If only he could talk.

title: Bendigo Vintage Trams
summary: If you're lucky you might spot the Vintage Talking Tram Tour. Hop on to join the tour but note that you'll have to stay on till it comes back to this spot again to continue your walk.

title: Alexandra Fountain - Charing Cross
summary: Imagine having a fountain named after you. This was named after Alexandra, Princess of Wales whose sons, Princes Albert and George, attended the opening ceremony on 5 July 1881.

title: Bendigo Ice Creamery
summary: Check out the many flavours available here. You can sit outside to enjoy your ice-cream while making other people jealous!

title: Pennyweight Walk
summary: A free gallery with fantastically colourful artwork by young local artists. Get your fix of street art here.

title: Marysville Information Centre
summary: Open daily daily from 9am to 5pm. There are public toilets, water fountains, fantastic playgrounds, BBQs and picnic tables near the information centre.

title: Town history
summary: The history of Marysville and its response to Black Saturday is expressed in words throughout the picnic area and playground. Keep an eye out for murals and images as you explore.

title: Gallipoli Park
summary: On 7 February 2009, a fire front destroyed nearly all the town's buildings. Some of the residents who survived the fire came to Gallipoli Park before being evacuated the next day.

title: Into the forest
summary: The path climbs as you leave Marysville, with views to your right and a gully of fern trees ahead. Tourism took off here in 1886 when the railway linked Healesville to the city,  inviting interest.

title: Look up
summary: As you walk, keep your eyes high to see remnants from the bushfires and signs of new life, closer to the ground at your feet. Marysville has a hidden valley feel, surrounded by mountains at all sides.

title: Like the lichen
summary: As well as tree ferns and mountain ash, there's also plenty of moss and lichen to admire along this walk. The mostly dark conditions suit the mossy blanket well.

title: Tiny mushrooms
summary: Depending on the season, you might see a mushroom or two, clinging to a tree branch or nestled in the roots below.

title: Return to Marysville
summary: At the end of the trail, you can visit Steavenson Falls and walk back to town the way you came. Enjoy the shade of the tall manna gums before the shorter tree ferns appear.

title: New Life
summary: Once back in Marysville, see the 2011 sculpture titled, 'New Life' by local artist, Bruno Torfs. The dedication reads: 'to honour the past and embrace the future'.  Bruno has a sculpture garden too.

title: Meteorite Park
summary: Dedicated to a meteorite that fell over Murchison on the 28 Sept 1969. See the newspaper clippings from across the globe on display. Fragments of the meteorite are on display in museums around

title: Gregorys Bridge Hotel
summary: Built 1865 and 1868, it was a country hotel, large general store and cellar with stables at the rear. The tree out front was planted in 1916 and is one of Victorias finest London Plane trees.

title: River bank gardens, boardwalk and three information lecterns
summary: Discover Murchisons bygone era with images of the old streetscape, pub and paddle steamers. The boardwalk provides an impressive view of the Goulburn River.

title: Goulburn River
summary: Saw its first paddle steamer in 1875. At the time Murchison had six hotels, two flour mills and numerous stores and services.

title: Murchison Heritage Centre
summary: Located out the side of the museum is a large pump that was used to pump water from the river for the townspeople.

title: Sparks Reserve
summary: An open space with a playground, sitting area, dog poo bag dispenser and creek-side picnic spot

title: New path, connecting the Darebin Creek Trail with the Main Yarra Trail
summary: Look left here to see the new path to the Main Yarra Trail, via Napier Waller Reserve.  This path is due to open to the public in 2017, though it is already well-trodden.

title: Bridge under Heidelberg Road
summary: This terrific bridge joined Sparks Reserve with the Darebin Creek Trail, making life much easier for Fairy Hills residents wanting to walk along the creek.

title: Flood-proof fencing
summary: The Darebin Creek floods regularly - to avoid fence losses, the owners of creek-side properties installed cable-based fencing with pivots with water flow.

title: A good spot to spot carp
summary: At the annual 'catch-a-carp' day, these pest fishes are sometime spotted here - though rarely caught.

title: Hill stabilisation works
summary: Build on an old tip, this hill is prone to slipping.  New stabilisation works and planting will keep the hill in place.

title: Ivanhoe Wetlands
summary: Look across to the Ivanhoe Wetlands - constructed in 1992, they are a haven for birds and wildlife.  You can reach them via paths and stepping stones further along the creek.

title: Parklands entrance - and 're-bushing'
summary: Look to your right for where grass and weeds have been sprayed to make way for new planting - as part of an ongoing parkland-wide transition from grass to bush.

title: Darebin Parklands map
summary: Just next to the path, this map shows the main walking and cycle routes through the parklands, as well as provision for dog-off leash areas and a number of historical markers.

title: A spot for everyone - seats and nesting boxes
summary: As you stroll through the park, look up to see nest boxes for native birds and small animals - they are an ongoing project of the DCMC and DPA to help wildlife protect their young from predators.

title: Path to the Ivanhoe Wetlands
summary: Follow this path to the right to find the stepping stones over the creek - then onto the Ivanhoe Wetlands, created in 1992.

title: Mount Puffalo
summary: Mount Puffalo was created in 1998, and provides superb view of the park.

title: Not just a duck pond
summary: Part of the parklands is built over a landfill, which 'leaches' liquid - a system on ponds, reed beds, waterfalls and wetlands clean and treats the water before it reaches the creek.

title: Waterfall - aerating the water
summary: Lovely to look at and listen to, this waterfall plays a key role in the water treatment system - it aerates the water as it travels from one pond to another.

title: Feeding the ducks - tempting, but discouraged
summary: Ducks love bread, but it's not good for them - while you might not be feeding them much, please consider that you may be the tenth visitor today.

title: On your bike!
summary: There are numerous shared trails through the parklands, though this one provides the easiest passage for wheels of all types.

title: Spend some quality time with the ducks
summary: Seats like this one are dotted throughout the parklands, providing a rest stop and an opportunity to watch the water birds .

title: Darebin Amphitheatre
summary: A perfectly placed amphitheatre, it is a popular spot for large family picnics, concerts and festivals.

title: Brand new public toilets
summary: At the Separation Street entrance to the parklands, you'll find a car park and these brand new public toilets - clean, accessible and unisex.

title: Keep up to date with parklands happenings
summary: Want to know what's happening in the parklands?  You can check out the DPA Facebook - but if you're passing by, you're sure to find something interesting on this notice board.

title: Environment Centre - learn more and meet the rangers
summary: Home to the DCMC rangers and a place to learn about parklands history and management - pictured here, Ranger Pete has played a leading role in creation of the parklands over the past 25 years.

title: Kensington Neighbourhood House (KNH)
summary: KNH runs various activities including vocational education, English language lessons, digital literacy, arts and crafts, social groups, weekend workshops and children's activities etc etc

title: 6th Melbourne Scouts
summary: 6th Melbourne Scout Group has a proud 100 year history, and is the City of Melbourne’s only remaining Scout Group.

title: Kumquat Tree
summary: McCracken st is a delight. Many of the beautiful cottages have citrus trees and lavender bushes spilling out on to the sidewalk.

title: Unnamed park.
summary: This park makes a lovely addition to the walk. Often there are warbling magpies to accompany you and there is a swing set and benches to enjoy the serenity.

title: Kensington Town Hall
summary: The Kensington Town Hall is a beautiful old building and an important civic space for the local community.

title: Pepper Cafe
summary: Pepper Cafe sits at the base of bustling Newmarket train station, on the popular shopping strip of Pin Oak Crescent in Flemington.

title: The HV McKay Rural Discovery Centre - Campaspe Run
summary: Elmore’s tribute to the Sunshine Harvester, early pioneers and the sheep and grain industries. Campaspe Run is home to Elmore’s Community Quilt and has a fabulous gift shop. Open 7 days a week.

title: Overhead Railway Bridge
summary: The Overhead Bridge was opened on June 16 1928 (costing £454 to build) and removed Nov 24 1980. It was sold to the Elmore Progress Association and today links Campaspe Run and the EPA Museum.

title: Elmore Railway Station Water Tower
summary: Built in 1870 to supply water to steam trains, the 18'x15' tower was made from locally made bricks. Water was pumped from the Campaspe River. The tower was donated to the EPA in 1972.

title: Elmore Railway Station
summary: Opened 1870, originally named Runnymede Railway Station, the station was renamed Elmore Railway Station in 1876. The Queen travelled by train through Elmore on her 1954 tour.

title: Elmore Progress Association (EPA) Museum
summary: Situated in the Railway Station Buildings, this volunteer run Museum is free and well worth a visit. Open Wednesdays from 9.30-2.

title: Cardwell Street 1920s - Heritage sign
summary: One of four signs installed as an initiative of the Elmore Progress Association. This sign features a photo of Cardwell St including the original Victoria Hotel.

title: Cardwell Street
summary: Gazetted as the main street. Named after Rt. Hon. Edward Cardwell, Secretary of State for the Colonies, 1864. Traffic flow altered when a new bridge was built & Margaret St was constructed in the 60s.

title: Former Bank of NSW/Westpac
summary: This double story building on the South side of the street is now privately owned and operates as Elmore Old Wares.

title: Elmore Plaque Project
summary: Wander down Cardwell Street and learn about some of the historic buildings by reading the plaques. The Elmore Plaque Project is an initiative funded by property owners.

title: Former Parson’s Store
summary: This store was established in 1893 and traded as a general store until 1982. Today, Parson’s Store is used as a display area, storage and workroom for the Elmore Miniature Railway.

title: Michie Street
summary: Named after Hon. Sir Archibald Michie, MLC, MLA, Attorney-General.

title: Athenaeum Hall
summary: Built in 1885 for £800, & opened in 1886, the Athenaeum Hall was designed by W.C. Vahland & built by Mr G. Galbraith.

title: Elmore Scout Hall
summary: This former Methodist Church, built in 1874, was purchased as the Scout Hall in 1983.

title: Michie Street Play Space
summary: The Michie Street Play Space features play equipment, drink fountain, seating, shade sails and a lush lawn space at the rear.

title: Clarke Street
summary: Named after John Clarke, owner of Boramboot or Stewart’s Plains station from 1850-1852.

title: Uniting Church
summary: Originally St Andrew’s Presbyterian Church (WC Vahland design) opened June 18 1899, the Uniting Church was formed by an amalgamation of Methodist and Presbyterian Churches in 1969.

title: Elmore and District Preschool
summary: The Preschool was built as an Infant Welfare Centre (circa 1960s) and extended as a Preschool in 1972.

title: Elmore Memorial Hall
summary: In 1920 it was proposed to build a Memorial to the local service men of World War 1 & provide work for some returned service men. The information board provides greater detail.

title: Elmore CFA Fire Station
summary: The Fire Station was opened on September 26 1972, replacing the one in Railway Place (1910-1972). The former site is now known as Progress Park near the Raywood Road Rail Crossing.

title: Elmore Police Station
summary: The current Station was built recently to replace the former station, opened in 1968. Before this time, the Police Station was situated diagonally across the intersection, now a private residence.

title: Law Courts
summary: The building next to the Police Station was built as the Law Courts but is now privately owned and used as a Solicitors and Accountants office.

title: The Old Water Tower
summary: Used to store the town’s water supply (pumped from the Campaspe). The pumping station was on rails to move up the bank in times of flood. The station also produced the town’s electricity until 1948.

title: Coffee Palace/James’s Bakery
summary: Originally a Coffee Palace & later James’s Bakery which was well known as the place for lovely bread fresh from the oven. This building (South side of Cardwell St) is now a private residence.

title: Jeffrey Street
summary: Named after the Jeffrey brothers who owned Burnewang Station from 1852 to 1867.

title: Campaspe River
summary: The Campaspe River rises in the Kyneton area & enters The River Murray at Echuca. Lake Eppalock (constructed by State Rivers & Water Supply Commission of Victoria 1961-64) is situated on the Campaspe.

title: Campaspe River Natural Play Space
summary: The Elmore Progress Association in conjunction with the City of Greater Bendigo are currently creating a natural play space on a former playground site. Drink fountain, seating and parking available.

title: Campaspe River Walking Track
summary: The Campaspe River Walking Track meanders alongside the captivating Campaspe River. Dotted along the track are information boards which highlight the unique attributes of this stretch of the river.

title: Campaspe River Pepper Tree Avenue
summary: The Avenue of pepper trees between the Campaspe River Bridge and Childers Street along Campaspe Street was planted on August 10 1898. The trees were donated by the Elmore Water Trust.

title: Senior Citizens Flats (now Public Housing)
summary: The Catholic Church donated the triangle land (junction of Campaspe & Jeffrey Streets) to the former Shire of Huntly to build flats for Senior Citizens.

title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Catholic Church
summary: The Church (WC Vahland design) was built in 1904. The Presbytery is next door.

title: Elmore Senior Citizens
summary: The Elmore Senior Citizens Clubrooms were built in 1973.

title: Brummy’s Seat
summary: An Elm tree (which has since been removed) had a circular seat placed around it and was known as Brummy’s Seat after Mr Bremner, blacksmith & Fire Brigade Captain, who loved to smoke his pipe there.

title: Shopping Strip (Railway Place/Northern Highway)
summary: Cardwell Street was the original main street, but with the construction of the new bridge & Margaret St, traffic flow changed & Railway Place/Northern Highway became the new main street.

title: Elmore Miniature Railway/Apex Park
summary: Built on the site of the Cohuna Goods yard, the Elmore Miniature Railway (EMR) line extends for 1.5kms, with the EMR station situated at Apex Park.

title: Campaspe Run Play Space
summary: Situated in the centre of town between the Railway station & Campaspe Run, the Play Space has lush lawns, parking, public toilets, picnic tables and a BBQ. A great space to enjoy a picnic.

title: Dandenong Civic Square
summary: The Civic Square is a great new meeting place and the perfect place to start and finish the walk.

title: Rob's British Butcher
summary: Visit Rob's British Butchers for home made UK Produce. Pork Pies, Black Pudding, Haggis, British style Bacon & Gammon, Gourmet Sausages and much more!

title: Rye Crust Polish Bakery
summary: Rye Crust Bakery is  family owned and operated. The Bakery makes great cakes, biscuits, pies, sweets, soups, salads, bagels, cabbage rolls, pierogi and much more

title: Little India
summary: Little India is the strip of Indian shops in and around Foster Street. It has a wide variety of Indian food, clothes, accessories and even an Indian museum.

title: Dandenong Train Station
summary: Dandenong Train Station is right in the middle of downtown Dandenong, with lots of services to and from Melbourne CBD.

title: Afghan Bazaar
summary: The Afghan Bazaar is the name of the strip of Afghani shops in and around Thomas Street. There is a growing number of Afghani restaurants and clothes stores here.

title: Maiwand Tandory Hot Bread Bakery
summary: The Bakery specialises in tasty Tandoori breads, the breads are baked right in front of customers eyes in the three in-store ovens.

title: Plenty of nice seats along the way
summary: The newly improved Palm Plaza provides plenty of seats and shade, great place to sit and digest!

title: Dandenong Market
summary: At Dandenong Market you will find almost every ingredient you can imagine—not to mention some you might never have dreamed of—making it the perfect place for anyone with a passion for cook.

title: A1 Lebanese Bakery
summary: The Bakery serves authentic Middle Eastern and Lebanese food as well as stocking a large range of grocery products direct from all over the Middle East and Lebanon.

title: Cardinia Cultural Centre
summary: Complete with cafe, toilets, a theatre and some local artwork. Also available for function hire.

title: Duck feeding frenzy!
summary: Throughout the loop, there are multiple piers - perfect for fishing or feeding ducks. The  pier at the eastern end of the lake, is the best spot to feed the local ducks and swans .

title: Amphitheatre  and grassed area
summary: A lot of local events are held in the  Amphitheatre. It is also  in front of a huge grassed area, perfect for playing sports.

title: Watch your step...
summary: Although most of the lake has no safety railing, the footpaths are quite wide, and the lake is very  shallow.

title: Take a breather.
summary: Throughout the whole loop, there is plenty of seating with amazing lake views.

title: BBQ's, playground and toilets.
summary: At the western end of the loop is a great picnic area and playground, complete with multiple BBQ's, toilets and tonnes of play equipment - it's the perfect place to bring the family!

title: A little artwork..
summary:
Huh? Where did these guys come from?

"Segmented Landscape" - Jennyfer Stratman

title: Just keep walking, just keep walking..
summary: The whole loop is averaged at 2,000 steps (1.5km) which is a fifth of the recommended amount of daily steps.

title: Fountain
summary: Have a sit down and watch the fountain for a while. Very relaxing!

title: Did someone say Swans?
summary: Try and spot these guys around the loop! They can be out in the open, or hiding in the reeds..

title: Fishing!
summary: A great pier perfect for catching fish out on the lake.

title: Wheelchair and Pram friendly!
summary: The entire walk is surfaced in either concreted or boardwalk. Suitable for pretty much everyone!

title: Start of Guide Track
summary: Its a 200m walk along Guide Track to the start of the Button-grass walk.

title: Friends of Bunyip State Park
summary: Friends of Bunyip State Park developed the walk over three years with the aid of Parks Victoria Community Grant funding.  For more information about the group see http://bit.ly/VTBsXk.

title: Hakea
summary: Look out for hakeas, particularly along the first part of the walk.  Hakeas need bushfires to propagate. The fire opens the woody fruits on the parent plant, releasing the seeds to germinate.

title: Heathy Woodland
summary: Walkers wandering through a forest of Silver-leaf Stringybark and Narrow-leaf Peppermint trees.  Look out for wattles, hakeas and tea-trees in the shrub.

title: Skink
summary: Pay attention to where you step.  You might spot a skink out enjoying the sun.  They are well camouflaged to avoid detection.

title: Numbered Markers
summary: For lots of detail about the abundant flora along the walk, pick up a copy of the flora notes at the beginning of the walk.  The notes have matching numbered markers along the route.

title: Wet Heathland
summary: Notice the dramatic changes in flora as we drop down into the wet heathland areas along the walk. You will also be treated to excellent views of the nearby Black Snake Range.

title: Boardwalk
summary: A boardwalk allows the waker to keep their feet dry while giving the opportunity to explore parts of the wet heathland that would otherwise be hard to access.

title: Button-grass and Spike Wattle
summary: Sedges, such as Button-grass, are tufted plants and over time develop quite dense and tall stools from which the leaves grow. These tufts are elevated above the water-table.

title: The dam
summary: The dam is feed by Button-grass creek.  Notice the many water plants and ferns that boarder the waters edge, a habitat for birds, frogs and insects.

title: Make some friends
summary: Say hello to these beautiful creatures on your way

title: Autumn beauty
summary: These beautiful trees create splendid colour in Autumn and lush cover in summer ensuring that you are shaded from the harsh summer sun. Not to mention they are pretty easy on the eyes!

title: Tyre swing
summary: This hidden gem has a picnic table and a tyre swing making it the perfect spot to stop, rest and play.

title: Old railway
summary: Take a stroll under the old railway line and take in some of our history. Make sure you turn to the right to keep on the track!

title: Over path bridge
summary: This is another of Wodonga's many excellent under road paths. Not only is it practical in removing the need to cross in front on traffic, but it is an engineering beauty

title: Skate Park
summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!

title: Oval & Playground
summary: Willow park is home to an oval and play area and is great recreational hub. Perfect for a picnic of a short rest before you begin the return part of the circuit

title: Netball courts
summary: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at Martin Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park

title: Nature at its finest
summary: The path is edged by beautiful trees almost the whole way along. Providing much needed shade in the warmer months and an excellent display of colour in Autumn, they are also home to many types of Bird

title: Football Oval
summary: If you are walking along this path, why not stop for a kick of football on the way. The oval is well manicured and is home to permanent AFL posts. A little friendly competition never hurt anyone...

title: Under road crossing
summary: Avoid crossing this busy road by taking the optional path underneath the thoroughfare. Great low risk option for people walking with groups of children or animals.

title: Les Stone Park Wetlands
summary: A great spot to try your hand at fishing. Even better if you have young children as it offers a safe space to teach them the skills.

title: Pirate Ship
summary: This play area is great. A safe space that lets the imagination run wild. Grab your eye patch and perch a bird on your shoulder and see what adventure you end up on

title: Map and information
summary: Start off by having a look at the information board to orientate yourself. There are public toilets, barbeque and picnic tables here.

title: Yarra River
summary: Yarra River is a great spot for a dip on a warm day. You'll be sharing the river with the ducks and other bird life! You can launch your canoes from here.

title: Begin Blue Tongue Bend Walk
summary: Marker for the start of the Blue Tongue Bend Walk. Only a couple of kilometres of blissful bushland to wander through.

title: Bushy goodness
summary: Take a sniff or two of the fresh air around you.

title: River view
summary: You'll be able to glimpse the river from the track at various sections.

title: Wild mushrooms tour
summary: Q: Did you hear the joke about the fungus? A: I could tell it to you, but it might need time to grow on you.

title: More mushies
summary: Q: Why did the Fungi leave the party? A: There wasn't mushroom.

title: A darker variety
summary: Q: Why did the Mushroom get invited to all the parties? A: 'Cos he's a fungi!

title: Stuck on you
summary: Ok, I've run out of fungi jokes. This one's the biggest that I came across during the walk.

title: Dappled sunlight through the forest
summary: A perfect location to practice your camera taking skills, or simply enjoy the light and shadows.

title: Slightly steep sections
summary: There are occasional uphills and downhills on the track, perfectly manageable - just distract yourself with the scenery while you make your way up.

title: Last view of mushrooms
summary: Group of fungi last seen making their own stairway to heaven.

title: Braybrook Community Hub
summary: The hub is where it’s at in Braybrook. It offers indoor and outdoor spaces for the Braybrook community. Classes on offer at low or no cost. Join with a friend or make new friends at the hub!

title: Braybrook Library
summary: This library is buzzing with families reading and learning together. The friendly staff are happy to help with information. There are books available to borrow in Vietnamese, Chinese and English.

title: Basketball and Tennis Courts
summary: Gather your friends and start training for the WNBL or NBL by shooting some hoops at Braybrook Park. Or work on your tennis serve at the tennis court nearby.

title: Skinner Reserve
summary: Home to the Sunshine Football Club Victorian Football Association (VFA) from 1959 until 1989. The club colours were navy blue and white. The sporting oval is now used primarily for soccer.

title: Dinjerra Primary School
summary: Dinjerra is proudly multicultural with over 25 different nationalities represented among the student cohort. Classes are kept  small to maximise teaching and learning.

title: Western English Language School (WELS)
summary: WELS offers an intensive program in English Language prior to enrolment in a mainstream setting.  A Breakfast Program runs for all students at the Braybrook site.

title: Braybrook Commons Community Garden
summary: The Braybrook Commons Community Garden offers a shared community space for locals to come together and grow and share produce. There are individual plots and some communal beds available at low cost.

title: Lance Reichstein Playground (photo from Council plans)
summary: The Lance Reichstein playground was built in 1999 following donations from the community, businesses, council and the Lance Reichstein Foundation. It is being rebuilt following a fire in 2015.

title: Double Canoe Tree
summary: The Goolum Goolum Aboriginal Co-operative Ltd placed this here in 1997 after the family on whose property the tree stood at in Lubeck until 1977 donated it.

title: Weir Park
summary: Formerly called Jaycees Park. This was developed during the beautification in the late 60s as well as building of the new weir in 1968.

title: Fitness Equipment
summary: A chance to break up your walk with some exercises along the way.  Choose from 4 pieces of equipment

title: Horsham Fly Fishers and Trout Anglers Club
summary: Due to the drought trout fishing has not really been possible.  With the lakes now having water and fish added, trout fishing has once again become popular

title: Apex Island and Playground
summary: This is a man-made island built by the local Apex clubs during the river beautification of the 1960s and 70s.

title: Rowing Club
summary: This was built in 1976.  The club was formed in 1883 although their first regatta was not held until 1972

title: Apex Club
summary: This is the home of one of the local Apex clubs.  Up until the 1980s you could hire paddleboats from here.

title: Old Horsham Weir and Swimming Pool Historical Sign
summary: Site of Horsham Weir 1875-1959.  Used as swimming pool until the new weir was built

title: Flood Markers
summary: These indicate three of Horshams largest floods, in 1909, 1981 and more recently 2011.  The second is an indication of the water height of the 1909 flood if the river beautification was effective.

title: Soundshell
summary: The soundshell was built in 1986 and is the site of many events including the Kannamaroo Festival and Carols by Candlelight.

title: Sawyer Park
summary: This land was owned by the Sawyer family who ran brickworks on this site from 1874-1939. At the eastern end of the park is a relica kilm built from bricks made at the brickworks.

title: Memorial Cenotaph and Vietnam Memorials
summary: The Memorial Cenotaph was designed and most of the erection completed by the RSL and volunteers in the town. Opened in 2004

title: History of Bridges and Tramline Historical Sign
summary: A horse drawn Tramway opened in 1885 transported road-making materials from McKenzie Creek (six miles south of Horsham) on second hand railway trucks

title: Seeliger's Brewery
summary: Ernst Seeliger worked as a brewer in South Australia before purchasing the Wimmera Brewery from Treacy and Smith at Meadowbank near the showground.

title: Swinging Bridge to Old Golf Course Sign
summary: This is the site of the 4th tee of Horsham's second Golf Course. Players hit across Burnt Creek.  A pedestrian swing bridge crossed the river to reach the course.

title: Old Pumping Station
summary: Walk south towards the river to find the sign.  The pumphouse for Horsham's first reticulated water supply was built near this spot about 1875

title: Corio Shopping Centre
summary: Opened in 1973 The Corio Shopping Centre has a range of  shops, supermarkets, major banks, Centrelink, Medicare, Jobservice agencies and specialty food stores including Halal and Asian grocers

title: Corio Bay Medical Centre
summary: The Corio Bay Medical centre cater for people from non-english speaking backgrounds and provides access to Doctors that speak many languages. The Centre is open Mon-Fi 8.30-6.00pm, Sat 8.30-12.30pm.

title: Northern Bay Secondary College Goldsworthy Campus Years 9-12

summary: This is an example of the prefabricated timber houses that were imported from Austria.

summary: This is an example of the prefabricated cement sheet houses that were imported from Holland

summary: William Palmer and his daughter Marie were killed after their horse drawn carriage collided with an express train to Melbourne. Their vehicle was thrown into a cattle pit and filled with water

summary: In 1925, Ford announced that Geelong would be the Australia's  headquarters for Ford. The 'Whole town is smiling' was the newpaper headlines with the prospect of increasing employment for the area.

title: 48 & 34 Brooks St
summary: These houses are examples  of the rendered concrete prefabricated houses built and designed at Holmesglen and erected on site to house workers and the  influx of displaced persons from WW2.

title: Stradbroke St
summary: Named after the Third Earl of Stradbroke who was the Governor of Victoria from 1921-26. His families motto was 'I live in Hope'

title: Waverly Reserve
summary: Land for Pocket Parks was allocated in new public housing subdivisions of the time.

summary: The Pettitt family farmed the land in this area. The Pettitt Bros. also manufactured and patented farm gates. Both John Senior and Junior were Corio Shire councillors and were community minded.

title: 23 Tennyson St
summary: This is an example of the large number of prefabricated timber houses that were imported from France.

title: Labuan Square
summary: This precinct was first time public housing was established outside of Melbourne. The shopping square was designed for localised shopping as most people had difficulty getting into the City.

title: The historic cairn
summary: A memorial to Jim Peterson welcomes the walker and provides the historic context of the walk.

title: Safety rails can be handy
summary: The Lookout track is secured by safety rails, which provide a welcome degree of reassurance as you head towards the lookout.

title: The Lookout
summary: This place will take your breath away. It’s truly an awesome view.

title: Bird's eye view
summary: The lookout has been built high above the Tyers Gorge, and casts a wide eye across a magnificent landscape.

title: Tyers Gorge
summary: Two hundred metres below, the Tyers River carves its way through steep mountains.

title: On top of the mountain
summary: You will get an excellent view to the south and the north along the Tyers River valley.

title: Geologist's delight
summary: If you’re looking for rocks, this is the place to visit.

title: Conglomerates
summary: The mountain face is cemented with conglomerates.

title: Dee Road Car Park
summary: We drove to Dee Road Car Park to start the loop. The turn off is in Millgrove. Plenty of parking and picnic tables but no toilet. The view across the Upper Yarra Valley is superb.

title: Interesting pieces of engineering
summary: The Aquaduct was built between 1911 and 1915 by predominantly Italian migrants to provide water to metropolitan Melbourne. The trail follows the maintenance track so its wide, flat and easy walking.

title: View of Mt Little Jo
summary: Through breaks in the trees you can see the other side of the Upper Yarra Valley. As a 2 time Oxfam trail walker, the sight of Mt Little Jo brings back mixed memories - tiredness, awe, inspiration!

title: Yuonga Road Car Park
summary: We walked on the morning of 2 Jan 2012, with 40 degrees expected in Melbourne. We chose to do 7km to Yuonga Road and back before the north wind picked up. Morning tea was mince pies and strawberries!

title: 350 William St green facade
summary: This west facing facade extends 12 metres above the street level and hosts a combination of climbing vines and decorative grasses.

title: Memorial Passage
summary: The resting place of unnamed pioneers who occupied Melbourne's first cemetery

title: EPA green wall
summary: Completed in 2012 this south facing 76m2 green wall is speckled with flowering species and hosts 15 species of bromeliads, ferns and ground-covers.

title: Paddy Pallin
summary: External green wall experiencing some vegetation damage

title: GPO
summary: This green wall  uses a felt pocket system to house shade-tolerant plants, many of which are used commonly indoors.

title: Council House 2
summary: Built in 2005, this became the first purpose-built office building in Australia to achieve a maximum six green star rating, and is the headquarters of the City of Melbourne.

title: Collins Place Podium Planters
summary: Completed in February 2015, the Collins Place food court includes 8 totem-style green poles ranging from 3 to 5 metres in height.

title: Lake Sambell
summary: Lake Sambell is a leafy retreat and bird haven not far from the township of Beechworth.

title: Beechworth Chinese Gardens
summary: Beechworth Chinese Gardens were designed in recognition of Beechworth's Chinese heritage with feng shui principles.

title: Beechworth Chinese Gardens
summary: Beechworth Chinese Gardens seen from McConville Avenue.

title: Ducks on Lake Sambell
summary: There are a variety of ducks and bird life at this lake. It's a good spot for bird watching!

title: Silver Creek
summary: A charming bridge over Silver Creek, a picturesque location to soak up the serenity.

title: Giant's Grave
summary: Giant's Grave, the local name for the large granite mound in Queen Victoria Park, is home to two cannons.

title: Beechworth Gaol
summary: The Beechworth Gaol ran from 1856 to 2004 and had many notorious prisoners, including Ned Kelly and Carl Williams.

title: Town Hall Gardens
summary: Baron Ferdinand von Muller sent trees and seeds from the Royal Botanical Gardens in Melbourne. These gardens have been open public space since 1857.

title: Burke Museum
summary: After the death of Beechworth's former Superintendant of Police, Robert O'Hara Burke at Coopers Creek in 1861, the formerAthenaeum was renamed in his honour as The Robert O’Hara Burke Memorial Museum.

title: Beechworth Visitor Information Centre
summary: All the information you need about Beechworth can be obtained here.

title: Beechworth Historic and Cultural Precinct
summary: The Courthouse from 1858 in Beechworth's Historic and Cultural Precinct

title: Post Office
summary: The Post Office was rebuilt with the bell and clock tower in 1867.

title: Start of track
summary: The start of the walk is not clearly marked, it starts just past the toilets. There is a water tap there but it is not for drinking.

title: Rough track
summary: The track gets a little rough and rocky in parts but doesn't stay that way for too long.

title: The gate
summary: Walk though the small top car park and onto the road,  go through the small gate after about 10 metres.

title: Centenary Track sign
summary: Take the path to Centenary Track, not the Circuit walk (which is a much longer walk).

title: Wild flowers
summary: Depending on the time of year, you will see many wild flowers.

title: Farmland views
summary: Lots of views through the trees to the bald hills of neighbouring farms.

title: Little bridge
summary: Somewhere around here you will come to this newly constructed little bridge that helps protect the land from erosion.

title: Beautiful trees
summary: Look out for some of the distinctly beautiful vegetation.

title: Wooden steps
summary: These steps mark the small descent down to the river.

title: The junction
summary: This wonderful pool is the junction of the Myrniong Creek (when flowing) and Werribee River.

title: Werribee River
summary: A beautiful and tranquil spot for a picnic. Although in heavy rain, the river can become a bit of a torrent as the logs up on the rick ledge attest- they had to get there somehow!

title: The view from the carpark
summary: This is a lovely spot to picnic before or after your walk

title: Riverside track
summary: Take the riverside track for better views of the river

title: Barwon River rock hop spot
summary: Great place to rock with the kids and first view of the paper mill

title: Steep stairs
summary: These stairs take you to the first lookout of Bunyip pool

title: Bunyip Pool Lookout
summary: Great view of Bunyip Pool and further upstream of the Barwon River

title: Lower lookout
summary: From the lower lookout, you can get closer to the falls themselves and also a view of downstream.  A suitable spot to stop and rest

title: Goat track
summary: Access to the goat track where you can continue further upstream

title: Rough track
summary: watch your step as the track is rough and can vary along the way

title: resting point/bird viewing
summary: a nice spot to rest and/or do some birdwatching

title: Bushy track
summary: the vegetation becomes more dense . Fun for the kids walking through here!

title: end of the track
summary: the riverside track ends here and you can choose to go back the way you came or cut across the top, back to the lower lookout.

title: taking the "high road"
summary: you can take a short-cut back to the lower lookout

title: stand of pine trees
summary: a lovely area for the kids to play among the pine trees, including a great big climbing tree. Just be wary for hazards here such as barbed wire.

title: Topiary heaven
summary: The owner is often in his garden trimming his topiaries.  There is a statue of the Virgin Mary, illuminated at night by hundreds of coloured flashing lights.

title: CH Sullivan Memorial Park
summary: Darebin Creek has large areas of native grassland with occasional visits from Kangaroos! I haven't seen them yet but it's good to know they're there.

summary: What I don't like in our area is the abandoned shopping strip. Probably unable to compete with nearby Northland, all the shops have closed except for the lonely milk bar.

title: Japanese style garden
summary: This garden is in the Japanese style with bamboo, bonzais, lotus and a Buddha statue.

title: Edible nature strip
summary: An edible nature strip with rhubarb, rosemary, sage, lavendar.  The front yard of this house is also filled with vegetables and fruit trees.

title: Artificial Wetland
summary: This artificial wetland harvests stormwater and provides habitat for local wildlife.

title: Horseshoe Billabong
summary: Horseshoe Billabong at Wilsons Reserve is a fantastic place for birdwatching, or simply sitting and enjoying the natural setting.

title: Walking Track
summary: The walking track is well maintained, with remnant vegetation and golf courses bordering either side.

title: Weeping Grass
summary: The local Friends group (Friends of Wilsons Reserve) is actively replanting native vegetation throughout the reserve, such as this weeping grass (Microlaena stipoides).

title: Restoration
summary: There is also signage along the walk documenting the restoration efforts undertaken in the area, and why it was undertaken.

title: Yarra Flats Park
summary: Walkers get to experience Yarra Flats Park, a large park of remnant vegetation that provides fantastic opportunities for spotting wildlife such as eastern grey kangaroos, tawny frogmouths, and snakes.

title: Yarra River
summary: On this track, walkers are able to experience a large section of the Yarra River. Along this section, there are popular swimming, fishing and canoeing locations that walkers may choose to use.

title: Wild Melbourne

title: Daisy, Daisy
summary: Some of the many wildflowers - everlasting daisies in this case.

title: Murnong
summary: There is a lot of re-vegetation work going on here, including re-establishing a population of Murnong - once a staple foodstuff of the indigenous people.

title: Bindweed
summary: Pink Bindweed, or Convovulus, is one of the commonest grassland plants, and shows a wide variety of shades of pink.

title: Pimelea
summary: This grassland has a number of Pimelea, or Spiny Rice Flower plants in it. It also has a lot of very healthy Themida triandra, or Kangaroo Grass.

title: Veronica
summary: A large patch of Veronica, a ground cover that gets covered with little purple flowers.

title: Veronica 2
summary: On of the things about grasslands is that you don't see much from a distance, but they are very rich in detail.

title: Themida
summary: Kangaroo Grass - and the fluffy grass in the background is Danthonia, or Wallaby Grass.

title: Featherheads
summary: In many ways this grassland is the jewel in the crown, as it floral richness is quite amazing. Getting it such a great state has been a labour of love for the grassland management team .

title: Blue Devils
summary: One of the more unusual grassland plants - this is a particularly fine specimen.

title: Bluedevils 2
summary: Worth a close up!

title: Looking good
summary: Not a lot of weeds there!

title: Post Office
summary: The original post office was rebuilt in 1867 with the bell and clock tower as you see it now.
