Weekly walking group on Wednesdays 11.30am.

title: Goddard Street sports ground
summary: A very popular sports ground with families. Has BBQ, seats, water fountain, playground and sports oval. Very busy on weekends and summer evenings!

title: Hummingbird Boulevard Reserve
summary: A very scenic wetland with boardwalk. When completed, it will have a playground, sports fields, BBQ and shelter.

title: Shelter and seats and view
summary: A lovely place to sit and read, or to enjoy the serenity.

title: Wetlands and retarding basin
summary: A beautiful walk through this small wetland. We heard the sound of frogs and birds chirping away.

title: Senegal Road Playground
summary: Features BBQ, basketball court, playground and seating.

title: Great for 2 and 4 legged walkers
summary: This is a great walk if you have a dog, there is plenty of space to let them of the lead and they can roam to their heart’s content.

title: Pedestrian bridge under Broadmedows Road
summary: A great feature of this walk is the number of pedestrian bridges under busy roads, meaning walkers can move straight through in absolute safety.

title: The path snakes its way through beautiful grassed areas
summary: For much of the walk there is lush grassland , trees, rivers and creeks on either side.

title: Be careful crossing the road and lovely old bridge
summary: This part of the walk requires you to cross the road, be careful as there are no traffic lights! However you get to cross a lovely old bridge.

title: Public toilets and BBQ area
summary: Public toilets and BBQ area next to the playing ground.

title: Pedestrian bridge under Mickleham Road
summary: A great feature of this walk is the number of pedestrian bridges under busy roads, meaning walkers can move straight through in absolute safety.

title: Cooper Hill Drive Playground
summary: This is a huge grassed area with a great playground, perfect spot to have a breather and the kids go crazy.

title: Westmeadows Tennis and Football clubs
summary: The tennis Club has 6 courts plus facilities and the football ground hosts local suburban football and cricket games.

title: Keep walking straight!
summary: There are a lots of places to veer off and take alternative routes, however if you want to keep following this particular walk keeping going straight at this point.

title: What a great spot for a rest!
summary: This is one of the most tranquil spots of the walk – no noise, lots of birds and, if you are lucky, sunshine.

title: Willowbrook Reserve
summary: The Reserve is beautiful open grassland with many native trees. From this point you can keep walking along the path, or maybe stop for a picnic.

title: So many choice where to walk
summary: There are lots of routes you can take, the signs are clear and plentiful. This route we have mapped is just one possible route!

title: Lovely river below!
summary: The Moonee Valley creek is a lovely clean waterway with lots of flora and fauna – especially water birds.

title: Children's Playground
summary: Take a breather while the children play on the trendy playground equipment.

title: Kids' swings
summary: Children's play area.

title: Seat
summary: Starting spot to meet your friends and start your walk.

title: Green picnic area
summary: Picnic benches.

title: Centennial Gardens
summary: Full of native trees and scrubs.

title: Shaded seated area
summary: A park bench under some gum trees to relax at the end of your walk.

title: The Boardwalk
summary: The boardwalk allows you to get up close and personal with the wetlands, birds and enjoy the views while forgetting there are busy streets and residential areas in close vacinity.

title: Meet the hungry birds
summary: Plenty of the feathered creatures will be your friends, if you have food for them. As you can see there can be plenty of mouths to feed.

title: The Gazebo
summary: This is a beautiful place to have your picnic, with vines about to envelope the structure this will be cool in summer and away from the birds, who might steel your lunch, the rest of the year.

title: Wetlands Research
summary: Spot the number of nesting boxes in the wetlands used to monitor and research bird species and number that come to and breed in the wetlands.

title: The Henderson Creek Wetlands
summary: The mapped path here is only for starters, you can spend hours exploring further afield. Please respect the the bird and wild life in the wetlands and take care where you do explore.

title: Recreational+++
summary: There are beautiful views, generous wide paths and plenty of bird life.  A little piece of tranquility or activity; whatever you want or need.

title: Quick game of basketball?
summary: There is a great full-size basketball court for every one to use

title: Look at all the birds
summary: There are lots of native birds to see throughout the reserve and Darebin Creek

title: Bocce Fields
summary: There are two Bocce Fields right next to the walking track. (Bocce: an Italian variety of lawn bowling played on a dirt court that is shorter and narrower than a lawn bowls green).

title: Bridge over creek
summary: There are a number of little bridges spanning small creeks, the creeks feed into the Darebin Creek.

title: Lovely view of the Darebin Creek
summary: Much of the walk is beside the idyllic Darebin River, the river bank is a great place for a picnic

title: A good starting point
summary: Although the walk can be started or stopped anywhere, this is a nice place to start as it is adjacent ot Settlement Road and near the public toilets and BBQ area

title: You can keep going from here!
summary: If you keep heading north along the track it continues to follow the Darebin Creek andyou will eventually meet a pedestrian tunnel under the Metropolitan Ring Road

title: Playground and BBQ
summary: This a great place to rest after doing the 3km loop. Why not bring the kids and let them play on the great playground while you cook up a storm on the BBQs!

title: Beautiful resting spot
summary: There are many spots to rest along the way, this might just be the most picturesque.

title: Signage is plentiful
summary: If you are feeling a bit disorientated, do not worry there are lots of signs letting you know where you are

title: Skate Ramp
summary: If you dare, this skate ramp is right next to the large playing field

title: Norris Park Tennis Club
summary: The tennis club has 6 courts plus facilities

title: Public toilets
summary: The public toilets are right next to the playground and walking track

title: McLeans Bridge
summary: There is no need to stop for vehicles as you go under McLeans Bridge

title: Duck Point
summary: Beautiful views out over the lake

title: Lake Views
summary: View up the lake from the bridge

title: Blackburn Lake Wetland
summary: Wetland at the top of the lake helps to filter stormwater as it enters the lake from the stormwater system.

title: Rio Vista
summary: Walk across the lawn to see the majestic Rio Vista, spanish for River View. It was completed in 1892 and was the work of architects E.C Sharland and D.T Edmunds and was commissioned by W.B Chaffey.

title: Rio Vista
summary: A tour of Rio Vista is highly recommended,  there is much to see and appreciate. Stained and hand painted glass, a stunning staircase and intricate wood paneling are just some of the highlights.

title: Gardener’s cottage
summary: The gardener’s cottage to the rear of Rio Vista is also a delightful building and well worth a look

title: Chaffey Avenue
summary: This avenue was originally called Palm Avenue because of the number of palms planted in the area. However, residents were keen to have a street named in honour of the Chaffey family.

title: The Bungalow.
summary:
Opposite Rio Vista is a striking home, known as the Bungalow. A Queen Anne style home, it is in keeping with its revered neighbor. The original owner
of the Bungalow was Lancelot Conway-Gordon.

title: 25 Chaffey Avenue
summary: Continuing along Chaffey Avenue, the walk passes a number of old homes. Number 25, although much altered, dates back to 1892.

title: 27 Chaffey Avenue
summary: 27, built in 1891 was the home of riverboat captain William Miers, who took up permanent residence here upon his retirement in 1901.It was designed by Rio Vista architect, D.T Edmunds.

title: 37 Chaffey Avenue
summary: 37 was for a short time, the home of Samuel Risbey, the owner of the sawmills. The house was built in1913 and retains much of its original Edwardian charm.

title: 38 Chaffey Avenue
summary: 38 was the home of Alice Lapthorne, daughter of Henry Lapthorne, editor of the Cultivator newspaper from 1896 to 1920.

title: 64 Olive Avenue
summary: Olive Avenue has a number of lovely old homes that have been restored, with respect shown to their original design.  Number 64 is a wonderful example of an ironclad cottage, built in 1910.

title: 78 Olive Avenue
summary: 78, a brick building dates back to 1891 and was the home of James Cruikshank, it has a number of notable features.

title: The Langtree Hall Museum
summary: A short walk up Walnut Ave is the The Langtree Hall Museum (number 79). Mildura’s first public hall built in 1889, the large collection of memorabilia was  relocated to this site In 1991.

title: 41-43 Chaffey Ave
summary: On the corner of Eighth Street and Chaffey sits the one time home of W.J Bowring, owner of the Bowring Store, once prominent in Mildura. The building was completed in 1911 and an interesting home.

title: Cunningham Pier
summary: Cunningham Pier with lifesaving bollards

title: Buoys imbedded in Steampacket Gardens
summary: Buoys imbedded in Steampacket Gardens

title: Marina
summary: Fishermen’s Pier Restaurant overlooks the bay and many sailing vessels in the marina.

title: Bollard at the corner of Ritchie Blvd
summary: Bollard at the corner of Ritchie Blvd

title: Lifesaving bollards
summary: Lifesaving bollards

title: Bathing beauty bollards
summary: Bathing beauty bollards

title: Stately houses along Eastern Beach
summary: Stately houses along Eastern Beach in front of a beach shelter

title: View to Eastern Beach from Swimming Enclosure
summary: View to Eastern Beach from Swimming Enclosure

title: Eastern Beach Swimming Enclosure and Promenade
summary: Eastern Beach Swimming Enclosure and Promenade

title: Children's pool with fountain
summary: Children's pool with fountain

title: Batman Park
summary: Once a riverside wetlands, then a freight rail yard, Batman Park was built in 1982 and consists of paths, lawns, gum tress and some BBQs.

title: Spencer St footbridge
summary: This glass and steel footbridge is set back from the Spencer Street Bridge and  provides a pleasant way to cross the Yarra.

title: The boardwalk
summary: The well maintained boardwalk makes a perfect walking route.

title: Polly Woodside
summary: The now restored cargo vessel, launched in 1885, is managed by the National Trust and is a museum and a popular attraction .

title: Seafarers Bridge
summary: One of a few footbridges crossing the Yarra. It is named in homage to the ‘Mission to Seafarers’ located nearby and represents Melbourne’s maritime history.

title: Russell Anderson’s artwork
summary: This fascinating work is  called 'Apparatus for Transtemporal Occurrence of Impending Space'. Cast in bronze, brass, steel and copper it celebrates the aesthetic of early science fiction.

title: Three bollards
summary: Continue on to the start is another 0.7 km (10mins) or return the same way for a slightly longer walk 1.0km (16 mins).

title: Altona Pier
summary: Altona Pier

title: R J Logan Reserve
summary: R J Logan Reserve picnic area

title: View along Altona Beach to the Altona pier
summary: View along Altona Beach to the Altona pier

title: View to Port Phillip Bay
summary: View to Port Phillip Bay

title: Norfolk Island Pines along Altona Beach
summary: Norfolk Island Pines along Altona Beach

title: Children's playground
summary: Children's playground at Cresser Reserve

title: Looking back along Altona Beach
summary: Looking back along Altona Beach

title: Pier at Altona Yacht Club
summary: Pier at Altona Yacht Club

title: Altona Angling Club
summary: Altona Angling Club

title: Altona Boat Ramp
summary: Altona Boat Ramp

title: Picnic table
summary: Picnic table

title: Bridge over canal
summary: Bridge over canal

title: View of Altona Beach from Altona Coastal Park end
summary: View of Altona Beach from Altona Coastal Park end

title: Ruins of Williamstown Racecourse
summary: Ruins of Williamstown Racecourse

title: Requiem for a Champion sculpture
summary:
Requiem for a Champion sculpture
Exit point for path along Kororoit Creek to Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve in Williamstown

title: Rounded Noon Flower
summary: Rounded Noon Flower is a succulent spreading plant which can form dense carpets of stunning colour. It is native to the Altona area.

title: The Grange Community Centre
summary: Offering Occasional Care, 3+ Activity Group, Before & After School Care, School Holiday Program, Playgroup, Autism Support Group, First Aid Course,  Morning Melodies, Walking Group, Cafe and lots more

title: Grange Reserve Playground
summary: Features 2 huge stainless steel slides, basketball half-court, BBQ, seating and shelter, and sports ovals.

title: Deloraine Drive garden
summary: Quite a spectacular garden complete with fountain and colourful flowers.

title: More fabulous front yards
summary: Just some of the fabulous front yards that you'll see along the way.

title: Colourful plants
summary: Simply stunning, especially in spring when they're in full bloom.

title: Bethany Road Playground
summary: A charming playground with BBQ, seats, shelter, and basketball half-court.

title: Snowgum Court Park
summary: Snowgum Court Park will be getting a much needed makeover soon. Council plans to install a baskbetball half court, BBQ and seating. We look forward to seeing these developments soon!

title: Arcade of trees
summary: Start your walk through an arcade of shady trees.

title: Shady entrance to Railway Crossing
summary: A lovely entrance as you enter the Ol' railway yards and to the crossing.

title: Local Bowling Club
summary: The old local Bowling Club surround by well maintained greens that overlooks the Murray River.

title: Chaffey Bros Homestead
summary: This historical homestead is magnificent, surrounded by open green spaces, adorned with local artworks. The Arts Museum & Arts Center Theatre  is right next door. Stop for a rest to view this sight.

title: To view more greenery and old homes restored
summary: Chaffey Avenue has some lovely old homes restored and surrounded by beautiful gardens and trees. It will be a pleasure to walk back.

title: Bike Hub
summary: This bike hub is a great place to start the walk.

title: Majorca Town Hall, Talbot Road
summary: Majorca’s hub for community events. Built in 1876, this bluestone & render structure was ravaged by fire in 1985 however the shell was salvaged and renovations have brought the building back to life.

title: Majorca Cenotaph, Talbot Road
summary: A poignant symbol of lives lost in WWI & II, consider the impact on the village. This memorial was regilded in 2013 with community donations & support from Peter Stewart at FJC Memorials, Maryborough.

title: Majorca Public garden & lake
summary: A decorative lake with crafted bluestone spillway and drain. Once a romantic promenade with beautiful gardens, a few specimen trees remain on the east side and huge sugar gums reach to the sky.

title: Majorca school residence, Williams St
summary: This privately owned cottage was once the residence for Primary School Headmasters. After many years abandoned, the current owners have restored its charm.

title: Majorca Primary School site
summary: The site of historic Majorca Primary School (No. 764), built in 1868. This grand school was damaged in the 1985 fire but, allegedly demolished and removed before restoration assessment was made.

title: Majorca Post Office, Galloways Road
summary: Built in 1871, this old Post and Telegraph Office was once the key communication point in the township. With its original front counter and post boxes, it is now a private residence.

title: Site of the Majorca Court House
summary: Little is known about the Majorca Court House. It was demolished early in the 1900’s but the site indentation and some of the huge bluestone footings can still be seen on the vacant land.

title: Former Methodist Church
summary: Now a private home, this imposing Gothic styled Church overlooks the once-bustling township.

title: Majorca bushland
summary: Enjoy the natural bush track with local flora and fauna. To the west is the old reservoir, providing water to the township back in the 1800s. The pine trees form a perimeter.

title: Church of England site
summary: The St James Church of England was destroyed in the 1985 bushfires and only loose bricks remain as a sad reminder of the past.

title: Standpipe and memorial trough
summary: The original 1860 cast iron and bluestone standpipe remains from days where water would be collected for residential and commercial use. The memorial troughs are throughout regional Victoria.

title: Old Haberdashery and Newsagency
summary: This crumbling redbrick building was once a hive of activity for dressmakers, then as a newsagency. Derelict for many years now, the building has sadly been allowed to deteriorate beyond repair.

title: Harp of Erin Hotel remains
summary: The bustling Harp Of Erin Hotel remained in business from the late 1800’s until the early 1900’s, finally falling into disrepair. There are only a few bluestones remaining now.

title: Former London Chartered Bank
summary: Built in 1865, this grand building with block-work render and arched windows and doors is classified by the National Trust. Of note are the arched boot scrapers beside the doorway.

title: “Witch” advertising sign
summary: This painted sign on the wall represents a common form of advertising before the billboard era. Now known as Ghost Signs, these faded reminders of old advertisements will one day be lost forever.

title: Old Majorca Store
summary: With its intriguing façade, this building once housed a general store then fabric supplies. Now a private residence, the building is showing signs of its age.

title: Long view of the waterway at the start of the walk
summary: Gives you a lovely view of approaching waterways.

title: Wildlife on the waterways
summary: A number of ducks and a pelican can be seen taking advantage of the waterways.

title: family fun BBQ area & drinking tap
summary: Time to stop and relax with the family and have a barbie

title: Children\'s Playground
summary: Kids can play in the playgroung while parents cook a BBQ

title: Crossing Waterway Bridge
summary: Approaching the bridge that oversees the waterways and wildlife.

title: View of waterways from Bridge
summary: Looking over the waterways from the Bridge

title: Over the Bridge View
summary: Over the bridge and havea closer look at the wildlife

title: Lucknow - Eastwood IGA Supermarket
summary: Lucknow - Eastwood IGA Supermarket is a place to park safely and start the walk

title: Enter the walk here
summary: You can enter the walk after crossing Howitt Avenue. This is where the busses turn for the Lucknow Primary School

title: Hacks Track
summary: This is known as Hacks Track

title: The Display Sign
summary: Look out for this display sign as it points out where the track changes direction

title: A couple of tall gums
summary: There are magnificent gums all through the parkland

title: Wonderful parklands to run a dog
summary: You can let the dog run around here

title: Watch out for the Eastern Rosellas nesting in trees.
summary: Wonderful parrots and other birdlife all through the area

title: Very steep incline path to the river..
summary: I hope your wheels can be braked, this is very steep here.. Well made and bitumen but very steep, needs a brake on the wheelchair.

title: A rotunda for picnic
summary: A small wetland but quite pretty

title: A crossing well made at this point
summary: a well made road crossing here

title: Along the river side
summary: The Mitchell River Backwater walk section

title: The well formed tracks along the river
summary: The walking track is in good condition all year round

title: More along the track
summary: The river walk

title: The wetlands area
summary: The wetlands

title: The fishing pod
summary: There are a few fishing platforms on the river

title: Wetlands view
summary: Very pretty views

title: Wildlife everywhere
summary: There is wildlife everywhere

title: Steep incline down to the wetlands and river walk
summary: Watch out the steep track as it is very difficult without an assistant pushing or good brakes.

title: Beautiful Bushland
summary: There are four major vegetation communities within Yellow Gum Park. They include grassy woodland, escarpment woodland, box ironbark woodland and riparian woodland.

title: Walker
summary: When walking allow yourself to be immersed in birdsong, the sound of the flowing river and the beautiful flora.

title: A reminder of the lakes history
summary: This area used to be a mineral quarry.  It closed in the early 1970s as a result of ground water seeping into the quarry hole. The ground water seepage has produced the lake we see today.

title: The lake
summary: The blue lake is named for its turquoise blue colour at certain times of the year and is home to birds including Eurasian coots, Purple Swamphens and Australasian Grebes.

title: Australasian Grebe
summary: They form small flocks during the non-breeding season and dive underwater when alarmed.

title: Rainbow Lorikeet
summary: Not so hard to spot with their wonderfully coloured feathers, Rainbow Lorikeets feed mainly on nectar.  Both male and female Lorikeets feed their young.

title: Laughing Kookaburra
summary: Kookaburras hunt by perching on branches and swooping onto their prey below.  This one has caught a small snack for lunch.  Larger prey like snakes are bashed against branches before being eaten.

title: Look high and low
summary: This areas environmental values are of national and state significance.  All native flora in the area must not be picked.

title: Sulpher crested Cockatoo
summary: You'll probably hear one before you see one.  Their loud, harsh calls can be heard from quite a distance.  They breed in hollows in old growth trees.

title: White Cedar
summary: Look for these deciduous trees on the left of the path as you pass the Children's Garden.

title: Jacaranda
summary: Stop in at the mighty Jacaranda tree on the left. What stage of its annual life cycle is it up to? Don't forget to record what you see on the ClimateWatch app or recording sheet.

title: Firewheel Tree
summary: This beautiful native tree on your left has striking red flowers. Are they out today?

title: Illawarra Flame Tree
summary: An iconic Australian tree which flowers in spring. Scientists think that these trees and others might flower earlier due to climate change, so please record what you see.

title: English Oak
summary: This tree can be quite tricky to find, but if you spot it, record what stage of its annual cycle it is at. Leaves falling? Flowers opening? Submit your sightings on the ClimateWatch app

title: Silky Oak
summary: This giant tree is just past the cafe. Silky Oaks aren't related to other oak trees at all but are actually a species of Grevilla and are very popular with birds!

title: Lake
summary: As you walk around the lake, look for birds. Dusky moorhens, black swans, willie wagtails, and many other ClimateWatch species love this beautiful spot.

title: Silver Banksia and Victorian Christmas Bush
summary: As the tip of Long Island you will find both of these native plants. Check to see if they are flowering, and be sure to smell the minty leaves of the VIC Christmas Bush

title: Marri
summary: The last stop on the ClimateWatch trail is the Western Australian Marri eucalypt. Check to see if it is flowering, or whether it is sporting has any gumnuts (known as honky nuts in the west).

title: Native flowers and bushes
summary: There are plenty of native trees and flowers planted just a few steps back from the beach.  There are a few grassy areas that are shady and away from the sand if you need refuge from the beach.

title: Walk, skate or scoot
summary: It's great that the paths for walkers and cyclists are separated for most of the trail. The pedestrian trail is smooth, well maintained and clearly marked.  Or you can simply walk along the beach!

title: Beach as far as you can see
summary: Beach with a lovely view of the sea. Read a book, have a nap, bring a picnic, build a sandcastle, go for a swim... the possibilities are endless.

title: Ships ahoy - playground
summary: A fabulous wooden construction that looks like a ship!  Great for kids to clamber and explore.  Plenty of shade provided as well.

title: Information boards
summary: Information boards are great for telling you more about the area - the birds, Indigenous culture, names of local plants etc.

title: Barraimal (Emu) Constellation
summary: The Emu Constellation according to the Boon Wurrung people. More information available on nearby information boards.

title: Black swans
summary: We saw a pair of canoodling black swans!

title: Middle Brighton Baths
summary: The legendary Ice Berger swimmers swim here. They swim all year around, even in winter! There is also a gym, steam room, cafe and restaurant - all housed in a lovely historic art deco building.

title: Royal Brighton Yacht Club and dog off lead area
summary: Great view of the yachts from here. This is also a dog off lead area, though off lead times do change depending on the time of year.

title: Inspiration chairs
summary: Take a seat and be inspired, reflect and celebrate! A nice touch - each chair has a little plaque with a theme.  This one's The Togetherness Chair

title: Brighton Beach Boxes
summary: The Brighton Beach Boxes are iconic. All painted in bright colours, they're popular with photographers and tourists.  Some of the boxes have wonderful artwork painted on them too.

title: Mosaic
summary: A few pieces of colourful mosaic can be found here.

title: Drinks for 2 and 4 legged walkers!
summary: There are plenty of drinking fountains throughout the walk.

title: Good spot for a picnic lunch
summary: Table and chairs outside the old angling club, great spot to view the ducks and other water birds

title: BBQ and Playground
summary: Next to the footy ground is a great playground with BBQ facilities

title: Heaven for dog walking
summary: There is plenty to keep even the most inquisitive dog occupied along the way.

title: Careful crossing the busy road
summary: Wait for green pedestrian lights before crossing, don't try to cross this road without the traffic lights.

title: View from bridge
summary: Looking down onto the tranquil river below the busy bridge, makes you wish you were a platypus living in peace.

title: Wide open spaces
summary: Wyndham Park is the perfect spot to run around, kick the footy or simply get away from it all.

title: Connecting point with other walking tracks
summary: You have lots of choices where to walk from here.

title: Very cool new orange pedestrian bridge
summary: New orange pedestrian bridge

title: Coffee time?
summary: Why not have a break and take the stairs/paths up to one of the many cafes along Watton Street

title: Better than any classroom
summary: The local primary school visits the park to help the kids stay active and learn about their beautiful backyard.

title: Old public swimming Pool
summary: Now it seems to be mainly used by the ducks

title: What a view!
summary: A sanctuary in the middle of Werribee

title: Choose your own adventure
summary: We picked the shortest route for this trip as we had a toddler in tow and the sun was getting warm by mid-morning.

title: View from the top
summary: The view of the surrounding valley is pretty spectacular from here.  The hill is steep so it's a great workout if you need to get your heart rate up.

title: Extensive revegetation
summary: Since the park was declared in 1972, a great deal of work has been done to restore the indigenous vegetation to the area. (See Parknotes)

title: Picnic table and seats
summary: A lovely shady spot for lunch or a cuppa.

title: The Organ Pipes
summary: More than a million years ago, lava from nearby volcanoes flowed into the area, cooled, hardened, then cracked, forming the columns that we see today.

title: Popular walk for families with younger children
summary: On our visit, we met at least 10 other children, which confirms that the walk is suitable for young ones too.

title: Exploring Jacksons Creek
summary: The shores of the creek is a good spot for young explorers.

title: View upstream
summary: The creek is cool and shady if you need a break from the heat of the sun.

title: Start walk at bridge, Bluff Road end, in clockwise direction
summary: Notice the lake sign made from red gum.  Timber cutting for firewood was the reason St. Leonards was originally settled by Captain George Ward Cole.

title: Optional detour to Mount St Leonards, a short steep walk
summary:
From the top there are expansive views over the town, bay and surrounds. 

The hill was formed when the man-made lake was excavated.

title: Continue along the shaded track & notice the birds
summary:
Frequently there is active bird life - swamp hens, coots, cormorants.  Can you hear frogs?  

Distance markers are painted on the track.

title: Walk past the Sewerage Pump Station & take rest in the shade
summary:
Around the bend behind the native trees, the Sewerage Pump takes the town waste to the Portarlington Sewerage facility. 

Now you leave the wooded area and walk towards the Recreation Reserve.

title: Stroll through the 'Len Trewin Reserve'
summary:
Len secured a 99 year lease when he & others started the cricket club in the 1940's.  A handmade wrought iron sign over an entrance can be seen from the road. 

Public toilets located here.

title: Pass Cole St Reserve Hall & Clubrooms
summary: This is a cluster of community facilities for recreation and service activities.  The long anticipated Men's Shed will be here when renovations are carried out.

title: Optional detour to see wetlands
summary: Cross Cole Street with care. Here you will find tennis, bocce and a children's playground.  This area is popular in summer.

title: Continue along the winding track
summary:
This wetland seasonally floods & attracts wading birds such as the Royal Spoonbill, herons & egrets. 

Watch for bike riders.

title: Cross McBeth St to the Native Flora display board
summary:
This board depicts the protected flora species in the Charles McCarthy Oval area.  This oval is used for sports training.

There is a bus shelter here but no seating.

title: Retrace your steps to rejoin the Lake Track
summary:
On the left, notice the Arboretum planted by St. Leonards Primary School in 1981, creating an area of native flora for the benefit of wildlife & the community. 

Pass the rear of the Bowling Club.

title: Continue along Lake track clockwise
summary:
Join Murradoc Road, the main access road into St. Leonards.  Geese might greet you here.  The local rule is 'Give way to geese!'
  
The bus stop here has seating.

title: Follow track along McLeod St
summary: This gives a viewing point to the oval across the lake. Common birds seen here are cormorants, water hens, coots and pelicans.

title: Notice the picnic facilities for rest, shade & shelter
summary: There are 2 free electric BBQs in the shelter, tables, a playground & toilet facilities.  A convenient place to meet with family and friends.

title: Close by find an activity area
summary: There is a skate park, basketball/netball rings & a sandpit area.  See the Murals on the Toilet Block, part of a community project in 2001.

title: Finish lake circuit at the bridge
summary: To access the beach and foreshore, leaving the lake, cross Bluff Road with care.  Enjoy water views across Port Philip Bay and activity at the Boat Ramp.

title: Elevation Graph for the Walk
summary: It looks worse that it actually is.

title: A Joke Sign
summary: The Grampians most inaccurate sign, I think. Iit’s actually about 1.4 km.

title: Emu
summary: Dromaius novaehollandiae

title: Milkmaids
summary: Burchardia umbellata

title: Waxlip Orchid
summary: Glossodia major

title: Jacky Lizard
summary: Amphibolurus muricatus

summary: Tiliqua rugosa

summary: Part of the Grampians flora.

summary: Xanthorrhoea

title: Mount Zero Olives
summary: Well known brand of olive oil.

summary: You can also Hollow Mountain in the foreground. It is difficult to see.

title: Wombat Creek reservoir
summary: This reservoir is the water supply for Daylesford. The picnic area is on the former sawmill site. There are no toilets or drinking water

title: Tramway formation
summary: The 4WD track visibly becomes a former tramway at about this point. The formation is dug into the steep hillside, which is unusual as such excavation was of course expensive

title: Gully tracks
summary: The tramway followed a different path in some of the gullys to the modern track. At locations such as this, the former tramway can be seen clearly on both sides of the gully

title: Sweeping curves
summary: Some of the gullys are impressive. The broad views give some idea of the scope of the enterprise (the name of one of the sawmills)  of the men who lived an worked in these forests

title: end of the line
summary: The former tramway formation is clear enough, but a securely locked gate bars the way.

title: The Basin shopping centre
summary:
The Basin’s first shops were established in the 1920s, and the Progress Hall was erected in 1926. 
The present Mountain Hwy   shops date from 1965

title: Wicks Reserve
summary: Ferntree Gully Shire Council acquired 9 ha of land formerly owned by Edmund and Janet Wicks in 1942 as a reserve. The Wicks ’selected’ their land in 1873. Edmund died in 1880.

title: Chandler oak
summary: William Chandler planted an acorn beside Dobsons Creek in 1875 to mark the birth of his son, Archibald. Dobsons Creek has the highest ecological values of any City of Knox waterway.

title: The Basin Theatre
summary:
Edna Chandler, wife of William Chandler’s grand-son Fergus, founded The Basin Theatre in 1954. The Chandler family  
donated land for the building in 1973.

title: Dandenong Creek
summary: Dandenong Creek is of significance to the Aboriginal people as marking a ‘song-line’ placed by their creator spirit,    Bunjil. The creek crossing is a good spot for sighting wild-life.

title: The Stables
summary: The former stables were located below the main homestead. A small tramway used to transport construction materials from the valley for the house terminated here.

title: Doongalla Homestead
summary: Doongalla homestead was constructed in 1892 by Sir Matthew Davies, a well known land speculator in the 1880s land boom, who named the property ‘Invermay'. The house burned down in 1932.

title: Footbridge
summary: An easy walk with well formed tracks.

title: Heyfield
summary: At then end of your walk, check out  the country town of Heyfield - well worth a visit.

title: Heyfield Wetlands Information Centre
summary: The Wetlands Information Centre is the home of the Neville-Smith Timber Industries display and has a wide range of souvenirs.

title: Beautiful wetlands
summary: Once the site of the Heyfield racecourse, the Wetlands are now the home to a number of different species of bird and animal life.

title: Penrose Promenade Community Centre
summary:
A fabulous community hub with excellent facilities and activities. Art and educational courses of children, tai-chi, music, cooking, cultural meet-ups.
Weekly walking group on Wednesdays 11.30am.

title: Goddard Street Sports Ground
summary: Complete with BBQ, seats, shelter, a much loved and much used playground, sports oval and facilities. Busy on weekends!

title: Camelot Drive Park
summary: This park has a playground, seats and shelter.

title: View from shelter
summary: A pretty good view of the trees from here!

title: Wetland views
summary: The wetlands are an important habitat for birds and other wildlife. Plus it's a lovely place for a walk!

title: Outdoor gym
summary: There are several pieces of outdoor gym equipment dotted around the wetland.

title: Derrimut Road
summary: A bright little spot to have a seat if you need to take a rest.

title: Which birds can you spot?
summary: Pelicans and ducks are regular visitors. You may spot cormorants and purple swamp hens too. Want to identify the birds you see? Check out this app (iPhone), also available for Android.

title: Seats and shelter
summary: There are seats along the wetland, and shade. Very useful!

title: BBQ, seats and shelter
summary: Bring along a picnic or sausages for a BBQ. The park is good spot to meet your friends and neighbours too.

title: Meeree Reserve
summary: This reserve has a playground, BBQ, seats and shelter. There's plenty of space for ball games, kite flying and general lounging or running around. Meeree means sun in the local Aboriginal language.

title: Red Sand Garden
summary: The Red Sand Garden is the first sight just outside the Visitor Centre

title: Rockpool Waterway
summary: The Rockpool Waterway is the only place that paddling is allowed.

title: Waterhole Bridge
summary: Waterhole Bridge is at the end of the Rockpool Waterway

title: Serpentine Path
summary: The Serpentine Path leads into the Arid Garden or up Gibson Hill

title: Arid Garden
summary: Grass trees (formerly called black boys) in the Arid Garden

title: Gibson Hill
summary: View from the top of Gibson Hill across the Red Sand Garden back to the Visitor Centre

title: Weird & Wonderful Garden
summary: Weird & Wonderful Garden

title: Gondwana Garden
summary: Gondwana Garden

title: Casuarina Grove to Seaside Garden
summary: Casuarina Grove to Seaside Garden

title: Melaleuca Spits
summary: Melaleuca Spits looking back to the Waterhole Bridge

title: Howson Hill overlooking River Bend
summary: Howson Hill overlooking River Bend

title: River Bend
summary: River Bend

title: Water Saving Garden
summary: Water Saving Garden

title: Diversity Garden
summary: Diversity Garden

title: Giddy up
summary: It’s not uncommon to meet horse riders on the track as well as dog walkers, joggers and keen birdwatchers.

title: Walk through the wetland
summary: Important to the Gunaikurnai nation for their basket-weaving properties is a wetlands mix of reeds, the home of numerous birds, frogs, insects and reptiles.

title: Historic railway
summary: A key piece of infrastructure for the region was the introduction of the railway, signs of which are still evident on the rail trail.

title: Ned Stringer Memorial
summary: In honour of the first European settler to find gold in what is now called Stringers Creek, this discovery is credited with starting the Walhalla goldrush.

title: Rose Garden
summary: In bloom, this is a superb spot to close your eyes and breathe in the perfume of roses as you reflect on Toongabbie’s history.

title: St David's Uniting Church
summary: A beautifully cared-for 1895 building that features 13 different pressed metal designs on its internal walls is a great place for taking your breath away.

title: Plenty of play space
summary: The historic primary school has several areas dedicated to play time as well as an interpretative shelter that provides a historic map of the township.

title: What a grand stand
summary: Constructed in celebration of the federation of Australia, this beautiful building on the Village Green is still used for sporting events and is adjunct to an excellent BBQ and picnic facility.

title: General Store
summary: The General Store not only provides delicious food but has a collection of historic wagons and other farm machinery, as well as a wonderful place to picnic under the trees.

title: Bridge takes you to Geelong Baseball Centre
summary: Continue straight here

title: Cobbin Farm Chapel
summary: lovely old chapel and gardens

title: Take the track on far side of chapel
summary: Track on far side of chapel will loop back across the creek on the other side

title: Track crosses back over the creek
summary: Cross the creek here

title: creek close-up
summary: native vegetation lines the creek

title: beautiful section of the creek
summary: This section is particularly pretty, eg. this Eucalyptus tree with beautiful big spiky seed pods!

title: Norman Beach
summary: Well hidden by the healthy coastal flora, the Tidal River campground is at the far end of Norman Beach.

title: Coastline View
summary: Leaving Norman Bay, the track hugs the coastline, providing views across Bass Strait to the horizon.

title: Little Oberon Bay
summary: Around the first headland is this sparkling view of the second beach on this walk.

title: Little Oberon Bay
summary: After leaving the beach, the walk continues along the coast on a compacted sandy track.

title: Oberon Bay
summary: Around the next headland, more beauty awaits. The campground is at the far end of this beach.

title: Orange rocks
summary: Xanthoria Parietina (Common Orange Lichen) give the granite boulders their distinctive colour. There is a shallow flowing river to cross here.

title: The track
summary: The track varies with the landscape, sometimes narrow, sometimes wide, sometimes flat and sandy, sometimes steep and rocky!

title: Granite boulders
summary: A cluster of enormous boulders perched at the top of this peak. Imagine how old they are!

title: View of Little Waterloo Bay
summary: A breathtaking view of the East coast of the Prom.

title: Boardwalk Track
summary: Descending the sand dunes and over the swamps. Keep your feet dry thanks to the many boardwalk sections.

title: Track to Little Waterloo Bay Beach
summary: Love this part of the track, but can get a bit windy sometimes.

title: Little Waterloo Bay
summary: Yes, its a gorgeous bay!

title: Little Waterloo Bay
summary: At the southern end of the beach is this fresh water but it's not suitable for drinking.

title: Tiger Snake
summary: The Prom does have a lot of snakes, and if you're lucky you might get to see one or two.

title: Refuge Cove Campsite
summary: You are here!

title: Eltham Station underpass
summary: Cross the tracks by going under the gloomy underpass.

title: The ugly car park
summary: Don't be put off by the ugly car park and watch out crossing the road!

title: The path
summary: Walk along Diamond St until you get to the path (gate in the fence), then you are set.

title: Eltham Central Park
summary: If it's winter, you might even get the chance to stop and watch some local footy.

title: Eltham Trestle Bridge
summary: The bridge was built in 1901 and is one of the last remaining on the Melbounre train network, it's a beauty!

title: The Diamond Creek
summary: The path snakes around the Diamond Creek (if you are very lucky, you might see a snake in summer).

title: The Gate
summary: I love this gate. Why is it there, what lies behind, does anyone know?

title: The slippery path
summary: The path is a bit slippery here in Autumn and Winter because of the fallen rotten leaves, but beautiful nonetheless.

title: The tree
summary: Wonderful big tree. Also there are toilets nearby. Look out for signs and paintings from the "Heidelberg School Artists Trail".

title: Wingrove Park
summary: A nice clearing where there are often picnicners or people playing.

title: Diamond Valley Railway  crossing
summary: The first glimpse of the Diamond Valley Railway is the crossing on Main Rd.

title: Diamond Valley Railway steam train
summary: There are lots a places to watch the trains, both diesel and steam engines. Better still, jump on and go for a ride, it is not expensive.

title: Como Park
summary: Como Park is adjacent to the Yarra River.  The historic Como House is located on the grounds. It contains exercising equipment, playground, BBQ area, bike path  and plenty of space to kick the footy.

title: South Yarra Station
summary: South Yarra Station is easy accessible from any train as they all stop at South Yarra. Our walk start's at South Yarra Station so it is easy to get to.

title: Yarra River, walking trail
summary: This is where the walking path along the Yarra River starts. This is such a nice part of the walk and one of the best key features. It it wheelchair/ pram friendly.

title: Jam Factory
summary: The Jam Factory is full of shops, places to eat and the cinemas.

title: Chapel Street
summary: Chaple Street is full of unique shops and fine dining restaurants.

title: Trams
summary: Trams frequently run along Toorak Road.

title: Trams
summary: Trams frequently run along Chapel Street.

title: River Red Gum
summary: Look up and marvel at the wonderful twisting branches of an old River Red Gum.  It plays an important role in stabilising river banks.

title: Red Wattle Bird
summary: If you spot one, notice what it is feeding on.  As a honeyeater it has a highly developed brush-tipped tongue adapted for nectar feeding.  It also eats berries and can catch insects in mid air.

title: Australian Wood Ducks
summary: You are sure to see Australian Wood Ducks.  They form monogamous breeding pairs that stay together year round. They nest in tree holes, above or near water, often re-using the same site.

title: Kangaroo Apple
summary: You can't mistake this plants kangaroo paw leaves.  The fruits were eaten by Aboriginal people, but only when very ripe, as they are said to be poisonous at other times.

title: Red Rump Parrot
summary: Keep your eyes out for Red Rump Parrots.  They spend a great deal of time feeding on the ground, and often call to one another.  The male (front) is very colourful.

title: Maribyrnong river
summary: A bluestone ford across the river gives you a chance to pause, enjoy the beautiful view, and listen to the sounds of the prolific birdlife.

title: You are not the first walker here
summary: Archaeological studies have found that the Brimbank Park area is among the oldest known human-inhabited sites in Australia, with Aboriginal occupation extending back over 40,000 years.

title: Taylors Creek
summary: If you are lucky you might spot a long-necked tortoise with its nostrils barely above the shallows.  If it hears you, it will submerge for several minutes.

title: The upper trail
summary:
Most of the park is 55m below the surrounding plains.
An optional part of the walk ascends up to the edge of the park giving you wonderful views down to the parkland below.

title: Willie Wagtail
summary: The Willie Wagtail is common in the park. You will probably see it doing what it loves the most, chasing insects.

title: River time
summary: The river is very patient, and over time is has exposed layers of sandstone deposited here around 400 million years ago.

title: White faced heron (and Eastern egret)
summary: The heron feeds on fish, insects and amphibians. You might see it walking to disturb it's prey, searching among damp crevices or simply standing in the water and watching for movement.

title: Dodd's Homestead
summary: The park was operated as farmland by the Dodd family from 1860 to 1974.  This is the original Dodd homestead.

title: Ruins of the old School house
summary: Ruins of the old School house

title: Blue Box eucalypts
summary: These trees are a botanical anomaly, found only here and in East Gippsland. They are obviously very old

title: Volcanic escarpments
summary: The river cuts through the volcanic plain revealing the many layers of volcanic activity that have taken place over the last 5 million years or so.

title: Abundant Bird Life
summary: Here some of the local Red Rump Parrots

title: The Old Ford
summary: Supposedly where Hume and Hovell crossed the River in 1826.

title: CWA Gardens
summary: CWA Gardens is home to the towns historic clock, originally housed in the historic Dookie Chataeu tower and cellars, built in 1889.

title: Mount Saddleback
summary: The trail is set at the base of Mount Saddlback. To the South you can see Mount Major, Gentle Annie hill to the South East and to the West you will see St. Mary's Church, build in 1998.

title: Branch line
summary: The branch line to Katamatite was constructed by the Yarrawonga Shire in 1890 and taken over by the Victorian Railways in 1892. The railway was closed in 1986 and the rails removed shortly after.

title: Willy the Wombat
summary: You might be lucky to spot this local resident whose den is under the road drain.

title: Various fauna and flora
summary: including echidnas, blue tongue lizzards, kangaroos and even wedge tailed eagles.

title: O'Donnell Gardens
summary: This where our walk begins, right next to cosmopolitan Acland Street, where you can stop for a meal, coffee and cake or pick up some souvenirs from the many gift shops.

title: Luna Park
summary: Acclaimed as one of the world's oldest amusement parks, Luna Park has been an icon of St Kilda since it was opened in 1912 .

title: The Palais
summary: Cross Cavell St and wander along the Lower Esplanade.  Generations of Melbourne residents have come here to dance, listen to live music and even watch movies.

title: Catani Arch
summary: Built in 1916, it provides a great place to stop and enjoy the view and is a popular photo spot for wedding couples.

title: St Kilda Sea Baths
summary: ou can stop for a swim, spa or seaweed wrap here or grab a bite to eat in one of the cafes or restaurants based here.

title: Mirka Mora Mosaic
summary: Beautiful mosaic map of St Kilda by Mirka Mora, a Jewish refugee who came to Australia to avoid persecution during World War II.

title: St Kilda Pier
summary: home of the famous Kirby's Kiosk.  Beyond the kiosk is the breakwater - home to St Kilda's own penguin colony.  If you keep your eyes open around dusk you may see them swimming home to roost.

title: Catani Park
summary: Catani Gardens, where you can stop for a picnic or a BBQ.  If you have the time, take a walk along the Esplanade towards Port Melbourne.  Look out for kite boarders on the bay.

title: The Upper Esplanade
summary: The Upper Esplanade, which boasts fantastic views of Port Phillip Bay.  On Sundays there is an arts and crafts market here.

title: The Upper Esplanade 2
summary: From here, you can continue along the Upper Esplanade until you return to O'Donnell Gardens, or on to Fitzroy Street, where you can enjoy the food, wine and great shopping that's on offer.

title: Punting on the Ornamental Lake
summary: Have a coffee and lunch at the cafe just near where the punt is available to take you on a trip around the lake

title: Pioneer Women's Memorial Garden
summary: Victorian premier Thomas Argyle dedicated the garden in November 1934, and in June 1935, Lady Huntingfield and the president of Women's Centenary Council, Mrs I.H. Moss, unveiled two bronze plaques.

title: The Arts Centre spire
summary: The Arts Centre spire taken from the garden of the National Gallery of Victoria

title: Kylie on Stage
summary: 'Kylie on Stage' is an exhibition of fabulous costumes from Kylie Minogue's colourful career.

title: The National Gallery of Victoria stained glass ceiling
summary: One of the most famous parts of the National Gallery of Victoria is the stained glass ceiling in the Great Hall. People used to lie on the floor to admire it!

title: The Lych Gate
summary: One of the many entrances to the Royal Botanic Gardens

title: Temple of the Winds
summary: The temple was built in 1901 and sits on a hill overlooking The Yarra River.  It is built in grey masonry, is circular and has 10 columns to support it.

title: Government House
summary: Government House is in a walled garden inside the Royal Botanic Gardens boundaries. The flag is full mast so the Governor is at home.

title: Gardens House
summary: Gardens House was once home to the Directors of the Royal Botanic Gardens.

title: Sidney Myer Music Bowl
summary: The Sidney Myer Music Bowl is a very large outdoor venue - home to Carols by Candlelight on Christmas eve.

title: Alexandra Gardens
summary: Across St Kilda Rd from Hamer Hall, the Alexandra Gardens connect to Kings Domain, the Domain parklands and the landscaped Royal Botanic Gardens.

title: Princes Bridge
summary: Built between 1886 and 1888, the bridge is of historical importance as it represents a boom period in Melbourne.

title: The Yarra River from Princes Bridge
summary: This view of the Yarra River shows Southbank with Eureka Tower dominating the landscape.

title: The Ornamental Lake
summary: A view of the Ornamental Lake close to The Terrace.

title: Boathouse Cafe
summary: Casual dining with a view! The cafe is open for brunch and lunch till 3pm. This photo is of the Boathouse Cafe viewed from the far end of the lake.

title: Small jetty
summary: A lovely resting point to enjoy the serenity of the surroundings.

title: John Egan's Cairn
summary: Memorial erected to commemorate the 150th anniversary of the discovery of gold on this site.

title: Wombat Flat Mineral Spring
summary: A lovely spot for a picnic, or to enjoy the mineral spring water!

title: Book Barn
summary: The Book Barn is a great place to stop for a coffee break and a browse of the many used books on offer.

title: Cormorants resting place
summary: These might be Little Black Cormorants, who usually congregate in a flock.

title: Many kinds of ducks inhabit the lake
summary: Ducks are commonly found in and around the lake. Some are quite tame as they are accustomed to people feeding them (but please don't feed them bread, try grains or seeds instead).

title: Historic change rooms and stone steps
summary: There used to be a swimming pool in this area and the historic change rooms and stone steps are remnants of this time.

title: View of the path
summary: You'll hear birds chirping through this wooded area as it's full of bird life. Stop for a minute or two and you might even spot them!

title: Decorative bridge
summary: Continue your walk over this bridge to admire the wide variety of trees planted next to the lake.

title: Path beside the bridge on Bleakley st
summary: Continue your walk along this shaded path.

title: Open grassy area
summary: The perfect spot to enjoy the changing colours of autumn.

title: Rambling wooded area
summary: More examples of the shrub and bushes that you find in this local area.

title: Rio Vista- Home of the Chaffey Brothers
summary: The Rio Vista is Spanish for River View and was completed in 1892.

title: Rustic native traill
summary: This walks leaves the  grounds of Rio Vista and enters Cureton  Ave. Along this walk is a look out to view the majestic Murray River.

title: The Old Mildura Station Homestead
summary: The building on this site is a re-creation of The Old Mildura Station Homestead which was built around 1850.

title: "Someday, the whole of Mildura will be as this garden," -George Chaffey
summary: The Homestead garden later inspired George Chaffey to select Mildura as the site for his irrigation colony.

title: Mildura Homestead Cemetery
summary: The Mildura Homestead Cemetery actually consists of two adjacent graves. One solitary grave stood in the Homestead Cemetery in Mildura, for nearly 40 years.

title: Entrance to where the Chaffey Women are buried
summary: Just sit and relax in the quietness of this place as you journey back in time and feel the presence of our historians.

title: In Honour of His Wife.
summary: WB Chaffey erected this magnificent monument to honour his young wife. His wife Hattie was spoken of with affection and was well respected for her acts of kindness.

title: BBQ Area
summary: An electric BBQ is kept clean and is situated with water, picnic tables, under cover & concrete flooring. There is plenty of tables and more not shown so many people could be accommodated at the BBQ.

title: Play Gym
summary: A kiddies play gym is located close to the BBQ area so they can be kept an eye on whilst cooking

title: Skate Park
summary: If you have a skate boarder, they will love the different jumps at the park.

title: skate park
summary: another view of the skate park jumps

title: Skate park
summary: More of the jumps

title: Footbridge
summary: There are a few creeks running in to fill the lake and footbridges are a feature..

title: Lake view
summary: There is a wonderful lake that is different shapes and has a good deal of wildlife, including coots, ducks, and even fish species

title: Toilet Block and Tourism Map
summary: There is a brick toilet block that is well kept, clean and concrete floor.  It is located in easy walk from the carpark and BBQ area and wheelchairs are well catered for.

title: Wonderful footbridge
summary: I have photographed people on this footbridge many times.. I some situations when the willows are in follage, it is very lush, it is shady and when in autumn, it has a mass of yellow

title: Footbridge
summary: At the side of the footbridge is a seat, rubbish bins and they even supply doogie poo bags if you are walking the dog and forget the bag to pick the doo up..

title: Bins and benches
summary: There are many bins and benches all around the park and they are all in good order and well kept clean

title: Old Railway Bridge
summary: The re-located 1896 Murtoa Railway Station footbridge spanning the lake narrows

title: Northern end view
summary: There is a few lovely views or scenes around the lake

title: Platforms or Piers
summary: There are two piers or platforms where you could launch a canoe or kayak but be careful as the water is deep in parts, a bouyancy vest would be needed.

title: Well formed tracks
summary: Well made tracks in some areas around the park

title: Track at the Southern end of Rabl Park
summary: The Track is very easy and quite well formed in some areas.

title: Loads of birdlife
summary: There are tons of bird life nesting around the lake and with care, there are some very good photo opportunities

title: Eastern Spinebill
summary: The first stop on the ClimateWatch trail is the Eastern Spinebill. You will probably spot them around flowers, particularly fuchsias and correas.

title: Grey Fantail
summary: Look for this little, dark grey bird. It usually has an agile but erratic flight, can you notice something different?

title: Willie Wagtail
summary: Follow the chirping of these birds. Can you hear them singing "sweet-pretty-creatures"?

title: Firewheel Tree
summary: This beautiful native tree on your left has striking red flowers. Are they out today?

title: Jacaranda
summary: Stop in at the mighty Jacaranda tree on the right. What stage of its annual life cycle is it up to? Don't forget to record what you see on the ClimateWatch app.

title: English Oak
summary: This tree can be quite tricky to find, but if you spot it, record what stage of its annual cycle it is at. Leaves falling? Flowers opening? Submit your sightings on the ClimateWatch app

title: Illawarra Flame Tree
summary: An iconic Australian tree which flowers in spring. Scientists think that these trees and others might flower earlier due to climate change, so please record what you see.

title: Orchard Swallowtail Butterfly
summary: From October through May, you will have the chance to spot their beautiful wings. Upload the image on ClimateWatch and help the science to save our environment.

title: Jewel Spider
summary: Take a picture of a female and male Jewel spider. Females sit in the middle of the web and males can be found in the vegetation around the web.

title: Cardinia Cultural Centre
summary: The Cardinia Cultural Centre is the perfect place to get something to eat at the end of the walk as there is a cafe.

title: Lakeside Amphitheatre
summary: The Lakeside Amphitheatre host several events throughout the year including Christmas Carols.

title: Meet the locals!
summary: The lake is filled with ducks and swans. If you're lucky, you might see a whole family.

title: Playground
summary: A great place for children to play.

title: Barbecue Rotunda
summary: There is a rotunda with barbecues, tables and public toilets. The perfect place to stop and have lunch.

title: Fountains
summary: On a warm day, the fountains might be on. You can stand and watch the fountains.

title: The Eastwood IGA shopping centre is a good start
summary: The Eastwood IGA is a great place to start and finish as it has a good sized car park and provides amenities

title: Safe road crossing
summary: Cross the main road here

summary: There is all manner of community exercise equipment around the oval

summary: Have some fun with the exercise gear

summary: The whole area is clean and well maintained especially the footpaths.
