summary: For people with wheelchairs that have someone to pick them up, this is a perfect car park as it is not used and has tons of room

title: Street View
summary: The wider street view along Howitt Avenue

title: Howitt Avenue
summary: The wider street view along Howitt Avenue

title: Back to the Supermarket
summary: The Eastwood IGA Supermarket

title: Entrance gate to Sandy Point Conservation Area
summary: Entrance gate to Sandy Point Conservation Area

title: Million dollar views of The Strand
summary: Sandy Point gives unique views to the real estate as well as Greenwich Bay

title: Port of Melbourne from Sandy Point
summary: Melbourne's new container terminal is visible with its colours of grey and orange from Sandy Point

title: View over Hobsons Bay
summary: View over Hobsons Bay with the container terminal on the left and Williamstown on the right.

title: Mangroves with Newport Power Station in the background
summary: Revegetated mangroves with Newport Power Station in the background

title: Newport Boat Ramp
summary: Newport Boat Ramp is popular with local boat owners

title: Greenwich Baseball Reserve
summary: Toilets are available at the Williamstown Wolves Baseball Club pavilion

title: Hobsons Bay Coastal Trail walking/cycling path
summary: Watch out for bike riders passing  Sandy Point. The bike path is very popular on sunny days.

title: The Spit is popular with fishermen
summary: The Spit is popular with fishermen

title: Remains of Great Extended Hustler's Reef Goldmine - machinery foundations.
summary: The mine opened in 1865 and closed in 1921. It was a kilometre deep and extended outwards up to 3 kms beneath Bendigo. The remains are the foundations for large mine machinery.

title: Memorial to the 7 men killed on 2nd May 1914.
summary: In May 2008 the Friends of Hustlers Reef dedicated this memorial to the men who died in 1914. In May 2014 the Bendigo commemorated the centenary of the disaster with a community history open day.

title: Box Iron Bark Living Memorial Revegetation.
summary: The Friends of Hustler's Reserve have worked hard to clear invasive weeds,  re-vegetate with local indigenous plants and reinforce eroded paths re-using existing materials from the site.

title: Remains of Great Extended Hustler's Reef Gold Mine.
summary: It's undergone a significant clean up since this photo was taken in 2013 & is considerably less spooky. Remains of foundations for boilers, compressors and sidewinders litter the Bendigo landscape.

title: Gentle rise
summary: Bendigo is spotted with mullock hills covered in light scrub. In late winter they are often ablaze in wattle gold & are always filled with native birds. The Bendigo Bird Guide is linked below.

title: Memorial to Goldfield Widows.
summary: Situated at the Eastern end of the Reserve is another memorial - this one for the 100’s of widows who lost their husbands through mining accidents or miners phthisis (silicosis).

title: Boundry Arms Hotel.
summary: Not only does this pub have cold beer and a good feed but there is also a huge range of classic old photos of Bendigo's mining heyday available for close inspection.

title: Beautiful Houses and Incredible Views.
summary: Extend your walk out of the Reserve to follow the curve of Moore St, and see beautiful old homes and clear views of Bendigo. If you're able, head into town to climb the Poppet Head in Rosalind Park.

title: Paper Plane Crash Site.
summary: Someone crashed a huge iron paper plane  into their front yard! The sculpture is a local novelty. No photo out of interest for the homeowner's privacy but I do recommend a look - kids will love it!

title: Remember - Frederick James Chinn.
summary: Born in Bendigo in 1888 he was the eighth child of Annie Yates and James Chinn. Frederick was 26 years old and unmarried. He was buried at Kangaroo Flat Cemetery and his headstone can still be viewed.

title: Remember - William Ryan.
summary: Also 26 and unmarried he left behind his parents John and Jessie.

title: Remember - William Crowther Blair.
summary: The oldest of those killed in the blast. Born in Ballarat he was forty years old when the explosion widowed his wife Catherine and three children.

title: Remember - Matthew George Forster.
summary: At 28 Matthew left behind his wife Maud with two children. Although she remarried two years later and moved to Collingwood, she eventually returned to Bendigo to be buried with Matthew.

title: Remember - Herbert John Thomas.
summary: At 30 Herbert was 8 years younger than his father John when he was also killed in an  explosion at Hustler's. Herbert was 15 & had 4 siblings.His wife Ethel was left with 3 children when he died.

title: Remember - Leslie Duncan Martin.
summary: Leslie was 23 and the youngest of those killed. He was buried with his older brother Murdock who had been killed nine years earlier aged just 18 at the Clarence United Mine.

title: Remember - John Henry Campbell.
summary: The explosion left 31 year old John's wife widowed with two children and after his death, she delivered their daughter Ida. Margaret went on to bury Ida with John just five years later.

title: Poppet Head
summary:
This used to be the site where a replica of a poppet head from the mining days was situated. 
It was used for mining Antimony at the Ringwood Antimony mine. A plaque remains.

title: Miner's Cottage
summary:
A replica of a miner's cottage from the days of Antimony mining stood here but was destroyed by fire. 
What remains is a plaque and board providing information.

title: Grassy Area
summary: Bring your family, a picnic and some ball games and have fun!

title: Creek
summary: Storm water runs off from surrounding suburbs into the lake.

title: Flora
summary: The park features an abundance of native trees and shrubs.

title: Walking/Cycling Tracks
summary:
Sealed and unsealed shared walking/cycling tracks with easy grades circle the lake's 1km shoreline in the 8.5 hectare park. 
The tracks have easy grades and are suitable for wheelchairs.

title: Tree Canopy
summary: A continuous tree canopy provides shade over three-quarters of the site (excluding the lake).

title: Bird Watching
summary: There are several spots suitable for bird watching or just sitting down and relaxing.

title: The Lake
summary:
The lake is about 1 hectare in size and has a maximum depth of 4.3 metres. 
It is not suitable for swimming.

title: Cafes & Restaurants
summary: Just across the road you will find places to eat or have a coffee.

title: Views
summary: Enjoy the views of the lake :)

title: Water Refill Sation
summary: Fill up your water bottle here.

title: Playground
summary:
The playground is particularly nice. 
Enjoy flying foxes, monkey bars, a spiral slide, bouncers, rockers, a see-saw and spring-seats among others.

title: Liberty Swing
summary:
It offers people in wheelchairs the opportunity to enjoy the fun and recreation of swinging.
A key is needed to access the Liberty Swing (details in the description of this walk).

title: Wooden Sculptures
summary: Find the large wooden sculptures of indigenous fauna made by local artists.

title: Ducks
summary:
You will usually be able to see some ducks and other birds in this area.
You're asked not to feed the ducks for the health of the water.

title: Barbecues & Picnic Shelters
summary:
This is just one of three barbecues available in the park.
They are available free of charge.

title: Personalised Pavers
summary:
At this barbecue you will find pavers decorated by local school children.
Take some time to check out their designs!

title: Fishing
summary: Try your luck at catching some fish from this platform.

title: Bridge & Pavilion
summary: A walking bridge and pavilion made out of timber are features of the park.

title: Flora & Fauna
summary: Keep an eye out for native flora and fauna.

title: Public Toilets
summary: The toilets for the park are located here.

title: Entrance
summary: This is the entrance and disabled drop-off point. There is some limited side street parking available.

title: Sound Shell
summary: It is used for festivities and concerts over summer.

title: Fern Gully
summary: Stroll along the boardwalk through the fern gully.

title: Grassy Area
summary: Here you will find another large grassy area, ideal for picnics.

title: Main Car Park
summary: This is the main car park, just off Mt Dandenong Road (Melways 49 K8).

title: The creek
summary: A great place to explore on our back door.

title: Walk start
summary: Pathway down to the bridge at the start of the walk

title: Creek view from bridge
summary: View along the creek from the bridge

title: Start of the gravel track
summary: One of only a few small uphill sections on the walk.

title: Wandering through the trees
summary: Wandering through the clusters of trees.

title: Down to the bridge
summary: The short hill down to the pedestrian bridge cna look a lot bigger depending on your point of view.

title: A fine creek view
summary: A fine view of the flora growing in and along the creek from the small pedestrian bridge.

title: The bridge
summary: The new pedestrian bridge that allows us to cross the creek and return along the opposite bank to the starting point of the walk.

title: Common Reed
summary: Look out for the semi-aquatic Common Reed along the creek.  It provides a habitat for certain birds and the leaves were used by aboriginal people to weave baskets.

title: Cumbungi
summary: Look out for Cumbungi along the creek.  It is a good frog habitat.  Aboriginal people used to harvest the roots which can be cleaned, steamed and roasted.

title: A hidden gem
summary: A view along the east side of the creek.  Feels just like being in the countryside.  A hidden gem.

title: Walking in nature
summary: Trees and abundant vegetation along the eastern slopes next to the creek.

title: Grand old tree
summary: Remnant Eucalypts form part of the vegetation, giving you an indication of the forest that used to embrace this creek.

title: Walking over water
summary: No need to get your feet wet as you cross the bridges along the trail.

title: Place for a picnic
summary: Take a hamper and enjoy the grasslands alongside the Eel Hole Creek.

title: Painted Poles
summary: See the beautiful images painted by local school children expressing what they learnt on a field trip connecting the sciences to the arts

title: The wetlands
summary: Cast a fishing line or just enjoy the view on the platform built over the water.

title: Walk or ride
summary: Sections of the trail are user-friendly to walkers and bike-riders alike.

title: Main Lake
summary: This is 'Main Lake' it's fairly large and one of my favourite attraction sites in the sanctuary. You might also spot a duck in there. You might also want to find a small bridge that crosses this lake.

title: Manna Gum Isthmus
summary: This is an interesting red river gum tree that's 300+ years old and provides homes to possums, bats and nesting birds. It's also a primary feature for visiting in the sanctuary.

title: Willis Billabong
summary: This is Willis Billabong and was quite covered by trees, branches and plants. I spotted a few magpies there.

title: Galaxiella Billabong
summary: Spotted another Billabong. This one looked very unique with a nice distinctive dark coloured water and what seems to me to be purplish pink coloured leaves.

title: Dismantled Car
summary: Something quite unexpected- A car. This old dismantled car near close to the track can't be missed, I think it adds a creative element with the natural surrounding. It sure caught me by surprise.

title: Twin Ponds
summary: There're two ponds on each side of the track. This picture is the one of the left. It was an interesting contrast to the other wetlands. The water was different, but interesting - choc brown and foamy

title: Iron Barks Hut
summary: A fantastic hut- highlight of the sanctuary for me. This hut is equipped with a gas barbeque for public use with all wooded seats and tablets. It's metal sheltered and makes a nice place for relaxing.

title: Weir Park
summary: This was developed during beautification in the late 60s.  This is where Barnes Boulevard terminated pre 1985

title: weir
summary: The new weir was built in the 1967/68.  Prior to this the weir was located further upstream where there was also a bathing hole.

title: Wetlands
summary: The wetlands provide a natural setting for local flora and fauna.

title: Bird Hide
summary: One of two bird hides that can be used to search for the various birds who inhabit this area.

title: Bird Hide
summary: Another bird hide providing an opportunity to see the various birds who visit or live in this area.

title: Boardwalk
summary: Downstream this is a chance to cross over the river and explore what the other side has to offer.  The track continues east on the other side and meets back at the base of the weir.

title: Weir Boardwalk
summary: This provides an opportunity to explore the other side of the river.  The track continues on the other side and can meet up west at the downstream boardwalk

title: Trentham Railway Station
summary: Disused train carriages still sit on the tracks at the old Trentham Railway Station, which you can walk around from the ground.

title: Old Railway Sleepers
summary: Watch out for the railway sleepers underfoot along this section of the trail, which are slightly uneven footing.

title: Footbridge
summary: A good point to turn around if you’re after a shorter walk.

title: Resting Point
summary: Take a break at the bench and see if you can notice the difference between the older growth and younger forests on either side of the path.

title: Old Bridge
summary: Following the diversion around the disused bridge will give you a great view of the wooden structure.

title: Lyonville
summary: The trail ends (or begins, depending on your direction) at the site of the former Lyonville Railway Station. There is parking at both ends of the track.

title: Wild Melbourne
summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

title: St Kilda Town Hall
summary: St Kilda Town Hall, home of most Port Phillip Council staff and services such as rates, events, immunisations, planning.

title: The Local Taphouse
summary: Over 100 beers and food served on the rooftop.

title: Raised crossings
summary: The yellow raised crossings on the side streets off Carlisle seem to be doing a great job of giving pedestrians priority. yay!

title: Inkerman St bottle brush
summary: In Walktober the bottle brush are glowing red up and down Inkerman.

title: Lady of St Kilda
summary: Look up to see the Lady of St Kilda artwork on the Balaclava railway bridge  (or look right to see people queuing on the street for Las Chicas- linseed soy and dandelion latte highly recommended)

title: Kids' side of the park
summary: Great playground for kids of all ages on this side of Alma Park. Highlights include the curly red slide, mosaic cave, and giant flying fox.

title: Flying fox
summary: It is a big flying fox! This is also a good spot to indulge in some real estate envy- wouldn't it be great to live in a flat backing onto Alma Park?

title: Nature strips
summary: A couple of personalised nature strips on Hammerdale Ave.

title: Stormwater treatment
summary: Check out the water sensitive urban design planting at the Alma Road end of the playground.

title: Treed path
summary: This path is surrounded by bushy flowering shrubs.

title: Dog park
summary: Dogs can be let off leash on both sides of the path west of the railway line.

title: Neighbours Cafe
summary: Some commissioned street art on both facades of Neighbours Cafe. It also has a surprisingly quiet garden out back if you fancy lunch in the sun.

title: Kensington Railway Station
summary: Originally opened by the Melbourne & Essendon Railway Company in 1860, it became a critical transport link for livestock. The signal box was built in 1897, Platform 1 in 1888 & platform 2 in 1905.

title: Islington House  166-168 Bellair St
summary: ‘Islington’ (1891), was the Kensington Property Exchange. Owned & built by James Wales, a former councillor & mayor in 1899. It was used as a set for the TV show ‘The Sullivans’.

title: Plumbers House  156 Bellair St
summary: Bill Pearce set up a plumbing business in the 1940s. The only gear he could afford was carried on his bike. By the turn of the century Bill was still here with a workshop out back. The façade remains.

title: Kuruc House  114 Bellair St
summary: Kuruc House (1898), architects Ussher & Kemp, is an early example of a Queen Anne villa & was occupied by surgeon Joseph Moss until 1910. It continued to be used as a doctor’s clinic until 1973.

title: Hal Porter House  86 Bellair St
summary: Hal Porter’s memoir "Watcher on the Cast-Iron Balcony" describes his early memories of growing up before WWI at 86 Bellair St, including his walk to Kensington Primary along the cobbled back lanes.

title: Kensington Town Hall  24 – 40 Bellair St
summary: Flemington & Kensington Town Hall (1901). Architecturally, it expresses grand intentions in a small scale. It became a social hub with dances, weddings, women’s groups & an infant welfare centre.

title: Newmarket Saleyards (1861-1987)/Now Community High School
summary: By 1888 almost ½ million animals passed annually through the Newmarket saleyards. In the 20th century it became the world’s biggest livestock auction market. Associated industries created many jobs.

title: 6th Melbourne Scout Hall  55 McCracken St
summary: The 135 year old hall, at the rear, used by the scouts since the 1920’s was formerly used by both Anglicans and Methodists before either church was built. Restored with community involvement in 2014.

title: Kensington Primary School
summary: Kensington State School No.2374 opened in 1881 with an initial enrolment of 228 children, which grew to 1,000 by 1898.  In 1914 the State School was the second largest in Victoria.

title: Christ Church Uniting
summary: The vacant lot is where the original timber Church (1882) stood. This served as Sunday school until burnt down in the 1970’s. Current Church was built 1889, now a combined Anglican and Uniting Church.

title: Hardiman’s Hotel
summary: The former Clarence Hotel built in the late 1870’s by the Hardiman family. Designed to look like an ocean liner, rebranded in the 40’s by Tim Hardiman and renovated by new owners in 1998.

title: Holy Rosary Catholic Church
summary: In 1902 the first Holy Rosary Church opened on Derby Street. It was replaced in 1928 by this Church which first celebrated Mass, and was officially opened, on Christmas Day that year.

title: Holy Rosary Primary School
summary: A Catholic primary school, Holy Rosary, opened at the parish hall in 1916 and moved to its present location in 1927.

title: Wolseley Parade Streetscape
summary: Wolseley Parade, Kensington is considered to be one of the most desirable streets in Melbourne. It is very typical of the suburb and its development over the Victorian era.

title: Wallaby and joey
summary: The wallabies around the camping area are quite tame, including this one with a joey!

title: Goanna
summary: In the warmer months you might see goannas. like this one.

title: Little creek
summary: The path leads down to a little creek.

title: The creek
summary: This is not the Bittangabee Creek!

title: Steps
summary: A gentle climb up a small hill.

title: The ruins
summary: The beginnings of a stone house that was never completed. Some believe it was constructed by the Imlay brothers.

title: Wombat burrows
summary: There are many wombat burrows around, but you need to walk at night to see them.

title: Anthills
summary: Anthills like this can be found across Ben Boyd.

title: Bittangebee Creek
summary: The creek is a wonderful place to stop or climb along the rocks along the creek bed.

title: Heath
summary: This is the floral emblem of Victoria, but also found in NSW.

title: Top of the lagoon
summary: When walking back, cut down to the lagoon to this point. b

title: Soldier crabs
summary: If you are lucky you will see thousands of soldier crabs walking along the shore, an amazing sight!

title: Rock pools
summary: Lots of rock pools to look at.

title: The lagoon
summary: The lagoon looking out to see. The is a wonderful little sandy beach round the corner that is great of swimming.

title: Three Businessmen Who Brought Their Own Lunch: Batman, Swanston and Hoddle
summary: These figures by Alison Weaver and Paul Quinn were installed in Swanston St. the first public sculpture in Melbourne since Vault was removed from the City Square in 1981

title: Time and Tide
summary: Akio Makigawa (born Japan 1948 - died in Perth 1999) has public sculptures in most Australian capital cities and several more in Melbourne.

title: Architectural Fragment
summary: Petrus Spronk 1992 sculpture is beloved by Melbourne's skateboard riders. It is also a fun piece of post-modernism quoting the neo-classical facade of the State Library.

title: La Trobe
summary: Governor La Trobe by Peter Corlett, 2006. This is the only Peter Corlett sculpture on this walk but he has may more around Melbourne, its suburbs and the rest of the world.

title: Larry La Trobe
summary: Pam Irving’s bronze dog, “Larry La Trobe” was install in 1993 and stolen in 1995. The current sculpture a new edition cast from the original mould.

title: Warin
summary: The wooden wombat, “Warin” was carved in situ in 2002 by Des McKenna. Another one for children to climb on.

title: Loretta Quinn, Beyond the Ocean of Existence, 1993
summary: Loretta Quinn is the brother of Paul Quinn one of the sculptors of The Three Businessmen. Nearby there are painted pole by indigenous artists, Maree Clarke and Sonja Hodge

title: Burke and Wills Monument
summary: This is the fourth location for that this monument has stood in Melbourne since 1865. It was originally cast in Charles Summers studio in Collins St. now the location of Burlington Chambers

title: Street art sculptures in Hosier Lane
summary: Along with all the aerosol art there are some unofficial street art sculptures in this lane. You will have to look carefully to find them.

title: Paul Montford, The Water Nypmh, 1920
summary: Paul Montford brought this sculpture with him when he emigrated to Australia in 1923. It was the first public sculpture bought by Melbourne City Council.

title: Inge King, Forward Surge 1972-74
summary: Installed in 1981 this modern fits perfectly into the curved architecture of the Arts Centre and Hamer Hall. The curves also delight children who try to climb them.

title: Matthew Flinders Memorial
summary: The sculptor Charles Web Gilbert, like to do everything himself, from the modelling to the casting of the sculptures.

title: George VII Memorial
summary: The sculptor Bertram Mackennal was born in Fitzroy but became Australia's first international art star.

title: The Phoenix
summary: Originally large curved feathers, or flames, were once attached at several points over the body of the sculpture. These have broken off and only fragments of two remain.

title: The Pathfinder
summary: An edition of English/Australian sculptor John Robinson 1974 bronze sculpture of a hammer thrower.  Only six years after this sculpture the Melbourne City Council installed Vault in the City Square.

title: Apollo and Hercules
summary: Politician and newspaper proprietor, Theodore Fink  acquired these marble copies of classical sculpture on a holiday in Rome.

title: Tom Bass, The Genie, 1973
summary: This sculpture is purpose built for children to play on. Sydney sculptor Tom Bass has several other sculptures around Melbourne and at Melbourne University.

title: Vault, Ron Robertson-Swann
summary: In 1980 this sculpture was in the City Square and Melbourne was divided by the controversy over this sculpture. In 1981 it was moved to Batman Park by the Yarra River.

title: The Public Purse,  Simon Perry
summary: In 1994, the City of Melbourne added what was described in the design brief as “unique and distinctive forms of street seating” in the streets, The Public Purse was one of them.

title: The Preston Market
summary: We love the Preston Market because it is really muilti-cultural. There is a great lolly store that sells American lollies. It is really cheap place where you can chill out.

title: Mai Lan Bakery
summary: One of our friend's dad found this bakery in the Age, and it was voted the best pork rolls in Melbourne. We went there to try something new and they was amazing! They are only $3.50 a roll.

title: High Street, Preston
summary: This stretch of High St (between Murray Rd and Gower St) is really cool. They have all these bargain stores. The vibes you get there are really chill.

title: Tram Stop to take you down to Arthurton Road
summary: We took the 86 tram to get to Arthurton Road, the trams go down High Street really often so it is easy to just jump on a tram.

title: Arthurton Road Stop Off
summary: Make sure you get off at this tram stop so you can walk down to CERES!

title: CERES
summary: CERES has a really natural feeling. Anyone can just hang out there. The food is great and the hot chocolates are pretty good, organic too! The markets on Saturdays are really fun too.

title: Merri Park
summary: Merri Park is fun and right next to Northcote High. There is a cool playground in the park that not bad for teens to hang out on after school hours.

title: Juline's Noodle Shop
summary: Juline's makes the best chips ever, so addictive! It is like our little community milk bar.

title: Jump on the 112 tram to take you to Brunswick Street!
summary: There is a tram stop right in front of Juline's Noodle Shop - so really easy to jump on that to take you down to Fitzroy.

title: Fitzroy Pool
summary: Just down the road from this marker towards Smith Street is our favourite pool. It costs only $2.10 to get in. So cheap and there are never lots of people. They have night sessions too!

title: Brunswick Street, Fitzroy
summary: We wish that more streets were like Brunswick St. It's got cool clothes shops, 2nd-hand shop called "Hunter Gatherer\". Heaps of parks nearby too and cheap food!

title: San Churros
summary: We finished up our walk at San Churros to reward ourselves. It's one of our favourite places to get something yum to eat.

title: National Storage
summary: Striking monochrome throws and characters really brighten up this corner. Be careful of the level crossing!

title: Bowie, Cash and a Clockwork Orange fence
summary: This homeowner clearly had a great time in the seventies!

title: Melbourne Bowls club
summary: Established in 1864, this bowls club is an institution. Good cold beers at reasonable prices too.

title: Artists Lane
summary: This laneway is overflowing with wow making artworks. Change is the only constant, but keep your eyes peeled for works by Mysterious Al, Unwell Bunny, Kaff-eine or Heesco.

title: Shame Mural and Ming the Merciless
summary: Putos is a prolific artist with a very recognisable style.

title: Classic Adnate, LucyLucy and Urban Cake Lady
summary: Some classic works that have stuck around for a long while, catch them before they're gone!

title: Saigon Sally Laneway
summary: A great Asian diner style restaurant with great artwork, inside and out.

title: Goddess Saraswati
summary: The Hindu goddess of the arts - how appropriate - classic by Deb.

title: River Red Gum
summary: Look up and marvel at the wonderful twisting branches of an old River Red Gum.  It plays an important role in stabilising river banks.

title: Walking tracks
summary: The walking tracks are mostly level with a few gentle uphill sections.  Some sections are very open.  On a sunny day make sure to bring a hat and a bottle of water.

title: Butterflies
summary: As you walk in the summer months, hundreds of butterflies will be out, dancing among the shrubs and trees.

title: Stumpy-tailed Lizard
summary: If you hear a rumble in the grass as you walk you might spot a lizard out finding a nice spot for sunbaking.

title: Dilwinia in flower
summary: Dilwinia is just one of many native flowers on the walk that show their true colours during Spring.

title: Eastern Grey Kangaroos
summary: At birth, the infant immediately climbs into its mother's pouch and does not emerge for two months. Until they reach 10 or 11 months of age, threatened joeys, will dive for the safety of mom's pouch.

title: Living Legends
summary: Just in front of the Homestead are real Living Legends! Established to bring retired champion horses back to the public, the front paddocks are home to some of Australia's finest retired racehorses.

title: The Woodlands Homestead
summary: Originally imported and erected by the Greene family in 1842, and extended by later owners, the homestead is a unique example of design, construction and decoration from that era.

title: A turn in the road
summary: After leaving the homestead, keep an eye out for these posts.  The path turns left up a small incline immediately afterwards.

title: The parklands
summary: The park contains a landscape that has changed little since pastoral settlement in the 1840s.  Large areas of little-disturbed grassy woodland provides habitat for kangaroos.

title: The Eastern Rosella
summary: There is a great diversity of birdlife in the park.  Some are easy to spot like the colourful Eastern Rosella.  Other tiny birds that nest in bushes near the creek require a little more patience.

title: Map
summary: At the main car park is a map of the Reserve, giving you a clear overview of your walking options.

title: The Walking Tracks
summary: Each track is named after one of the birds you’re likely to see on your stroll and it’s clear that the Reserve is being steadily revegetated.

title: Dog walkers' paradise
summary: The Crinigan Reserve is an extremely popular place to indulge your pooch in an enjoyable walk, but please keep your furry friend on a leash at all times.

title: Crossing the water
summary: This boardwalk in the Reserve takes you across waterway and onto Lion’s Dam.

title: Bring your binoculars
summary: Bird-watching is a well known activity in the Reserve, with a bountiful array of species to spot.

title: White earned honeyeater
summary: Found in eastern and southern Australia, it lives in dry eucalypt forests and woodlands. Find out more and hear its bird call in the link below.

title: Eastern Spinebill
summary: This gorgeous bird has a long fine and curved bill, with distinctive markings. It is found in eastern and southern Australia. Find out more in the link below.

title: Waxlip Orchid
summary: The Reserve is home to 30 different types of orchids, including this beautiful Waxlip Orchid (Glossodia Major). It flowers in late winter to early spring, and is found in heath land and open forests.

title: A world of wetlands
summary: The Lions, Hospital, Wallaby and Tortoise Dams occupy space in this bushland reserve, creating a rich wetland environment.

title: Rest and relax
summary: You can sit by the water, watch the wildlife and even have a picnic while enjoying the serenity.

title: Town Pier - now the Port Melbourne Yacht Club
summary: Black coal arrived here from Newcastle. Town Pier was the first significant pier structure in the early settlement of Sandridge. It was demolished in the 1950s.

title: Morley's Coal Depot
summary: This handsome coal store was one of the businesses owned by William Morley, the first mayor of Sandridge. Blue stone was preferred to timber as fire was a recurrent danger.

title: Railway Line
summary: The coal was conveyed by rail pulled by a dray up Dow St. Recent works to create a raingarden revealed the old tram tracks

title: Sandridge Bay Towers
summary: The former Harpers Starch Factory with its distinctive chimney - a significant landmark through the 20th century.

title: Esplanade East
summary: The coal continued its journey along Esplanade East - the eastern edge of the former Sandridge Lagoon. It is said that during the depression, coal would fall from the wagons accidentally on purpose

title: Gasholders
summary: Huge gasholders stored the gas.  The gas was contained in a huge bell that rested on water. The level would rise up or down, depending on how much was in storage.

title: The Weighbridge
summary: This is where the coal was brought into the Gasworks and weighed. In the thirties, workers gathered at the entrance in the hope of getting any work at all.

title: Brick Wall
summary: I love the patterning of this brick wall and the colours in the bricks. Contemplate the size and the length of the walls around Gasworks and imagine them being built brick by brick.

title: Solar!
summary: Note the solar panels appearing on houses in this neighbourhood. At one time, the Gasworks management had to pay to clean the neighbouring houses from grit and grime.

title: Mill Park Softball Reserve
summary: There is lots of room for softball, baseball or any other sport

title: Back on the walking path
summary: Say goodbye to suburbia and hello walking path

title: Careful crossing the road!
summary: Please look both ways before crossing Manning Clarke Road

title: Car park is accessible off Morang Road
summary: If you choose to drive this is a good parking spot, however why not catch the train and walk from South Morang Train Station which is only 1km away!

title: Transfer for walking path to footpath
summary: This part of the walk follows the residential streets

title: Mill Park Leisure and Services Centre
summary: Mill Park Leisure and Services Centre: "...a contemporary aquatics and recreation facilty..."

title: Morand Drive
summary: This short section of the walk is on the footpath next to Morang Drive

title: Turn right (south) here!
summary: Turn right here if you which to finish the Mill Park Reserve Walk loop

title: BBQ and covered picnic area
summary: This is a great spot near the playground for a BBQ or picnic with plenty of shade

title: Plenty of seats for tired legs
summary: Thre are plenty of seats for tired legs all around the loop

title: Playground
summary: There is a nice playground here which is a perfect spot for the kids to play while you have a breather!

title: Lots of native flora
summary: There are many native trees planted or protected along the walk. The signs explain what type trees you are looking at.

title: Continue the loop or go elsewhere
summary: There are plenty of signs to let you know where you are and where you can go. At this point you can leave the loop by heading north or east onto other paths

title: Residential Street
summary: This section of the walk takes you along a residential street, there are good footpaths  along both side

title: The Stables Playground
summary: This playground is huge and very cool! Hours of fun for everyone!

title: Plenty of seats
summary: There are plenty of seats along the way, both shaded and sunny
